// MedMasters: Gynae & Obs Paper 2: Anatomy of Reproductive Tract - Complete (Q1-Q600)
// 600 MCQs
(function(){
  if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
  window.MM['gynae_p2_anatomy'] = [
    {q:'The clitoris in the female external genitalia is embryologically homologous to which male structure?',o:['Prostate','Epididymis','Bulbourethral gland','Penis'],a:3,
    e:`The clitoris is the female homologue of the penis. Both develop from the genital tubercle and share erectile tissue, neurovascular supply and sensory innervation.<br><br>The clitoris has a glans, body and crura with the same erectile structure as the penis but does not transmit the urethra. Its sensory supply is via the dorsal nerve from the pudendal nerve.<br><br>Prostate (A) develops from the urogenital sinus, equivalent to female paraurethral glands; bulbourethral gland (C) corresponds to greater vestibular glands; epididymis (D) derives from the mesonephric duct.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology; Chapter: Urogenital System)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following structures forms the lateral boundary of the vulval vestibule?',o:['Labia majora','Mons pubis','Labia minora','Perineal body'],a:2,
    e:`The labia minora form the lateral boundary of the vulval vestibule, the cleft into which the urethra, vaginal orifice and vestibular gland ducts open.<br><br>The vestibule is bounded laterally by labia minora, meeting anteriorly at the clitoris and posteriorly at the fourchette. Bartholin glands open in the posterolateral aspect of the vaginal orifice.<br><br>Labia majora (A) form outermost folds, lateral to labia minora; mons pubis (B) overlies the symphysis pubis anteriorly; perineal body (D) is fibromuscular tissue between vagina and anus.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The greater vestibular glands (Bartholin glands) open into which anatomical location?',o:['Posterolateral aspect of the vaginal orifice','Urethral meatus','Cervical canal','Lateral vaginal wall'],a:0,
    e:`The greater vestibular (Bartholin) glands open into the posterolateral aspect of the vaginal orifice at approximately 5 and 7 o\'clock positions, deep to the bulbospongiosus muscle.<br><br>Each pea-sized gland is drained by a 2 cm duct opening into the vestibule and lubricates the introitus during arousal. Bartholin abscess and cyst formation occur with duct obstruction; treatment is marsupialisation or excision.<br><br>Anterior fornix (B) is a vaginal recess around the cervix; clitoral region (C) lies anteriorly and is unrelated; lateral wall of vagina (D) is not the duct opening site.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The arterial supply of the labia majora is primarily derived from branches of which artery?',o:['Inferior epigastric artery','Internal pudendal artery','Femoral artery','External iliac artery'],a:1,
    e:`The labia majora receive primary arterial supply from the internal pudendal artery, a branch of the anterior division of the internal iliac artery.<br><br>The external pudendal artery (a branch of the femoral artery) provides additional anterior supply. Venous drainage parallels arterial supply, with internal pudendal veins draining to the internal iliac vein.<br><br>Femoral artery (A) supplies lower limb directly, not labia; superior rectal artery (C) supplies upper rectum; ovarian artery (D) arises from aorta and supplies the ovary and tube, not labia.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The lymphatic drainage of the labia majora primarily goes to which lymph nodes?',o:['Para-aortic nodes','Internal iliac nodes','External iliac nodes','Superficial inguinal nodes'],a:3,
    e:`The labia majora drain to the superficial inguinal lymph nodes, then to the deep inguinal and external iliac nodes.<br><br>This pattern is important in vulval malignancy where inguinal lymphadenectomy may be required. Bilateral involvement is common with midline lesions; sentinel lymph node biopsy is increasingly used in early vulval cancer cases.<br><br>Internal iliac nodes (A) receive drainage from upper vagina and cervix; para-aortic nodes (B) receive ovarian and tubal drainage; obturator nodes (C) receive primarily from cervix and upper vagina.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterus is normally positioned in which orientation in most women?',o:['Retroverted and retroflexed','Retroverted and anteflexed','Anteverted and anteflexed','Anteverted and retroflexed'],a:2,
    e:`The uterus is normally anteverted and anteflexed in most women. Anteversion is the angle between cervical and vaginal axes; anteflexion is the angle between body and cervix.<br><br>About 80 percent of women have an anteverted-anteflexed uterus. Retroverted-retroflexed positions occur in 20 percent and are usually a normal variant influencing examination and instrumentation during procedures.<br><br>Retroverted and retroflexed (A) is a less common variant; midposition (B) is uncommon; horizontal (D) is not a normal anatomical description of uterine position.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which part of the uterus lies above the openings of the fallopian tubes?',o:['Cervix','Fundus','Body','Isthmus'],a:1,
    e:`The fundus is the dome-shaped uppermost part of the uterus, lying above the openings (cornua) of the fallopian tubes.<br><br>Below the fundus lie the body, isthmus and cervix. Fundal height is measured clinically in pregnancy from the symphysis pubis to estimate gestational age. The fundus is the usual site of placental implantation in most pregnancies.<br><br>Body (A) lies below the fundus, between the cornua and isthmus; isthmus (C) is the narrow segment between body and cervix; cervix (D) is the lowermost part projecting into the vagina.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterine artery usually arises from which artery?',o:['Internal iliac artery','External iliac artery','Inferior mesenteric artery','Common iliac artery'],a:0,
    e:`The uterine artery typically arises from the anterior division of the internal iliac (hypogastric) artery, passing medially in the broad ligament base toward the cervix.<br><br>It crosses above the ureter near the cervix (\'water under the bridge\') and reaches the uterus, anastomosing with the ovarian artery near the cornu. This anastomosis provides collateral supply if one vessel is ligated.<br><br>External iliac artery (B) supplies the lower limb; ovarian artery (C) arises directly from the aorta, not the source of uterine artery; internal pudendal artery (D) supplies the perineum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The ureter passes beneath which artery near the cervix in the female pelvis ("water under the bridge" relation)?',o:['Ovarian artery','Uterine artery','Internal pudendal artery','Vaginal artery'],a:1,
    e:`The ureter passes beneath the uterine artery near the cervix, classically described as \'water (ureter) under the bridge (uterine artery)\'. This occurs about 2 cm lateral to the cervix.<br><br>The relationship is critical during hysterectomy: the ureter is at risk of injury during clamping or ligation of the uterine artery. Identification of the ureter before uterine artery ligation is essential to avoid injury.<br><br>Ovarian artery (A) lies in the suspensory ligament, not near the cervix; internal pudendal artery (C) lies in the perineum; vaginal artery (D) supplies the vagina, not the cervical relationship.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which ligament of the uterus passes through the inguinal canal and ends in the labia majora?',o:['Cardinal ligament','Uterosacral ligament','Round ligament','Broad ligament'],a:2,
    e:`The round ligament passes through the inguinal canal and ends in the labium majus, a remnant of the gubernaculum from embryological development.<br><br>It originates from the uterine cornu, runs through the broad ligament, deep inguinal ring and inguinal canal. The round ligament helps maintain anteversion of the uterus; the artery of the round ligament accompanies it.<br><br>Broad ligament (A) is a peritoneal fold lateral to the uterus; cardinal ligament (B) extends from cervix to lateral pelvic wall; uterosacral ligament (D) extends from cervix to sacrum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The broad ligament is best described as which of the following anatomical structures?',o:['Fibromuscular cord connecting uterus to sacrum','Ligament connecting ovary to uterus','Fascia supporting cervix','Double layer of peritoneum extending from uterus to pelvic wall'],a:3,
    e:`The broad ligament is a double layer of peritoneum extending from the lateral border of the uterus to the lateral pelvic wall.<br><br>It contains the fallopian tube, round ligament, ovarian ligament, vessels and ureter. Three parts include mesosalpinx (encloses tube), mesovarium (encloses ovary) and mesometrium (the larger lower part of broad ligament).<br><br>Single layer of peritoneum (A) is incorrect; ligament from uterus to sacrum (B) describes the uterosacral ligament; muscular ligament around cervix (C) describes the cardinal ligament.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The part of the broad ligament that encloses the fallopian tube is called:',o:['Mesosalpinx','Mesometrium','Mesovarium','Suspensory ligament'],a:0,
    e:`The mesosalpinx is the part of the broad ligament that encloses the fallopian tube. It is the upper free fold and contains the tubal vessels and nerves.<br><br>The mesosalpinx is thin and translucent, allowing inspection of the fallopian tube during laparoscopy. Tubal procedures (sterilisation, salpingectomy, salpingostomy) involve careful handling of the mesosalpinx and its vascular supply.<br><br>Mesovarium (B) connects ovary to broad ligament; mesometrium (C) is the lower main part of broad ligament; mesoappendix (D) is unrelated, attaching the appendix to terminal ileum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The ligament that connects the ovary to the uterus is known as:',o:['Suspensory ligament of ovary','Round ligament','Uterosacral ligament','Ovarian ligament'],a:3,
    e:`The ovarian ligament connects the ovary to the uterus, running from the medial pole of the ovary to the lateral side of the uterine cornu, just below the tubal entry.<br><br>It is a remnant of the gubernaculum, continuous with the round ligament. The ovarian ligament carries no significant vessels, distinguishing it from the suspensory ligament which contains the ovarian vessels and lymphatics.<br><br>Round ligament (A) connects uterus to labium majus via inguinal canal; broad ligament (B) is a peritoneal fold; suspensory ligament (C) connects ovary to lateral pelvic wall.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The suspensory ligament of the ovary contains which important vascular structure?',o:['Uterine artery','Internal pudendal vessels','Ovarian vessels','Inferior epigastric vessels'],a:2,
    e:`The suspensory ligament of the ovary (infundibulopelvic ligament) contains the ovarian artery, ovarian vein and lymphatics, connecting lateral pole of ovary to lateral pelvic wall.<br><br>Surgically, the suspensory ligament is clamped and ligated during oophorectomy to control the ovarian vessels. The ureter lies close to the suspensory ligament at the pelvic brim and is at risk of injury.<br><br>Round ligament (A) contains the artery of round ligament; ureter (B) lies posterior to suspensory ligament, not within it; uterine artery (D) lies in the cardinal ligament near the cervix.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The main lymphatic drainage of the cervix is to which lymph nodes?',o:['Para-aortic nodes','Internal iliac nodes','Superficial inguinal nodes','Celiac nodes'],a:1,
    e:`The cervix drains primarily to the internal iliac (hypogastric) nodes, with secondary drainage to the obturator, external iliac, presacral and para-aortic nodes.<br><br>Pelvic lymphadenectomy in cervical cancer involves removal of internal iliac, external iliac, obturator and common iliac nodes. Para-aortic node involvement indicates more advanced disease and influences treatment planning.<br><br>Para-aortic nodes (A) receive primary drainage from ovaries and fallopian tubes; superficial inguinal nodes (C) drain vulva and lower vagina; superficial cervical nodes (D) drain head and neck, unrelated.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which nerve provides the main sensory innervation to the vulva?',o:['Pudendal nerve','Femoral nerve','Sciatic nerve','Obturator nerve'],a:0,
    e:`The pudendal nerve provides the main sensory innervation to the vulva. It arises from sacral nerve roots S2-S4 and reaches the perineum via the lesser sciatic foramen.<br><br>It also supplies the perineum, lower vagina and external anal sphincter. Pudendal nerve block at the ischial spine provides analgesia for second-stage labour, episiotomy repair and outlet forceps delivery procedures.<br><br>Femoral nerve (B) supplies anterior thigh; obturator nerve (C) supplies medial thigh and adductors; ilioinguinal nerve (D) supplies a small area of labium majus and mons pubis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The ovarian artery originates directly from which vessel?',o:['Internal iliac artery','Abdominal aorta','External iliac artery','Renal artery'],a:1,
    e:`The ovarian artery originates directly from the abdominal aorta, just below the renal arteries (around L2 vertebral level). The high origin reflects embryological descent of the ovary from upper abdomen.<br><br>The ovarian artery descends along the posterior abdominal wall, crosses the ureter at the pelvic brim, then enters the suspensory ligament to reach the ovary, anastomosing with the uterine artery.<br><br>Internal iliac artery (B) gives off the uterine artery, not the ovarian; external iliac artery (C) supplies lower limb; renal artery (D) supplies kidney, not ovary.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The venous drainage of the ovary on the right side usually drains into:',o:['Portal vein','Renal vein','Internal iliac vein','Inferior vena cava'],a:3,
    e:`The right ovarian vein drains directly into the inferior vena cava, at a slightly oblique angle below the right renal vein.<br><br>The direct drainage pattern reflects the embryological course of the right gonadal vein. The asymmetric drainage explains why ovarian vein thrombosis is more common on the right and why peripartum thrombosis often involves this side.<br><br>Right renal vein (A) is unrelated to ovarian drainage; portal vein (B) receives gut drainage, not gonadal; left renal vein (C) receives the left ovarian vein, not the right.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The venous drainage of the left ovarian vein usually drains into:',o:['Left renal vein','Splenic vein','Inferior vena cava','Internal iliac vein'],a:0,
    e:`The left ovarian vein drains into the left renal vein at a right angle, before joining the inferior vena cava through the renal vein.<br><br>The indirect right-angled entry creates higher venous pressure on the left. Pelvic congestion syndrome more often involves left-sided varicosities; left ovarian vein thrombosis is also more common in peripartum thrombosis cases.<br><br>Inferior vena cava (B) receives the right ovarian vein directly; portal vein (C) receives gut drainage; right renal vein (D) is unrelated to left ovarian drainage.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which structure forms the deepest peritoneal recess in the female pelvis?',o:['Vesicouterine pouch','Paravesical space','Rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas)','Retropubic space'],a:2,
    e:`The rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas) forms the deepest peritoneal recess in the female pelvis, lying between rectum and posterior wall of uterus and upper vagina.<br><br>The pouch is the most dependent peritoneal space, where free pelvic fluid, blood (haemoperitoneum) or pus tends to collect. Posterior colpotomy through the posterior fornix accesses this pouch for drainage.<br><br>Vesicouterine pouch (A) lies between bladder and uterus, shallower; paravesical fossa (B) is a small lateral space; pararectal fossa (D) is lateral to rectum, also shallower.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterosacral ligaments extend from the cervix to which structure?',o:['Pubic symphysis','Sacrum','Pelvic side wall','Coccyx'],a:1,
    e:`The uterosacral ligaments extend from the cervix posteriorly to the sacrum, attaching to the periosteum at the level of S2-S4.<br><br>They contain smooth muscle, fibrous tissue and the autonomic nerves of the pelvic plexus. The uterosacral ligaments are commonly involved in endometriosis and may be palpable as nodular tenderness on rectovaginal examination.<br><br>Pubic symphysis (A) lies anteriorly, not the uterosacral attachment; pubic bone (C) lies anteriorly; ischial spine (D) is the attachment site for the cardinal ligament near the cervix.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The cardinal (Mackenrodt) ligaments are important because they:',o:['Contain uterine vessels and support cervix','Maintain uterine anteversion','Attach ovary to uterus','Form peritoneal folds'],a:0,
    e:`The cardinal (Mackenrodt) ligaments contain the uterine vessels and provide major support to the cervix, extending from the lateral aspects of the cervix to lateral pelvic wall.<br><br>They are the strongest mechanical support of the uterus, working with uterosacral and pubocervical ligaments. The ureter passes beneath the uterine artery within the cardinal ligament near the cervix during surgery.<br><br>Connect uterus to sacrum (B) describes uterosacral ligaments; connect ovary to pelvic wall (C) describes the suspensory ligament; pass through inguinal canal (D) describes the round ligament.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The main structural support preventing uterine prolapse is provided by:',o:['Round ligament','Broad ligament','Pelvic diaphragm and cardinal ligaments','Suspensory ligament'],a:2,
    e:`The main structural support preventing uterine prolapse is provided by the pelvic diaphragm and cardinal ligaments together.<br><br>The pelvic floor (levator ani) provides primary muscular support; the cardinal and uterosacral ligaments provide ligamentous support. Damage from childbirth or menopausal laxity leads to pelvic organ prolapse requiring surgical repair of both components.<br><br>Round ligament alone (A) maintains anteversion but does not prevent prolapse; broad ligament alone (B) is peritoneal, not a true support; ovarian ligament alone (D) is not a uterine support.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Urogynaecology)</em>`},
    {q:'The fallopian tube opens into the uterine cavity at which part?',o:['Infundibulum','Ampulla','Isthmus','Intramural part'],a:3,
    e:`The fallopian tube opens into the uterine cavity at the intramural (interstitial) part, the narrowest segment passing through the cornu with a lumen of about 1 mm.<br><br>The tube has four parts: intramural, isthmus, ampulla and infundibulum (with fimbriae). The intramural part is the most common site of cornual ectopic pregnancy, which carries higher rupture risk than other sites.<br><br>Ampulla (A) is the wide middle part where fertilisation occurs; isthmus (B) is the narrow part adjacent to the uterus; infundibulum (C) is the funnel-shaped distal end with fimbriae.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Fertilization most commonly occurs in which part of the fallopian tube?',o:['Infundibulum','Isthmus','Ampulla','Interstitial part'],a:2,
    e:`Fertilisation most commonly occurs in the ampulla of the fallopian tube, the wide thin-walled longest segment where ovum and sperm meet shortly after ovulation.<br><br>The ampulla\'s wide lumen and ciliated epithelium facilitate ovum capture and transport. Ectopic pregnancy is most common in the ampulla (~70 percent), with lower rupture risk than isthmic or cornual ectopics due to larger lumen.<br><br>Isthmus (A) is the narrow part where the tube enters the uterine wall; intramural part (B) is the smallest segment; infundibulum (D) is the funnel-shaped distal end with fimbriae.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The fimbriae of the fallopian tube are located at the:',o:['Infundibulum','Isthmus','Ampulla','Intramural part'],a:0,
    e:`The fimbriae of the fallopian tube are located at the infundibulum, the funnel-shaped distal end opening into the peritoneal cavity near the ovary.<br><br>The fimbriae are finger-like projections that capture the released ovum at ovulation. The longest fimbria (fimbria ovarica) extends to and is attached to the ovary, helping guide the ovum into the tube lumen.<br><br>Ampulla (B) is the wide middle part where fertilisation occurs; intramural part (C) passes through the uterine wall; isthmus (D) is the narrow part adjacent to the uterus.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The vaginal arterial supply is mainly derived from:',o:['Renal artery','Internal pudendal and vaginal arteries','Ovarian artery','Inferior mesenteric artery'],a:1,
    e:`The vaginal arterial supply is derived mainly from the internal pudendal and vaginal arteries. The vaginal artery is usually a branch of the internal iliac artery.<br><br>Additional supply comes from the middle rectal artery and the cervico-vaginal branch of the uterine artery, forming a rich anastomotic network ensuring good vascular supply to the vagina throughout its length.<br><br>Femoral artery alone (A) supplies lower limb; ovarian artery (C) supplies ovary and tube; superior rectal artery (D) supplies upper rectum, not vagina.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The lymphatic drainage of the upper vagina is mainly to:',o:['Superficial inguinal nodes','Celiac nodes','Para-aortic nodes','Internal iliac nodes'],a:3,
    e:`The upper vagina drains mainly to the internal iliac (hypogastric) lymph nodes, similar to the cervix and uterus.<br><br>The vagina has a dual lymphatic drainage based on level: upper vagina drains with the cervix to internal iliac nodes; lower vagina drains with the vulva to superficial inguinal nodes; middle vagina drains to both.<br><br>Para-aortic nodes (A) receive primary drainage from ovaries and tubes; superficial inguinal nodes (B) drain lower vagina and vulva; deep cervical nodes (C) drain head and neck.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The lymphatic drainage of the lower vagina is mainly to:',o:['Para-aortic nodes','Superficial inguinal nodes','External iliac nodes','Internal iliac nodes'],a:1,
    e:`The lower vagina drains mainly to the superficial inguinal lymph nodes, similar to the vulva, then to the deep inguinal and external iliac nodes.<br><br>This pattern is important in vaginal cancer staging: lower vaginal lesions require inguinal lymph node assessment, while upper vaginal lesions are staged with pelvic node imaging. The middle vagina has dual drainage.<br><br>Internal iliac nodes (A) receive drainage from upper vagina and cervix; para-aortic nodes (C) receive primary drainage from ovaries and tubes; obturator nodes (D) receive from cervix mainly.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which structure separates the vagina from the rectum?',o:['Perineal body','Pelvic fascia','Broad ligament','Rectovaginal septum'],a:3,
    e:`The rectovaginal septum (Denonvilliers fascia in males) separates the vagina from the rectum. It is a fibrous tissue layer between posterior vaginal wall and anterior rectal wall.<br><br>The septum is important in pelvic floor surgery and rectocele repair. It is also a site of deep infiltrating endometriosis. The Pouch of Douglas lies above the septum, accessible via posterior colpotomy for drainage.<br><br>Broad ligament (A) is lateral, not posterior; perineal body (B) lies between vagina and anus inferiorly; pelvic diaphragm (C) supports the pelvic organs from below.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'During radical hysterectomy for carcinoma cervix, the surgeon must carefully dissect the uterine artery close to its origin from the internal iliac artery. At the level of the cervix the ureter passes inferior to the uterine artery approximately 1-2 cm lateral to the cervix before entering the bladder. Injury to this structure during ligation of the uterine artery is a well-recognized complication of pelvic surgery. Which structure is most likely to be injured in this scenario?',o:['Obturator nerve','External iliac vein','Ureter','Pudendal nerve'],a:2,
    e:`During radical hysterectomy, the surgeon must carefully identify the ureter to avoid injury, as the ureter passes beneath the uterine artery near the cervix (\'water under the bridge\').<br><br>The ureter is also at risk near the suspensory ligament of the ovary at the pelvic brim and during dissection of vesicouterine and rectovaginal spaces. Pre-operative imaging and intraoperative identification reduce injury risk significantly.<br><br>Bladder (A) is identified but is anterior; rectum (B) lies posteriorly with less direct risk; common iliac vein (D) is encountered during lymphadenectomy but not principal concern.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A multiparous woman with long-standing uterine prolapse undergoes pelvic floor repair. The gynecologist explains that the most significant fibrous support of the cervix and upper vagina is provided by a pair of ligaments extending from the cervix and lateral vaginal fornices to the lateral pelvic wall and containing uterine vessels. Which ligament is being described?',o:['Cardinal ligament','Round ligament','Uterosacral ligament','Ovarian ligament'],a:0,
    e:`The cardinal ligament is the most important pelvic support involved in long-standing uterine prolapse, providing major support to the cervix and upper vagina.<br><br>The cardinal (Mackenrodt) ligament extends from the cervix to the lateral pelvic wall and contains uterine vessels. Repair of prolapse often involves shortening or repositioning the cardinal ligaments along with pelvic floor reconstruction surgery.<br><br>Round ligament (B) maintains anteversion but does not prevent prolapse; broad ligament (C) is peritoneal, not a true support; ovarian ligament (D) attaches ovary to uterus, not a uterine support.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Urogynaecology)</em>`},
    {q:'During posterior colpotomy, surgical access to drain pelvic abscess is obtained through the posterior vaginal fornix into the deepest peritoneal recess in the female pelvis located between the posterior wall of uterus and anterior surface of rectum. This anatomical space is known as:',o:['Vesicouterine pouch','Paravesical space','Retropubic space','Rectouterine pouch'],a:3,
    e:`Posterior colpotomy provides surgical access to the rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas) for drainage of pelvic abscess. The incision is made through the posterior fornix of the vagina.<br><br>The pouch is the most dependent peritoneal space where pus collects; transvaginal access through the posterior fornix avoids abdominal entry. The procedure is also used to drain endometriotic cysts and pelvic haematomas effectively.<br><br>Vesicouterine pouch (A) lies between bladder and uterus, accessed differently; broad ligament (B) is lateral; suspensory ligament (C) is the connection of ovary to pelvic wall.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The ovarian artery reaches the ovary through which ligament?',o:['Ovarian ligament','Broad ligament','Suspensory ligament of ovary','Round ligament'],a:2,
    e:`The ovarian artery reaches the ovary through the suspensory ligament of the ovary (infundibulopelvic ligament).<br><br>The ligament connects the lateral pole of the ovary to the lateral pelvic wall above the pelvic brim and contains the ovarian artery, vein and lymphatics. Surgically, this ligament is clamped and ligated during oophorectomy procedures.<br><br>Round ligament (A) connects uterus to labium majus via inguinal canal; ovarian ligament (B) connects ovary to uterus; broad ligament (D) is a peritoneal fold, not the route of ovarian vessels.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic diaphragm is mainly formed by which muscles?',o:['Levator ani and coccygeus','Obturator internus and piriformis','Rectus abdominis and transversus','Psoas major and iliacus'],a:0,
    e:`The pelvic diaphragm is mainly formed by the levator ani and coccygeus muscles, providing primary muscular support of pelvic organs and resisting downward pressure.<br><br>Levator ani has three components: pubococcygeus, puborectalis and iliococcygeus. The pelvic diaphragm has openings for urethra, vagina and rectum. Damage during childbirth or chronic strain leads to pelvic organ prolapse and incontinence.<br><br>Iliopsoas (B) is a hip flexor, not pelvic floor; piriformis (C) lies on the posterior pelvic wall; obturator internus (D) lies on the lateral pelvic wall, not part of pelvic diaphragm.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which muscle forms the main part of levator ani responsible for pelvic organ support?',o:['Iliococcygeus','Pubococcygeus','Puborectalis','Coccygeus'],a:1,
    e:`Pubococcygeus is the main part of levator ani responsible for pelvic organ support. It arises from the body of the pubic bone, passes around the urethra, vagina and rectum, and inserts into the coccyx.<br><br>The pubococcygeus contains specific portions: puboprostaticus (men), pubovaginalis (women) and puborectalis. Damage during vaginal delivery contributes to pelvic organ prolapse and stress urinary incontinence in women.<br><br>Piriformis (A) is part of the lateral pelvic wall; obturator internus (C) lies on the lateral pelvic wall; coccygeus (D) is part of pelvic diaphragm but not the main support.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The nerve supply to the ovary mainly arises from:',o:['Pudendal nerve','Femoral nerve','Ovarian plexus from aortic plexus','Sacral plexus'],a:2,
    e:`The nerve supply to the ovary mainly arises from the ovarian plexus from the aortic plexus, with both sympathetic (T10-L1) and parasympathetic fibres travelling along the ovarian artery.<br><br>The ovarian plexus is part of the renal/aortic plexus, reflecting embryological origin. This is why ovarian pathology can refer pain to the umbilical area (T10) and explains the dermatomal pattern of ovarian pain.<br><br>Pudendal nerve (A) supplies vulva and perineum; sacral plexus (B) supplies pelvic floor; uterine plexus (D) supplies uterus, not the ovary.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterus is divided into body and cervix at which anatomical landmark?',o:['Fundus','Isthmus','Internal os','External os'],a:1,
    e:`The uterus is divided into body and cervix at the isthmus, the narrow constriction between the two parts at the level of the internal os.<br><br>The isthmus is about 0.5 to 1 cm long in the non-pregnant uterus and forms the lower uterine segment in late pregnancy. The lower segment is the site of incision in caesarean section, being thinner and more accessible.<br><br>Fundus (A) is the dome-shaped upper part above the cornua; cornu (C) is the upper lateral angle where tube enters; external os (D) is the lower opening of the cervix into vagina.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which structure forms the anterior boundary of the vesicouterine pouch?',o:['Bladder','Rectum','Cervix','Ovary'],a:0,
    e:`The bladder forms the anterior boundary of the vesicouterine pouch, the peritoneal recess between the bladder posteriorly and the anterior wall of the uterus.<br><br>The vesicouterine pouch is a shallow space (compared to Pouch of Douglas posteriorly). During caesarean section, the bladder is reflected downward to expose the lower uterine segment for incision and delivery.<br><br>Rectum (B) lies posteriorly, forming the posterior boundary of the rectouterine pouch; cervix (C) lies posteriorly to the bladder; anterior abdominal wall (D) lies further anterior.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The hymen is derived embryologically from which structure?',o:['Müllerian duct','Genital ridge','Mesonephric duct','Urogenital sinus'],a:3,
    e:`The hymen is derived embryologically from the urogenital sinus. It forms at the junction between the sinovaginal bulbs (urogenital sinus origin) and the lower end of the developing vagina.<br><br>The hymen is a membrane that partially closes the vaginal opening. Imperforate hymen presents at puberty with primary amenorrhoea, cyclical pelvic pain and haematocolpos. Treatment is hymenotomy with cruciate incision.<br><br>Mesonephric duct (A) gives rise to male reproductive structures; paramesonephric duct (B) forms upper vagina, uterus and tubes; cloaca (C) gives rise to bladder, urethra and rectum.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology; Chapter: Urogenital System)</em>`},
    {q:'During a difficult abdominal hysterectomy in a woman with large fibroids, the surgeon encounters heavy bleeding from vessels running within the cardinal ligament close to the cervix. These vessels must be carefully ligated to control hemorrhage. Which artery is primarily responsible for this bleeding?',o:['Uterine artery','Internal pudendal artery','Ovarian artery','Inferior epigastric artery'],a:0,
    e:`During abdominal hysterectomy with large fibroids, the uterine artery is the most likely vessel encountered and ligated near the lateral border of the uterus at the cervix level.<br><br>The uterine artery is clamped, cut and ligated as a key step. The relationship of the ureter passing beneath the uterine artery (\'water under the bridge\') makes ureteric injury a major risk requiring careful identification before ligation.<br><br>Ovarian artery (B) is dealt with separately at the suspensory ligament; superior rectal artery (C) is unrelated; inferior epigastric artery (D) is in the abdominal wall, not pelvic.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A gynecologic oncologist evaluating carcinoma of the cervix explains that lymphatic spread most commonly occurs first to the internal iliac and obturator lymph nodes because these nodes drain the cervix through lymphatic channels running along the uterine vessels within the cardinal ligament. Which lymph nodes are most commonly involved first in carcinoma cervix?',o:['Para-aortic nodes','Inguinal nodes','Internal iliac nodes','Celiac nodes'],a:2,
    e:`Cervical carcinoma spreads to the internal iliac (hypogastric) nodes as the primary route, with secondary spread to obturator, external iliac and presacral nodes.<br><br>Pelvic lymphadenectomy in cervical cancer involves removal of these node groups. Para-aortic node involvement indicates more advanced disease (Stage IIIC2) and influences treatment planning, including extended-field radiotherapy.<br><br>Para-aortic nodes (A) receive primary drainage from ovaries and tubes; superficial inguinal nodes (B) drain vulva; deep cervical nodes (D) drain head and neck, unrelated to cervix.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Gynaecological oncology)</em>`},
    {q:'During pelvic examination the cervix projects into the vagina forming recesses known as fornices. Which fornix is the deepest and clinically important for procedures like culdocentesis?',o:['Anterior fornix','Left lateral fornix','Right lateral fornix','Posterior fornix'],a:3,
    e:`On pelvic examination, the cervix projects into the vagina forming the posterior fornix as the deepest of the four vaginal recesses around the cervix.<br><br>The fornices are anterior, posterior, and two lateral. The posterior fornix is the deepest because the cervix projects more anteriorly. Posterior colpotomy through the posterior fornix accesses the Pouch of Douglas for drainage.<br><br>Anterior fornix (A) is shallower, adjacent to the bladder; lateral fornix (B) lies on either side at the cervix; vesical fornix (C) is not an anatomical term in standard use.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The perineal body lies between which two structures?',o:['Urethra and clitoris','Vagina and anus','Cervix and vagina','Bladder and uterus'],a:1,
    e:`The perineal body lies between the vagina and the anus, a fibromuscular pyramidal structure central to perineal support and continence.<br><br>It serves as the central point of attachment for several muscles: bulbospongiosus, superficial and deep transverse perineal, levator ani and external anal sphincter. Damage during vaginal delivery contributes to pelvic floor dysfunction and incontinence.<br><br>Vagina and urethra (A) lie anteriorly to the perineal body; bladder and rectum (C) are pelvic structures, not perineal; clitoris and urethra (D) lie anteriorly.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which ligament primarily maintains uterine anteversion?',o:['Uterosacral ligament','Broad ligament','Ovarian ligament','Round ligament'],a:3,
    e:`The round ligament primarily maintains uterine anteversion. It pulls the fundus forward toward the anterior abdominal wall via its passage through the inguinal canal.<br><br>The round ligament is a remnant of the gubernaculum. It is not a major support against prolapse (which is provided by pelvic diaphragm and cardinal ligaments) but contributes to maintaining the normal anteverted uterine position.<br><br>Broad ligament (A) is peritoneal, not a true positional support; cardinal ligament (B) supports cervix; uterosacral ligament (C) attaches cervix to sacrum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The mesovarium connects the ovary to which structure?',o:['Broad ligament','Fallopian tube','Uterus','Pelvic wall'],a:0,
    e:`The mesovarium connects the ovary to the broad ligament. It is a short fold of peritoneum extending from the posterior layer of the broad ligament to the anterior surface of the ovary.<br><br>The mesovarium contains the ovarian vessels reaching the ovary from the suspensory ligament. The ovarian surface itself is not covered by peritoneum, allowing ovum release at ovulation through the surface epithelium.<br><br>Lateral pelvic wall (B) is connected via the suspensory ligament; uterus (C) is connected via the ovarian ligament; bladder (D) is unrelated to ovarian attachment.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The ampulla of the fallopian tube is characterized by:',o:['Narrow lumen and thick muscular wall','Wide lumen and thin wall','No mucosal folds','Absence of cilia'],a:1,
    e:`The ampulla of the fallopian tube is characterised by a wide lumen and a thin wall. It is the longest segment (about 5 to 7 cm) and the usual site of fertilisation.<br><br>The wide thin-walled ampulla allows easy ovum-sperm meeting and embryonic development before transport to the uterus. Ectopic pregnancy is most common in the ampulla (~70 percent), with lower rupture risk than other sites.<br><br>Narrow lumen and thick wall (A) describes the isthmus; uniform diameter (C) is not a tubal feature; muscular thickening with no lumen (D) is not a fallopian tube feature.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The isthmus of the fallopian tube is characterized by:',o:['Numerous fimbriae','Wide lumen','Thick muscular wall and narrow lumen','Direct communication with ovary'],a:2,
    e:`The isthmus of the fallopian tube is characterised by a thick muscular wall and narrow lumen. It is the segment immediately lateral to the uterine cornu, about 2 to 3 cm long.<br><br>The narrow lumen and thick wall make the isthmus a common site of tubal sterilisation procedures (ligation, clipping, division). It is also a relatively common site of ectopic pregnancy with higher rupture risk.<br><br>Wide lumen and thin wall (A) describes the ampulla; fimbriated end (B) is the infundibulum; lined with non-ciliated epithelium (D) is incorrect (tube is ciliated throughout).<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The blood supply of the fallopian tube is derived from:',o:['Both uterine and ovarian arteries','Only ovarian artery','Only uterine artery','Internal pudendal artery'],a:0,
    e:`The blood supply of the fallopian tube is derived from both uterine and ovarian arteries, forming an anastomotic arcade running through the mesosalpinx along the tube.<br><br>The medial part is supplied mainly by tubal branches of the uterine artery, the lateral part by branches of the ovarian artery. The anastomosis ensures good vascular supply and is preserved during fertility-sparing tubal surgery.<br><br>Internal pudendal artery alone (B) supplies perineum, not tube; ovarian artery alone (C) supplies only the lateral tube; vaginal artery (D) supplies vagina, not tube.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The nerve supply to the vulva is primarily via:',o:['Iliohypogastric nerve','Femoral nerve','Obturator nerve','Pudendal nerve'],a:3,
    e:`The nerve supply to the vulva is primarily via the pudendal nerve, arising from sacral nerve roots S2-S4 and reaching the perineum via the lesser sciatic foramen near the ischial spine.<br><br>Additional contributions come from the ilioinguinal nerve (anterior labium majus) and genitofemoral nerve. Pudendal nerve block at the ischial spine provides analgesia for perineal procedures, second-stage labour and outlet forceps delivery.<br><br>Femoral nerve (A) supplies anterior thigh, not vulva; obturator nerve (B) supplies medial thigh; sciatic nerve (C) supplies lower limb, not vulva.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'A surgeon performing radical surgery for advanced cervical carcinoma must identify and preserve the ureter while ligating the uterine artery near the cervix. The ureter runs inferior to the uterine artery approximately 1-2 cm lateral to the cervix before entering the bladder. This anatomical relationship is classically described by which phrase used in pelvic surgery?',o:['Bridge over water','River below ligament','Water under the bridge','Vein beneath artery'],a:2,
    e:`During radical surgery for advanced cervical carcinoma, the relationship described as \'water under the bridge\' refers to the ureter passing beneath the uterine artery near the cervix.<br><br>This is the most critical surgical landmark in pelvic surgery, occurring about 2 cm lateral to the cervix at the cervical isthmus level. The ureter must be identified before uterine artery ligation to avoid injury during dissection.<br><br>Ovarian artery over ureter (A) is at pelvic brim level; vaginal artery over rectum (B) is not the standard description; round ligament over inguinal canal (D) describes the ligament course.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A gynecologist explaining pelvic anatomy to residents describes the broad ligament as a double fold of peritoneum extending from the lateral margins of the uterus to the pelvic walls and floor. Within this structure run the uterine tubes, round ligaments, ovarian ligaments, vessels, and nerves supplying the uterus and adnexa. Which structure is NOT a component of the broad ligament?',o:['Mesosalpinx','Uterosacral ligament','Mesometrium','Mesovarium'],a:1,
    e:`The uterosacral ligament is the structure most commonly involved in deep infiltrating endometriosis and palpable as nodular tenderness on rectovaginal examination.<br><br>It extends from the cervix posteriorly to the sacrum at S2-S4 level and contains autonomic nerves of the pelvic plexus. Endometriotic deposits in this ligament cause cyclical dyspareunia and chronic pelvic pain in patients.<br><br>Cardinal ligament (A) supports the cervix laterally; round ligament (C) maintains anteversion; broad ligament (D) is a peritoneal fold, not a usual deep endometriosis site.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The ovarian ligament connects the ovary to which part of the uterus?',o:['Uterine horn','Body','Cervix','Fundus'],a:0,
    e:`The ovarian ligament connects the medial pole of the ovary to the uterine horn (cornu), just below the entry of the fallopian tube into the uterus.<br><br>It is a remnant of the gubernaculum, continuous with the round ligament. The ovarian ligament carries no significant vessels, distinguishing it from the suspensory ligament which contains the ovarian vessels and lymphatics.<br><br>Cervix (B) is connected to lateral pelvic wall by cardinal ligament; lateral pelvic wall (C) is connected by suspensory ligament; vagina (D) is connected to surrounding tissues, not ovary directly.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The lymphatic drainage of the uterine fundus following the round ligament may reach which lymph nodes?',o:['External iliac nodes','Internal iliac nodes','Para-aortic nodes','Superficial inguinal nodes'],a:3,
    e:`The uterine fundus has an additional lymphatic drainage pathway following the round ligament through the inguinal canal to the superficial inguinal nodes.<br><br>This unusual route reflects the round ligament being a gubernaculum remnant. Most uterine drainage goes to internal iliac and para-aortic nodes; the round ligament pathway is minor but explains rare inguinal metastases from uterine cancer.<br><br>Para-aortic nodes (A) receive primary drainage from ovaries and tubes; internal iliac nodes (B) drain cervix and upper vagina; deep cervical nodes (C) drain head and neck only.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic fascia supporting the cervix and vagina is mainly known as:',o:['Transversalis fascia','Endopelvic fascia','Scarpa fascia','Camper fascia'],a:1,
    e:`The pelvic fascia supporting the cervix and vagina is mainly known as the endopelvic fascia, a connective tissue framework continuous throughout the pelvis.<br><br>The endopelvic fascia condenses to form the cardinal ligaments laterally, uterosacral ligaments posteriorly and pubocervical ligaments anteriorly. Damage from childbirth or chronic strain leads to pelvic organ prolapse requiring surgical reconstruction.<br><br>Pelvic peritoneum (A) is a serous membrane, not a support; transversalis fascia (C) lies in the abdominal wall; Camper\'s fascia (D) is in the abdominal wall superficial layer.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The ovary is attached to the lateral pelvic wall by which ligament?',o:['Broad ligament','Round ligament','Suspensory ligament of ovary','Uterosacral ligament'],a:2,
    e:`The ovary is attached to the lateral pelvic wall by the suspensory ligament of the ovary (infundibulopelvic ligament), which contains the ovarian vessels.<br><br>The ligament passes from the lateral pole of the ovary over the pelvic brim to the lateral pelvic wall. The ureter lies close at the pelvic brim and is at risk during oophorectomy when this ligament is clamped.<br><br>Round ligament (A) connects uterus to labium majus; ovarian ligament (B) connects ovary to uterus; broad ligament (D) is a peritoneal fold containing other structures.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which artery accompanies the round ligament through the inguinal canal?',o:['Ovarian artery','Uterine artery','Inferior epigastric artery','Artery of round ligament'],a:3,
    e:`The artery of the round ligament (Sampson\'s artery) accompanies the round ligament through the inguinal canal. It is a branch of the inferior epigastric artery.<br><br>The artery is small but clinically relevant: it can be a source of bleeding during round ligament division in laparoscopic procedures and inguinal hernia repair. It anastomoses with branches from the uterine artery within the broad ligament.<br><br>Uterine artery (A) supplies uterus mainly; ovarian artery (B) supplies ovary and tube; internal pudendal artery (C) supplies perineum, not the round ligament.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'During laparoscopic exploration for suspected ectopic pregnancy, the surgeon observes a dilated segment of the fallopian tube with extensive mucosal folds where fertilization most commonly occurs. Which part of the tube is most likely involved in this scenario?',o:['Isthmus','Infundibulum','Ampulla','Intramural part'],a:2,
    e:`The ampulla is the most common site of ectopic pregnancy on laparoscopic exploration, accounting for about 70 percent of tubal ectopic pregnancies.<br><br>The ampulla\'s wide thin-walled lumen accommodates implantation but eventually outgrows blood supply, leading to tubal abortion or rupture. Lower rupture risk than isthmic or cornual ectopics due to greater distensibility of the ampullary wall.<br><br>Isthmus (A) accounts for about 12 percent with higher rupture risk; intramural part (B) accounts for 2 percent (cornual); fimbrial end (D) accounts for about 5 percent.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'In a woman undergoing posterior colpotomy for drainage of pelvic abscess, the surgeon enters the peritoneal cavity through the posterior vaginal fornix into the rectouterine pouch, which is the most dependent part of the female peritoneal cavity in the erect position. Which anatomical structures bound this space anteriorly?',o:['Uterus and posterior vaginal wall','Bladder and urethra','Rectum and anal canal','Pelvic diaphragm'],a:0,
    e:`Posterior colpotomy for drainage of pelvic abscess provides access to the rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas) lying between the uterus and posterior vaginal wall.<br><br>The pouch is the most dependent peritoneal space where pus collects. Transvaginal access through the posterior fornix avoids abdominal entry. The procedure is also used to drain endometriotic cysts and pelvic haematomas effectively.<br><br>Bladder and uterus (B) define the vesicouterine pouch, accessed differently; uterus and broad ligament (C) is not the abscess site; rectum and vagina (D) is the rectovaginal septum area.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with carcinoma of the vulva most commonly shows early metastasis to which lymph nodes because the lymphatics from the labia majora drain primarily into these nodes before spreading to deeper pelvic nodes?',o:['Para-aortic nodes','Superficial inguinal nodes','Internal iliac nodes','External iliac nodes'],a:1,
    e:`Carcinoma of the vulva most commonly shows early metastasis to the superficial inguinal lymph nodes, then to the deep inguinal and external iliac nodes.<br><br>Inguinal lymphadenectomy or sentinel lymph node biopsy is part of vulval cancer staging and treatment. Bilateral inguinal involvement is common with midline lesions or lesions crossing the midline of the vulva.<br><br>Internal iliac nodes (A) drain upper vagina and cervix; para-aortic nodes (C) drain ovaries and tubes; deep cervical nodes (D) drain head and neck, unrelated to vulva.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The bony pelvis is formed by which of the following bones?',o:['Ilium and sacrum only','Two femurs and sacrum','Two hip bones, sacrum and coccyx','Pubis and ischium only'],a:2,
    e:`The bony pelvis is formed by two hip bones (innominate bones), the sacrum and the coccyx. Each hip bone consists of fused ilium, ischium and pubis.<br><br>The hip bones meet anteriorly at the pubic symphysis and posteriorly with the sacrum at the sacroiliac joints. The pelvis is divided into greater (false) pelvis above and lesser (true) pelvis below the pelvic brim.<br><br>Two hip bones only (A) excludes sacrum and coccyx; sacrum and lumbar vertebrae (B) is incorrect; coccyx and ischium (D) is partial and excludes other components.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic inlet is bounded posteriorly by which structure?',o:['Sacral promontory','Pubic symphysis','Ischial tuberosity','Coccyx'],a:0,
    e:`The pelvic inlet is bounded posteriorly by the sacral promontory, the prominent anterior margin of the first sacral vertebra (S1).<br><br>The pelvic inlet (brim) is bounded anteriorly by the pubic symphysis, laterally by the iliopectineal lines and posteriorly by the sacral promontory. The shape of the pelvic inlet is critical for fetal head engagement and labour progress.<br><br>Pubic symphysis (B) bounds the inlet anteriorly; ischial tuberosity (C) is part of the pelvic outlet; iliac crest (D) is the upper border of the iliac bone, not pelvic inlet.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic outlet is bounded anteriorly by:',o:['Sacrum','Pubic symphysis','Ischial spine','Iliac crest'],a:1,
    e:`The pelvic outlet is bounded anteriorly by the pubic symphysis (specifically the lower border of the symphysis at the inferior pubic angle).<br><br>The outlet is bounded posteriorly by the tip of the coccyx, laterally by the ischial tuberosities and the sacrotuberous ligaments. The outlet shape is important for fetal head delivery; outlet contraction can cause obstructed labour at this stage.<br><br>Sacral promontory (A) is part of the pelvic inlet posteriorly; ischial spine (C) is at the level of the mid-pelvis; iliac crest (D) is at the false pelvis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The obstetric conjugate is the distance between:',o:['Iliac crest and pubic symphysis','Sacral promontory and upper border of pubic symphysis','Sacral promontory and lower border of pubic symphysis','Sacral promontory and pubic symphysis (inner surface)'],a:3,
    e:`The obstetric conjugate is the distance between the sacral promontory and the inner surface of the pubic symphysis (inner aspect of the upper border).<br><br>It is the shortest anteroposterior diameter of the pelvic inlet through which the fetal head must pass, normally about 11 cm. It cannot be measured directly clinically but is estimated from the diagonal conjugate (subtract 1.5 to 2 cm).<br><br>Pubic symphysis to ischial tuberosity (A) is the outlet AP; sacrum to ischial tuberosity (B) is not an obstetric conjugate; sacral promontory to coccyx (C) is anteroposterior of inlet to outlet.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which pelvic diameter is most important for engagement of the fetal head?',o:['Diagonal conjugate','Obstetric conjugate','True conjugate','Transverse diameter'],a:1,
    e:`The obstetric conjugate is the most important pelvic diameter for engagement of the fetal head, the shortest anteroposterior dimension of the pelvic inlet at about 11 cm.<br><br>Engagement occurs when the biparietal diameter passes through this plane. If the obstetric conjugate is contracted (less than 10 cm), the fetal head cannot engage, leading to cephalopelvic disproportion and obstructed labour requiring caesarean section.<br><br>Diagonal conjugate (A) is clinically measurable but slightly larger; transverse diameter (C) of inlet is wider but not the limiting factor; oblique diameter (D) is not standard for engagement.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The diagonal conjugate is measured clinically from the sacral promontory to which landmark?',o:['Upper border of pubic symphysis','Ischial spine','Lower border of pubic symphysis','Coccyx'],a:2,
    e:`The diagonal conjugate is measured clinically from the sacral promontory to the lower border of the pubic symphysis using the examining fingers.<br><br>It is normally 12.5 cm or more. The obstetric conjugate is then estimated by subtracting 1.5 to 2 cm. If the sacral promontory cannot be reached on examination, the pelvis is considered adequate for normal delivery.<br><br>Upper border of pubic symphysis (A) is the obstetric conjugate; iliac crest (B) is irrelevant; ischial spine (D) is the level for measuring station of presenting part.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic floor is mainly formed by:',o:['Obturator internus','Piriformis','Gluteus maximus','Levator ani and coccygeus'],a:3,
    e:`The pelvic floor is mainly formed by the levator ani and coccygeus muscles, together forming the pelvic diaphragm.<br><br>Levator ani has three components: pubococcygeus, puborectalis and iliococcygeus. The pelvic floor has openings for urethra, vagina and rectum and provides primary support to pelvic organs. Damage from childbirth leads to pelvic organ prolapse.<br><br>Iliopsoas (A) is a hip flexor, not pelvic floor; piriformis (B) lies on the posterior pelvic wall; obturator internus (C) lies on the lateral pelvic wall.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which muscle is NOT part of levator ani?',o:['Piriformis','Iliococcygeus','Puborectalis','Pubococcygeus'],a:0,
    e:`Piriformis is NOT part of levator ani. It is a separate muscle that forms part of the posterior pelvic wall, exiting the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen to insert on the greater trochanter.<br><br>Levator ani has three components: pubococcygeus, puborectalis and iliococcygeus. Coccygeus is sometimes included as a fourth component or considered separate but adjacent. Piriformis lies above and behind levator ani.<br><br>Pubococcygeus (B) is the main part of levator ani; puborectalis (C) maintains the anorectal angle; iliococcygeus (D) is the most lateral and posterior part of levator ani.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The puborectalis muscle is important because it:',o:['Supports bladder','Maintains anorectal angle','Controls urethra','Stabilizes sacrum'],a:1,
    e:`The puborectalis muscle is important because it maintains the anorectal angle (about 90 degrees), critical for faecal continence.<br><br>Puborectalis loops around the anorectal junction, pulling it forward. During defecation, the muscle relaxes, straightening the angle. Damage from childbirth or chronic straining causes loss of continence and pelvic floor dysfunction in affected patients.<br><br>Supports vagina (A) is provided by levator ani as a whole; closes urethra (C) is by sphincter urethrae; supports the bladder (D) is by levator ani and pubocervical fascia mainly.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The rectouterine pouch lies between which structures?',o:['Uterus and rectum','Bladder and uterus','Rectum and vagina','Bladder and vagina'],a:0,
    e:`The rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas) lies between the uterus anteriorly and the rectum posteriorly. It is the deepest peritoneal recess in the female pelvis.<br><br>The pouch is the most dependent peritoneal space where free pelvic fluid, blood (haemoperitoneum) or pus tends to collect. Posterior colpotomy through the posterior fornix accesses this pouch for drainage of pelvic abscess or fluid collections.<br><br>Bladder and uterus (B) define the vesicouterine pouch; ovary and rectum (C) is not a defined pouch; bladder and rectum (D) defines the rectovesical pouch in males.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'In males, the rectovesical pouch lies between:',o:['Seminal vesicle and rectum','Rectum and prostate','Prostate and bladder','Bladder and rectum'],a:3,
    e:`In males, the rectovesical pouch lies between the bladder anteriorly and the rectum posteriorly. It is the equivalent of the female rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas).<br><br>The rectovesical pouch is the deepest peritoneal recess in the male pelvis where free fluid collects. The seminal vesicles and prostate lie below this pouch in the male pelvis.<br><br>Uterus and rectum (A) is the female Pouch of Douglas; bladder and uterus (B) is the female vesicouterine pouch; ovary and rectum (C) is not a defined pouch in either sex.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The ischial spine is clinically important because it:',o:['Marks the pelvic inlet','Forms pelvic outlet','Indicates station of fetal head','Supports bladder'],a:2,
    e:`The ischial spine is clinically important because it indicates the station of fetal head during labour. Station 0 is when the leading bony point of the fetal head reaches the level of the ischial spines.<br><br>The ischial spines also serve as landmarks for pudendal nerve block (the nerve passes around the spine) and define the pelvic mid-cavity. They are palpable on vaginal examination as bony prominences laterally.<br><br>Marks the inlet (A) is the sacral promontory; marks pelvic outlet (B) is the ischial tuberosity; landmark for cardinal ligament (D) is correct but not the principal clinical use.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The obturator internus muscle forms part of:',o:['Pelvic wall','Pelvic diaphragm','Abdominal wall','Perineal membrane'],a:0,
    e:`The obturator internus muscle forms part of the lateral pelvic wall. It arises from the inner surface of the obturator membrane and surrounding bone, leaving the pelvis through the lesser sciatic foramen.<br><br>It inserts on the greater trochanter of the femur and acts as a lateral rotator of the hip. The obturator nerve and vessels run along the lateral pelvic wall above this muscle, supplying the medial thigh.<br><br>Pelvic floor (B) is formed by levator ani and coccygeus; posterior pelvic wall (C) is formed by piriformis; anterior pelvic wall (D) is formed by pubic bone and ligaments.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The piriformis muscle exits the pelvis through:',o:['Lesser sciatic foramen','Greater sciatic foramen','Obturator canal','Inguinal canal'],a:1,
    e:`The piriformis muscle exits the pelvis through the greater sciatic foramen, dividing the foramen into spaces above and below the muscle.<br><br>The superior gluteal nerve and vessels exit above piriformis; the sciatic nerve, inferior gluteal nerve and pudendal nerve exit below. The pudendal nerve then re-enters the perineum via the lesser sciatic foramen around the ischial spine.<br><br>Lesser sciatic foramen (A) is for pudendal nerve re-entry; obturator foramen (C) is for obturator nerve and vessels; femoral canal (D) is for femoral vessels in the lower limb.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pudendal nerve exits pelvis via:',o:['Femoral canal','Obturator canal','Inguinal canal','Greater sciatic foramen below piriformis'],a:3,
    e:`The pudendal nerve exits the pelvis via the greater sciatic foramen below piriformis, then re-enters the perineum through the lesser sciatic foramen around the ischial spine.<br><br>This course is the basis for pudendal nerve block, performed transvaginally by depositing local anaesthetic near the ischial spine. The block provides analgesia for second-stage labour, episiotomy repair and outlet forceps delivery procedures.<br><br>Lesser sciatic foramen alone (A) is the re-entry point only; obturator foramen (B) is for obturator nerve; greater sciatic foramen above piriformis (C) is for superior gluteal nerve.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pudendal nerve re-enters the perineum through:',o:['Greater sciatic foramen','Obturator canal','Lesser sciatic foramen','Femoral ring'],a:2,
    e:`The pudendal nerve re-enters the perineum through the lesser sciatic foramen, after curving around the ischial spine and sacrospinous ligament.<br><br>It first exits the pelvis via the greater sciatic foramen below piriformis, then passes around the ischial spine to enter the pudendal canal (Alcock canal) on the medial wall of the ischiorectal fossa, supplying the perineum.<br><br>Greater sciatic foramen alone (A) is exit point only; obturator foramen (B) is for obturator nerve and vessels; femoral canal (D) is for femoral vessels in lower limb.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic splanchnic nerves arise from:',o:['T10-T12','S2-S4','L1-L2','S1-S2'],a:1,
    e:`The pelvic splanchnic nerves arise from S2-S4 sacral nerve roots, carrying parasympathetic preganglionic fibres to pelvic viscera.<br><br>These nerves join the inferior hypogastric plexus and supply pelvic organs including bladder, uterus, rectum and erectile tissue. Parasympathetic stimulation causes detrusor contraction, bladder emptying, erection and rectal evacuation in pelvic functions.<br><br>T10-L2 (A) supplies sympathetic to pelvic viscera; L1-L2 (C) is sympathetic from lumbar splanchnic nerves; T1-T12 (D) is general thoracic sympathetic outflow.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Parasympathetic supply to pelvic viscera is mainly through:',o:['Hypogastric nerves','Pudendal nerve','Pelvic splanchnic nerves','Obturator nerve'],a:2,
    e:`Parasympathetic supply to pelvic viscera is mainly through the pelvic splanchnic nerves (nervi erigentes) arising from S2-S4 sacral roots.<br><br>They join the inferior hypogastric plexus and supply bladder, uterus, rectum and erectile tissue. Parasympathetic stimulation causes detrusor contraction, vasodilation in erectile tissue (erection), and increased peristalsis of rectum and sigmoid colon.<br><br>Vagus nerve (A) supplies foregut and midgut, not pelvis; sympathetic chain (B) supplies sympathetic only; phrenic nerve (D) supplies the diaphragm.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Sympathetic fibers to pelvic organs mainly arise from:',o:['Lumbar sympathetic trunk','Sacral plexus','Pudendal nerve','Femoral nerve'],a:0,
    e:`Sympathetic fibres to pelvic organs mainly arise from the lumbar sympathetic trunk (L1-L2), reaching pelvic viscera via the lumbar splanchnic nerves and superior hypogastric plexus.<br><br>These fibres join the inferior hypogastric plexus and supply pelvic viscera. Sympathetic stimulation inhibits detrusor contraction, contracts the internal urethral sphincter (urinary continence), and mediates ejaculation in males.<br><br>S2-S4 (B) provides parasympathetic supply via pelvic splanchnic nerves; vagus nerve (C) does not supply pelvis; thoracic sympathetic chain T1-T6 (D) supplies upper body.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterine venous plexus drains mainly into:',o:['Portal vein','Inferior vena cava','Renal vein','Internal iliac vein'],a:3,
    e:`The uterine venous plexus drains mainly into the internal iliac vein. The plexus surrounds the uterus and cervix, communicating with vaginal, vesical and rectal venous plexuses.<br><br>From the internal iliac vein, blood reaches the common iliac vein and inferior vena cava. The plexus is engorged during pregnancy; pelvic congestion can cause varicosities and contribute to chronic pelvic pain in some women.<br><br>Inferior vena cava directly (A) is the route for right ovarian vein; portal vein (B) drains gut, not uterus; external iliac vein (C) drains lower limb mainly.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'During radical hysterectomy for carcinoma cervix, careful identification of the ureter is essential because it courses inferior to the uterine artery approximately 1-2 cm lateral to the cervix before entering the bladder. This anatomical relationship is classically summarized by the phrase "water under the bridge," referring to the ureter passing beneath the uterine artery. Injury to which structure would lead to urinary fistula formation if accidentally ligated?',o:['Ureter','Internal iliac vein','Obturator nerve','Pudendal nerve'],a:0,
    e:`During radical hysterectomy for carcinoma cervix, careful identification of the ureter is essential to prevent injury, as the ureter passes beneath the uterine artery near the cervix.<br><br>The ureter is also at risk near the suspensory ligament at the pelvic brim and during dissection of vesicouterine and rectovaginal spaces. Pre-operative imaging and intraoperative identification reduce injury risk significantly during dissection.<br><br>Bladder (B) is identified but anterior; rectum (C) lies posteriorly with less direct risk; common iliac vein (D) is encountered during lymphadenectomy but not principal concern.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The obturator nerve runs along which pelvic structure before exiting through the obturator canal?',o:['Rectum','Pelvic diaphragm','Lateral pelvic wall','Sacral plexus'],a:2,
    e:`The obturator nerve runs along the lateral pelvic wall before exiting through the obturator foramen to enter the medial thigh.<br><br>It arises from L2-L4 of the lumbar plexus, descends along the medial border of psoas major, and crosses the pelvic brim. The nerve is at risk during pelvic lymphadenectomy as it lies among the obturator nodes that are routinely removed.<br><br>Anterior pelvic wall (A) houses pubic structures; pelvic floor (B) is levator ani region; posterior pelvic wall (D) houses piriformis and sacral plexus.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The obturator artery arises from:',o:['External iliac artery','Inferior epigastric artery','Femoral artery','Internal iliac artery'],a:3,
    e:`The obturator artery arises from the internal iliac artery (anterior division), accompanying the obturator nerve through the obturator canal to the medial thigh.<br><br>It supplies medial thigh muscles and contributes to hip joint blood supply via the artery to the head of the femur (acetabular branch). In about 30 percent, an aberrant obturator artery arises from the inferior epigastric artery (corona mortis).<br><br>External iliac artery (A) supplies lower limb; abdominal aorta (B) gives off ovarian and other branches; femoral artery (C) supplies lower limb, not pelvis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The vesical arteries supplying the bladder arise from:',o:['External iliac artery','Internal iliac artery','Femoral artery','Abdominal aorta'],a:1,
    e:`The vesical arteries supplying the bladder arise from the internal iliac artery, mainly from its anterior division.<br><br>Superior vesical arteries supply the upper bladder and may give off branches to the ureter. Inferior vesical arteries (in males) supply the bladder base, prostate and seminal vesicles. The vaginal artery in females may take the role of inferior vesical artery.<br><br>External iliac artery (A) supplies lower limb; abdominal aorta (C) gives off ovarian and other branches; femoral artery (D) supplies lower limb only.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The inferior vesical artery is present mainly in:',o:['Females','Children only','Both sexes equally','Males'],a:3,
    e:`The inferior vesical artery is present mainly in males. It supplies the bladder base, prostate, seminal vesicles and lower ureter, branching from the internal iliac artery.<br><br>In females, the vaginal artery is considered the equivalent of the inferior vesical artery, supplying the vagina, bladder base and lower ureter. This reflects the embryological homology of pelvic structures between sexes.<br><br>Females (A) have the vaginal artery as equivalent; both sexes (B) is partially true but the named artery is male; neither sex (C) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'In females, the vaginal artery commonly arises from:',o:['Femoral artery','Internal iliac artery','Inferior mesenteric artery','External iliac artery'],a:1,
    e:`In females, the vaginal artery commonly arises from the internal iliac artery (anterior division), sometimes from the uterine artery directly.<br><br>It supplies the vagina, bladder base and lower ureter, considered the female equivalent of the inferior vesical artery. The vagina has rich vascular supply also from middle rectal and cervico-vaginal branches of the uterine artery.<br><br>External iliac artery (A) supplies lower limb; abdominal aorta (C) gives off ovarian arteries; femoral artery (D) supplies lower limb, not pelvis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The lymphatic drainage of the ovary primarily goes to:',o:['Para-aortic nodes','Internal iliac nodes','Inguinal nodes','External iliac nodes'],a:0,
    e:`The lymphatic drainage of the ovary primarily goes to the para-aortic (lumbar) lymph nodes, following the ovarian vessels along their embryological course.<br><br>The high-level drainage reflects the ovary\'s embryological origin in the upper abdomen. This is important in ovarian cancer staging: para-aortic lymphadenectomy is part of staging surgery, with right and left side dissection up to the renal vessels.<br><br>Internal iliac nodes (B) drain cervix and upper vagina; superficial inguinal nodes (C) drain vulva and lower vagina; obturator nodes (D) drain cervix mainly.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The lymphatic drainage of the prostate primarily goes to:',o:['Para-aortic nodes','Superficial inguinal nodes','Internal iliac nodes','Celiac nodes'],a:2,
    e:`The lymphatic drainage of the prostate primarily goes to the internal iliac (hypogastric) and obturator lymph nodes, with later spread to external iliac and presacral nodes.<br><br>Lymph node involvement is important in prostate cancer staging and influences treatment. Pelvic lymphadenectomy may be performed during radical prostatectomy. Para-aortic node involvement indicates more advanced metastatic disease beyond the regional pelvic nodes.<br><br>Para-aortic nodes (A) receive secondary drainage; superficial inguinal nodes (B) drain perineum and lower limb; deep cervical nodes (D) drain head and neck only.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The male urethra passes through which muscle of the pelvic floor?',o:['Pubococcygeus','Puborectalis','Coccygeus','External urethral sphincter'],a:3,
    e:`The male urethra passes through the external urethral sphincter (sphincter urethrae) of the deep perineal pouch, providing voluntary control of micturition.<br><br>The sphincter is composed of skeletal muscle innervated by the pudendal nerve. The internal urethral sphincter at the bladder neck is smooth muscle under autonomic control. Both sphincters work together to maintain urinary continence in normal conditions.<br><br>Levator ani (A) supports pelvic organs but is not the urethral sphincter; obturator internus (B) is on lateral pelvic wall; piriformis (C) is on posterior pelvic wall.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The prostate lies directly inferior to:',o:['Rectum','Seminal vesicles','Bladder','Pubic symphysis'],a:2,
    e:`The prostate lies directly inferior to the bladder, surrounding the prostatic urethra. It is about 3 cm in length and shaped like an inverted cone with the base at the bladder neck.<br><br>The prostate has anatomical zones (peripheral, central, transitional) with different clinical significance: BPH affects the transitional zone; prostate cancer typically arises in the peripheral zone. The seminal vesicles lie posterior, the rectum behind them.<br><br>Prostate (A) cannot lie below itself; rectum (B) lies posterior to the prostate; seminal vesicles (D) lie posterior and superior to the prostate.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'A 65-year-old male with carcinoma of the prostate develops metastasis to lymph nodes located along the internal iliac vessels. This pattern of spread occurs because lymphatics from the prostate drain primarily into the internal iliac and sacral nodes before spreading further. Which lymph nodes are most commonly involved early in prostate cancer?',o:['Internal iliac nodes','Superficial inguinal nodes','Para-aortic nodes','Celiac nodes'],a:0,
    e:`A 65-year-old male with carcinoma of the prostate develops metastasis to the internal iliac nodes as the primary regional lymph node group.<br><br>The internal iliac (hypogastric) and obturator nodes are the first-station regional nodes. Spread can extend to external iliac, presacral and later para-aortic nodes. Distant metastases commonly involve bone (especially axial skeleton with osteoblastic lesions).<br><br>Para-aortic nodes (B) receive later secondary drainage; superficial inguinal nodes (C) drain perineum and lower limb; deep cervical nodes (D) drain head and neck.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The seminal vesicles lie posterior to:',o:['Rectum','Bladder','Prostate','Urethra'],a:1,
    e:`The seminal vesicles lie posterior to the bladder, between the bladder base anteriorly and the rectum posteriorly. They are paired sacculated tubular structures storing and producing seminal fluid.<br><br>Each seminal vesicle joins the vas deferens to form the ejaculatory duct, which opens into the prostatic urethra. The seminal vesicles can be palpated on digital rectal examination, though they are not normally felt clearly.<br><br>Prostate (A) lies inferior to the seminal vesicles; rectum (C) lies posterior to seminal vesicles; ureter (D) crosses anterior to seminal vesicle ducts.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The vas deferens crosses which structure before joining the seminal vesicle?',o:['Ureter','Uterine artery','External iliac artery','Bladder neck'],a:0,
    e:`The vas deferens crosses the ureter from lateral to medial side before joining the duct of the seminal vesicle to form the ejaculatory duct.<br><br>This relationship is described as \'water (ureter) under the bridge (vas deferens)\' in males, similar to the female ureter-uterine artery relationship. It is an important surgical landmark during pelvic surgery and vasectomy procedures in males.<br><br>Bladder (B) is anterior to vas; rectum (C) is posterior; iliac vessels (D) are lateral, not crossed by the vas in this manner.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic plexus lies near which structure?',o:['Pelvic diaphragm','Sacral promontory','Lateral pelvic wall','Ischial spine'],a:2,
    e:`The pelvic plexus (inferior hypogastric plexus) lies near the lateral pelvic wall, on the medial aspect of the internal iliac vessels and lateral to the rectum, cervix and bladder.<br><br>It receives sympathetic fibres from hypogastric nerves (L1-L2) and parasympathetic fibres from pelvic splanchnic nerves (S2-S4), distributing autonomic supply to all pelvic viscera. Damage during pelvic surgery causes pelvic organ dysfunction.<br><br>Anterior pelvic wall (A) is pubic region; pelvic floor (B) is levator ani; posterior pelvic wall (D) is piriformis area.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The nerve responsible for erection is mainly:',o:['Pudendal nerve','Pelvic splanchnic nerve','Femoral nerve','Obturator nerve'],a:1,
    e:`Erection is mainly mediated by the pelvic splanchnic nerves (parasympathetic, S2-S4 origin), causing arterial vasodilation in the cavernous tissue.<br><br>The vasodilation increases blood flow into corpora cavernosa, compressing venous outflow and producing rigidity. Sildenafil and similar drugs work by inhibiting phosphodiesterase 5, prolonging the parasympathetic-mediated vasodilation in penile erectile tissue.<br><br>Sympathetic fibres (A) mainly mediate ejaculation, not erection; pudendal nerve (C) provides somatic sensation; obturator nerve (D) supplies medial thigh, not erection.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The nerve responsible for ejaculation is mainly:',o:['Parasympathetic fibers','Femoral nerve','Pudendal nerve','Sympathetic fibers'],a:3,
    e:`Ejaculation is mainly mediated by sympathetic fibres (L1-L2 origin) via the hypogastric nerves and pelvic plexus. The sympathetic stimulation causes peristaltic contractions of the vas deferens, seminal vesicles and prostate.<br><br>Sympathetic stimulation also closes the internal urethral sphincter, preventing retrograde ejaculation into the bladder. Damage to sympathetic supply during retroperitoneal surgery can cause retrograde ejaculation, an important consideration in men of reproductive age.<br><br>Pelvic splanchnic nerves (A) mediate erection (parasympathetic); pudendal nerve (B) provides somatic perineal supply; obturator nerve (C) supplies medial thigh.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The ischiorectal fossa lies between:',o:['Bladder and uterus','Rectum and bladder','Rectum and pelvic wall','Prostate and bladder'],a:2,
    e:`The ischiorectal (ischioanal) fossa lies between the rectum medially and the pelvic wall laterally (specifically between the anal canal and the obturator internus muscle).<br><br>It is a wedge-shaped fat-filled space with the pudendal canal (Alcock canal) on its lateral wall, transmitting the pudendal nerve and internal pudendal vessels. It is a common site of perianal abscess and may be drained surgically.<br><br>Bladder and rectum (A) define the rectovesical pouch in males; bladder and uterus (B) define vesicouterine pouch; uterus and rectum (D) define rectouterine pouch.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The perineal body provides attachment for:',o:['Levator ani muscles','All of the above','Bulbospongiosus','External anal sphincter'],a:1,
    e:`The perineal body provides attachment for several muscles: the bulbospongiosus, superficial and deep transverse perineal muscles, levator ani and external anal sphincter.<br><br>It is a fibromuscular pyramidal structure central to perineal support and continence. Damage during vaginal delivery (with or without third- or fourth-degree perineal tears) contributes to pelvic floor dysfunction, prolapse and incontinence in affected women.<br><br>Bulbospongiosus only (A) is partial; transverse perineal only (C) is partial; external anal sphincter only (D) is partial; all three muscle groups attach.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The sacral plexus is formed from:',o:['L2-L4','L1-L3','S1-S4','L4-S4'],a:3,
    e:`The sacral plexus is formed from the anterior rami of L4 (lumbosacral trunk) to S4 nerve roots, lying on the posterior pelvic wall on the piriformis muscle.<br><br>Major branches include the sciatic nerve (largest in body), pudendal nerve, superior and inferior gluteal nerves, posterior cutaneous nerve of thigh and the nerve to obturator internus. The plexus supplies most of the lower limb and pelvis.<br><br>L1-L4 (A) is the lumbar plexus; T12-L1 (B) is subcostal/iliohypogastric; S1-S5 (C) is partial.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic inlet is widest in which pelvic type?',o:['Gynecoid','Android','Anthropoid','Platypelloid'],a:0,
    e:`The pelvic inlet is widest in the gynecoid pelvis, the typical female pelvic shape, with a rounded transverse diameter slightly larger than the anteroposterior diameter.<br><br>The four classic pelvic types are gynecoid (50 percent of women, ideal for normal delivery), android (male-type, narrow), anthropoid (oval, AP greater than transverse) and platypelloid (flat, transverse much greater than AP). Gynecoid favours normal vaginal delivery.<br><br>Android (B) is heart-shaped, narrow at front; anthropoid (C) is oval with long AP; platypelloid (D) is flat with narrow AP.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'A gynecologic surgeon performing laparoscopic drainage of pelvic abscess approaches the posterior vaginal fornix because it provides direct access to the rectouterine pouch, which is the most dependent portion of the female peritoneal cavity where infected fluid or blood may accumulate. Which structure forms the posterior boundary of this pouch?',o:['Uterus','Rectum','Bladder','Ovary'],a:1,
    e:`Laparoscopic drainage of pelvic abscess (collected in Pouch of Douglas) is approached safely via the rectum posteriorly, taking care to avoid bowel injury.<br><br>The Pouch of Douglas is the most dependent peritoneal recess in females, lying between rectum and posterior wall of uterus and upper vagina. Posterior colpotomy through the posterior fornix is another route accessing this same pouch transvaginally for drainage.<br><br>Bladder (A) lies anterior, far from the abscess site; ureter (C) is lateral; ovary (D) is lateral and not the abscess access route.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The coccygeus muscle lies between:',o:['Ischial spine and coccyx','Sacrum and ischial spine','Sacrum and pubis','Coccyx and femur'],a:0,
    e:`The coccygeus muscle lies between the ischial spine and the coccyx, forming the posterior part of the pelvic diaphragm.<br><br>It overlies the sacrospinous ligament. Together with levator ani, coccygeus completes the pelvic diaphragm, supporting pelvic viscera. Some classifications include coccygeus as the fourth component of levator ani; others consider it separate but adjacent in pelvic floor anatomy.<br><br>Pubic bone and ischial tuberosity (B) is wrong landmarks; ischial tuberosity and coccyx (C) is partial; pubic symphysis and ischial spine (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic brim separates:',o:['Bladder and rectum','Pelvis and abdomen','True and false pelvis','Rectum and vagina'],a:2,
    e:`The pelvic brim separates the true and false pelvis. The brim is bounded by the sacral promontory, iliopectineal lines and pubic symphysis upper border.<br><br>The false (greater) pelvis lies above and contains lower abdominal contents and intestinal loops. The true (lesser) pelvis lies below the brim and contains pelvic viscera (bladder, rectum, uterus, ovaries) and is the obstetric pelvis through which the fetal head passes.<br><br>Abdomen and pelvis (A) is too broad; pelvis and perineum (B) is the pelvic diaphragm; pelvis and lower limb (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The false pelvis mainly contains:',o:['Pelvic organs','Uterus','Bladder','Intestinal loops'],a:3,
    e:`The false (greater) pelvis mainly contains intestinal loops (small bowel and sigmoid colon). It lies above the pelvic brim, between the iliac fossae of the hip bones.<br><br>The false pelvis is anatomically part of the abdomen and contains lower abdominal contents. The true pelvis below the brim contains pelvic viscera. The false pelvis can be considered the entrance to the obstetric pelvis above the inlet.<br><br>Bladder (A) lies in true pelvis; uterus (B) lies in true pelvis; rectum (C) lies in true pelvis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The true pelvis mainly contains:',o:['Pelvic viscera','Kidneys','Liver','Spleen'],a:0,
    e:`The true (lesser) pelvis mainly contains pelvic viscera: bladder, rectum, uterus, fallopian tubes, ovaries, vagina and supporting structures.<br><br>It lies below the pelvic brim and is the obstetric pelvis through which the fetal head passes during labour. The space is bounded by hip bones laterally, sacrum posteriorly and pubic bones anteriorly, with pelvic floor below.<br><br>Intestinal loops (B) are in false pelvis above; lower limb structures (C) are below pelvic floor; abdominal viscera (D) are in abdomen, not true pelvis.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The most lateral part of the levator ani muscle is:',o:['Pubococcygeus','Puborectalis','Iliococcygeus','Coccygeus'],a:2,
    e:`The most lateral part of the levator ani muscle is the iliococcygeus, arising from the tendinous arch of the obturator fascia and the ischial spine.<br><br>Levator ani has three components from medial to lateral: pubococcygeus (most medial, around urogenital and rectal openings), puborectalis (around rectum) and iliococcygeus (most lateral, attaching to coccyx and median raphe). They form the muscular pelvic floor.<br><br>Pubococcygeus (A) is most medial; puborectalis (B) is around the rectum; coccygeus (D) is separate, lying behind levator ani.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The inferior rectal nerve arises from:',o:['Femoral nerve','Pudendal nerve','Obturator nerve','Sciatic nerve'],a:1,
    e:`The inferior rectal nerve arises from the pudendal nerve in the pudendal canal (Alcock canal) on the lateral wall of the ischiorectal fossa.<br><br>It supplies the external anal sphincter and the perianal skin. Pudendal nerve block at the ischial spine anaesthetises the inferior rectal, perineal and dorsal nerves of clitoris/penis - useful for episiotomy repair, second-stage labour and outlet forceps delivery.<br><br>Sciatic nerve (A) supplies lower limb; obturator nerve (C) supplies medial thigh; femoral nerve (D) supplies anterior thigh, not perineum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The rectum receives arterial supply mainly from:',o:['Superior rectal artery','Middle rectal artery','Inferior rectal artery','All of the above'],a:3,
    e:`The rectum receives arterial supply from multiple sources: superior rectal (terminal branch of inferior mesenteric), middle rectal (from internal iliac) and inferior rectal (from internal pudendal artery).<br><br>This dual arterial supply forms a portal-systemic anastomosis at the anorectal junction, important in portal hypertension when haemorrhoids may develop. The lymphatic drainage similarly varies by level: above pectinate line goes to internal iliac nodes.<br><br>Superior rectal only (A) is partial; middle rectal only (B) is partial; inferior rectal only (C) is partial; all three contribute.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The superior rectal artery is a continuation of:',o:['External iliac artery','Internal iliac artery','Inferior mesenteric artery','Femoral artery'],a:2,
    e:`The superior rectal artery is a continuation of the inferior mesenteric artery, supplying the upper rectum above the pelvic brim.<br><br>It descends in the sigmoid mesocolon, crosses into the pelvis and divides into right and left branches that descend on the rectum. The superior rectal artery anastomoses with middle and inferior rectal arteries, providing a portal-systemic communication at the anal canal.<br><br>Internal iliac artery (A) gives off middle rectal; internal pudendal artery (B) gives off inferior rectal; abdominal aorta (D) gives off ovarian and other branches.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The middle rectal artery arises from:',o:['Internal iliac artery','Inferior mesenteric artery','Femoral artery','External iliac artery'],a:0,
    e:`The middle rectal artery arises from the internal iliac artery, usually from its anterior division. It supplies the middle part of the rectum.<br><br>The middle rectal artery anastomoses with the superior rectal (from inferior mesenteric) and inferior rectal (from internal pudendal) arteries, providing a portal-systemic communication at the anorectal junction. This anastomosis is clinically relevant in portal hypertension and haemorrhoids.<br><br>Inferior mesenteric artery (B) gives off superior rectal; internal pudendal artery (C) gives off inferior rectal; femoral artery (D) supplies lower limb.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'During pelvic surgery for rectal carcinoma, the surgeon carefully dissects the rectum away from the posterior vaginal wall in females. The fascial layer separating these structures is clinically important because it prevents spread of infection and tumor between the rectum and vagina. This layer is known as:',o:['Endopelvic fascia','Rectovaginal septum','Perineal membrane','Transversalis fascia'],a:1,
    e:`During pelvic surgery for rectal carcinoma, the surgeon carefully dissects the rectovaginal septum to separate rectum from vagina without injury to either organ.<br><br>The rectovaginal septum is a fibrous tissue layer between the posterior vaginal wall and anterior rectal wall, important in pelvic floor surgery and rectocele repair. It is also a common site of deep infiltrating endometriosis with cyclical dyspareunia.<br><br>Broad ligament (A) is lateral; perineal body (C) lies inferiorly; pelvic diaphragm (D) is the muscular floor below.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The anal canal above the pectinate line is supplied by:',o:['Inferior rectal nerve','Pudendal nerve','Femoral nerve','Autonomic nerves'],a:3,
    e:`The anal canal above the pectinate (dentate) line is supplied by autonomic nerves (visceral innervation), with sympathetic and parasympathetic fibres from the inferior hypogastric plexus.<br><br>This visceral innervation is sensitive to stretch but not pain or temperature, explaining painless internal haemorrhoids. The pectinate line marks the embryological junction between hindgut (endoderm) and proctodeum (ectoderm), with different nerve and lymphatic patterns above and below.<br><br>Pudendal nerve (A) supplies below pectinate line; sympathetic only (B) is partial; somatic nerves (C) supply below pectinate line.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The anal canal below the pectinate line is supplied by:',o:['Autonomic nerves','Femoral nerve','Pudendal nerve','Obturator nerve'],a:2,
    e:`The anal canal below the pectinate line is supplied by the pudendal nerve (somatic, S2-S4), specifically the inferior rectal nerve.<br><br>This somatic innervation is sensitive to pain, temperature and touch, explaining painful external haemorrhoids and anal fissures below the pectinate line. The pectinate line marks the embryological junction between hindgut and proctodeum, with different nerve and lymphatic patterns above and below.<br><br>Sympathetic only (A) is incorrect; parasympathetic only (B) is incorrect; vagus nerve (D) does not supply the perineum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'Internal hemorrhoids occur above which landmark?',o:['Anal verge','Pubic symphysis','Ischial spine','Pectinate line'],a:3,
    e:`Internal haemorrhoids occur above the pectinate line, arising from the internal rectal venous plexus (drainage to portal system via superior rectal vein).<br><br>They are covered by columnar epithelium with visceral innervation, so are usually painless but may bleed (bright red bleeding on toilet paper or in pan). Treatment depends on grade: grade 1-2 conservative; grade 3 banding or sclerotherapy; grade 4 may need haemorrhoidectomy surgery.<br><br>Anal verge (A) is the lower border; ischial spine (B) is unrelated landmark; coccyx (C) is unrelated to haemorrhoid classification.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'External hemorrhoids occur below:',o:['Rectal valve','Pectinate line','Anal sphincter','Pelvic diaphragm'],a:1,
    e:`External haemorrhoids occur below the pectinate (dentate) line, arising from the external rectal venous plexus (drainage to systemic circulation via inferior rectal veins).<br><br>They are covered by skin (squamous epithelium) with somatic innervation from the pudendal nerve, so are typically painful especially when thrombosed. Treatment of acute thrombosed external haemorrhoids may include excision under local anaesthesia for symptom relief.<br><br>Anal verge (A) is anatomical landmark, but the cutoff is pectinate line; ischial spine (C) is unrelated; coccyx (D) is unrelated to haemorrhoids.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic viscera receive sympathetic supply through:',o:['Hypogastric nerves','Pudendal nerve','Obturator nerve','Femoral nerve'],a:0,
    e:`The pelvic viscera receive sympathetic supply through the hypogastric nerves, which descend from the superior hypogastric plexus to the inferior hypogastric (pelvic) plexus.<br><br>Sympathetic preganglionic fibres arise from T10-L2 spinal cord, reach the lumbar sympathetic chain, then via lumbar splanchnic nerves to the superior hypogastric plexus, then hypogastric nerves to the pelvic plexus distributing to viscera.<br><br>Pelvic splanchnic nerves (B) carry parasympathetic; pudendal nerve (C) is somatic; vagus nerve (D) does not supply pelvis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The inferior hypogastric plexus lies in:',o:['Abdominal cavity','Pelvic cavity','Perineum','Thorax'],a:1,
    e:`The inferior hypogastric plexus lies in the pelvic cavity on the lateral pelvic wall, on the medial aspect of the internal iliac vessels and lateral to the rectum, cervix and bladder.<br><br>It receives sympathetic from hypogastric nerves and parasympathetic from pelvic splanchnic nerves, distributing autonomic supply to all pelvic viscera. Damage during radical pelvic surgery causes bladder, sexual and bowel dysfunction in patients post-operatively.<br><br>Abdominal cavity (A) houses superior hypogastric plexus; perineum (C) is below pelvic floor; lower limb (D) is irrelevant.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The bladder trigone is formed by:',o:['Bladder neck only','Urethra only','Ureteric openings and internal urethral opening','Ureter only'],a:2,
    e:`The bladder trigone is formed by the two ureteric openings (posterolaterally) and the internal urethral opening (anteriorly), forming a triangle on the bladder base.<br><br>The trigone is smooth-surfaced (unlike the rugose rest of the bladder). It is derived embryologically from mesoderm (mesonephric duct), unlike the rest of the bladder (endoderm of urogenital sinus). Trigonitis can cause urgency and frequency.<br><br>Two ureteric openings only (A) is incomplete; ureteric and umbilical (B) is incorrect; bladder neck and urethra (D) is not the trigone.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The lymphatic drainage of the bladder mainly goes to:',o:['Celiac nodes','Superficial inguinal nodes','Para-aortic nodes','Internal iliac nodes'],a:3,
    e:`The lymphatic drainage of the bladder mainly goes to the internal iliac (hypogastric) and external iliac nodes, with the obturator nodes also receiving drainage.<br><br>Bladder cancer staging includes assessment of pelvic lymph nodes; advanced disease spreads to common iliac and para-aortic nodes. Pelvic lymphadenectomy may be performed during radical cystectomy for bladder cancer treatment with curative intent.<br><br>Para-aortic nodes (A) receive secondary drainage; superficial inguinal nodes (B) drain perineum; deep cervical nodes (C) drain head and neck.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic floor is pierced by which structures in females?',o:['All of the above','Vagina','Rectum','Urethra'],a:0,
    e:`The pelvic floor in females is pierced by three structures: the urethra, vagina and rectum (anal canal). Each passes through openings in the pelvic diaphragm.<br><br>The urogenital hiatus accommodates the urethra and vagina; the rectum passes through the anal hiatus more posteriorly. These weak points are sites of pelvic organ prolapse: cystocele (bladder), urethrocele (urethra), rectocele (rectum) or uterine prolapse occur with weakness.<br><br>Urethra only (B) is partial; vagina only (C) is partial; rectum only (D) is partial; all three pierce the pelvic floor.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The coccyx moves posteriorly during childbirth primarily because of relaxation of which ligament and joint?',o:['Pubic symphysis','Sacroiliac joint','Sacrococcygeal joint','Lumbosacral joint'],a:2,
    e:`The coccyx moves posteriorly during childbirth primarily because of relaxation of the sacrococcygeal joint, increasing the AP diameter of the pelvic outlet to facilitate fetal head delivery.<br><br>During the second stage of labour, the fetal head pushes the coccyx backward by 2 cm or more, increasing the outlet space. Pregnancy-related ligament relaxation (relaxin hormone) contributes to this mobility, supporting the dynamic obstetric pelvis during birth.<br><br>Sacroiliac joint (A) provides minor movement; pubic symphysis (B) widens but is not the coccyx mobility; hip joint (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The sacrospinous ligament extends from:',o:['Sacrum to ischial spine','Coccyx to ischial tuberosity','Ilium to sacrum','Pubis to sacrum'],a:0,
    e:`The sacrospinous ligament extends from the sacrum (lower part) to the ischial spine, dividing the greater and lesser sciatic foramina.<br><br>It separates the greater sciatic foramen above from the lesser sciatic foramen below. The pudendal nerve passes posterior to the ischial spine and the sacrospinous ligament during its course around the spine to enter the perineum from greater to lesser sciatic foramen.<br><br>Sacrum to ischial tuberosity (B) is sacrotuberous; ischial spine to coccyx (C) is part of pelvic floor; pubic bone to ischial spine (D) is not a defined ligament.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The sacrotuberous ligament extends from:',o:['Sacrum to pubis','Sacrum to ischial tuberosity','Ilium to coccyx','Pubis to coccyx'],a:1,
    e:`The sacrotuberous ligament extends from the sacrum and coccyx to the ischial tuberosity, forming the inferior boundary of the lesser sciatic foramen.<br><br>Together with the sacrospinous ligament, the sacrotuberous ligament converts the sciatic notches of the hip bone into greater and lesser sciatic foramina. The pudendal nerve and internal pudendal vessels pass between these two ligaments around the ischial spine.<br><br>Sacrum to ischial spine (A) is sacrospinous; ischial spine to pubis (C) is incorrect; coccyx to pubis (D) is not a defined pelvic ligament.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The greater sciatic foramen is formed by:',o:['Inguinal ligament','Sacroiliac ligament','Pubic ligament','Sacrospinous and sacrotuberous ligaments'],a:3,
    e:`The greater sciatic foramen is formed by the greater sciatic notch of the hip bone, with the sacrospinous and sacrotuberous ligaments forming its inferior and posterior boundaries respectively.<br><br>It transmits the sciatic nerve, superior and inferior gluteal nerves and vessels, posterior cutaneous nerve of thigh, pudendal nerve, internal pudendal vessels, nerves to obturator internus and quadratus femoris, and the piriformis muscle exits here.<br><br>Sacrospinous only (A) is partial; sacrotuberous only (B) is partial; obturator membrane (C) is for obturator foramen.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The lesser sciatic foramen transmits:',o:['All of the above','Internal pudendal vessels','Tendon of obturator internus','Pudendal nerve'],a:0,
    e:`The lesser sciatic foramen transmits the tendon of obturator internus, the nerve to obturator internus, the pudendal nerve and internal pudendal vessels (re-entering the perineum).<br><br>The pudendal nerve and vessels first exit the pelvis via the greater sciatic foramen below piriformis, curve around the ischial spine, then re-enter the perineum through the lesser sciatic foramen to enter the pudendal canal.<br><br>Pudendal nerve only (B) is partial; obturator internus tendon only (C) is partial; internal pudendal vessels only (D) is partial; all three traverse the foramen.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The bladder is mainly supplied by which arteries?',o:['Superior vesical arteries','Inferior vesical arteries','Vaginal arteries (female)','All of the above'],a:3,
    e:`The bladder is mainly supplied by superior vesical arteries (from internal iliac), inferior vesical arteries (in males) or vaginal arteries (in females, equivalent), and small branches from obturator and inferior gluteal arteries.<br><br>The dual supply ensures rich vascularisation. Venous drainage is via the vesical venous plexus to internal iliac vein. Lymphatics drain to internal iliac and external iliac nodes, important in bladder cancer staging and radical cystectomy lymphadenectomy.<br><br>Superior vesical only (A) is partial; inferior vesical only (B) is partial; vaginal artery only (C) is partial in females.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The apex of the bladder is connected to the umbilicus by:',o:['Round ligament','Medial umbilical ligament','Median umbilical ligament','Suspensory ligament'],a:2,
    e:`The apex of the bladder is connected to the umbilicus by the median umbilical ligament, a remnant of the urachus (allantoic remnant).<br><br>The urachus connects fetal bladder to allantois during development. After birth, it obliterates to form the median umbilical ligament. Urachal remnants can persist as cysts, fistulas or sinuses; rare urachal carcinoma may develop in adults from these embryological remnants.<br><br>Lateral umbilical ligament (A) contains inferior epigastric vessels; medial umbilical ligament (B) is obliterated umbilical artery; round ligament of liver (D) is in liver.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The urachus in adults becomes:',o:['Round ligament','Median umbilical ligament','Suspensory ligament','Pubovesical ligament'],a:1,
    e:`The urachus in adults becomes the median umbilical ligament, a fibrous cord extending from the apex of the bladder to the umbilicus along the anterior abdominal wall.<br><br>It is a remnant of the embryological allantois which connected fetal bladder to umbilicus. Persistence can cause urachal cysts, fistulas or sinuses; rare urachal carcinoma may develop in adults from epithelial remnants of this embryological structure.<br><br>Round ligament of liver (A) is the obliterated umbilical vein; medial umbilical ligament (C) is obliterated umbilical artery; lateral umbilical ligament (D) contains inferior epigastric vessels.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The bladder neck in males lies superior to:',o:['Prostate','Rectum','Seminal vesicle','Urethra'],a:0,
    e:`The bladder neck in males lies superior to the prostate, which surrounds the prostatic urethra immediately below the internal urethral opening.<br><br>The prostate is about 3 cm in length and shaped like an inverted cone with its base at the bladder neck. Benign prostatic hyperplasia of the transitional zone causes urethral compression, leading to urinary retention, frequency and weak stream in older men.<br><br>Seminal vesicles (B) lie posterior to bladder; rectum (C) lies posterior; pubic symphysis (D) lies anterior to bladder.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic fascia that surrounds pelvic organs is known as:',o:['Camper fascia','Scarpa fascia','Endopelvic fascia','Transversalis fascia'],a:2,
    e:`The pelvic fascia surrounding pelvic organs is known as the endopelvic fascia, a connective tissue framework continuous throughout the pelvis providing support and pathways for vessels and nerves.<br><br>It condenses to form ligaments: cardinal laterally, uterosacral posteriorly, pubocervical anteriorly. Damage from childbirth or chronic strain causes pelvic organ prolapse requiring surgical reconstruction. The endopelvic fascia is also called pelvic visceral fascia in some texts.<br><br>Pelvic peritoneum (A) is serous membrane; transversalis fascia (B) is in abdominal wall; Camper\'s fascia (D) is in abdominal wall superficial layer.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'A gynecologic surgeon repairing uterine prolapse identifies a fibromuscular band extending from the cervix and upper vagina to the sacrum. This structure helps maintain the uterus in its normal position and forms part of the major support system of the uterus. Which ligament is this?',o:['Ovarian ligament','Round ligament','Broad ligament','Uterosacral ligament'],a:3,
    e:`A gynecologic surgeon repairing uterine prolapse identifies the uterosacral ligament, a fibromuscular band extending from the cervix posteriorly to the sacrum at S2-S4.<br><br>The uterosacral ligaments contain smooth muscle, fibrous tissue and the autonomic nerves of the pelvic plexus. They are commonly involved in endometriosis and serve as anchoring points in apical prolapse repairs (uterosacral ligament suspension).<br><br>Round ligament (A) maintains anteversion; cardinal ligament (B) supports cervix laterally; broad ligament (C) is a peritoneal fold, not a true support.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Urogynaecology)</em>`},
    {q:'The levator ani muscles are innervated mainly by:',o:['Femoral nerve','Pudendal nerve and sacral nerves','Obturator nerve','Sciatic nerve'],a:1,
    e:`The levator ani muscles are innervated by the pudendal nerve and direct branches from sacral nerves S3-S4 (the \'nerve to levator ani\').<br><br>Innervation has both somatic (voluntary) control and reflex involvement. Pudendal nerve damage during prolonged labour can contribute to pelvic floor dysfunction, fecal incontinence and stress urinary incontinence in women post-delivery, especially after instrumental vaginal birth.<br><br>Obturator nerve only (A) supplies medial thigh; femoral nerve (C) supplies anterior thigh; sciatic nerve (D) supplies lower limb posterior.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The ischiorectal fossa contains:',o:['Fat','Pudendal canal','All of the above','Inferior rectal vessels'],a:2,
    e:`The ischiorectal fossa contains fat, the pudendal canal (Alcock canal) on its lateral wall, and the inferior rectal vessels and nerves crossing to supply the anal canal.<br><br>The fat-filled space allows expansion of anal canal during defecation. Perianal abscesses commonly occur in this fossa and may extend horseshoe-shaped to the contralateral side. Surgical drainage is via incision over the most fluctuant area in the perianal skin.<br><br>Fat only (A) is partial; pudendal nerve only (B) is partial; inferior rectal vessels only (C) is partial; all three.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pudendal canal (Alcock canal) is located in:',o:['Perineal membrane','Levator ani muscle','Pelvic diaphragm','Obturator internus fascia'],a:3,
    e:`The pudendal canal (Alcock canal) is located in the obturator internus fascia on the lateral wall of the ischiorectal fossa.<br><br>It transmits the pudendal nerve and internal pudendal vessels as they enter the perineum from the lesser sciatic foramen. The pudendal nerve gives off inferior rectal nerve in the canal, then continues as perineal and dorsal nerves of clitoris/penis to supply the perineum.<br><br>Levator ani fascia (A) is on pelvic side; deep perineal pouch (B) is anterior; superficial perineal pouch (C) is more superficial.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The artery accompanying the pudendal nerve in the pudendal canal is:',o:['Internal pudendal artery','External pudendal artery','Femoral artery','Inferior epigastric artery'],a:0,
    e:`The artery accompanying the pudendal nerve in the pudendal canal is the internal pudendal artery, a branch of the internal iliac artery (anterior division).<br><br>Both pudendal nerve and internal pudendal vessels exit the pelvis via the greater sciatic foramen, curve around the ischial spine, then re-enter the perineum through the lesser sciatic foramen into the pudendal canal on the lateral wall of ischiorectal fossa.<br><br>External pudendal artery (B) is from femoral, supplies anterior labia; obturator artery (C) accompanies obturator nerve; superior gluteal artery (D) is in gluteal region.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The internal pudendal artery arises from:',o:['External iliac artery','Internal iliac artery','Femoral artery','Abdominal aorta'],a:1,
    e:`The internal pudendal artery arises from the internal iliac artery (anterior division), exiting the pelvis via the greater sciatic foramen below piriformis.<br><br>It then curves around the ischial spine and re-enters the perineum through the lesser sciatic foramen to enter the pudendal canal. The artery supplies the perineum, anal canal, external genitalia and erectile tissue, accompanying the pudendal nerve throughout.<br><br>External iliac artery (A) supplies lower limb; abdominal aorta (C) gives off ovarian; femoral artery (D) supplies lower limb only.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic viscera are mainly supported by:',o:['All of the above','Endopelvic fascia','Perineal body','Pelvic diaphragm'],a:0,
    e:`The pelvic viscera are mainly supported by the pelvic diaphragm (levator ani and coccygeus), endopelvic fascia (cardinal, uterosacral, pubocervical ligaments) and perineal body.<br><br>All three components work together to provide muscular and ligamentous support, resisting downward forces from intra-abdominal pressure. Damage to any component during childbirth or with chronic strain leads to pelvic organ prolapse requiring surgical reconstruction in symptomatic cases.<br><br>Pelvic diaphragm only (B) is partial; endopelvic fascia only (C) is partial; perineal body only (D) is partial; all three.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The ureter crosses which artery at the pelvic brim?',o:['Internal iliac artery','External iliac artery','Femoral artery','Inferior mesenteric artery'],a:1,
    e:`The ureter crosses the external iliac artery (or the bifurcation of common iliac into internal and external iliac) at the pelvic brim as it enters the pelvis.<br><br>This is a key surgical landmark for identifying the ureter at the pelvic brim. The ureter then descends along the lateral pelvic wall, passes beneath the uterine artery near the cervix (\'water under the bridge\') and enters the bladder posteriorly.<br><br>Common iliac artery (A) - actually the bifurcation level; internal iliac artery (C) is medial; femoral artery (D) is in the thigh.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The ureter enters the bladder at the level of:',o:['Neck','Apex','Trigone','Dome'],a:2,
    e:`The ureter enters the bladder at the level of the trigone, passing obliquely through the bladder wall for about 2 cm before opening at the upper lateral angle of the trigone.<br><br>The oblique passage acts as a valve preventing reflux of urine into the ureter during bladder filling and contraction. The two ureteric openings and the internal urethral opening form the corners of the bladder trigone, embryologically derived from mesoderm.<br><br>Apex of bladder (A) is opposite end; bladder neck (B) is the urethral opening; fundus (D) is not a standard bladder anatomical term.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'A surgeon performing pelvic lymph node dissection for carcinoma cervix notes that lymphatic drainage from the cervix follows vessels within the cardinal ligament toward nodes located along the internal iliac and obturator vessels. These nodes represent the most common first site of lymphatic spread. Which group of lymph nodes is primarily involved?',o:['Superficial inguinal nodes','Celiac nodes','Para-aortic nodes','Internal iliac nodes'],a:3,
    e:`Pelvic lymph node dissection for carcinoma cervix involves removal of internal iliac, external iliac, obturator and common iliac nodes as the primary regional drainage.<br><br>Para-aortic node involvement indicates more advanced disease (Stage IIIC2) and influences treatment with extended-field radiotherapy. Sentinel lymph node biopsy is being explored as an alternative to full pelvic lymphadenectomy in early-stage cervical cancer with reduced morbidity.<br><br>Para-aortic nodes (A) receive secondary drainage; superficial inguinal nodes (B) drain vulva; deep cervical nodes (C) drain head and neck.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Gynaecological oncology)</em>`},
    {q:'The coccygeus muscle forms part of:',o:['Pelvic diaphragm','Pelvic wall','Abdominal wall','Perineum'],a:0,
    e:`The coccygeus muscle forms part of the pelvic diaphragm, lying posterior to levator ani, between the ischial spine and the coccyx.<br><br>Together with levator ani, coccygeus completes the pelvic diaphragm, supporting pelvic viscera and resisting downward pressure. Some classifications include coccygeus as a fourth component of levator ani; others consider it a separate but adjacent muscle of the pelvic floor.<br><br>Anterior pelvic wall (B) is pubic structures; lateral pelvic wall (C) is obturator internus; posterior abdominal wall (D) is irrelevant.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pubic arch is formed by:',o:['Sacral promontory','Iliac crest','Ischial spine','Inferior rami of pubis'],a:3,
    e:`The pubic arch is formed by the inferior rami of the pubis (and the ischiopubic rami) on each side, meeting anteriorly at the pubic symphysis.<br><br>The angle of the pubic arch (subpubic angle) differs by sex: about 90 degrees in females (rounded) and about 50-60 degrees in males (acute). The wide female subpubic angle facilitates fetal head delivery during second stage of labour.<br><br>Iliac crests (A) are upper borders of hip bones; ischial tuberosities (B) are part of pelvic outlet; sacral promontory (C) is part of pelvic inlet.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The subpubic angle in females is usually:',o:['Less than 70°','About 90°','About 50°','About 30°'],a:1,
    e:`The subpubic angle in females is usually about 90 degrees (rounded), wider than in males where it is acute (50-60 degrees).<br><br>The wide female subpubic angle is one of the key sex differences in pelvic anatomy, facilitating fetal head delivery during second stage of labour. A narrower angle (android pelvis) can cause outlet contraction and obstructed labour, requiring assisted vaginal or caesarean delivery.<br><br>About 50 degrees (A) is male typical; about 60 degrees (C) is also male; about 30 degrees (D) is too narrow.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic cavity is lined by:',o:['Camper fascia','Transversalis fascia','Endopelvic fascia','Scarpa fascia'],a:2,
    e:`The pelvic cavity is lined by endopelvic fascia, a connective tissue framework continuous throughout the pelvis providing support and pathways for vessels, nerves and lymphatics.<br><br>It condenses to form supporting ligaments: cardinal laterally, uterosacral posteriorly, pubocervical anteriorly. Damage from childbirth or chronic strain causes pelvic organ prolapse requiring surgical reconstruction. The pelvic peritoneum is reflected over upper surfaces of pelvic viscera.<br><br>Pelvic peritoneum (A) covers upper surfaces only; transversalis fascia (B) is in abdominal wall; Camper\'s fascia (D) is in abdominal wall.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The rectum begins at the level of:',o:['Coccyx','L5 vertebra','S1 vertebra','S3 vertebra'],a:3,
    e:`The rectum begins at the level of the S3 vertebra (rectosigmoid junction) and extends to the anorectal junction (about 12-15 cm long), passing through the pelvis.<br><br>The rectum follows the curve of the sacrum, lying retroperitoneally in its upper part. It does not have a true mesentery (sigmoid colon does). The rectum has three lateral curves with internal valves of Houston, important landmarks during sigmoidoscopy.<br><br>S1 vertebra (A) is upper sacral; L5 vertebra (B) is lumbar; coccyx (C) is at lower end of rectum.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The anal canal is approximately:',o:['2 cm long','4 cm long','8 cm long','10 cm long'],a:1,
    e:`The anal canal is approximately 4 cm long, extending from the anorectal junction to the anal verge.<br><br>It passes through the pelvic floor, surrounded by internal and external anal sphincters. The pectinate (dentate) line at the midpoint marks the embryological junction between hindgut (above) and proctodeum (below), with different epithelium, innervation and lymphatic drainage above and below.<br><br>2 cm long (A) is too short; 6 cm long (C) is too long; 8 cm long (D) is too long, more like rectum length.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The internal anal sphincter is composed of:',o:['Cardiac muscle','Skeletal muscle','Smooth muscle','Fibrous tissue'],a:2,
    e:`The internal anal sphincter is composed of smooth muscle, a thickening of the inner circular muscle layer of the rectal wall, under involuntary autonomic control.<br><br>It contributes to resting anal tone (about 80 percent of resting pressure), maintaining continence at rest. Sympathetic stimulation contracts it, parasympathetic relaxes during defecation. Internal sphincter dysfunction can cause faecal incontinence and may be assessed with anorectal manometry.<br><br>Skeletal muscle (A) is the external anal sphincter; both types (B) is incorrect; cardiac muscle (D) is in the heart only.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The external anal sphincter is composed of:',o:['Skeletal muscle','Smooth muscle','Cardiac muscle','Fibrous tissue'],a:0,
    e:`The external anal sphincter is composed of skeletal muscle (striated, voluntary) under control of the pudendal nerve (inferior rectal branch).<br><br>It surrounds the lower anal canal in three parts (subcutaneous, superficial and deep). Voluntary contraction maintains continence during increased intra-abdominal pressure. Damage during obstetric injury (third or fourth-degree perineal tear) causes faecal incontinence and may require surgical sphincter repair.<br><br>Smooth muscle (B) is the internal sphincter; both types (C) is incorrect; cardiac muscle (D) is in the heart only.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic diaphragm separates:',o:['Abdomen and pelvis','Pelvic cavity and perineum','Thorax and abdomen','Bladder and rectum'],a:1,
    e:`The pelvic diaphragm separates the pelvic cavity above from the perineum below. It is formed by levator ani and coccygeus muscles, providing primary muscular support to pelvic organs.<br><br>The diaphragm has openings for urethra, vagina (in females) and rectum. Damage during childbirth weakens the support, leading to pelvic organ prolapse and incontinence in affected women, requiring physiotherapy or surgical reconstruction in symptomatic cases.<br><br>Abdomen and pelvis (A) is separated by pelvic brim; pelvis and lower limb (C) is by pelvic outlet/inguinal ligament; perineum and lower limb (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'The peritoneum covering the bladder reflects onto the uterus in females forming the:',o:['Rectouterine pouch','Rectovesical pouch','Vesicouterine pouch','Paravesical pouch'],a:2,
    e:`The peritoneum covering the bladder reflects onto the uterus in females forming the vesicouterine pouch, the shallow recess between the bladder and the anterior wall of the uterus.<br><br>It is shallower than the rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas) posteriorly. During caesarean section, the bladder is reflected downward by incising the vesicouterine peritoneum to expose the lower uterine segment for incision and delivery of the fetus.<br><br>Rectouterine pouch (A) is between rectum and uterus; rectovesical pouch (B) is in males; paravesical fossa (D) is lateral to bladder.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Anatomy of the female pelvis)</em>`},
    {q:'During pelvic surgery, a surgeon identifies the pelvic splanchnic nerves arising from the sacral spinal segments and joining the inferior hypogastric plexus to supply parasympathetic fibers to pelvic organs including the bladder, rectum, uterus, and erectile tissues. From which spinal segments do these nerves arise?',o:['S2-S4','L1-L2','T10-T12','L4-S1'],a:0,
    e:`The pelvic splanchnic nerves arise from S2-S4 sacral nerve roots, carrying parasympathetic preganglionic fibres to pelvic viscera.<br><br>These nerves join the inferior hypogastric plexus and supply pelvic organs including bladder, uterus, rectum and erectile tissue. Parasympathetic stimulation causes detrusor contraction, bladder emptying, erection and rectal evacuation in normal pelvic functions.<br><br>T10-L2 (B) supplies sympathetic to pelvic viscera; L1-L2 (C) is sympathetic from lumbar splanchnic nerves; T1-T12 (D) is general thoracic sympathetic outflow.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic organs receive sympathetic fibers through:',o:['Femoral nerve','Pudendal nerve','Obturator nerve','Hypogastric nerves'],a:3,
    e:`The pelvic organs receive sympathetic fibres through the hypogastric nerves, which descend from the superior hypogastric plexus to the inferior hypogastric (pelvic) plexus.<br><br>Sympathetic preganglionic fibres arise from T10-L2 spinal cord, reach the lumbar sympathetic chain, then via lumbar splanchnic nerves to the superior hypogastric plexus, then hypogastric nerves to the pelvic plexus distributing to viscera.<br><br>Pudendal nerve (A) is somatic; vagus nerve (B) does not supply pelvis; pelvic splanchnic nerves (C) carry parasympathetic supply.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The inferior hypogastric plexus lies:',o:['On pelvic diaphragm','On sacral promontory','On lateral pelvic wall','On rectum'],a:2,
    e:`The inferior hypogastric plexus lies on the lateral pelvic wall, on the medial aspect of the internal iliac vessels, lateral to the rectum, cervix and bladder.<br><br>It receives sympathetic from hypogastric nerves and parasympathetic from pelvic splanchnic nerves, distributing autonomic supply to pelvic viscera. Damage during radical pelvic surgery causes bladder, sexual and bowel dysfunction in patients post-operatively.<br><br>Anterior pelvic wall (A) is pubic structures; pelvic floor (B) is levator ani; perineum (D) is below pelvic floor.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic inlet is heart-shaped in which pelvic type?',o:['Gynecoid','Android','Anthropoid','Platypelloid'],a:1,
    e:`The pelvic inlet is heart-shaped in the android (male-type) pelvis, narrow at the front with a prominent sacral promontory and a narrow forepelvis.<br><br>The four classic pelvic types are gynecoid (50 percent of women, ideal), android (heart-shaped, 30 percent of women), anthropoid (oval, 20 percent) and platypelloid (flat, less than 5 percent). Android pelvis predisposes to obstructed labour and assisted delivery.<br><br>Gynecoid (A) is rounded; anthropoid (C) is oval; platypelloid (D) is flat with narrow AP diameter.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic inlet is oval in which pelvic type?',o:['Anthropoid','Android','Gynecoid','Platypelloid'],a:0,
    e:`The pelvic inlet is oval (long AP, narrow transverse) in the anthropoid pelvis, with the AP diameter greater than the transverse.<br><br>Anthropoid pelvis occurs in about 20 percent of women and is more common in tall, slim women. The deep AP allows occipitoposterior positions to deliver more readily as direct OP. The transverse diameter limitation can complicate engagement of large fetal heads.<br><br>Android (B) is heart-shaped; gynecoid (C) is rounded; platypelloid (D) is flat with narrow AP.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic inlet is flat and wide in which pelvic type?',o:['Gynecoid','Anthropoid','Android','Platypelloid'],a:3,
    e:`The pelvic inlet is flat and wide in the platypelloid pelvis, with the transverse diameter much greater than the anteroposterior.<br><br>Platypelloid pelvis occurs in less than 5 percent of women and is associated with deep transverse arrest in labour. The narrow AP diameter at the inlet prevents engagement of the fetal head in the usual occipitotransverse position, often requiring caesarean delivery for safe outcome.<br><br>Gynecoid (A) is rounded; android (B) is heart-shaped; anthropoid (C) is oval with long AP diameter.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The sacral promontory projects into:',o:['Abdominal cavity','Pelvic outlet','Pelvic inlet','Perineum'],a:2,
    e:`The sacral promontory projects into the pelvic inlet, forming the posterior boundary of the inlet at the level of the first sacral vertebra (S1).<br><br>The promontory is a key landmark: the obstetric conjugate is measured from sacral promontory to the inner upper border of pubic symphysis. The diagonal conjugate is measured clinically to the lower border of pubic symphysis when the promontory can be reached.<br><br>Pelvic outlet (A) is bounded by coccyx posteriorly; pelvic mid-cavity (B) is at level of ischial spines; abdominal cavity (D) is above the pelvic brim.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The arcuate line is located on:',o:['Sacrum','Pubis','Ischium','Ilium'],a:3,
    e:`The arcuate line is located on the ilium, forming part of the iliopectineal line that demarcates the pelvic brim (boundary between false and true pelvis).<br><br>The iliopectineal line is formed by the arcuate line of the ilium (posteriorly) and the pectineal line of the pubis (anteriorly), meeting at the iliopubic eminence. Together they form the lateral boundary of the pelvic brim used in obstetric measurements.<br><br>Pubis (A) bears the pectineal line; sacrum (B) has the promontory and ala; ischium (C) has tuberosity and spine.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The pectineal line is located on:',o:['Ilium','Pubis','Ischium','Sacrum'],a:1,
    e:`The pectineal line is located on the pubis (superior pubic ramus), forming part of the iliopectineal line that demarcates the pelvic brim.<br><br>The pectineal line continues posteriorly with the arcuate line of ilium to form the iliopectineal line, the lateral boundary of the pelvic brim. It separates the false (greater) pelvis above from the true (lesser) pelvis below.<br><br>Ilium (A) bears the arcuate line; sacrum (C) has the promontory and ala; ischium (D) has tuberosity and spine.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During extensive pelvic surgery, the surgeon notes that lymphatic drainage from pelvic organs such as the cervix, bladder, and prostate often first reaches lymph nodes located along the internal iliac vessels before spreading to common iliac and para-aortic nodes. Which lymph node group therefore represents the primary pelvic drainage basin for many pelvic viscera?',o:['Internal iliac nodes','Superficial inguinal nodes','Axillary nodes','Mediastinal nodes'],a:0,
    e:`Lymphatic drainage from the cervix and upper vagina goes primarily to the internal iliac (hypogastric) nodes, with secondary drainage to obturator, external iliac and presacral nodes.<br><br>Pelvic lymphadenectomy in cervical cancer involves removal of internal iliac, external iliac, obturator and common iliac nodes. Para-aortic node involvement indicates more advanced disease (Stage IIIC2) and influences treatment with extended-field radiotherapy planning.<br><br>Para-aortic nodes (B) drain ovaries primarily; superficial inguinal nodes (C) drain vulva and lower vagina; deep cervical nodes (D) drain head and neck.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The interspinous diameter of the pelvis is measured between which anatomical landmarks and is considered the narrowest diameter of the pelvic cavity during labor?',o:['Ischial tuberosities','Ischial spines','Iliac crests','Pubic rami'],a:1,
    e:`The interspinous diameter of the pelvis is measured between the ischial spines, the prominent points on the medial aspect of the ischium at the level of the pelvic mid-cavity.<br><br>It is normally about 10.5 cm, the narrowest pelvic diameter. The fetal head reaches station 0 when the leading bony point is at the level of the ischial spines. Contraction at this level (mid-pelvis) can cause arrest of descent during labour.<br><br>Ischial tuberosities (A) define intertuberous diameter at outlet; iliac crests (C) are too wide; sacral promontory and pubis (D) define obstetric conjugate.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The transverse diameter of the pelvic inlet extends between which two structures?',o:['Ischial spines','Iliac crests','Widest points of the linea terminalis','Pubic tubercles'],a:2,
    e:`The transverse diameter of the pelvic inlet extends between the widest points of the linea terminalis (the iliopectineal line) on each side.<br><br>It is the largest transverse measurement of the inlet, normally about 13 cm. In gynecoid pelvis, the transverse diameter is slightly greater than the AP, allowing occipitotransverse engagement of the fetal head, which is the typical mechanism of normal labour.<br><br>Ischial spines (A) define interspinous in mid-pelvis; ischial tuberosities (B) define intertuberous at outlet; sacrum to symphysis (D) is the AP, not transverse.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The sacral promontory forms part of which important pelvic landmark?',o:['Pelvic outlet','Perineal body','Ischiorectal fossa','Pelvic inlet'],a:3,
    e:`The sacral promontory forms part of the pelvic inlet (brim), as the posterior boundary at the level of the first sacral vertebra.<br><br>The pelvic inlet is bounded anteriorly by the pubic symphysis upper border, laterally by the iliopectineal lines and posteriorly by the sacral promontory. It is the entry to the true pelvis through which the fetal head must pass to engage during labour.<br><br>Pelvic outlet (A) is bounded by coccyx posteriorly; pelvic mid-cavity (B) is at ischial spine level; abdominal cavity (C) is above the pelvic brim.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic diaphragm is perforated by which of the following structures in females?',o:['All of the above','Vagina','Rectum','Urethra'],a:0,
    e:`The pelvic diaphragm in females is perforated by three structures: the urethra, vagina and rectum (anal canal).<br><br>The urogenital hiatus accommodates the urethra and vagina; the rectum passes through the anal hiatus more posteriorly. These weak points are sites of pelvic organ prolapse: cystocele (bladder), urethrocele (urethra), rectocele (rectum) or uterine prolapse occur with weakness.<br><br>Urethra only (B) is partial; vagina only (C) is partial; rectum only (D) is partial; all three perforate the female pelvic diaphragm.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The arcus tendineus levator ani represents a thickening of which fascia and serves as the origin of part of the levator ani muscle?',o:['Rectal fascia','Transversalis fascia','Endopelvic fascia','Obturator fascia'],a:3,
    e:`The arcus tendineus levator ani is a thickening of the obturator fascia (covering obturator internus muscle), serving as the lateral attachment of the levator ani.<br><br>It runs from the pubic body to the ischial spine on each side, anchoring the iliococcygeus part of levator ani. The arcus tendineus fasciae pelvis (a separate structure) supports the urethra and vagina; damage during childbirth contributes to stress incontinence.<br><br>Endopelvic fascia (A) is a more general term; transversalis fascia (B) is in abdominal wall; Camper\'s fascia (C) is in abdominal wall.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The ureter enters the pelvis by crossing anterior to which structure at the pelvic brim?',o:['External iliac artery','Internal iliac artery','Femoral artery','Inferior epigastric artery'],a:0,
    e:`The ureter enters the pelvis by crossing anterior to the external iliac artery (or the bifurcation of common iliac artery into internal and external iliac) at the pelvic brim.<br><br>This is a key surgical landmark for identifying the ureter. The ureter then descends along the lateral pelvic wall, passes beneath the uterine artery near the cervix (\'water under the bridge\') and enters the bladder posteriorly at the trigone.<br><br>Internal iliac artery (B) is medial; common iliac artery (C) is the bifurcation level itself; femoral artery (D) is in the thigh.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The rectovesical pouch in males is formed by the reflection of peritoneum between which organs?',o:['Rectum and prostate','Rectum and bladder','Bladder and prostate','Bladder and seminal vesicles'],a:1,
    e:`The rectovesical pouch in males is formed by the reflection of peritoneum between the rectum and the bladder.<br><br>It is the deepest peritoneal recess in the male pelvis where free fluid collects, equivalent to the female rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas). The seminal vesicles and prostate lie below this pouch in the male pelvis, posterior to bladder.<br><br>Rectum and uterus (A) is female Pouch of Douglas; bladder and uterus (C) is female vesicouterine pouch; rectum and prostate (D) is below the pouch level.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The pudendal nerve provides motor supply to which of the following muscles?',o:['External anal sphincter','Bulbospongiosus','All of the above','Ischiocavernosus'],a:2,
    e:`The pudendal nerve provides motor supply to several muscles: external anal sphincter, sphincter urethrae (external urethral sphincter), bulbospongiosus, ischiocavernosus and superficial/deep transverse perineal muscles.<br><br>It also supplies sensation to vulva, perineum and lower vagina. Pudendal nerve block at the ischial spine provides analgesia for second-stage labour, episiotomy repair and outlet forceps delivery procedures effectively.<br><br>External anal sphincter only (A) is partial; sphincter urethrae only (B) is partial; bulbospongiosus only (D) is partial; all three are supplied.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During pelvic lymphadenectomy for carcinoma cervix, the obturator lymph nodes are frequently removed. These nodes lie in close relation to which nerve that runs along the lateral pelvic wall and may be injured during surgery?',o:['Pudendal nerve','Obturator nerve','Femoral nerve','Sciatic nerve'],a:1,
    e:`During pelvic lymphadenectomy for carcinoma cervix, the obturator lymph nodes are most closely related to the obturator nerve, which runs along the lateral pelvic wall.<br><br>The obturator nerve arises from L2-L4 and exits the pelvis through the obturator canal to supply medial thigh muscles. Injury during obturator lymphadenectomy causes weakness of thigh adduction and sensory loss in the medial thigh.<br><br>Femoral nerve (A) is more lateral; sciatic nerve (C) is posterior; pudendal nerve (D) is in the perineum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The sacroiliac joint connects which bones?',o:['Sacrum and ilium','Pubis and ilium','Sacrum and coccyx','Ischium and pubis'],a:0,
    e:`The sacroiliac joint connects the sacrum and the ilium of the hip bone bilaterally. It is a synovial joint with limited movement, providing posterior stability to the pelvic ring.<br><br>The joint is reinforced by strong anterior and posterior sacroiliac ligaments. During pregnancy, relaxin hormone allows slight relaxation of the joint, contributing to the dynamic obstetric pelvis. SI joint dysfunction is a common cause of low back pain in pregnancy.<br><br>Sacrum and pubis (B) meet at the pubic symphysis indirectly; coccyx and ilium (C) is unrelated; ilium and ischium (D) fuse in childhood.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic outlet is bounded posteriorly by which structure?',o:['Sacral promontory','Pubic symphysis','Coccyx','Ischial spine'],a:2,
    e:`The pelvic outlet is bounded posteriorly by the coccyx, the small triangular bone at the lower end of the sacrum.<br><br>The outlet is bounded anteriorly by the pubic symphysis, laterally by the ischial tuberosities and the sacrotuberous ligaments. During second stage of labour, the coccyx moves posteriorly to increase the AP diameter, facilitating fetal head delivery.<br><br>Sacral promontory (A) bounds the inlet posteriorly; ischial spine (B) is at mid-pelvis; pubic symphysis (D) bounds the outlet anteriorly.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The internal iliac artery divides into anterior and posterior divisions which supply most pelvic organs. Which branch of the anterior division is primarily responsible for blood supply to the uterus?',o:['Superior vesical artery','Inferior gluteal artery','Obturator artery','Uterine artery'],a:3,
    e:`The internal iliac artery divides into anterior and posterior divisions; the uterine artery is one of the major branches of the anterior division supplying the uterus.<br><br>The anterior division also gives umbilical, vesical, vaginal, middle rectal, internal pudendal, obturator, inferior gluteal arteries. The posterior division gives iliolumbar, lateral sacral and superior gluteal arteries supplying posterior pelvic structures and gluteal region.<br><br>Ovarian artery (A) is from aorta; superior rectal artery (B) is from inferior mesenteric; femoral artery (C) supplies lower limb.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The inferior hypogastric plexus contains fibers from which of the following components?',o:['All of the above','Pelvic splanchnic nerves','Sacral sympathetic trunk','Hypogastric nerves'],a:0,
    e:`The inferior hypogastric plexus contains fibres from sympathetic (hypogastric nerves), parasympathetic (pelvic splanchnic nerves) and visceral afferent components.<br><br>The plexus integrates autonomic supply to all pelvic viscera. Sympathetic from T10-L2 reaches via hypogastric nerves; parasympathetic from S2-S4 via pelvic splanchnic nerves. Damage during radical pelvic surgery causes bladder, sexual and bowel dysfunction in patients.<br><br>Sympathetic only (B) is partial; parasympathetic only (C) is partial; somatic only (D) is incorrect; all three components.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The perineal membrane stretches between which bony structures?',o:['Ischial spines','Inferior pubic rami','Ischial tuberosities','Iliac crests'],a:1,
    e:`The perineal membrane stretches between the inferior pubic rami (and the ischiopubic rami) on each side, forming a triangular fibrous sheet covering the urogenital triangle.<br><br>It separates the deep perineal pouch above from the superficial perineal pouch below. The membrane provides attachment for the muscles and erectile tissues of the perineum, and is pierced by the urethra and vagina (in females) or urethra alone (in males).<br><br>Iliac crests (A) are upper hip bone borders; ischial tuberosities (C) define outlet; sacrum and ilium (D) form sacroiliac joint.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The male bladder lies anterior to which structure?',o:['Urethra','Prostate','Seminal vesicles','Rectum'],a:3,
    e:`The male bladder lies anterior to the rectum, with the peritoneal rectovesical pouch between them above and direct fascial relationship below.<br><br>The seminal vesicles, vasa deferentia and prostate lie between the bladder and rectum below the pouch. The Denonvilliers fascia separates these structures from the rectum, important plane for radical prostatectomy and abdominoperineal resection of rectum.<br><br>Pubic symphysis (A) lies anterior to bladder; uterus (B) is in females only; ureter (C) lies lateral, not behind bladder.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterine artery reaches the uterus through which ligament?',o:['Broad ligament','Round ligament','Cardinal ligament','Ovarian ligament'],a:2,
    e:`The uterine artery reaches the uterus through the cardinal ligament (transverse cervical ligament of Mackenrodt), passing in its base medially toward the cervix.<br><br>The cardinal ligament extends from the lateral aspects of the cervix to the lateral pelvic wall. The ureter passes beneath the uterine artery within this ligament near the cervix, the classic \'water under the bridge\' relationship requiring careful surgical identification.<br><br>Round ligament (A) maintains anteversion; broad ligament (B) is peritoneal; uterosacral ligament (D) extends to sacrum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The lymphatic drainage of the upper rectum primarily follows the superior rectal vessels to which lymph nodes?',o:['Para-aortic nodes','Inferior mesenteric nodes','Internal iliac nodes','Superficial inguinal nodes'],a:1,
    e:`The lymphatic drainage of the upper rectum follows the superior rectal vessels to the inferior mesenteric nodes, which drain to para-aortic nodes.<br><br>Lymphatic drainage of rectum varies by level: upper rectum to inferior mesenteric nodes; middle rectum to internal iliac nodes; lower rectum and anal canal above pectinate line to internal iliac nodes; below pectinate line to superficial inguinal nodes.<br><br>Internal iliac nodes (A) receive middle rectum drainage; superficial inguinal nodes (C) drain perineum; deep cervical nodes (D) drain head and neck.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The inferior rectal artery arises from which vessel?',o:['Internal pudendal artery','Superior rectal artery','Inferior mesenteric artery','Femoral artery'],a:0,
    e:`The inferior rectal artery arises from the internal pudendal artery, while the latter is in the pudendal canal (Alcock canal) on the lateral wall of the ischiorectal fossa.<br><br>It crosses the ischiorectal fossa to reach the anal canal below the pectinate line, supplying the lower anal canal and external anal sphincter. The artery may be injured during anal surgery or perineal trauma, causing significant haemorrhage in this region.<br><br>Inferior mesenteric artery (B) gives off superior rectal; internal iliac artery (C) directly gives middle rectal; femoral artery (D) supplies lower limb.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During posterior colpotomy, a surgeon accesses the peritoneal cavity through the posterior vaginal fornix to reach the rectouterine pouch, which is the most dependent portion of the peritoneal cavity in females when standing. Accumulation of blood in ruptured ectopic pregnancy often collects in this space. Which structure forms the anterior boundary of this pouch?',o:['Rectum','Bladder','Posterior wall of uterus','Ovary'],a:2,
    e:`During posterior colpotomy, a surgeon accesses the peritoneal cavity through the posterior wall of the uterus area (specifically the peritoneum of Pouch of Douglas) via the posterior fornix of the vagina.<br><br>The procedure is used to drain pelvic abscess collected in Pouch of Douglas, the most dependent peritoneal recess in females. It is also used to drain endometriotic cysts and pelvic haematomas, avoiding abdominal entry for these collections.<br><br>Anterior wall of bladder (A) is anterior; lateral pelvic wall (B) is lateral; perineal body (D) is below.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic viscera are primarily supported by which combined anatomical structures?',o:['Pelvic diaphragm','Endopelvic fascia','Perineal body','All of the above'],a:3,
    e:`The pelvic viscera are primarily supported by the pelvic diaphragm (levator ani and coccygeus), endopelvic fascia (cardinal, uterosacral, pubocervical ligaments) and perineal body together.<br><br>All three components work synergistically to provide muscular and ligamentous support, resisting downward forces from intra-abdominal pressure. Damage to any component during childbirth or with chronic strain leads to pelvic organ prolapse requiring surgical reconstruction in symptomatic cases.<br><br>Pelvic diaphragm only (A) is partial; endopelvic fascia only (B) is partial; perineal body only (C) is partial; all three components.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The fetal skull differs from the adult skull primarily because:',o:['Bones are separated by sutures and fontanelles','Bones are rigid and immovable','Sutures are completely fused','It lacks parietal bones'],a:0,
    e:`The fetal skull differs from the adult skull primarily because the bones are separated by sutures and fontanelles, allowing some movement during labour.<br><br>The sutures (sagittal, coronal, lambdoid, frontal) and fontanelles (anterior diamond-shaped, posterior triangular) allow molding of the fetal head as it passes through the birth canal. The flat bones of the vault overlap slightly during labour, reducing skull diameters.<br><br>Bones are completely fused (B) is incorrect; skull is smaller absolutely (C) is true but not the primary functional difference; bones are flatter (D) is descriptive but not key.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The largest diameter of the fetal skull is:',o:['Suboccipitobregmatic','Occipitofrontal','Mentovertical','Biparietal'],a:2,
    e:`The largest diameter of the fetal skull is the mentovertical diameter (about 13.5 cm), measured from the chin to the most prominent point on the vertex.<br><br>The mentovertical is the presenting diameter in brow presentation, which is incompatible with vaginal delivery (except in very small babies) and usually requires caesarean section. Other key diameters: biparietal 9.5 cm; suboccipitobregmatic 9.5 cm; occipitofrontal 11.5 cm.<br><br>Suboccipitobregmatic (A) is 9.5 cm in well-flexed vertex; occipitofrontal (B) is 11.5 cm; biparietal (D) is 9.5 cm.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The biparietal diameter of the fetal skull measures approximately:',o:['7.5 cm','13.5 cm','11.5 cm','9.5 cm'],a:3,
    e:`The biparietal diameter of the fetal skull measures approximately 9.5 cm, between the two parietal eminences. It is the greatest transverse diameter of the fetal head.<br><br>Engagement of the fetal head occurs when the biparietal diameter passes through the pelvic inlet. The biparietal diameter is also widely used in fetal ultrasound for estimating gestational age and fetal head size during pregnancy.<br><br>8 cm (A) is bitemporal diameter; 11.5 cm (B) is occipitofrontal; 13.5 cm (C) is mentovertical.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The suboccipitobregmatic diameter measures:',o:['11.5 cm','9.5 cm','13.5 cm','8.0 cm'],a:1,
    e:`The suboccipitobregmatic diameter measures 9.5 cm, from the suboccipital region (just below the occipital protuberance) to the centre of the anterior fontanelle (bregma).<br><br>It is the presenting diameter in a well-flexed vertex presentation, the smallest AP diameter of the fetal skull. Maintaining flexion (chin on chest) keeps this small diameter as the leading edge during normal labour, facilitating vaginal delivery efficiently.<br><br>8 cm (A) is bitemporal; 11.5 cm (C) is occipitofrontal; 13.5 cm (D) is mentovertical.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The occipitofrontal diameter of the fetal skull measures approximately:',o:['9.5 cm','10 cm','13.5 cm','11.5 cm'],a:3,
    e:`The occipitofrontal diameter of the fetal skull measures approximately 11.5 cm, from the external occipital protuberance to the centre of the forehead.<br><br>It is the presenting diameter when the fetal head is partially deflexed (military attitude or occipitoposterior position). The larger diameter compared to suboccipitobregmatic (9.5 cm) makes deflexed head delivery more difficult and may prolong labour or require operative intervention.<br><br>8 cm (A) is bitemporal; 9.5 cm (B) is suboccipitobregmatic and biparietal; 13.5 cm (C) is mentovertical.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The mentovertical diameter measures approximately:',o:['9.5 cm','11.5 cm','13.5 cm','10.5 cm'],a:2,
    e:`The mentovertical diameter measures approximately 13.5 cm, from the chin (mentum) to the most prominent point on the vertex.<br><br>It is the largest diameter of the fetal skull, the presenting diameter in brow presentation. Brow presentation occurs when the fetal head is partially extended (between vertex flexion and full face extension) and is incompatible with vaginal delivery, usually requiring caesarean section.<br><br>8 cm (A) is bitemporal; 9.5 cm (B) is biparietal; 11.5 cm (D) is occipitofrontal diameter.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The anterior fontanelle is located at the junction of which sutures?',o:['Coronal, sagittal and frontal sutures','Coronal and sagittal','Sagittal and lambdoid','Frontal and lambdoid'],a:0,
    e:`The anterior fontanelle (bregma) is located at the junction of the coronal, sagittal and frontal sutures, between the two frontal and two parietal bones.<br><br>It is diamond-shaped, about 3 by 2 cm at birth, and closes by 18 months of age. Palpation in labour helps determine fetal head position and degree of flexion. The bregma is also a clinical site for ventricular tap or fontanelle examination in neonates.<br><br>Sagittal and lambdoid (B) define posterior fontanelle; sagittal and coronal only (C) is incomplete; lambdoid and coronal (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The posterior fontanelle lies at the junction of:',o:['Coronal and sagittal sutures','Sagittal and lambdoid sutures','Frontal and coronal sutures','Squamous sutures'],a:1,
    e:`The posterior fontanelle lies at the junction of the sagittal and lambdoid sutures, between the two parietal bones and the occipital bone.<br><br>It is triangular (Y-shaped junction), small (about 1 cm), and closes by 2-3 months of age. On vaginal examination during labour, identification of the triangular posterior fontanelle indicates a well-flexed occipitoanterior position, the most favourable for normal delivery.<br><br>Coronal and frontal (A) is incorrect; coronal and sagittal (C) is anterior fontanelle; lambdoid only (D) is incomplete.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The sagittal suture lies between which bones?',o:['Parietal bones','Frontal bones','Occipital bones','Temporal bones'],a:0,
    e:`The sagittal suture lies between the two parietal bones, running in the midline from the anterior fontanelle to the posterior fontanelle.<br><br>Its position on vaginal examination indicates the orientation of the fetal head: in occipitoanterior position the sagittal suture is in the AP diameter of the pelvis; in occipitotransverse it lies in the transverse diameter; rotation during labour aligns it for delivery.<br><br>Frontal and parietal bones (B) define coronal suture; parietal and occipital (C) define lambdoid suture; two frontal bones (D) define frontal suture.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The coronal suture lies between:',o:['Parietal and occipital bones','Frontal and parietal bones','Frontal bones','Temporal and parietal bones'],a:1,
    e:`The coronal suture lies between the frontal and parietal bones, running transversely on each side from the anterior fontanelle.<br><br>It is one of the major sutures of the fetal skull vault, allowing molding during labour as the cranial bones overlap slightly. The coronal suture is identifiable on neonatal cranial ultrasound and may be used as a landmark during craniosynostosis assessment in infants.<br><br>Two parietal bones (A) define sagittal suture; parietal and occipital (C) define lambdoid; two frontal bones (D) define frontal suture.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The lambdoid suture lies between:',o:['Occipital and temporal bones','Frontal and parietal bones','Temporal and frontal bones','Parietal and occipital bones'],a:3,
    e:`The lambdoid suture lies between the parietal and occipital bones, running on each side from the posterior fontanelle.<br><br>It is shaped like the Greek letter lambda (Λ). The lambdoid suture allows molding during labour as the cranial bones overlap. Identifying the triangular posterior fontanelle and lambdoid sutures on vaginal examination indicates a well-flexed occipital position favourable for delivery.<br><br>Two parietal bones (A) define sagittal; frontal and parietal (B) define coronal; two frontal bones (C) define frontal suture.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During labor, molding of the fetal head occurs because:',o:['Sutures are fused','Skull bones are rigid','Cranial bones overlap','Fontanelles close'],a:2,
    e:`During labour, molding of the fetal head occurs because cranial bones overlap at the sutures, reducing the skull diameters as the head passes through the birth canal.<br><br>Molding is greatest at the parietal bones overlapping at the sagittal suture, and the occipital bone slipping under the parietals at the lambdoid suture. Molding usually resolves within days after birth. Excessive molding can cause caput succedaneum or cephalhaematoma.<br><br>Bones become flexible (A) is incorrect; skull is small (B) is true but not the molding mechanism; pelvis expands (D) is partly true but the fetal head adjusts.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The presenting diameter in a well-flexed vertex presentation is:',o:['Submentobregmatic','Occipitofrontal','Mentovertical','Suboccipitobregmatic'],a:3,
    e:`The presenting diameter in a well-flexed vertex presentation is the suboccipitobregmatic diameter (9.5 cm), the smallest AP diameter of the fetal skull.<br><br>Flexion (chin on chest) maintains this small diameter as the leading edge, facilitating efficient passage through the birth canal. Maintaining flexion is the key mechanism of normal labour; deflexion increases presenting diameter to occipitofrontal (11.5 cm) and prolongs labour.<br><br>Biparietal (A) is transverse; occipitofrontal (B) is in deflexed positions; mentovertical (C) is in brow presentation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The submentobregmatic diameter measures:',o:['13.5 cm','11.5 cm','9.5 cm','10 cm'],a:2,
    e:`The submentobregmatic diameter measures 9.5 cm, from below the chin (submental region) to the centre of the anterior fontanelle (bregma).<br><br>It is the presenting diameter in face presentation when the head is fully extended (with mentum anterior position). Mentoanterior face presentation can deliver vaginally; mentoposterior cannot deliver vaginally and requires caesarean section due to mechanical incompatibility with the pelvis.<br><br>8 cm (A) is bitemporal; 11.5 cm (C) is occipitofrontal; 13.5 cm (D) is mentovertical.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The biparietal diameter extends between:',o:['Two temporal bones','Two parietal eminences','Frontal bones','Occipital bones'],a:1,
    e:`The biparietal diameter extends between the two parietal eminences, the most prominent points on the parietal bones laterally.<br><br>It is the greatest transverse diameter of the fetal head, measuring approximately 9.5 cm. Engagement of the fetal head is defined by the biparietal diameter passing through the pelvic inlet. The biparietal diameter is widely used in fetal ultrasound for biometry assessment.<br><br>Two temporal bones (A) define bitemporal; occiput and forehead (C) is occipitofrontal; chin and vertex (D) is mentovertical.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The transverse diameter of the fetal skull is represented by:',o:['Biparietal diameter','Bitemporal diameter','Occipitofrontal diameter','Mentovertical diameter'],a:0,
    e:`The transverse diameter of the fetal skull is represented by the biparietal diameter, the widest transverse measurement (9.5 cm) between the two parietal eminences.<br><br>The biparietal diameter is the key transverse measurement for fetal head engagement: when it has passed through the pelvic inlet, the head is engaged. The bitemporal diameter (8 cm) is smaller and not used as the standard transverse measurement of the fetal skull.<br><br>Suboccipitobregmatic (B) is AP diameter; occipitofrontal (C) is AP; mentovertical (D) is AP.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The bitemporal diameter measures approximately:',o:['7 cm','10 cm','9 cm','8 cm'],a:3,
    e:`The bitemporal diameter measures approximately 8 cm, between the most prominent points of the temporal bones laterally on each side of the head.<br><br>It is smaller than the biparietal diameter (9.5 cm). The bitemporal diameter is the widest transverse measurement at the level of the temporal bones, used in some obstetric contexts but less clinically relevant than biparietal for engagement assessment in normal labour.<br><br>9.5 cm (A) is biparietal; 11 cm (B) is too large; 13.5 cm (C) is mentovertical.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During vaginal examination in labor, identification of the triangular posterior fontanelle indicates:',o:['Brow presentation','Face presentation','Occipital position','Breech presentation'],a:2,
    e:`Identification of the triangular posterior fontanelle on vaginal examination in labour helps determine the occipital position of the fetal head.<br><br>If the posterior fontanelle is felt anteriorly in the pelvis, the position is occipitoanterior (favourable for delivery). If felt posteriorly, the position is occipitoposterior (less favourable, may require rotation or assisted delivery). The fontanelle\'s shape is a reliable landmark.<br><br>Degree of flexion (A) is determined by anterior fontanelle palpation; presence of caput (B) is by softness; uterine contractions (D) are timed externally.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The diamond-shaped anterior fontanelle helps determine:',o:['Degree of flexion of fetal head','Placental location','Fetal weight','Fetal sex'],a:0,
    e:`The diamond-shaped anterior fontanelle helps determine the degree of flexion of fetal head during vaginal examination in labour.<br><br>If the bregma (anterior fontanelle) is felt easily and centrally on examination, the head is partially deflexed; if not palpable or only felt at the edge of presenting part, the head is well flexed. Maintaining flexion keeps the smaller suboccipitobregmatic diameter as the leading edge.<br><br>Position of head (B) is by sagittal suture and posterior fontanelle; molding (C) is by overlap; caput (D) is by softness.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The bones forming the vault of the fetal skull include:',o:['Frontal','All of the above','Occipital','Parietal'],a:1,
    e:`The bones forming the vault of the fetal skull include two frontal bones, two parietal bones and the occipital bone (and sometimes the upper part of temporal bones).<br><br>These flat bones are connected by sutures (sagittal, coronal, lambdoid, frontal) and fontanelles (anterior, posterior). They allow molding during labour as the bones overlap slightly. The base of the skull (sphenoid, ethmoid, temporal) is fixed and does not mold during labour.<br><br>Frontal only (A) is partial; parietal only (C) is partial; occipital only (D) is partial; all are part of the vault.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During vaginal examination in labor, the obstetrician palpates the sagittal suture running in the anteroposterior diameter of the pelvis. The posterior fontanelle is felt toward the maternal sacrum indicating that the occiput is directed posteriorly. This finding suggests which fetal head position?',o:['Occipitoposterior','Occipitoanterior','Occipitotransverse','Mentoposterior'],a:0,
    e:`The obstetrician palpates the sagittal suture in the AP diameter of the pelvis with the anterior fontanelle anteriorly, indicating an occipitoposterior (OP) position.<br><br>In OP, the occiput is posterior in the maternal pelvis and the bregma anterior. OP is associated with prolonged labour, deflexed head with larger occipitofrontal diameter (11.5 cm) presenting, and may need rotational forceps, manual rotation or caesarean section delivery.<br><br>Occipitoanterior (B) has bregma posterior; occipitotransverse (C) has suture in transverse diameter; occipitolateral (D) is not standard term.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The fetal skull is divided into vault, base and face. The vault consists of flat bones joined by sutures and fontanelles that allow molding during labor, while the base consists of firmly united bones that do not undergo molding. Which part of the fetal skull undergoes molding during labor?',o:['Skull base','Facial bones','Mandible','Skull vault'],a:3,
    e:`The fetal skull is divided into vault, base and face. The vault consists of flat bones connected by sutures, allowing molding during labour through bone overlap.<br><br>The vault includes two frontal, two parietal and the occipital bones. The base consists of the sphenoid, ethmoid and temporal bones (rigid, no molding). The face is the lower part of the skull. Molding occurs only in the vault, not the base, during labour passage.<br><br>Skull base (A) is rigid; face (B) is the lower skull; whole skull (C) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The sinciput corresponds to which part of the fetal skull?',o:['Occiput','Brow and forehead','Face','Chin'],a:1,
    e:`The sinciput corresponds to the brow and forehead region of the fetal skull, the area in front of the anterior fontanelle (bregma).<br><br>Anatomical landmarks of the fetal skull include occiput (back), vertex (between fontanelles), bregma (anterior fontanelle), sinciput (forehead/brow), and face (below brows). These regions identify presentation type and the diameter presenting at the pelvic inlet.<br><br>Occipital region (A) is occiput; vertex (C) is between fontanelles; mentum (D) is the chin region of the face.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The occiput corresponds to:',o:['Chin','Forehead','Posterior part of skull','Face'],a:2,
    e:`The occiput corresponds to the posterior part of the fetal skull, the region behind the lambdoid suture and posterior fontanelle.<br><br>In a well-flexed vertex presentation (occipitoanterior position), the occiput is the leading point of the fetal head. The position of the occiput in maternal pelvis defines the position of the fetal head: OA (favourable), OP (less favourable), OT (transverse, requiring rotation).<br><br>Brow and forehead (A) is sinciput; cranial vault (B) is the whole upper part; chin region (D) is the face mentum.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'In brow presentation, the presenting diameter of the fetal skull is:',o:['Suboccipitobregmatic','Occipitofrontal','Submentobregmatic','Mentovertical'],a:3,
    e:`In brow presentation, the presenting diameter of the fetal skull is the mentovertical (13.5 cm), the largest diameter of the fetal skull.<br><br>Brow presentation occurs when the head is partially extended (between vertex flexion and full face extension). The mentovertical diameter is incompatible with vaginal delivery (except in very small babies or large pelvis), so caesarean section is usually required for safe delivery.<br><br>Suboccipitobregmatic (A) is well-flexed vertex; occipitofrontal (B) is deflexed vertex; submentobregmatic (C) is face presentation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'In face presentation, the presenting diameter is:',o:['Submentobregmatic','Suboccipitobregmatic','Occipitofrontal','Mentovertical'],a:0,
    e:`In face presentation, the presenting diameter is the submentobregmatic (9.5 cm), measured from below the chin to the centre of the anterior fontanelle.<br><br>Face presentation occurs when the head is fully extended. Mentoanterior position can deliver vaginally as the chin engages and rotates anteriorly. Mentoposterior position cannot deliver vaginally (chin cannot tuck under symphysis) and requires caesarean section for safe delivery.<br><br>Mentovertical (B) is brow presentation; suboccipitobregmatic (C) is well-flexed vertex; occipitofrontal (D) is deflexed vertex.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The greatest transverse diameter of the fetal head is:',o:['Occipitofrontal diameter','Bitemporal diameter','Biparietal diameter','Mentovertical diameter'],a:2,
    e:`The greatest transverse diameter of the fetal head is the biparietal diameter (9.5 cm), measured between the two parietal eminences.<br><br>Engagement of the fetal head is defined by the biparietal diameter passing through the pelvic inlet. The biparietal diameter is widely used in fetal ultrasound for biometry to estimate gestational age and fetal head size during pregnancy assessment.<br><br>Bitemporal (A) is 8 cm, smaller than biparietal; submentobregmatic (B) is AP diameter (face presentation); occipitofrontal (D) is AP diameter (deflexed vertex).<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The anterior fontanelle normally closes at approximately:',o:['6 months','18 months','12 months','24 months'],a:1,
    e:`The anterior fontanelle (bregma) normally closes at approximately 18 months of age. It is diamond-shaped and palpable until then in normal infants.<br><br>Premature closure (craniosynostosis of associated sutures) can cause skull deformity. Delayed closure beyond 24 months suggests rickets, hypothyroidism, hydrocephalus or chromosomal disorders. The size and tension of the anterior fontanelle are clinically assessed in well-baby checks.<br><br>6 months (A) is too early; 12 months (C) is also too early; 24 months (D) is delayed and suggests pathology.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The posterior fontanelle normally closes at approximately:',o:['18 months','6 months','12 months','2-3 months'],a:3,
    e:`The posterior fontanelle normally closes at approximately 2-3 months of age. It is small (about 1 cm), triangular, and closes much earlier than the anterior fontanelle (which closes by 18 months).<br><br>If the posterior fontanelle is wide-open beyond 3 months or large at birth, it may suggest hydrocephalus, hypothyroidism or osteogenesis imperfecta. Routine neonatal examination assesses both fontanelles for size, tension and closure timing during well-baby visits.<br><br>6 months (A) is too late; 12 months (B) is too late; 18 months (C) is when anterior fontanelle closes.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During labor, excessive molding of the fetal skull may lead to formation of a swelling on the presenting part of the scalp caused by pressure of the cervix and birth canal. This swelling, which crosses suture lines and resolves spontaneously after birth, is known as:',o:['Cephalhematoma','Caput succedaneum','Subgaleal hemorrhage','Cranial hematoma'],a:1,
    e:`Caput succedaneum is a swelling of the fetal scalp that may form during labour with excessive molding and pressure on the presenting part of the head.<br><br>It is an oedematous swelling of subcutaneous tissue overlying the presenting part, crossing suture lines (unlike cephalhaematoma which is confined to one bone). Caput typically resolves within 24-48 hours after birth without treatment, leaving no long-term sequelae normally.<br><br>Cephalhaematoma (A) is bleeding under periosteum, confined to one bone; subgaleal haemorrhage (C) is more serious bleeding; chignon (D) is from vacuum extraction.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The primordial germ cells that ultimately form the gametes originate from which embryological structure before migrating to the developing gonads?',o:['Yolk sac endoderm','Neural crest','Intermediate mesoderm','Allantois'],a:0,
    e:`The primordial germ cells (PGCs), which ultimately form the gametes, originate from the yolk sac endoderm during early embryonic development.<br><br>PGCs migrate from the wall of the yolk sac to the genital ridge (intermediate mesoderm of the developing kidney) by the fifth week of gestation. There they associate with somatic cells to form the gonad. Disruption of migration can cause germ cell tumours along the migration path.<br><br>Mesoderm (B) forms the genital ridge somatic cells; ectoderm (C) forms skin and nervous system; gonadal ridge (D) is destination, not origin of PGCs.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The ovaries develop from which embryological structure?',o:['Surface ectoderm','Neural crest','Genital ridge derived from intermediate mesoderm','Lateral plate mesoderm'],a:2,
    e:`The ovaries develop from the genital ridge derived from intermediate mesoderm, on the medial aspect of the mesonephros, in the lower thoracic and upper lumbar region.<br><br>Primordial germ cells (from yolk sac) migrate to the genital ridge by the fifth week. Without SRY gene, the gonad develops as ovary by week 8-10. The ovary then descends to its pelvic position by birth, retaining its blood supply from upper abdomen (ovarian artery from aorta).<br><br>Mesonephric duct (A) gives male reproductive structures; paramesonephric duct (B) forms uterus and tubes; urogenital sinus (D) gives lower vagina.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The paramesonephric ducts are also known as:',o:['Wolffian ducts','Allantoic ducts','Gartner ducts','Müllerian ducts'],a:3,
    e:`The paramesonephric ducts are also known as Müllerian ducts. They develop lateral to the mesonephric ducts and form the female reproductive tract above the lower vagina.<br><br>The Müllerian ducts give rise to the fallopian tubes (cranial parts), the uterus and upper two-thirds of vagina (fused caudal parts). In males, anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH) from Sertoli cells causes Müllerian regression, leaving only small remnants (appendix testis).<br><br>Wolffian ducts (A) are mesonephric ducts; Gartner ducts (B) are mesonephric remnants in females; Bartholin ducts (C) are vestibular gland ducts.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The Müllerian ducts give rise to which of the following structures in females?',o:['Uterus','Fallopian tubes','All of the above','Upper part of vagina'],a:2,
    e:`The Müllerian ducts give rise to the fallopian tubes, uterus and upper two-thirds of vagina in females.<br><br>The cranial parts remain unfused, becoming the fallopian tubes. The caudal parts fuse to form the uterus and upper vagina. The midline septum normally resorbs by week 20 to create a single uterine cavity. Failure of fusion or resorption causes uterine anomalies (didelphys, bicornuate, septate).<br><br>Fallopian tubes only (A) is partial; uterus only (B) is partial; upper vagina only (D) is partial; all three structures.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The mesonephric ducts are also called:',o:['Wolffian ducts','Müllerian ducts','Gartner ducts','Urogenital sinus ducts'],a:0,
    e:`The mesonephric ducts are also called Wolffian ducts. They form the male reproductive tract under the influence of testosterone (epididymis, vas deferens, seminal vesicles, ejaculatory ducts).<br><br>In females, the mesonephric ducts largely regress due to absence of testosterone, leaving only minor remnants: epoöphoron, paroöphoron and Gartner duct cysts (which can occur in the lateral vaginal wall). The trigone of the bladder is derived partly from these ducts.<br><br>Müllerian ducts (B) are paramesonephric; pronephric ducts (C) are vestigial; metanephric ducts (D) form the ureteric bud.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'In females, the mesonephric ducts largely regress due to absence of:',o:['Estrogen','Testosterone','Anti-Müllerian hormone','Human chorionic gonadotropin'],a:1,
    e:`In females, the mesonephric ducts largely regress due to absence of testosterone, which is required for their maintenance and differentiation in male reproductive tract development.<br><br>Without testosterone (no functional Leydig cells in absence of testes), the Wolffian ducts regress, leaving only minor remnants. Without anti-Müllerian hormone, the paramesonephric (Müllerian) ducts persist and develop into the female reproductive tract structures.<br><br>Estrogen (A) is not the maintenance factor for Wolffian ducts; AMH (C) causes Müllerian regression in males; progesterone (D) is for endometrial maintenance.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The lower one-third of the vagina develops from:',o:['Müllerian ducts','Mesonephric ducts','Urogenital sinus','Genital ridge'],a:2,
    e:`The lower one-third of the vagina develops from the urogenital sinus, specifically from the sinovaginal bulbs that proliferate from the posterior wall of the urogenital sinus.<br><br>The upper two-thirds of the vagina develops from the fused Müllerian ducts. The two parts canalise during fetal development; the hymen marks the junction between Müllerian and urogenital sinus origin. Vaginal atresia or septa can occur if these processes fail.<br><br>Müllerian ducts (A) form upper vagina; mesonephric ducts (B) form male tract; cloaca (D) is broader, divides into urogenital sinus and rectum.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The upper two-thirds of the vagina develops from:',o:['Mesonephric ducts','Müllerian ducts','Urogenital sinus','Neural crest'],a:1,
    e:`The upper two-thirds of the vagina develops from the Müllerian (paramesonephric) ducts, specifically from the fused caudal parts forming the uterovaginal canal.<br><br>The lower one-third of the vagina develops from the urogenital sinus (sinovaginal bulbs). The two parts canalise during fetal development; the hymen marks the junction. Failure of fusion or canalisation causes vaginal anomalies including transverse vaginal septum or vaginal atresia.<br><br>Mesonephric ducts (A) form male tract; urogenital sinus (C) forms lower vagina; cloaca (D) divides into urogenital sinus and rectum.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The hymen develops from:',o:['Urogenital sinus','Müllerian ducts','Mesonephric ducts','Genital tubercle'],a:0,
    e:`The hymen develops from the urogenital sinus, at the junction between the sinovaginal bulbs and the lower end of the developing vagina.<br><br>The hymen is a membrane that partially closes the vaginal opening at birth. Imperforate hymen presents at puberty with primary amenorrhoea, cyclical pelvic pain and haematocolpos (collection of menstrual blood). Treatment is hymenotomy with cruciate incision under anaesthesia.<br><br>Müllerian ducts (B) form upper vagina; mesonephric ducts (C) form male tract; cloaca (D) divides into urogenital sinus and rectum, broader origin.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The clitoris develops from:',o:['Cloacal membrane','Urogenital folds','Labioscrotal swellings','Genital tubercle'],a:3,
    e:`The clitoris develops from the genital tubercle, the same midline anterior swelling that forms the penis in males. They are embryologically homologous structures.<br><br>Without androgen exposure, the genital tubercle becomes the clitoris with glans, body and crura. With androgens (5-alpha-reductase converting testosterone to dihydrotestosterone), it elongates to form the penis. Disorders of sex development can cause clitoromegaly or ambiguous genitalia presentation.<br><br>Urogenital folds (A) form labia minora/penile urethra; labioscrotal swellings (B) form labia majora/scrotum; urogenital sinus (C) forms lower vagina/prostate.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The labia majora develop from:',o:['Labioscrotal swellings','Urogenital folds','Genital tubercle','Cloacal folds'],a:0,
    e:`The labia majora develop from the labioscrotal swellings, the paired lateral swellings on either side of the urogenital opening that fuse partially in females.<br><br>In males, the labioscrotal swellings fuse completely in the midline to form the scrotum. The labia majora and scrotum are therefore embryologically homologous structures. The labia majora contain hair, sebaceous and apocrine glands, equivalent to scrotal skin in males.<br><br>Urogenital folds (B) form labia minora; genital tubercle (C) forms clitoris/penis; urogenital sinus (D) forms lower vagina.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The labia minora develop from:',o:['Genital tubercle','Urogenital folds','Labioscrotal swellings','Cloacal membrane'],a:1,
    e:`The labia minora develop from the urogenital folds (urethral folds), the paired medial folds adjacent to the urogenital opening.<br><br>In males, the urogenital folds fuse to form the penile urethra (closing the urethral groove). In females, the folds remain unfused and become the labia minora. Hypospadias in males results from failure of urethral fold fusion, leaving an abnormal urethral opening on the ventral penis.<br><br>Labioscrotal swellings (A) form labia majora/scrotum; genital tubercle (C) forms clitoris/penis; urogenital sinus (D) forms lower vagina.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterus is formed by fusion of which embryological structures?',o:['Mesonephric ducts','Genital ridge','Urogenital sinus','Müllerian ducts'],a:3,
    e:`The uterus is formed by fusion of the Müllerian (paramesonephric) ducts in their caudal portions, with subsequent resorption of the midline septum.<br><br>The two paramesonephric ducts develop in females (without anti-Müllerian hormone); their caudal parts fuse and the midline septum normally resorbs by week 20 to create a single uterine cavity. Failure of fusion or resorption causes uterine anomalies (didelphys, bicornuate, septate).<br><br>Mesonephric ducts (A) form male tract; cloaca (B) is broader; urogenital sinus (C) forms lower vagina.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts results in:',o:['Bicornuate uterus','Unicornuate uterus','All of the above','Septate uterus'],a:2,
    e:`Failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts results in uterine anomalies including uterus didelphys (two complete uteri), bicornuate uterus (partial fusion), and unicornuate uterus (one duct fails to develop).<br><br>These anomalies vary in severity. Some are asymptomatic and detected on imaging; others cause infertility, recurrent miscarriage, preterm labour or malpresentation. Surgical repair (metroplasty) may be considered for symptomatic cases impacting reproductive outcomes significantly.<br><br>Uterus didelphys only (A) is partial; bicornuate only (B) is partial; unicornuate only (D) is partial; all three are fusion anomalies.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A septate uterus results from:',o:['Failure of Müllerian duct fusion','Failure of resorption of Müllerian septum','Absence of Müllerian ducts','Abnormal urogenital sinus'],a:1,
    e:`A septate uterus results from failure of resorption of Müllerian septum after the paramesonephric ducts have fused. The external uterine contour is normal, but a septum persists in the cavity.<br><br>A complete septum extends to the cervix; an incomplete (partial) septum extends part way down. Septate uterus is the most common Müllerian anomaly causing recurrent miscarriage; hysteroscopic septum resection improves pregnancy outcomes for most affected women.<br><br>Failure of fusion (A) causes bicornuate or didelphys; failure of canalisation (C) causes vaginal anomalies; failure of descent (D) is for ovaries.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The gubernaculum in females gives rise to which ligaments?',o:['Round ligament and ovarian ligament','Broad ligament','Cardinal ligament','Uterosacral ligament'],a:0,
    e:`The gubernaculum in females gives rise to the round ligament of the uterus and the ovarian ligament, formed by division of the gubernaculum at its attachment to the uterus.<br><br>The cranial part becomes the ovarian ligament (ovary to uterus); the caudal part becomes the round ligament (uterus to labium majus through inguinal canal). In males, the entire gubernaculum becomes the gubernaculum testis, guiding testicular descent into the scrotum.<br><br>Cardinal and uterosacral (B) are condensations of pelvic fascia; broad and round (C) is partial; uterosacral and round (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The ovaries initially develop in which region of the embryo?',o:['Pelvic cavity','Thoracic cavity','Lumbar region of posterior abdominal wall','Sacral region'],a:2,
    e:`The ovaries initially develop in the lumbar region of the posterior abdominal wall, on the medial aspect of the mesonephros at the genital ridge.<br><br>Primordial germ cells migrate from the yolk sac to the genital ridge by the fifth week. Without SRY gene, the gonad develops as ovary by week 8-10. The ovary then descends along the gubernaculum to its final pelvic position by birth, retaining its blood supply from upper abdomen.<br><br>Pelvic cavity directly (A) is final position; thoracic region (B) is too high; sacral region (D) is too low.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The descent of the ovaries into the pelvis occurs mainly due to:',o:['Broad ligament','Round ligament','Suspensory ligament','Gubernaculum'],a:3,
    e:`The descent of the ovaries into the pelvis occurs mainly due to the gubernaculum, a fibromuscular cord guiding the ovary downward as the embryo grows.<br><br>The gubernaculum extends from the lower pole of the developing ovary to the labioscrotal swelling. Differential growth between the gubernaculum and the lengthening trunk causes apparent descent of the ovary. Eventually the gubernaculum becomes the ovarian and round ligaments.<br><br>Hormonal influence (A) is partial; muscular contraction (B) is incorrect; gravity (C) is not the main factor.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'During development, the cloaca divides into urogenital sinus and anorectal canal by formation of:',o:['Neural crest cells','Cloacal membrane','Urorectal septum','Allantois'],a:2,
    e:`During development, the cloaca divides into urogenital sinus (anteriorly) and anorectal canal (posteriorly) by growth of the urorectal septum.<br><br>The urorectal septum is a wedge of mesoderm that grows downward to fuse with the cloacal membrane around week 7. Failure of this division causes cloacal anomalies including imperforate anus, rectovaginal fistula or persistent cloaca, requiring surgical correction in the neonatal period.<br><br>Müllerian duct (A) forms upper female tract; mesonephric duct (B) forms male tract; gubernaculum (D) guides gonadal descent.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The urinary bladder develops from:',o:['Mesonephric duct','Allantois','Müllerian duct','Urogenital sinus'],a:3,
    e:`The urinary bladder develops from the urogenital sinus, specifically from the upper part (vesico-urethral canal) after the cloaca is divided by the urorectal septum.<br><br>The mesonephric ducts contribute to the trigone of the bladder. The upper part of the urogenital sinus forms the bladder; the middle part forms the urethra (in females) and prostatic urethra (in males); the lower part forms the lower vagina (females) or penile urethra (males).<br><br>Mesonephric duct (A) forms male tract; Müllerian duct (B) forms female upper tract; cloaca (C) is broader, divides into urogenital sinus and anorectal canal.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'During embryological development of the female genital tract, the paired Müllerian ducts grow caudally and medially and fuse in the midline to form the uterovaginal canal. This fused structure eventually differentiates into the uterus, cervix and upper part of the vagina. Failure of this fusion can result in duplication anomalies such as uterus didelphys. Which embryological structure forms the uterus in the female fetus?',o:['Mesonephric ducts','Müllerian ducts','Urogenital sinus','Allantoic duct'],a:1,
    e:`During embryological development of the female genital tract, the paired Müllerian (paramesonephric) ducts give rise to fallopian tubes, uterus and upper two-thirds of vagina.<br><br>The cranial parts of the Müllerian ducts remain unfused, becoming the fallopian tubes. The caudal parts fuse to form the uterus and upper vagina. The midline septum normally resorbs by week 20 to create a single uterine cavity. Anomalies of fusion or resorption produce uterine malformations.<br><br>Mesonephric ducts (A) form male tract; cloaca (C) is broader origin; urogenital sinus (D) forms lower vagina and bladder.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'A congenital anomaly characterized by a uterus with two separate cavities and two cervices occurs due to complete failure of fusion of the Müllerian ducts. What is this condition called?',o:['Uterus didelphys','Bicornuate uterus','Septate uterus','Unicornuate uterus'],a:0,
    e:`Uterus didelphys is a congenital anomaly characterised by a uterus with two separate cavities and two cervices (often with a longitudinal vaginal septum), resulting from complete failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts.<br><br>Each Müllerian duct develops independently into a uterine horn with its own cervix. Pregnancy can occur in either horn but with increased risk of preterm labour and malpresentation. Surgical correction is rarely indicated unless reproductive outcomes are significantly affected.<br><br>Bicornuate uterus (B) has partial fusion (one cervix); septate uterus (C) has fusion but failed septum resorption; arcuate uterus (D) has minor indentation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A unicornuate uterus develops due to:',o:['Failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts','Abnormal urogenital sinus','Failure of septal resorption','Failure of development of one Müllerian duct'],a:3,
    e:`A unicornuate uterus develops due to failure of development of one Müllerian duct. Only one duct forms a uterine horn with one fallopian tube; the other side fails to develop.<br><br>Unicornuate uterus accounts for about 5 percent of Müllerian anomalies. It is associated with renal anomalies (ipsilateral renal agenesis in 40 percent) due to shared embryological origin from intermediate mesoderm. Pregnancy outcomes can be poorer with increased miscarriage and preterm birth risks.<br><br>Failure of fusion (A) causes didelphys/bicornuate; failure of resorption (B) causes septate; failure of canalisation (C) causes vaginal anomalies.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The genital ridge is formed from:',o:['Ectoderm','Intermediate mesoderm','Endoderm','Neural crest'],a:1,
    e:`The genital ridge is formed from intermediate mesoderm, which lies between the paraxial and lateral plate mesoderm and gives rise to the urogenital system.<br><br>The intermediate mesoderm forms the urogenital ridges (urinary and genital); the genital ridge is the medial part. Primordial germ cells (from yolk sac endoderm) migrate to the genital ridge by week 5, where they associate with somatic cells to form the gonad.<br><br>Endoderm (A) gives gut and yolk sac germ cells; ectoderm (C) forms skin and CNS; lateral plate mesoderm (D) forms body cavity walls.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The primitive gonads appear during which week of embryonic development?',o:['3rd week','7th week','5th week','10th week'],a:2,
    e:`The primitive gonads appear during the 5th week of embryonic development as paired longitudinal swellings on the medial aspect of the mesonephros.<br><br>These genital ridges are formed by proliferation of coelomic epithelium and underlying mesenchyme of intermediate mesoderm. Primordial germ cells arrive by migration from the yolk sac during the same period. The gonads remain indifferent until week 7-8, then differentiate by SRY gene.<br><br>3rd week (A) is gastrulation; 4th week (B) is too early; 7th week (D) is when sex differentiation begins.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The absence of anti-Müllerian hormone in female embryos results in:',o:['Persistence and development of Müllerian ducts','Regression of Müllerian ducts','Development of testes','Regression of ovaries'],a:0,
    e:`The absence of anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH) in female embryos results in persistence and development of Müllerian ducts, which form the female reproductive tract above the lower vagina.<br><br>AMH is produced by Sertoli cells of the testes in male embryos, causing Müllerian duct regression. Without testes (and AMH), the Müllerian ducts persist in females and develop into fallopian tubes, uterus and upper two-thirds of vagina, while mesonephric ducts regress.<br><br>Persistence of mesonephric ducts (B) requires testosterone (absent in females); failure of gonadal development (C) is gonadal dysgenesis; ovarian hyperplasia (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The broad ligament of the uterus develops from:',o:['Mesonephric duct','Genital ridge','Peritoneal folds formed during fusion of Müllerian ducts','Urogenital sinus'],a:2,
    e:`The broad ligament of the uterus develops from peritoneal folds formed during fusion of Müllerian ducts. As the ducts fuse and migrate medially, they pull the peritoneum into a transverse fold.<br><br>The broad ligament thus consists of two layers of peritoneum extending from the lateral border of the uterus to the lateral pelvic wall, containing fallopian tube, round ligament, ovarian ligament, vessels and ureter. It is not a true mechanical support of uterus.<br><br>Mesonephric remnants (A) form Gartner cysts; gubernaculum (B) forms round and ovarian ligaments; intermediate mesoderm (D) forms gonads and kidneys.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Gartner duct cysts are remnants of which embryological structure?',o:['Müllerian duct','Allantois','Urogenital sinus','Mesonephric duct'],a:3,
    e:`Gartner duct cysts are remnants of the mesonephric (Wolffian) duct, occurring in the lateral wall of the vagina or paracervical region in females.<br><br>The mesonephric ducts largely regress in females (due to absence of testosterone), but small remnants may persist as Gartner ducts running along the lateral aspects of the female reproductive tract. They occasionally develop into cysts on imaging or vaginal examination.<br><br>Müllerian duct (A) forms upper female tract; urogenital sinus (B) forms lower vagina; cloaca (C) is broader origin.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The paraovarian cyst arises from remnants of:',o:['Müllerian duct','Mesonephric duct','Urogenital sinus','Cloacal membrane'],a:1,
    e:`The paraovarian cyst arises from remnants of the mesonephric (Wolffian) duct in the broad ligament near the ovary, specifically from the epoöphoron or paroöphoron.<br><br>These cysts lie within the mesosalpinx between the ovary and fallopian tube. Most are small and asymptomatic, found incidentally on imaging or laparoscopy. Larger paraovarian cysts can cause torsion or pelvic discomfort, and may be excised surgically when symptomatic.<br><br>Müllerian duct (A) forms tubes/uterus/upper vagina; urogenital sinus (C) forms lower vagina; cloaca (D) is broader.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During embryological development of abdominal and pelvic organs, the ovaries descend from the posterior abdominal wall to the pelvis while maintaining their vascular supply from the abdominal aorta. As a result, the ovarian arteries arise directly from the abdominal aorta and travel through the suspensory ligament of the ovary to reach the gonad. From which embryological region do the ovaries originally develop before descending into the pelvis?',o:['Lumbar region of posterior abdominal wall','Thoracic cavity','Pelvic cavity','Sacral canal'],a:0,
    e:`The ovaries initially develop in the lumbar region of the posterior abdominal wall, then descend to the pelvis during fetal development guided by the gubernaculum.<br><br>The high lumbar origin explains why the ovarian artery arises directly from the abdominal aorta below the renal arteries (around L2 vertebral level), and why ovarian lymphatic drainage goes to para-aortic nodes rather than pelvic nodes - reflecting the embryological origin.<br><br>Pelvic cavity directly (B) is final position; thoracic region (C) is too high; sacral region (D) is too low.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The paramesonephric ducts in the female embryo develop into which pelvic structures?',o:['Epididymis','Uterus and fallopian tubes','Vas deferens','Seminal vesicles'],a:1,
    e:`The paramesonephric ducts in the female embryo develop into the uterus and fallopian tubes, plus the upper two-thirds of the vagina.<br><br>The cranial parts of the Müllerian ducts remain unfused, becoming the fallopian tubes (with their fimbriated open ends). The caudal parts fuse to form the uterus and upper vagina. The fused midline septum normally resorbs by week 20 to create a single uterine cavity.<br><br>Bladder and urethra (A) are from urogenital sinus; ovaries (C) develop from genital ridge; lower vagina (D) is from urogenital sinus.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The fused caudal ends of the Müllerian ducts form which pelvic structure?',o:['Ovaries','Clitoris','Labia majora','Uterus'],a:3,
    e:`The fused caudal ends of the Müllerian ducts form the uterus and upper vagina (together known as the uterovaginal canal during embryonic development).<br><br>The midline septum between the fused ducts normally resorbs by week 20 to create a single uterine cavity. Failure of fusion causes didelphys, bicornuate or unicornuate uterus; failure of resorption causes septate uterus. The fallopian tubes form from the unfused cranial parts.<br><br>Fallopian tubes only (A) are from cranial unfused parts; ovaries (B) from genital ridge; vagina lower (C) from urogenital sinus.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterovaginal canal formed during embryogenesis develops into:',o:['Fallopian tubes only','Lower vagina only','Uterus and upper vagina','Ovaries'],a:2,
    e:`The uterovaginal canal formed during embryogenesis develops into the uterus and upper vagina (upper two-thirds), formed by fusion of the caudal ends of the Müllerian ducts.<br><br>The midline septum resorbs by week 20 to create a single cavity. The lower one-third of vagina develops separately from the urogenital sinus (sinovaginal bulbs). The two parts canalise to form the continuous vagina; the hymen marks the junction between them.<br><br>Bladder only (A) is from urogenital sinus; fallopian tubes only (B) from cranial Müllerian; lower vagina only (D) from urogenital sinus.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The sinovaginal bulbs arise from which structure during development of the vagina?',o:['Urogenital sinus','Müllerian ducts','Mesonephric duct','Genital ridge'],a:0,
    e:`The sinovaginal bulbs arise from the urogenital sinus, specifically from the posterior wall of the sinus where the Müllerian ducts contact it.<br><br>The sinovaginal bulbs proliferate to form the vaginal plate, which then canalises to create the lower one-third of vagina. The upper two-thirds develops from the fused Müllerian ducts. The hymen marks the junction between the two embryological origins of the vagina.<br><br>Müllerian duct (B) forms upper vagina; mesonephric duct (C) forms male tract/Gartner remnants; gubernaculum (D) forms ligaments.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The vaginal plate formed during embryogenesis later undergoes:',o:['Calcification','Regression','Ossification','Canalization'],a:3,
    e:`The vaginal plate formed during embryogenesis later undergoes canalisation to form the lower vaginal lumen.<br><br>The vaginal plate is a solid epithelial structure formed by the sinovaginal bulbs (urogenital sinus origin). Canalisation begins centrally and proceeds craniocaudally. Failure of canalisation causes vaginal atresia or transverse vaginal septum, presenting at puberty with primary amenorrhoea and haematocolpos.<br><br>Atrophy (A) would lead to absent vagina; calcification (B) is irrelevant; muscularisation (C) does not occur in the vaginal plate.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Failure of canalization of the vaginal plate results in:',o:['Vaginal agenesis','Septate uterus','Imperforate hymen','Bicornuate uterus'],a:2,
    e:`Failure of canalisation of the vaginal plate (or the hymen specifically) results in imperforate hymen, presenting at puberty with primary amenorrhoea and cyclical pelvic pain.<br><br>Examination shows a bulging bluish hymenal membrane (haematocolpos behind it). Treatment is hymenotomy with cruciate incision under anaesthesia. Higher levels of canalisation failure produce transverse vaginal septum or vaginal atresia, requiring more complex surgical reconstruction in some cases.<br><br>Vaginal atresia (A) is more extensive failure; cervical atresia (B) is at higher level; uterine agenesis (D) is failure of Müllerian development.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The round ligament of the uterus is derived from which embryological structure?',o:['Müllerian duct','Gubernaculum','Mesonephric duct','Urogenital sinus'],a:1,
    e:`The round ligament of the uterus is derived from the gubernaculum, specifically the caudal part below the attachment to the uterus.<br><br>The cranial part of the gubernaculum becomes the ovarian ligament (ovary to uterus); the caudal part becomes the round ligament (uterus to labium majus through inguinal canal). Together they help maintain anteversion of the uterus and represent the female homologue of the male gubernaculum testis.<br><br>Mesonephric duct (A) forms male tract; Müllerian duct (C) forms upper female tract; intermediate mesoderm (D) forms gonads.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The ovarian ligament represents the cranial remnant of the:',o:['Gubernaculum','Mesonephric duct','Müllerian duct','Allantois'],a:0,
    e:`The ovarian ligament represents the cranial remnant of the gubernaculum, while the round ligament of uterus represents the caudal part below the uterine attachment.<br><br>The gubernaculum is divided at the level of its uterine attachment, with the cranial part becoming the ovarian ligament (medial pole of ovary to uterine cornu) and the caudal part becoming the round ligament (uterus to labium majus through inguinal canal).<br><br>Müllerian duct (B) forms upper tract; mesonephric duct (C) forms male tract; broad ligament (D) is peritoneal fold formed by Müllerian fusion.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'During development, the fusion of Müllerian ducts begins at which region?',o:['Cranial end','Middle portion','Caudal end','Lateral wall'],a:2,
    e:`During development, the fusion of Müllerian ducts begins at the caudal end (below) and proceeds cranially (upward) toward the cranial unfused parts that become the fallopian tubes.<br><br>The two paired ducts fuse in the midline starting from the caudal end, forming the uterovaginal canal. The midline septum then resorbs by week 20 to create a single cavity. Failure or partial fusion creates uterine anomalies; the cranial parts remain unfused as fallopian tubes.<br><br>Cranial end (A) is where tubes form (unfused); midline (B) is general but caudal first; both ends simultaneously (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Failure of development of both Müllerian ducts results in:',o:['Bicornuate uterus','Uterine agenesis','Uterus didelphys','Septate uterus'],a:1,
    e:`Failure of development of both Müllerian ducts results in uterine agenesis (and absence of upper two-thirds of vagina), since these structures are derived entirely from Müllerian ducts.<br><br>This is the basis of Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser (MRKH) syndrome, characterised by absence of uterus and upper vagina with normal ovaries (which develop separately from genital ridge). Patients present with primary amenorrhoea but normal secondary sexual characteristics.<br><br>Bicornuate uterus (A) requires partial fusion failure; septate uterus (C) requires failure of resorption; vaginal atresia (D) involves urogenital sinus failure.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser syndrome is characterized by:',o:['Absence of rectum','Absence of ovaries','Absence of bladder','Absence of uterus and upper vagina'],a:3,
    e:`Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser (MRKH) syndrome is characterised by absence of uterus and upper vagina with normal ovaries and normal secondary sexual characteristics.<br><br>It results from failure of Müllerian duct development. Karyotype is 46,XX; ovaries function normally (genital ridge origin) producing normal hormones. Patients present with primary amenorrhoea. Treatment includes vaginal dilatation or surgical creation of a neovagina for sexual function.<br><br>Absence of ovaries (A) is gonadal dysgenesis; ambiguous genitalia (B) is intersex; karyotype 45,X (C) is Turner syndrome.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The genital tubercle develops into which female pelvic structure?',o:['Clitoris','Labia majora','Vagina','Cervix'],a:0,
    e:`The genital tubercle develops into the clitoris in females (or penis in males with androgen exposure). It is the midline anterior swelling of external genitalia in the indifferent stage.<br><br>Without androgen exposure, the genital tubercle becomes the clitoris with glans, body and crura. With androgens (5-alpha-reductase converting testosterone to dihydrotestosterone), it elongates to form the penis. Disorders of sex development can cause clitoromegaly or ambiguous genitalia.<br><br>Labia majora (B) develop from labioscrotal swellings; labia minora (C) from urogenital folds; vagina (D) from Müllerian ducts/urogenital sinus.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The labioscrotal swellings develop into:',o:['Labia minora','Hymen','Clitoris','Labia majora'],a:3,
    e:`The labioscrotal swellings develop into the labia majora in females (or scrotum in males with androgen exposure). They are paired lateral swellings on either side of the urogenital opening.<br><br>In males, the labioscrotal swellings fuse completely in the midline to form the scrotum under androgen influence. In females, without androgen, they remain unfused as the labia majora. The two structures are embryologically homologous, containing similar skin and gland types.<br><br>Clitoris (A) is from genital tubercle; labia minora (B) from urogenital folds; mons pubis (C) is from anterior fusion area.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The urogenital folds develop into:',o:['Labia majora','Cervix','Labia minora','Ovaries'],a:2,
    e:`The urogenital folds (urethral folds) develop into the labia minora in females. They are paired medial folds adjacent to the urogenital opening.<br><br>In males, the urogenital folds fuse to form the penile urethra (closing the urethral groove). In females, the folds remain unfused and become the labia minora. Hypospadias in males results from failure of urethral fold fusion, leaving an abnormal urethral opening on the ventral penis.<br><br>Clitoris (A) is from genital tubercle; vagina (B) from Müllerian ducts/urogenital sinus; labia majora (D) from labioscrotal swellings.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic part of the ureter develops from:',o:['Ureteric bud','Müllerian duct','Mesonephric duct','Allantois'],a:0,
    e:`The pelvic part of the ureter develops from the ureteric bud, an outgrowth of the mesonephric (Wolffian) duct that grows cranially to induce metanephric kidney formation.<br><br>The ureteric bud forms the ureter (entire length), renal pelvis, calyces and collecting ducts. The metanephric blastema (intermediate mesoderm) forms the nephrons (glomerulus to distal tubule). Errors in ureteric bud branching cause renal anomalies including duplex kidney or hydronephrosis.<br><br>Müllerian duct (B) forms upper female tract; cloaca (C) is broader origin; urogenital sinus (D) forms bladder.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The trigone of the urinary bladder develops from:',o:['Urogenital sinus','Mesonephric ducts','Müllerian ducts','Cloacal membrane'],a:1,
    e:`The trigone of the urinary bladder develops from the mesonephric ducts, while the rest of the bladder develops from the urogenital sinus.<br><br>The mesonephric duct contributes the smooth-surfaced trigone (mesoderm origin). The remaining bladder wall is derived from the urogenital sinus (endoderm). Different embryological origins explain the distinct histology and innervation of the trigone compared to the rest of the bladder.<br><br>Müllerian ducts (A) form upper female tract; urogenital sinus (C) forms most of bladder; cloaca (D) is broader, divides further.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'During pelvic development, the cloacal membrane divides into urogenital membrane and anal membrane due to formation of:',o:['Neural crest','Müllerian ridge','Urorectal septum','Allantois'],a:2,
    e:`During pelvic development, the cloacal membrane is divided by the urorectal septum into urogenital membrane (anteriorly) and anal membrane (posteriorly).<br><br>The urorectal septum is a wedge of mesoderm that grows downward to fuse with the cloacal membrane around week 7, dividing the cloaca into urogenital sinus (anteriorly) and anorectal canal (posteriorly). Failure causes cloacal anomalies including imperforate anus or rectovaginal fistula.<br><br>Müllerian ducts (A) form upper female tract; mesonephric ducts (B) form male tract; gubernaculum (D) guides gonadal descent.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The rectouterine pouch forms embryologically due to:',o:['Regression of mesonephric ducts','Peritoneal reflections between uterus and rectum','Development of genital ridge','Migration of primordial germ cells'],a:1,
    e:`The rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas) forms embryologically due to peritoneal reflections between uterus and rectum, as the uterus develops in the midline pelvis.<br><br>The peritoneum drapes over the developing uterus anteriorly and posteriorly, forming the vesicouterine pouch (between bladder and uterus, shallow) and rectouterine pouch (between uterus and rectum, deeper). The Pouch of Douglas is the deepest peritoneal recess in females.<br><br>Cloaca (A) divides into urogenital sinus and anorectal canal; gubernaculum descent (C) forms ligaments; Müllerian fusion (D) forms uterus.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The vesicouterine pouch develops between:',o:['Bladder and uterus','Rectum and uterus','Bladder and rectum','Cervix and vagina'],a:0,
    e:`The vesicouterine pouch develops between bladder and uterus, formed by peritoneum reflecting from the bladder posteriorly onto the anterior wall of the uterus.<br><br>It is shallower than the rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas) posteriorly. During caesarean section, the bladder is reflected downward by incising the vesicouterine peritoneum to expose the lower uterine segment for safe incision and delivery of the fetus.<br><br>Bladder and rectum (B) define rectovesical pouch in males; uterus and rectum (C) define rectouterine pouch; rectum and ovary (D) is not a defined pouch.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The descent of ovaries from the posterior abdominal wall into the pelvis occurs during:',o:['Early embryonic stage','Birth','Puberty','Late fetal period'],a:3,
    e:`The descent of ovaries from the posterior abdominal wall into the pelvis occurs during the late fetal period, completing by birth or shortly after.<br><br>The ovaries develop initially in the lumbar region (genital ridge of intermediate mesoderm) and descend along the gubernaculum. They retain their original blood supply (ovarian artery from aorta) and lymphatic drainage (para-aortic nodes), unlike the male testes which descend further into the scrotum.<br><br>Embryonic period (A) is too early; early fetal period (B) is too early; postnatal period (C) is after descent is complete.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'During embryological development of the female pelvis, the paired Müllerian ducts grow caudally and fuse in the midline forming the uterovaginal canal. This canal eventually differentiates into the uterus, cervix, and upper vagina. Failure of complete fusion of the Müllerian ducts results in duplication anomalies of the uterus. Which congenital anomaly results from partial fusion of the Müllerian ducts producing two uterine horns with a single cervix?',o:['Septate uterus','Bicornuate uterus','Uterus didelphys','Unicornuate uterus'],a:1,
    e:`The paired Müllerian ducts undergo partial fusion to form a bicornuate uterus when fusion is incomplete. Two horns share one cervix but the upper portions remain separate.<br><br>Bicornuate uterus is a common Müllerian fusion anomaly. Pregnancy can occur but with increased risk of preterm labour, malpresentation and miscarriage. It is differentiated from didelphys (two cervices, complete failure of fusion) and septate uterus (normal external contour, failed septum resorption).<br><br>Septate (A) is failed septum resorption; uterus didelphys (C) is complete fusion failure; arcuate (D) is minor indentation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The sinovaginal bulbs that form the lower vagina arise from which pelvic embryological structure?',o:['Urogenital sinus','Müllerian duct','Mesonephric duct','Genital ridge'],a:0,
    e:`The sinovaginal bulbs that form the lower vagina arise from the urogenital sinus, specifically from the posterior wall where the Müllerian ducts contact it.<br><br>The sinovaginal bulbs proliferate to form the vaginal plate, which then canalises to create the lower one-third of vagina. The upper two-thirds develops from the fused Müllerian ducts. The hymen marks the junction between the two embryological origins of the vagina.<br><br>Müllerian duct (B) forms upper vagina; mesonephric duct (C) forms male tract/Gartner; cloaca (D) is broader origin.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Vaginal agenesis occurs due to failure of development of:',o:['Müllerian ducts','Mesonephric ducts','Sinovaginal bulbs','Allantois'],a:2,
    e:`Vaginal agenesis occurs due to failure of development of sinovaginal bulbs from the urogenital sinus. The lower vagina depends on this development for normal canalisation.<br><br>Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser (MRKH) syndrome involves combined failure: Müllerian agenesis (no upper vagina/uterus) plus failure of sinovaginal bulb development. Treatment may involve vaginal dilatation or surgical creation of a neovagina for sexual function and cosmetic restoration.<br><br>Müllerian ducts (A) form upper vagina; urogenital sinus (B) is general; cloaca (D) is broader.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The hymen represents the remnant of:',o:['Genital ridge','Müllerian duct','Mesonephric duct','Cloacal membrane'],a:3,
    e:`The hymen represents the remnant of the cloacal membrane (urogenital membrane portion), at the junction between the sinovaginal bulbs and the vaginal plate.<br><br>The hymen is a membrane partially closing the vaginal opening at birth. Imperforate hymen presents at puberty with primary amenorrhoea, cyclical pelvic pain and haematocolpos. Treatment is hymenotomy with cruciate incision under anaesthesia for symptomatic relief.<br><br>Müllerian duct (A) forms upper vagina; mesonephric duct (B) forms male tract; urogenital sinus (C) forms lower vagina contributing to hymen.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The broad ligament forms during development due to:',o:['Migration of germ cells','Regression of mesonephric ducts','Fusion of Müllerian ducts with peritoneal folds','Development of cloaca'],a:2,
    e:`The broad ligament forms during development due to fusion of Müllerian ducts with peritoneal folds. As the paired ducts fuse and migrate medially, they pull the peritoneum into a transverse fold.<br><br>The broad ligament thus consists of two layers of peritoneum extending from the lateral border of the uterus to the lateral pelvic wall, containing fallopian tube, round ligament, ovarian ligament, vessels and ureter. It is not a true mechanical support of the uterus.<br><br>Mesonephric remnants (A) form Gartner cysts; gubernaculum (B) forms round/ovarian ligaments; intermediate mesoderm (D) forms gonads.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic ureter in females passes close to which embryologically derived structure during development of the uterus?',o:['Ovarian artery','Uterine artery','Vaginal artery','Inferior epigastric artery'],a:1,
    e:`The pelvic ureter in females passes close to the uterine artery near the cervix, the classic \'water under the bridge\' relationship. The uterine artery (Müllerian-related vessel) crosses anterior to the ureter.<br><br>This relationship occurs about 2 cm lateral to the cervix at the cervical isthmus level. It is critical during hysterectomy: the ureter is at risk of injury during clamping or ligation of the uterine artery requiring careful identification before ligation.<br><br>Ovarian artery (A) lies in suspensory ligament at pelvic brim; vaginal artery (C) supplies vagina; round ligament (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The gubernaculum in females becomes divided into two structures due to development of the uterus. Which structures are these?',o:['Mesosalpinx and mesovarium','Broad ligament and uterosacral ligament','Suspensory ligament and cardinal ligament','Round ligament and ovarian ligament'],a:3,
    e:`The gubernaculum in females becomes divided into two structures - the ovarian ligament (cranial) and the round ligament of uterus (caudal) - due to development of the uterus, which attaches at the midpoint.<br><br>The cranial part connects ovary to uterine cornu (ovarian ligament). The caudal part connects uterus to labium majus through the inguinal canal (round ligament). In males, the entire gubernaculum becomes the gubernaculum testis, guiding testicular descent into the scrotum.<br><br>Cardinal and uterosacral (A) are pelvic fascia condensations; broad and round (B) are different origins; uterosacral and round (C) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The pelvic urethra in females develops from:',o:['Urogenital sinus','Müllerian duct','Mesonephric duct','Genital ridge'],a:0,
    e:`The pelvic urethra in females develops from the urogenital sinus, specifically from the middle (pelvic) part of the sinus.<br><br>The upper part of the urogenital sinus forms the bladder; the middle part forms the urethra (in females) and prostatic and membranous urethra (in males); the lower part forms the lower vagina (females) or penile urethra (males). The female urethra is short (4 cm).<br><br>Müllerian duct (B) forms upper female tract; mesonephric duct (C) forms male tract; cloaca (D) is broader, divides into urogenital sinus and anorectal canal.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'During development, remnants of the mesonephric duct in females may persist as structures located in the lateral vaginal wall known as:',o:['Bartholin ducts','Gartner ducts','Skene ducts','Müllerian ducts'],a:1,
    e:`During development, remnants of the mesonephric duct in females may persist as Gartner ducts in the lateral wall of the vagina or paracervical region.<br><br>These mesonephric remnants are usually small and asymptomatic, but occasionally develop into cysts on imaging or vaginal examination. Other female mesonephric remnants include epoöphoron and paroöphoron in the broad ligament near the ovary, sometimes forming paraovarian cysts.<br><br>Müllerian remnants (A) are usually absent if development is normal; epoöphoron (C) is mesonephric in mesosalpinx; corpus albicans (D) is post-luteal scar in ovary.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During embryological development of the pelvis, the peritoneum drapes over the developing pelvic organs creating pouches that remain in the adult anatomy. In females, the deepest of these peritoneal recesses lies between the posterior wall of the uterus and the anterior surface of the rectum and is clinically important because fluid or blood can accumulate in this space. What is the name of this peritoneal pouch?',o:['Rectouterine pouch','Vesicouterine pouch','Rectovesical pouch','Paravesical pouch'],a:0,
    e:`During embryological development of the pelvis, the peritoneum drapes over the developing uterus to form the rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas) posteriorly between rectum and uterus.<br><br>The vesicouterine pouch forms anteriorly between bladder and uterus. The rectouterine pouch is the deepest peritoneal recess in females, where free fluid, blood or pus tends to collect. Posterior colpotomy through the posterior fornix accesses this pouch for drainage.<br><br>Vesicouterine pouch (B) is shallower anteriorly; rectovesical pouch (C) is in males; paravesical fossa (D) is lateral to bladder.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The lining epithelium of the uterine endometrium is:',o:['Stratified squamous epithelium','Simple cuboidal epithelium','Transitional epithelium','Simple columnar epithelium'],a:3,
    e:`The lining epithelium of the uterine endometrium is simple columnar epithelium with secretory cells and ciliated cells.<br><br>The endometrium has two main layers: the functional layer (superficial, shed during menstruation) and the basal layer (deep, regenerative). The simple columnar lining undergoes cyclical changes under hormonal influence: proliferative phase (estrogen-driven) and secretory phase (progesterone-driven) in the menstrual cycle.<br><br>Stratified squamous (A) lines vagina/ectocervix; transitional (B) lines bladder; pseudostratified columnar (C) lines respiratory tract.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The endometrium is composed of which two main layers?',o:['Muscular and serosal layers','Cortical and medullary layers','Basal layer and functional layer','Fibrous and elastic layers'],a:2,
    e:`The endometrium is composed of two main layers: the basal layer (deep, regenerative) and the functional layer (superficial, shed during menstruation).<br><br>The functional layer responds to ovarian hormones with cyclical proliferation and secretion. It is shed during menstruation. The basal layer is preserved and regenerates the functional layer in each cycle. Spiral arteries supply the functional layer; straight arteries supply the basal layer.<br><br>Mucosal and serosal (A) is incorrect terminology for endometrium; muscularis only (B) is myometrium; outer and inner (D) is non-specific.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The functional layer of the endometrium is shed during:',o:['Ovulation','Implantation','Fertilization','Menstruation'],a:3,
    e:`The functional layer of the endometrium is shed during menstruation, occurring in the late luteal phase when corpus luteum regression causes progesterone withdrawal.<br><br>Progesterone withdrawal causes spiral artery vasoconstriction, ischaemia and necrosis of the functional layer, which sloughs along with menstrual blood. The basal layer is preserved and regenerates the functional layer in the next proliferative phase under estrogen influence in the cycle.<br><br>Ovulation (A) occurs mid-cycle without shedding; implantation (B) maintains endometrium; proliferative phase (C) is regrowth, not shedding.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The myometrium of the uterus mainly consists of:',o:['Skeletal muscle fibers','Dense connective tissue','Smooth muscle fibers','Elastic cartilage'],a:2,
    e:`The myometrium of the uterus mainly consists of smooth muscle fibres arranged in three layers: outer longitudinal, middle interlacing, and inner circular.<br><br>The middle interlacing layer is the thickest and contains many blood vessels (\'living ligatures\' that compress vessels during postpartum contraction, controlling bleeding). Estrogen and progesterone modulate myometrial activity; oxytocin causes powerful contractions during labour and postpartum.<br><br>Skeletal muscle (A) is voluntary; cardiac muscle (B) is in heart; connective tissue only (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The perimetrium is histologically composed of:',o:['Serous membrane','Dense cartilage','Reticular fibers','Stratified epithelium'],a:0,
    e:`The perimetrium is histologically composed of serous membrane (mesothelium overlying loose connective tissue), continuous with the peritoneum covering the uterus.<br><br>It is the outermost layer of the uterine wall, covering the fundus and most of the body anteriorly and posteriorly. The cervix and lower uterine segment have less peritoneal covering, allowing surgical access during caesarean section without entering the peritoneal cavity directly.<br><br>Smooth muscle (B) is myometrium; columnar epithelium (C) is endometrium; stratified squamous (D) lines vagina/ectocervix.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The cervix is lined by which epithelium in the endocervical canal?',o:['Stratified squamous epithelium','Simple columnar epithelium','Transitional epithelium','Cuboidal epithelium'],a:1,
    e:`The cervix is lined by simple columnar epithelium in the endocervical canal, with mucus-secreting glands that produce cervical mucus changing in consistency with the menstrual cycle.<br><br>The ectocervix (vaginal portion) is lined by stratified squamous non-keratinised epithelium. The transformation zone (T-zone) is the junction between the two epithelia, the site of squamous metaplasia and the most common location for cervical cancer development from HPV infection.<br><br>Stratified squamous (A) lines ectocervix; transitional (C) lines bladder; pseudostratified columnar (D) lines respiratory tract.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The ectocervix is lined by:',o:['Transitional epithelium','Cuboidal epithelium','Simple columnar epithelium','Stratified squamous non-keratinized epithelium'],a:3,
    e:`The ectocervix is lined by stratified squamous non-keratinised epithelium, similar to the vagina, providing protection against mechanical and chemical insults.<br><br>The endocervix is lined by simple columnar epithelium with mucus glands. The transformation zone (T-zone) is the junction between the two epithelia, the site of squamous metaplasia and the most common location for cervical cancer development from HPV infection. Pap smear samples the T-zone.<br><br>Simple columnar (A) lines endocervix; transitional (B) lines bladder; pseudostratified columnar (C) lines respiratory tract.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The transformation zone of the cervix refers to:',o:['Junction between squamous and columnar epithelium','Junction between uterus and vagina','Junction between cervix and uterus','Junction between ovary and tube'],a:0,
    e:`The transformation zone of the cervix refers to the junction between the squamous epithelium of ectocervix and columnar epithelium of endocervix.<br><br>The T-zone is the site of squamous metaplasia (columnar replaced by squamous) and the most common location for cervical cancer development from HPV infection. Pap smear samples this zone for cervical cytology screening. Colposcopic biopsies are also targeted to abnormal areas in this zone.<br><br>Junction of cervix and uterus (B) is the internal os; junction of cervix and vagina (C) is the external os; junction of cervix with broad ligament (D) is anatomical, not clinical.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The epithelium of the fallopian tube is primarily:',o:['Simple cuboidal epithelium','Stratified squamous epithelium','Ciliated simple columnar epithelium','Transitional epithelium'],a:2,
    e:`The epithelium of the fallopian tube is primarily ciliated simple columnar epithelium, with cilia beating toward the uterus to transport the ovum.<br><br>The tube has two cell types: ciliated cells (most numerous, beat toward uterus) and non-ciliated secretory cells (peg cells, produce tubal fluid). Estrogen increases cilia activity in mid-cycle, facilitating ovum transport. Tubal damage from PID can impair this transport, causing infertility or ectopic pregnancy.<br><br>Stratified squamous (A) lines vagina; pseudostratified columnar (B) lines respiratory tract; transitional (D) lines bladder.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The cells responsible for transport of ovum in the fallopian tube are:',o:['Basal cells','Ciliated columnar cells','Goblet cells','Squamous cells'],a:1,
    e:`The cells responsible for transport of ovum in the fallopian tube are the ciliated columnar cells, which beat their cilia toward the uterus, propelling the ovum along the tube.<br><br>The tube also contains non-ciliated secretory cells (peg cells) that produce tubal fluid for ovum nutrition. Estrogen increases cilia activity in mid-cycle, facilitating ovum transport. Tubal damage from PID, surgery or smoking can impair this transport, causing infertility or ectopic pregnancy risk.<br><br>Squamous cells (A) are not in the tube; secretory peg cells (C) provide nutrition not transport; muscular cells (D) cause peristalsis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The ovary is covered by which epithelium?',o:['Pseudostratified epithelium','Stratified squamous epithelium','Transitional epithelium','Germinal epithelium'],a:3,
    e:`The ovary is covered by germinal epithelium, a misnomer for a layer of simple cuboidal mesothelium continuous with the peritoneum at the mesovarium.<br><br>Despite the historical name, the germinal epithelium does not give rise to germ cells (which migrate from yolk sac). It is a peritoneal covering. Beneath it lies the tunica albuginea (dense connective tissue), then the cortex (containing follicles) and medulla (vessels and connective tissue).<br><br>Stratified squamous (A) lines vagina; columnar epithelium (B) lines tube/uterus; cuboidal epithelium (C) is partially correct but specific name is germinal epithelium.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The ovarian cortex contains:',o:['Ovarian follicles','Blood vessels only','Lymphatic tissue','Smooth muscle bundles'],a:0,
    e:`The ovarian cortex contains the ovarian follicles in various stages of development (primordial, primary, secondary, Graafian) plus the stroma.<br><br>Follicles develop from primordial (oocyte surrounded by single layer of flattened cells) through primary, secondary and Graafian (mature) under FSH stimulation. After ovulation, the corpus luteum forms from remaining cells. Atretic follicles regress without ovulating throughout reproductive life.<br><br>Blood vessels and nerves (B) are in the medulla; corpus luteum (C) is also in cortex but transient; corpus albicans (D) is also in cortex as scarring remnant.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The ovarian medulla mainly contains:',o:['Follicles','Smooth muscle cells','Blood vessels and nerves','Stratified epithelium'],a:2,
    e:`The ovarian medulla mainly contains blood vessels, nerves and lymphatics in loose connective tissue. It is the central core of the ovary.<br><br>The ovarian artery enters at the hilum (suspensory ligament side) and branches in the medulla, supplying the cortex with follicles. The medulla also contains hilus cells (similar to Leydig cells) which can rarely produce androgens, causing virilising syndromes from ovarian tumours arising from these cells.<br><br>Ovarian follicles (A) are in cortex; corpus luteum (B) in cortex; oocytes only (D) is partial of cortical follicle structure.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The primary follicle of ovary contains:',o:['Secondary oocyte','Primary oocyte surrounded by granulosa cells','Spermatocyte','Mature ovum'],a:1,
    e:`The primary follicle of ovary contains a primary oocyte surrounded by a single layer of cuboidal granulosa cells (instead of the flattened cells of primordial follicles).<br><br>The primary oocyte is arrested in prophase of meiosis I. As the follicle develops further, granulosa cells proliferate, theca cells form around them, and an antrum (fluid-filled cavity) appears in the secondary follicle. The Graafian (mature) follicle is ready for ovulation.<br><br>Secondary oocyte (A) is post-ovulation; mature ovum with antrum (C) is Graafian; corpus luteum (D) is post-ovulation luteal structure.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The antrum appears during which stage of follicular development?',o:['Primordial follicle','Primary follicle','Secondary follicle','Graafian follicle'],a:2,
    e:`The antrum (fluid-filled cavity) appears during the secondary (antral) follicle stage, formed by accumulation of follicular fluid (liquor folliculi) between granulosa cells.<br><br>Earlier stages (primordial, primary) lack an antrum. The Graafian (mature) follicle has a large antrum displacing the oocyte to one side on a cumulus oophorus. Antral fluid contains estrogen, FSH, LH and other factors that influence follicle and oocyte maturation in the cycle.<br><br>Primordial follicle (A) has no antrum; primary follicle (B) has no antrum; corpus luteum (D) is post-ovulation, without antrum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The Graafian follicle contains:',o:['Sertoli cells','Primary oocyte','Spermatogonia','Mature ovum'],a:3,
    e:`The Graafian (mature) follicle contains a mature ovum (secondary oocyte arrested in metaphase II) ready for ovulation, plus a large antrum, granulosa cells and theca cells.<br><br>The oocyte is positioned on the cumulus oophorus, surrounded by the corona radiata. At ovulation, the LH surge triggers final maturation, follicle wall rupture and release of the secondary oocyte into the peritoneal cavity, captured by the fimbriae of the fallopian tube.<br><br>Primary oocyte alone (A) is in primary follicle; primordial oocyte (B) is in primordial follicle; corpus luteum cells (C) form after ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The corpus luteum secretes mainly:',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin','Testosterone'],a:1,
    e:`The corpus luteum secretes mainly progesterone (with some estrogen), supporting the secretory phase of the endometrium and early pregnancy if implantation occurs.<br><br>After ovulation, granulosa and theca cells of the ruptured follicle luteinise to form the corpus luteum. It produces progesterone for about 14 days. If pregnancy occurs, hCG from trophoblast maintains it; if not, it regresses to corpus albicans, causing progesterone withdrawal and menstruation.<br><br>Estrogen (A) is mainly from granulosa cells of growing follicles; testosterone (C) from theca cells; FSH (D) from anterior pituitary, not corpus luteum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The vaginal epithelium is:',o:['Stratified squamous non-keratinized epithelium','Transitional epithelium','Simple columnar epithelium','Cuboidal epithelium'],a:0,
    e:`The vaginal epithelium is stratified squamous non-keratinised epithelium, providing protection against mechanical friction during intercourse and childbirth.<br><br>The vaginal epithelium contains glycogen (under estrogen influence), which is metabolised by Lactobacilli to lactic acid, maintaining the acidic vaginal pH (3.8-4.5) that protects against pathogens. Atrophic vaginitis in postmenopause causes thinning, dryness and increased susceptibility to infection.<br><br>Simple columnar (B) lines tube/uterus; transitional (C) lines bladder; pseudostratified columnar (D) lines respiratory tract.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The vagina lacks which structure histologically?',o:['Smooth muscle','Glands','Connective tissue','Blood vessels'],a:1,
    e:`The vagina lacks glands histologically. Vaginal lubrication is provided by transudate from blood vessels in the vaginal wall and by secretions from the cervical glands and Bartholin glands.<br><br>The absence of vaginal glands distinguishes it from other parts of the female reproductive tract. The Skene\'s (paraurethral) glands and Bartholin (greater vestibular) glands open into the vestibule, not the vagina proper. Vaginal pH is maintained by Lactobacilli metabolising glycogen.<br><br>Squamous epithelium (A) is present; smooth muscle (C) is in the wall; blood vessels (D) are present in lamina propria.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The prostate gland is composed of:',o:['Sweat glands','Serous glands','Mucous glands','Tubuloalveolar glands'],a:3,
    e:`The prostate gland is composed of tubuloalveolar glands (with both tubular and alveolar features) embedded in a fibromuscular stroma containing smooth muscle and connective tissue.<br><br>The prostate has anatomical zones: peripheral (where most cancers arise), central, transitional (site of BPH) and periurethral. Glandular acini are lined by simple columnar or pseudostratified columnar epithelium. Corpora amylacea (lamellated concretions) are characteristic histological features.<br><br>Simple alveolar (A) is partial; compound tubular (B) is partial; serous glands only (C) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The epithelium of the prostate gland is:',o:['Simple columnar or pseudostratified columnar','Transitional','Cuboidal','Stratified squamous'],a:0,
    e:`The epithelium of the prostate gland is simple columnar or pseudostratified columnar, lining the tubuloalveolar acini that secrete prostatic fluid into the prostatic urethra.<br><br>Prostatic fluid contains acid phosphatase, prostate-specific antigen (PSA), zinc and citric acid. It contributes about 30 percent of seminal fluid volume. PSA serum levels rise in prostate cancer, BPH and prostatitis, used clinically for screening and monitoring of prostate disorders.<br><br>Stratified squamous (B) is in vagina/ectocervix; transitional (C) is in bladder; cuboidal (D) is partial.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The characteristic structures seen in prostate histology are:',o:['Hassall corpuscles','Pacinian corpuscles','Prostatic concretions (corpora amylacea)','Meissner corpuscles'],a:2,
    e:`The characteristic structures seen in prostate histology are prostatic concretions (corpora amylacea), lamellated calcified or partially calcified bodies in the lumens of the prostatic acini.<br><br>Corpora amylacea increase in number with age and are typical findings in elderly prostates. They are not pathological per se but indicate prostatic gland activity. Other histological features include the tubuloalveolar acini, simple/pseudostratified columnar epithelium and fibromuscular stroma.<br><br>Müllerian remnants (A) form prostatic utricle; sertoli cells (B) are in testes; Leydig cells (D) in testes.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The seminiferous tubules of testes are lined by:',o:['Transitional epithelium','Germinal epithelium','Stratified squamous epithelium','Cuboidal epithelium'],a:1,
    e:`The seminiferous tubules of testes are lined by germinal epithelium consisting of spermatogenic cells (at various stages of spermatogenesis) and supporting Sertoli cells.<br><br>Spermatogenic cells include spermatogonia, primary spermatocytes, secondary spermatocytes, spermatids and spermatozoa, arranged in layers from basal lamina to lumen. Sertoli cells provide structural support and nutrition, form the blood-testis barrier and produce inhibin and AMH (in fetal life).<br><br>Stratified squamous (A) is in epidermis/oesophagus; pseudostratified columnar (C) is in respiratory tract; transitional (D) is in bladder.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The supporting cells in seminiferous tubules are:',o:['Leydig cells','Spermatocytes','Spermatogonia','Sertoli cells'],a:3,
    e:`The supporting cells in seminiferous tubules are Sertoli cells, tall columnar cells extending from the basal lamina to the tubular lumen, providing structure and nourishment for developing germ cells.<br><br>Sertoli cells form the blood-testis barrier (tight junctions), creating an immune-privileged environment for spermatogenesis. They secrete inhibin (negative feedback on FSH), androgen-binding protein (ABP) and anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH) in fetal life. FSH stimulates Sertoli cell function in adults.<br><br>Leydig cells (A) are interstitial; spermatogonia (B) are germ cells; myoid cells (C) are peritubular contractile cells.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The interstitial cells of Leydig primarily secrete:',o:['Testosterone','Progesterone','Estrogen','Prolactin'],a:0,
    e:`The interstitial cells of Leydig primarily secrete testosterone, the main androgen responsible for male secondary sexual characteristics, libido and spermatogenesis.<br><br>Leydig cells lie in the interstitial tissue between seminiferous tubules. They are stimulated by LH (luteinising hormone) from the anterior pituitary. Testosterone is converted peripherally to dihydrotestosterone (by 5-alpha-reductase, more active form) and to estradiol (by aromatase, in target tissues).<br><br>Estrogen (B) is in females and small amounts in males via aromatase; FSH (C) is from pituitary; inhibin (D) is from Sertoli cells.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The epididymis is lined by:',o:['Stratified squamous epithelium','Transitional epithelium','Pseudostratified columnar epithelium with stereocilia','Simple cuboidal epithelium'],a:2,
    e:`The epididymis is lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium with stereocilia (not motile, despite the name). The stereocilia are long microvilli that increase surface area for absorption of luminal fluid.<br><br>The epididymis has three parts (head, body, tail) and is the site of sperm maturation and storage. Sperm gain motility and fertilising capacity during transit through the epididymis. The wall contains smooth muscle that contracts during ejaculation, propelling sperm into the vas deferens.<br><br>Simple squamous (A) is in pleura/peritoneum; simple columnar (B) is in tube/uterus; stratified squamous (D) is in vagina/skin.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The stereocilia in epididymis function mainly in:',o:['Motility','Absorption','Protection','Secretion'],a:1,
    e:`The stereocilia in the epididymis function mainly in absorption of luminal fluid, removing excess fluid that accompanies sperm from the seminiferous tubules.<br><br>About 90 percent of testicular fluid is reabsorbed during epididymal transit, concentrating the sperm. The stereocilia (long microvilli) provide a large surface area for this absorption. They are non-motile, despite the name suggesting cilia. Sperm maturation also occurs during this transit time.<br><br>Movement (A) is provided by smooth muscle of wall; secretion (C) is partly by glands; protection (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The vas deferens wall contains:',o:['Elastic plates','Cartilage rings','Thick smooth muscle layers','Skeletal muscle'],a:2,
    e:`The vas deferens wall contains thick smooth muscle layers (three layers: inner longitudinal, middle circular, outer longitudinal) responsible for the powerful peristaltic contractions during ejaculation.<br><br>The thick muscular wall makes the vas palpable as a firm cord in the spermatic cord during physical examination of the scrotum. The lumen is small relative to the muscular wall thickness. Vasectomy involves cutting and ligating the vas deferens for permanent male contraception.<br><br>Thin smooth muscle (A) is in epididymis; skeletal muscle (B) is incorrect; absence of muscle (D) is wrong.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The seminal vesicle epithelium is:',o:['Stratified squamous','Transitional','Simple cuboidal','Pseudostratified columnar'],a:3,
    e:`The seminal vesicle epithelium is pseudostratified columnar, with apical secretory granules producing the alkaline fructose-rich fluid that contributes most of the seminal volume.<br><br>The seminal vesicles secrete about 60-70 percent of seminal fluid volume. The fluid contains fructose (energy source for sperm), prostaglandins, semenogelin (seminal coagulum), zinc and other factors. Each seminal vesicle joins the vas deferens to form the ejaculatory duct opening into prostatic urethra.<br><br>Simple squamous (A) is in pleura/peritoneum; stratified squamous (B) is in skin/vagina; transitional (C) is in bladder.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The seminal vesicles primarily secrete:',o:['Fructose-rich fluid','Testosterone','Mucus','Progesterone'],a:0,
    e:`The seminal vesicles primarily secrete fructose-rich fluid, providing energy for sperm motility, plus prostaglandins, semenogelin and other factors contributing 60-70 percent of seminal volume.<br><br>Fructose (rather than glucose) is the unusual sugar produced, used as energy substrate for sperm. Semen analysis includes seminal fructose measurement; absence suggests obstruction of ejaculatory ducts or congenital absence of vas deferens (CBAVD), seen in cystic fibrosis carriers and patients.<br><br>Acid phosphatase (B) is from prostate; mucus (C) is from bulbourethral glands; testosterone (D) is from Leydig cells.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'During the proliferative phase of the menstrual cycle, the endometrium shows regeneration of glands and stroma under the influence of estrogen produced by developing ovarian follicles. Which hormone is mainly responsible for this proliferative change in the endometrium?',o:['Progesterone','Prolactin','Estrogen','Oxytocin'],a:2,
    e:`During the proliferative phase of the menstrual cycle, the endometrium shows regrowth of the functional layer under estrogen influence from developing ovarian follicles.<br><br>Estrogen stimulates endometrial cell proliferation, gland elongation and increased blood vessel growth (angiogenesis). The endometrium thickens from 0.5 mm post-menstruation to about 5 mm by ovulation. Glands appear straight and tubular at this stage, in contrast to tortuous in secretory phase.<br><br>Progesterone (A) is dominant in secretory phase; FSH (B) stimulates follicle growth; LH (D) triggers ovulation, not endometrial proliferation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During the secretory phase of the menstrual cycle, endometrial glands become tortuous and start secreting glycogen-rich material under the influence of progesterone from the corpus luteum. Which structure secretes progesterone during this phase?',o:['Corpus albicans','Corpus luteum','Graafian follicle','Theca interna'],a:1,
    e:`During the secretory phase of the menstrual cycle, endometrial glands become tortuous due to progesterone from the corpus luteum. The corpus luteum forms after ovulation from granulosa and theca cells of the ruptured follicle.<br><br>Progesterone causes glandular tortuosity, glycogen accumulation, increased vascularity (spiral arteries) and stromal decidualisation, preparing the endometrium for implantation. Without pregnancy, the corpus luteum regresses, progesterone falls, and menstruation occurs in the next cycle.<br><br>Mature follicle (A) produces estrogen; primordial follicle (C) is dormant; corpus albicans (D) is post-luteal scar.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The urinary bladder is lined by which epithelium?',o:['Stratified squamous epithelium','Simple columnar epithelium','Pseudostratified epithelium','Transitional epithelium'],a:3,
    e:`The urinary bladder is lined by transitional epithelium (urothelium), which can change from cuboidal-like (when contracted) to flattened (when distended), allowing the bladder to stretch without tearing.<br><br>The transitional epithelium has umbrella cells (largest, top layer), intermediate cells and basal cells. It is impermeable to urine due to specialised tight junctions and uroplakins. Same epithelium lines the entire urinary tract from renal pelvis to proximal urethra.<br><br>Stratified squamous (A) is in vagina/skin; simple columnar (B) is in tube/uterus; pseudostratified columnar (C) is in respiratory tract.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The ureter is lined by:',o:['Transitional epithelium','Simple columnar epithelium','Stratified squamous epithelium','Cuboidal epithelium'],a:0,
    e:`The ureter is lined by transitional epithelium (urothelium), the same as the rest of the urinary tract from renal pelvis to proximal urethra.<br><br>The transitional epithelium accommodates changes in urine volume and pressure. The ureter wall also has smooth muscle (inner longitudinal, outer circular - reversed from gut) producing peristaltic waves to propel urine to the bladder. Adventitia connects the ureter to surrounding structures.<br><br>Stratified squamous (B) is in vagina/skin; simple columnar (C) is in tube/uterus; pseudostratified columnar (D) is in respiratory tract.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The female urethra is lined proximally by:',o:['Stratified squamous epithelium','Cuboidal epithelium','Transitional epithelium','Simple columnar epithelium'],a:2,
    e:`The female urethra is lined proximally by transitional epithelium (continuous with bladder), changing distally to stratified squamous epithelium near the external meatus.<br><br>The transition occurs gradually through stratified or pseudostratified columnar epithelium in the middle. The female urethra is short (about 4 cm), making women more susceptible to ascending UTI. Skene\'s glands (paraurethral glands) open into the distal urethra and may form abscesses.<br><br>Stratified squamous (A) is at the distal end only; simple columnar (B) is not in urethra; pseudostratified columnar (D) is in middle, not proximal.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The testes are covered by which dense fibrous capsule?',o:['Tunica albuginea','Tunica serosa','Tunica media','Tunica muscularis'],a:0,
    e:`The testes are covered by the tunica albuginea, a dense fibrous capsule that gives the testis its firm consistency and provides septae dividing it into lobules.<br><br>Each lobule contains 1-4 seminiferous tubules where spermatogenesis occurs. The tunica vaginalis (peritoneal-derived) covers the tunica albuginea anteriorly and laterally. Hydrocele is fluid accumulation between the layers of tunica vaginalis, presenting as scrotal swelling.<br><br>Tunica vaginalis (B) is peritoneal-derived covering; mediastinum testis (C) is internal connective tissue; rete testis (D) is internal tubule network.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The rete testis is located within:',o:['Seminiferous tubules','Epididymis','Vas deferens','Mediastinum testis'],a:3,
    e:`The rete testis is located within the mediastinum testis, the thickened part of the tunica albuginea on the posterior aspect of the testis where vessels and ducts enter.<br><br>Seminiferous tubules drain via straight tubules (tubuli recti) into the rete testis, then via efferent ductules (about 12-15 small ducts) into the epididymis. The rete testis is lined by simple cuboidal epithelium and is the convergence point of all sperm-bearing tubules.<br><br>Tunica albuginea (A) is the capsule; epididymis (B) is the next destination; pampiniform plexus (C) is the venous network around testicular artery.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The pampiniform plexus functions mainly in:',o:['Hormone secretion','Thermoregulation of testes','Sperm storage','Urine transport'],a:1,
    e:`The pampiniform plexus functions mainly in thermoregulation of testes, cooling arterial blood entering the testis to maintain testicular temperature about 2-3°C below body temperature.<br><br>The plexus is a network of veins surrounding the testicular artery in the spermatic cord, acting as a counter-current heat exchanger. Maintaining lower temperature is critical for spermatogenesis. Varicocele (dilation of pampiniform plexus) impairs cooling and can cause infertility.<br><br>Sperm production (A) is in seminiferous tubules; testosterone secretion (C) is by Leydig cells; sperm storage (D) is in epididymis.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The bulbourethral glands are histologically:',o:['Mucous glands','Serous glands','Endocrine glands','Mixed glands'],a:0,
    e:`The bulbourethral glands (Cowper glands) are histologically mucous glands, secreting alkaline mucus into the penile urethra during sexual arousal.<br><br>The two pea-sized glands are located in the deep perineal pouch, posterolateral to the membranous urethra. Their secretion lubricates the urethra, neutralises acidic urine residues and contributes a small amount to seminal fluid (\'pre-ejaculate\'). They are the male homologue of female greater vestibular (Bartholin) glands.<br><br>Serous glands (B) produce watery secretion; sebaceous glands (C) are in skin; endocrine glands (D) lack ducts.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The penis contains which erectile tissues?',o:['Three corpora cavernosa','Two corpora spongiosum','One corpus cavernosum and two corpus spongiosum','Two corpora cavernosa and one corpus spongiosum'],a:3,
    e:`The penis contains three erectile tissues: two corpora cavernosa (paired, dorsal) and one corpus spongiosum (single, ventral) which expands distally to form the glans penis.<br><br>The corpus spongiosum surrounds the urethra throughout its length. The two corpora cavernosa fill with blood during erection through cavernous spaces lined by endothelium, supplied by helicine arteries. Tunica albuginea surrounds each cavernosum, restricting expansion to maintain rigidity.<br><br>One corpus cavernosum (A) is incorrect; two cavernosa only (B) is incomplete; one spongiosum only (C) is incomplete.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The corpus spongiosum surrounds:',o:['Testicular artery','Urethra','Vas deferens','Prostate'],a:1,
    e:`The corpus spongiosum surrounds the urethra throughout its length, expanding distally to form the glans penis and proximally as the bulb of penis.<br><br>Unlike the corpora cavernosa (which are surrounded by thick tunica albuginea), the corpus spongiosum has a thinner tunica, allowing the urethra to remain patent during erection. This anatomical arrangement permits both micturition and ejaculation through the patent urethra at all times.<br><br>Vas deferens (A) is in scrotum/inguinal canal; testis (C) is in scrotum; bulbourethral gland duct (D) opens into urethra but is not surrounded.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterine glands are:',o:['Mucous glands','Compound acinar glands','Simple tubular glands','Serous glands'],a:2,
    e:`The uterine glands are simple tubular glands extending from the endometrial surface into the underlying lamina propria (stroma).<br><br>These glands are lined by simple columnar epithelium continuous with the surface epithelium. Their morphology changes with the menstrual cycle: straight in the proliferative phase, tortuous and saw-toothed in the secretory phase. Histological examination of glands helps date the endometrial sample in the cycle.<br><br>Compound tubular (A) is in mammary glands; tubuloalveolar (B) is in prostate; mucous glands (D) is general type.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The ovarian follicles are surrounded by which connective tissue layer?',o:['Fibrous capsule','Theca folliculi','Tunica media','Serosal layer'],a:1,
    e:`The ovarian follicles are surrounded by the theca folliculi, a connective tissue layer derived from the surrounding ovarian stroma as the follicle develops.<br><br>The theca folliculi differentiates into theca interna (vascular, steroidogenic, produces androgens under LH) and theca externa (fibrous, supporting). Granulosa cells of the follicle convert theca-derived androgens to estrogens via aromatase under FSH stimulation. This is the two-cell theory.<br><br>Tunica albuginea (A) covers the whole ovary; corpus luteum (C) is post-ovulation; corpus albicans (D) is post-luteal scar.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The theca interna cells produce:',o:['Progesterone only','Testosterone only','Prolactin','Estrogen precursors'],a:3,
    e:`The theca interna cells produce estrogen precursors, specifically androgens (mainly androstenedione and testosterone) under LH stimulation.<br><br>These androgens diffuse to the granulosa cells, which convert them to estradiol via the aromatase enzyme under FSH stimulation. This is the two-cell, two-gonadotrophin theory of ovarian estrogen production. The pathway is essential for follicular maturation and the LH surge that triggers ovulation.<br><br>Estrogen directly (A) is from granulosa; progesterone (B) is from corpus luteum; FSH (C) is from pituitary, not theca.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The granulosa cells convert androgens to estrogen using:',o:['Protease enzyme','Lipase enzyme','Aromatase enzyme','Amylase enzyme'],a:2,
    e:`The granulosa cells convert androgens to estrogen using the aromatase enzyme, under FSH stimulation. This is part of the two-cell, two-gonadotrophin theory of ovarian steroidogenesis.<br><br>Theca cells produce androgens (under LH); granulosa cells aromatise these androgens to estrogens (under FSH). Estrogen production peaks just before ovulation, triggering the LH surge. Aromatase inhibitors (anastrozole, letrozole) are used to block estrogen synthesis in breast cancer treatment.<br><br>5-alpha reductase (A) converts testosterone to DHT; 17-beta HSD (B) is in steroidogenesis; CYP17 (D) is in upstream synthesis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The zona pellucida surrounds:',o:['Oocyte','Granulosa cells','Corpus luteum','Theca externa'],a:0,
    e:`The zona pellucida surrounds the oocyte, separating it from the surrounding granulosa cells (corona radiata). It is a thick glycoprotein-rich extracellular matrix.<br><br>The zona pellucida is composed of glycoproteins (ZP1, ZP2, ZP3, ZP4) which bind sperm and trigger acrosomal reaction during fertilisation. After fertilisation, the zona reaction prevents polyspermy. The zona is shed at the blastocyst stage to allow implantation in the endometrium.<br><br>Granulosa cells (B) are outside zona pellucida; theca cells (C) are around follicle outside; corpus luteum cells (D) form after ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The corpus albicans is formed from:',o:['Degenerated follicle','Degenerated oocyte','Degenerated corpus luteum','Degenerated granulosa cells'],a:2,
    e:`The corpus albicans is formed from the degenerated corpus luteum after about 14 days if pregnancy does not occur. It appears as a white scar in the ovary.<br><br>The corpus luteum regresses if no pregnancy: progesterone production falls, granulosa lutein and theca lutein cells die, and connective tissue forms a scar (corpus albicans). If pregnancy occurs, hCG from trophoblast maintains the corpus luteum until placental progesterone takes over by week 10.<br><br>Atretic follicle (A) regresses but is not corpus luteum-derived; primary follicle (B) is early stage; mature follicle (D) is pre-ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterine tube mucosa is highly folded in which region?',o:['Isthmus','Intramural part','Infundibulum','Ampulla'],a:3,
    e:`The uterine tube mucosa is highly folded in the ampulla, the wide thin-walled middle segment where fertilisation usually occurs.<br><br>The mucosal folds (plicae) are most numerous and complex in the ampulla, increasing the surface area and creating channels that aid sperm-ovum interaction. The folds are simpler in isthmus (narrow segment) and intramural part. The fimbriae of the infundibulum are the most extreme mucosal projections.<br><br>Isthmus (A) has fewer folds; intramural part (B) has minimal folds; infundibulum (C) has fimbriae but ampullary folds are most complex.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The muscular layer of the fallopian tube is composed of:',o:['Circular and longitudinal smooth muscle','Elastic cartilage','Skeletal muscle','Fibrous tissue'],a:0,
    e:`The muscular layer of the fallopian tube is composed of circular and longitudinal smooth muscle (inner circular and outer longitudinal layers).<br><br>Peristaltic contractions propel the ovum from the fimbrial end toward the uterus, working with the cilia of the epithelium. Estrogen increases tubal motility in mid-cycle, facilitating ovum transport. Tubal damage from PID, surgery or smoking can impair this transport, causing infertility or ectopic pregnancy risk.<br><br>Skeletal muscle (B) is voluntary; cardiac muscle (C) is in heart; absence of muscle (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During spermatogenesis, spermatogonia undergo mitotic and meiotic divisions within seminiferous tubules supported by specialized cells forming the blood-testis barrier. Which cells form this barrier?',o:['Leydig cells','Sertoli cells','Spermatocytes','Peritubular cells'],a:1,
    e:`During spermatogenesis, spermatogonia undergo mitotic and meiotic divisions with the support of Sertoli cells in the seminiferous tubules.<br><br>Sertoli cells provide structural support, nutrition and form the blood-testis barrier (tight junctions) creating an immune-privileged environment. They secrete inhibin (negative feedback on FSH), androgen-binding protein (ABP) and anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH) in fetal life. FSH stimulates Sertoli cell function in adults.<br><br>Leydig cells (A) produce testosterone in interstitium; myoid cells (C) are peritubular contractile; basal cells (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The interstitial tissue of the testis contains which hormone-secreting cells?',o:['Leydig cells','Sertoli cells','Spermatogonia','Peritubular cells'],a:0,
    e:`The interstitial tissue of the testis contains Leydig cells, the hormone-secreting cells producing testosterone under LH stimulation from the anterior pituitary.<br><br>Leydig cells lie in the interstitial tissue between seminiferous tubules. Testosterone is converted peripherally to dihydrotestosterone (by 5-alpha-reductase, more active form) and to estradiol (by aromatase, in target tissues). Leydig cell tumours can cause virilising or feminising syndromes due to abnormal hormone production.<br><br>Sertoli cells (B) are within tubules; spermatogonia (C) are germ cells; myoid cells (D) are peritubular contractile cells.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The seminiferous tubules open into which structure before reaching the epididymis?',o:['Vas deferens','Straight tubules (tubuli recti)','Rete ovarii','Ejaculatory duct'],a:1,
    e:`The seminiferous tubules open into the straight tubules (tubuli recti), which then drain into the rete testis at the mediastinum testis before reaching the epididymis.<br><br>From the rete testis, sperm pass via efferent ductules (about 12-15 small ducts) into the epididymis. This sequence: seminiferous tubules → tubuli recti → rete testis → efferent ductules → epididymis → vas deferens → ejaculatory duct → urethra. Each level has different epithelium and function.<br><br>Vas deferens (A) is later in pathway; ejaculatory duct (C) is later; rete testis (D) is later but receives from tubuli recti.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The epithelium of the prostatic urethra is mainly:',o:['Stratified squamous epithelium','Simple cuboidal epithelium','Pseudostratified columnar epithelium','Transitional epithelium'],a:3,
    e:`The epithelium of the prostatic urethra is mainly transitional epithelium, continuous with the bladder above. It changes to pseudostratified columnar in the membranous urethra and stratified squamous near the external meatus.<br><br>The prostatic urethra contains the openings of the ejaculatory ducts (laterally on the seminal colliculus) and prostatic ducts (laterally in the gutters). The prostatic urethra is the widest and most distensible part of the male urethra.<br><br>Stratified squamous (A) is near external meatus; pseudostratified columnar (B) is in membranous urethra; simple columnar (C) is not in urethra.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The ductus deferens shows which prominent histological feature?',o:['Thin muscular wall','Absence of lumen','Very thick smooth muscle coat','Stratified squamous lining'],a:2,
    e:`The ductus deferens (vas deferens) shows a very thick smooth muscle coat with three layers (inner longitudinal, middle circular, outer longitudinal) responsible for powerful peristaltic contractions during ejaculation.<br><br>The thick muscular wall makes the vas palpable as a firm cord in the spermatic cord during physical examination. The lumen is small relative to the wall thickness, with longitudinal mucosal folds creating a star-shaped lumen on cross-section. Vasectomy involves cutting and ligating this duct.<br><br>Highly folded mucosa (A) is in seminal vesicle; thick stereocilia (B) is in epididymis; thin smooth muscle (D) is in epididymis.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The lamina propria of the vagina contains:',o:['Elastic fibers and venous plexuses','Numerous glands','Cartilage plates','Skeletal muscle bundles'],a:0,
    e:`The lamina propria of the vagina contains elastic fibres and venous plexuses. The elastic fibres allow distension during intercourse and childbirth; the venous plexuses contribute to lubrication via transudate.<br><br>The vagina lacks glands; lubrication during arousal comes from transudate through the vaginal wall plus secretions from cervical and Bartholin glands. The vaginal pH is maintained acidic (3.8-4.5) by Lactobacilli metabolising glycogen released from desquamated squamous cells of the epithelium.<br><br>Glands (B) are absent in vagina; smooth muscle (C) is in muscular layer; cartilage (D) is not in vagina.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Which cells of the ovarian follicle produce estrogen under stimulation of FSH?',o:['Theca externa cells','Stromal cells','Oocytes','Granulosa cells'],a:3,
    e:`Granulosa cells of the ovarian follicle produce estrogen under stimulation of FSH, by aromatising androgens that diffuse from theca interna cells.<br><br>This is the two-cell, two-gonadotrophin theory: theca cells produce androgens under LH; granulosa cells convert these to estrogens under FSH using aromatase. Estrogen production peaks just before ovulation, triggering the LH surge. The granulosa cells later luteinise to form the corpus luteum after ovulation.<br><br>Theca interna (A) produces androgens; theca externa (B) is fibrous supporting; stromal cells (C) are not the main estrogen source.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The ovarian stroma mainly consists of:',o:['Elastic cartilage','Cartilage and bone','Smooth muscle and connective tissue','Skeletal muscle'],a:2,
    e:`The ovarian stroma mainly consists of smooth muscle and connective tissue, with fibroblasts and spindle-shaped cells in a vascular network.<br><br>The stromal cells in the cortex contribute to follicle development and can be steroidogenic in some conditions. The medulla contains looser connective tissue with vessels, nerves and lymphatics. The stroma also contains hilus cells (similar to Leydig cells) which can produce androgens, sometimes causing virilising syndromes.<br><br>Glandular tissue (A) is not stroma; lymphoid tissue (B) is in lymph nodes; adipose tissue (D) is not predominant in stroma.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Which structure of the ovary surrounds the entire organ as a dense connective tissue capsule?',o:['Zona pellucida','Tunica albuginea','Theca interna','Corpus luteum'],a:1,
    e:`The tunica albuginea surrounds the entire ovary as a dense connective tissue capsule, lying immediately beneath the germinal epithelium (peritoneal mesothelium covering).<br><br>The tunica albuginea is thinner than that of the testis but provides structural integrity. Beneath it lies the cortex (containing follicles in various stages plus stroma), then the medulla (vessels, nerves, lymphatics in connective tissue). The ovarian surface is breached transiently at ovulation.<br><br>Germinal epithelium (A) is the outermost peritoneal covering; tunica vaginalis (C) is on the testis; corpus luteum (D) is transient post-ovulation structure.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The epithelium lining the penile urethra near the external meatus becomes:',o:['Simple cuboidal epithelium','Transitional epithelium','Pseudostratified columnar epithelium','Stratified squamous epithelium'],a:3,
    e:`The epithelium lining the penile urethra near the external meatus becomes stratified squamous epithelium, providing protection against mechanical and chemical insults at the urethral opening.<br><br>The penile urethra is mostly lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium (with patches of stratified columnar). Near the external meatus (in the navicular fossa), the epithelium changes to stratified squamous, similar to the surrounding skin and mucous membranes of the glans penis.<br><br>Transitional (A) is in proximal urethra/bladder; pseudostratified columnar (B) is in middle urethra; simple columnar (C) is not in urethra.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The duct of the seminal vesicle joins the vas deferens to form the:',o:['Prostatic duct','Urethral duct','Ejaculatory duct','Epididymal duct'],a:2,
    e:`The duct of the seminal vesicle joins the vas deferens (ductus deferens) to form the ejaculatory duct, which then passes through the prostate to open into the prostatic urethra.<br><br>The ejaculatory ducts (paired, one each side) are about 2 cm long, opening on the seminal colliculus (verumontanum) in the prostatic urethra. They transmit sperm and seminal vesicle secretion to the urethra during ejaculation. Obstruction can cause infertility and absence of fructose in semen.<br><br>Prostatic urethra (A) is the destination, not the joint structure; vas deferens (B) is one component; common ejaculatory chamber (D) is not standard term.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'During spermiogenesis, spermatids undergo morphological changes including development of the acrosome and flagellum while the nucleus condenses. This process transforms non-motile spermatids into mature spermatozoa capable of fertilization. Where does this transformation primarily occur?',o:['Epididymis','Seminiferous tubules','Vas deferens','Prostate'],a:1,
    e:`During spermiogenesis, spermatids undergo morphological changes including development of acrosome, formation of tail and condensation of nucleus, all within the seminiferous tubules.<br><br>Spermiogenesis is the post-meiotic transformation of round spermatids into mature spermatozoa. Key changes: acrosome formation from Golgi apparatus, flagellum development from centriole, mitochondrial helix formation around the midpiece, and excess cytoplasm removal as the residual body engulfed by Sertoli cells.<br><br>Epididymis (A) is for sperm maturation post-spermiogenesis; rete testis (C) is conduction; vas deferens (D) is later transport.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The acrosome of spermatozoa contains enzymes important for:',o:['Penetration of zona pellucida','Motility','Hormone synthesis','DNA replication'],a:0,
    e:`The acrosome of spermatozoa contains enzymes important for penetration of zona pellucida during fertilisation, including hyaluronidase and acrosin.<br><br>The acrosome is a cap-like structure overlying the nucleus, derived from the Golgi apparatus during spermiogenesis. The acrosomal reaction releases the enzymes upon contact with the zona pellucida, allowing the sperm to penetrate. After fertilisation, the cortical reaction modifies the zona to prevent polyspermy.<br><br>Energy production (B) is in mitochondria; sperm motility (C) is from flagellum; oocyte activation (D) is by sperm cytoplasm and signalling.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The endometrium during the secretory phase shows which characteristic histological feature?',o:['Straight tubular glands','Atrophic glands','Tortuous glands with secretions','Keratinization'],a:2,
    e:`The endometrium during the secretory phase shows tortuous glands with secretions, glycogen accumulation in cells and increased vascularity (spiral arteries).<br><br>These changes are driven by progesterone from the corpus luteum after ovulation. The glands become saw-toothed and dilated with luminal secretions of glycogen-rich material. Stromal cells decidualise. The endometrium is prepared for blastocyst implantation in the mid-secretory phase (window of implantation).<br><br>Straight tubular glands (A) are in proliferative phase; thinning of mucosa (B) is in menstrual phase; degeneration of glands (D) is in late secretory.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The stromal cells of the endometrium during the secretory phase undergo:',o:['Decidual transformation','Keratinization','Calcification','Fibrosis'],a:0,
    e:`The stromal cells of the endometrium during the secretory phase undergo decidual transformation (decidualisation) under progesterone influence, especially in late secretory phase if implantation is imminent.<br><br>Decidual cells are large, polygonal, glycogen and lipid-rich. They support the implanting blastocyst, modulate the maternal immune response, and form the decidua of pregnancy. Without pregnancy, decidualisation regresses and the endometrium is shed during menstruation.<br><br>Atrophy (B) occurs in postmenopause; squamous metaplasia (C) is rare/pathological; mucinous transformation (D) is not characteristic.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The mucosa of the epididymis is characterized by:',o:['Cartilage plates','Goblet cells','Keratinized epithelium','Long stereocilia on epithelial cells'],a:3,
    e:`The mucosa of the epididymis is characterised by long stereocilia on the pseudostratified columnar epithelium, increasing surface area for absorption of luminal fluid from sperm.<br><br>About 90 percent of testicular fluid is reabsorbed during epididymal transit, concentrating the sperm. Stereocilia are non-motile microvilli (despite the name). The wall contains smooth muscle that contracts during ejaculation, propelling stored sperm into the vas deferens for ejaculation.<br><br>Goblet cells (A) are in respiratory/intestinal mucosa; ciliated cells (B) are in fallopian tube; mucous glands (C) are in cervix or bulbourethral.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The pampiniform plexus surrounds which artery in the spermatic cord?',o:['Femoral artery','Testicular artery','Renal artery','Internal iliac artery'],a:1,
    e:`The pampiniform plexus surrounds the testicular artery in the spermatic cord, acting as a counter-current heat exchanger to cool arterial blood entering the testis.<br><br>Maintaining testicular temperature about 2-3°C below body temperature is critical for spermatogenesis. The plexus consists of 8-12 veins forming a network around the artery. Varicocele (dilation of pampiniform plexus, more common on left) impairs cooling and can cause infertility, requiring surgical correction.<br><br>Vas deferens (A) is in cord but not surrounded by plexus; ureter (C) is not in cord; common iliac artery (D) is in pelvis.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The corpus luteum is composed of:',o:['Skeletal muscle cells','Fibrous cells only','Cartilage cells','Granulosa lutein cells and theca lutein cells'],a:3,
    e:`The corpus luteum is composed of granulosa lutein cells (large, pale, derived from granulosa cells of ruptured follicle) and theca lutein cells (smaller, peripherally located, derived from theca interna cells).<br><br>Granulosa lutein cells are the major source of progesterone; theca lutein cells produce androgens that are converted to estrogens. The corpus luteum has a yellow color (lutein meaning yellow) due to lipid content. It functions for about 14 days unless rescued by hCG of pregnancy.<br><br>Granulosa only (A) is partial; theca only (B) is partial; stromal cells (C) are not the main components.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The rete testis is lined by:',o:['Simple cuboidal epithelium','Stratified squamous epithelium','Transitional epithelium','Columnar epithelium'],a:0,
    e:`The rete testis is lined by simple cuboidal epithelium, in contrast to the seminiferous tubules (germinal epithelium with spermatogenic cells and Sertoli cells) and the epididymis (pseudostratified columnar with stereocilia).<br><br>The rete testis is a labyrinthine network of channels in the mediastinum testis, the convergence point of all seminiferous tubules. Sperm pass from rete testis via efferent ductules (about 12-15) to the epididymis for further maturation and storage before ejaculation.<br><br>Stratified squamous (B) is in vagina/skin; pseudostratified columnar (C) is in epididymis; transitional (D) is in urinary tract.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The muscular coat of the uterus is thickest in which region?',o:['Cervix','Body of uterus','Fundus only','Endometrium'],a:1,
    e:`The muscular coat of the uterus (myometrium) is thickest in the body of uterus, where it forms most of the uterine wall. It is composed of three layers of smooth muscle: outer longitudinal, middle interlacing, and inner circular.<br><br>The middle interlacing layer is the thickest, containing many blood vessels (\'living ligatures\' that compress vessels during postpartum contraction, controlling bleeding). The cervix has less smooth muscle (about 10 percent compared to 70 percent in body) being mainly fibrous tissue.<br><br>Cervix (A) has less muscle; fundus (C) has thinner muscle than body; lower segment (D) is thinner in late pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Which structure in the ovary secretes progesterone after ovulation?',o:['Theca externa','Primary follicle','Corpus luteum','Germinal epithelium'],a:2,
    e:`The corpus luteum in the ovary secretes progesterone after ovulation. It forms from granulosa and theca cells of the ruptured follicle, supporting the secretory phase of endometrium.<br><br>Progesterone causes glandular tortuosity, glycogen accumulation, increased vascularity (spiral arteries) and stromal decidualisation, preparing the endometrium for implantation. Without pregnancy, the corpus luteum regresses to corpus albicans, and progesterone withdrawal triggers menstruation in the cycle.<br><br>Mature follicle (A) produces estrogen mainly; theca interna (B) produces androgens; granulosa cells (D) produce estrogen pre-luteinisation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The urethral glands of Littre are located in:',o:['Prostatic urethra','Penile urethra','Membranous urethra','Epididymis'],a:1,
    e:`The urethral glands of Littre are located in the penile urethra, opening into small pits called urethral lacunae throughout the penile urethra.<br><br>These small mucus-secreting glands lubricate the urethra and contribute to the pre-ejaculatory fluid. They are common sites for infection in gonorrhoeal urethritis. The female urethra has similar but fewer paraurethral glands (Skene\'s glands), most prominent near the external meatus opening.<br><br>Prostate (A) has prostatic glands; bladder (C) has no glands; bulbourethral glands (D) are in deep perineal pouch.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The ductuli efferentes are lined by:',o:['Cuboidal epithelium only','Stratified squamous cells','Transitional cells','Alternating ciliated and non-ciliated columnar cells'],a:3,
    e:`The ductuli efferentes are lined by alternating ciliated and non-ciliated columnar cells, giving the lumen a characteristic scalloped appearance on histology.<br><br>Ciliated cells beat toward the epididymis, propelling sperm and fluid; non-ciliated cells absorb most of the testicular fluid. About 12-15 efferent ductules connect the rete testis to the head of the epididymis. Their characteristic scalloped lumen distinguishes them from the smooth lumen of epididymis.<br><br>Pseudostratified with stereocilia (A) is epididymis; simple cuboidal (B) is rete testis; stratified squamous (C) is in skin/vagina.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The cervix contains numerous glands known as:',o:['Bartholin glands','Uterine glands','Endocervical glands','Skene glands'],a:2,
    e:`The cervix contains numerous glands known as endocervical glands, which secrete cervical mucus that varies in consistency with the menstrual cycle.<br><br>Cervical mucus is thin, watery and stretchy at ovulation (under estrogen, allowing sperm transit) and thick, scant and viscous in luteal phase or pregnancy (under progesterone, blocking sperm). Nabothian cysts form when endocervical glands are blocked, commonly seen on cervical examination.<br><br>Endometrial glands (A) are in uterine body; uterine glands (B) are in body; vaginal glands (D) are absent (vagina lacks glands).<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The mucosa of the seminal vesicle is characterized by:',o:['Highly folded mucosal surface','Flat smooth surface','Keratinized lining','Ciliated cuboidal epithelium'],a:0,
    e:`The mucosa of the seminal vesicle is characterised by a highly folded mucosal surface forming intricate primary, secondary and tertiary folds that increase surface area for secretion.<br><br>The folded mucosa creates a labyrinthine pattern with multiple chambers visible on histology. The lining is pseudostratified columnar epithelium with apical secretory granules producing the alkaline fructose-rich fluid (60-70 percent of seminal volume). The wall contains smooth muscle for ejaculatory contraction.<br><br>Smooth surface (B) is incorrect; villi (C) are in intestine; cilia (D) are in fallopian tube/efferent ductules.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which reproductive structure lacks a submucosa layer histologically?',o:['Uterus','Prostate','Vagina','Epididymis'],a:2,
    e:`The vagina lacks a submucosa layer histologically. The mucosa lies directly on the muscularis without an intervening submucosa, an unusual feature distinguishing it from most tubular organs.<br><br>The vaginal wall has three layers: mucosa (stratified squamous epithelium plus lamina propria), muscularis (smooth muscle), and adventitia (connective tissue connecting to surrounding structures). The lamina propria of mucosa contains elastic fibres and venous plexuses but no submucosa as a distinct layer.<br><br>Stomach (A) has all four layers; intestine (B) has all four; uterus (D) has endometrium-myometrium-perimetrium structure.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The glans penis is formed by expansion of:',o:['Tunica albuginea','Corpus cavernosum','Urethral glands','Corpus spongiosum'],a:3,
    e:`The glans penis is formed by expansion of the corpus spongiosum at the distal end of the penis. The corpus spongiosum surrounds the urethra throughout its length and expands distally as the glans.<br><br>The glans is covered by the prepuce (foreskin) until circumcision. It contains numerous sensory nerve endings (most densely innervated area of penis). The corona of the glans is the proximal raised border. The glans is highly vascularised but does not contain the rigid cavernous tissue of the corpora cavernosa.<br><br>Corpora cavernosa (A) form penile shaft erectile tissue; tunica albuginea (B) is connective tissue; deep dorsal vein (C) drains penis.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The tunica albuginea of the ovary lies immediately beneath:',o:['Theca interna','Germinal epithelium','Zona pellucida','Endometrium'],a:1,
    e:`The tunica albuginea of the ovary lies immediately beneath the germinal epithelium (peritoneal mesothelium covering the ovarian surface).<br><br>The tunica albuginea is a dense connective tissue capsule providing structural integrity. Beneath it lies the cortex (containing follicles in various stages of development plus stroma), then the medulla (vessels, nerves, lymphatics in connective tissue). The ovarian surface is breached transiently at ovulation.<br><br>Granulosa layer (A) is around oocyte in follicle; medulla (C) is innermost; stroma (D) is the supporting tissue.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The granulosa cells surrounding the oocyte are collectively called:',o:['Corona radiata','Tunica albuginea','Corpus albicans','Zona pellucida'],a:0,
    e:`The granulosa cells immediately surrounding the oocyte in the Graafian follicle are collectively called the corona radiata. They surround the oocyte and zona pellucida.<br><br>At ovulation, the secondary oocyte is released along with the corona radiata and zona pellucida into the peritoneal cavity, captured by the fimbriae of the fallopian tube. The corona radiata cells stay with the oocyte during early fertilisation; sperm must penetrate them along with the zona to reach the oocyte.<br><br>Cumulus oophorus (B) is the wider mound of granulosa cells; theca interna (C) is outside follicle; theca externa (D) is supporting layer.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Which structure provides nourishment to developing sperm cells within seminiferous tubules?',o:['Granulosa cells','Leydig cells','Theca cells','Sertoli cells'],a:3,
    e:`Sertoli cells provide nourishment to developing sperm cells within seminiferous tubules. They extend from the basal lamina to the lumen, surrounding and supporting germ cells at all stages of spermatogenesis.<br><br>Sertoli cells form the blood-testis barrier (tight junctions), creating an immune-privileged environment essential for spermatogenesis. They secrete inhibin, androgen-binding protein (ABP) and AMH (in fetal life). FSH stimulates Sertoli cell function, while LH stimulates Leydig cells in adults.<br><br>Leydig cells (A) produce testosterone; spermatogonia (B) are germ cells; myoid cells (C) are peritubular contractile cells.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The epithelial lining of the uterine cervix secretes:',o:['Cervical mucus','Progesterone','Testosterone','Fructose'],a:0,
    e:`The epithelial lining of the uterine cervix secretes cervical mucus, which varies in consistency with the menstrual cycle and serves multiple reproductive functions.<br><br>Cervical mucus is thin, watery and stretchy at ovulation (under estrogen, forming \'spinnbarkeit\' that allows sperm transit) and thick, scant and viscous in luteal phase or pregnancy (under progesterone, forming a barrier blocking sperm and pathogens). The mucus is sampled in fern test for ovulation assessment.<br><br>Estrogen (B) is from ovary; progesterone (C) from corpus luteum/placenta; LH (D) from pituitary.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During ovulation, the mature Graafian follicle ruptures releasing the secondary oocyte surrounded by corona radiata cells into the peritoneal cavity near the fimbriae of the uterine tube. This process occurs due to a surge in which hormone?',o:['Follicle stimulating hormone','Luteinizing hormone','Prolactin','Oxytocin'],a:1,
    e:`During ovulation, the mature Graafian follicle ruptures releasing the secondary oocyte in response to a surge of luteinising hormone (LH) from the anterior pituitary.<br><br>The LH surge is triggered by sustained high estrogen from the mature follicle (positive feedback). LH causes final maturation of oocyte (resumption of meiosis I), follicle wall rupture, and release of the secondary oocyte (arrested in metaphase II) into the peritoneal cavity, captured by tubal fimbriae.<br><br>FSH (A) stimulates follicle growth before LH surge; progesterone (C) is post-ovulation; estrogen (D) triggers LH surge but not directly ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The perimetrium of the uterus corresponds to:',o:['Glandular epithelium','Smooth muscle layer','Visceral peritoneum','Fibrous capsule'],a:2,
    e:`The perimetrium of the uterus corresponds to the visceral peritoneum, a serous membrane (mesothelium overlying loose connective tissue) covering most of the body of the uterus.<br><br>It is the outermost layer of the uterine wall, continuous with the broad ligament laterally. The cervix and lower uterine segment have less peritoneal covering, allowing surgical access during caesarean section without entering the peritoneal cavity directly. Endometritis affects the inner endometrium primarily.<br><br>Endometrium (A) is innermost mucosa; myometrium (B) is muscular layer; mucous membrane (D) is generic term.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The vas deferens mucosa shows:',o:['Longitudinal folds forming star-shaped lumen','Smooth flat lining','Keratinized epithelium','Goblet cells'],a:0,
    e:`The vas deferens mucosa shows longitudinal folds forming a star-shaped lumen on cross-section, characteristic on histology of the vas deferens.<br><br>The lumen is small relative to the very thick smooth muscle wall (three layers: inner longitudinal, middle circular, outer longitudinal) responsible for powerful peristaltic contractions during ejaculation. The mucosa is lined by pseudostratified columnar epithelium with stereocilia, similar to epididymis.<br><br>Smooth circular lumen (B) is incorrect; villi (C) are in intestine; cilia (D) are in fallopian tube/efferent ductules.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The ejaculatory ducts open into:',o:['Bladder','Membranous urethra','Prostatic urethra','Epididymis'],a:2,
    e:`The ejaculatory ducts open into the prostatic urethra at the seminal colliculus (verumontanum), a small elevation on the posterior wall of the prostatic urethra.<br><br>The ejaculatory ducts (paired) are about 2 cm long, formed by union of vas deferens and seminal vesicle duct. They pass through the prostate to open laterally on the seminal colliculus. The prostatic ducts also open into the prostatic urethra in lateral gutters around the colliculus.<br><br>Membranous urethra (A) is below prostatic; penile urethra (B) is distal; bladder (D) is above urethra.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The female urethra is approximately:',o:['10 cm long','4 cm long','15 cm long','20 cm long'],a:1,
    e:`The female urethra is approximately 4 cm long, much shorter than the male urethra (about 20 cm) which makes women more susceptible to ascending urinary tract infections.<br><br>The female urethra extends from the bladder neck to the external meatus in the vestibule between the clitoris and the vaginal opening. It is lined by transitional epithelium proximally, changing to stratified squamous distally. Skene\'s glands open near the external meatus opening.<br><br>2 cm (A) is too short; 6 cm (C) is too long; 8 cm (D) is too long for female.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The mucosa of the uterus is known as:',o:['Mesometrium','Myometrium','Perimetrium','Endometrium'],a:3,
    e:`The mucosa of the uterus is known as endometrium, lined by simple columnar epithelium with simple tubular glands extending into the lamina propria (stroma).<br><br>The endometrium has two layers: functional (superficial, shed during menstruation) and basal (deep, regenerative). It undergoes cyclical changes under hormonal influence: proliferative phase (estrogen-driven) and secretory phase (progesterone-driven). The myometrium is the muscular layer; perimetrium is the serous outer layer.<br><br>Myometrium (A) is muscular; perimetrium (B) is serous; mucous membrane (C) is generic term.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The muscular layer of the bladder is called:',o:['External sphincter','Levator ani','Detrusor muscle','Internal sphincter'],a:2,
    e:`The muscular layer of the bladder is called the detrusor muscle, composed of smooth muscle in three layers (inner longitudinal, middle circular, outer longitudinal).<br><br>The detrusor muscle contracts during micturition to expel urine, stimulated by parasympathetic supply (pelvic splanchnic nerves, S2-S4). Sympathetic supply (T10-L2 via hypogastric nerves) inhibits detrusor and contracts the internal urethral sphincter, maintaining continence during storage of urine.<br><br>Internal urethral sphincter (A) is at bladder neck; external urethral sphincter (B) is in deep perineal pouch; trigonal muscle (D) is part of trigone.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The ureteric wall contains:',o:['Cartilage','Stratified squamous epithelium','Skeletal muscle only','Transitional epithelium and smooth muscle'],a:3,
    e:`The ureteric wall contains transitional epithelium (urothelium) and smooth muscle, with no submucosa as a distinct layer.<br><br>The ureter has three layers: mucosa (transitional epithelium with star-shaped lumen), muscularis (inner longitudinal, outer circular - reversed from gut, plus an outer longitudinal layer in lower third), and adventitia (connective tissue). Peristaltic waves propel urine from kidney to bladder along the ureter.<br><br>Stratified squamous (A) is in vagina/skin; simple columnar (B) is in tube/uterus; pseudostratified columnar (C) is in respiratory tract.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Which cells produce androgen-binding protein within seminiferous tubules?',o:['Leydig cells','Sertoli cells','Spermatids','Peritubular cells'],a:1,
    e:`Sertoli cells produce androgen-binding protein (ABP) within seminiferous tubules. ABP binds testosterone, maintaining high local concentration of androgens needed for spermatogenesis.<br><br>Sertoli cells also secrete inhibin (negative feedback on FSH from anterior pituitary) and AMH (anti-Müllerian hormone, in fetal life causing Müllerian regression in males). Sertoli cells form the blood-testis barrier (tight junctions) creating an immune-privileged environment for spermatogenesis.<br><br>Leydig cells (A) produce testosterone; spermatogonia (C) are germ cells; myoid cells (D) are peritubular.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'During histological examination of the ovary, the outer cortex contains numerous follicles in different stages of development while the central medulla contains loose connective tissue with blood vessels and nerves. Which region primarily contains developing ovarian follicles?',o:['Ovarian cortex','Ovarian medulla','Tunica albuginea','Germinal epithelium'],a:0,
    e:`During histological examination of the ovary, the outer cortex contains numerous ovarian follicles in various stages of development plus the supporting stroma.<br><br>Follicles range from primordial (smallest, single layer of flattened cells around oocyte) through primary, secondary and Graafian (mature). After ovulation, the corpus luteum forms in the cortex from the ruptured follicle, eventually regressing to corpus albicans. The medulla contains vessels, nerves and connective tissue.<br><br>Ovarian medulla (B) contains vessels and nerves; ovarian hilum (C) is entry point of vessels; tunica albuginea (D) is the capsule.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The prostate gland stroma mainly consists of:',o:['Skeletal muscle','Cartilage','Smooth muscle and connective tissue','Elastic cartilage'],a:2,
    e:`The prostate gland stroma mainly consists of smooth muscle and connective tissue (fibromuscular stroma), embedded with the tubuloalveolar glands.<br><br>The smooth muscle in the stroma contracts during ejaculation to expel prostatic fluid into the urethra. The fibromuscular component distinguishes the prostate from purely glandular organs. BPH involves both glandular and stromal hyperplasia, particularly in the transitional zone, causing urethral compression and lower urinary tract symptoms.<br><br>Adipose tissue (A) is not main; glandular only (B) is partial; lymphatic tissue (D) is not main component.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The cervix differs histologically from the uterine body mainly because:',o:['It has abundant mucous glands','It lacks glands completely','It has skeletal muscle','It contains cartilage'],a:0,
    e:`The cervix differs histologically from the uterine body mainly because it has abundant mucous glands (endocervical glands), with much less smooth muscle than the uterine body.<br><br>The endocervical glands secrete cervical mucus that varies with the cycle (thin and stretchy at ovulation under estrogen, thick and scant in luteal phase under progesterone). The cervical wall is mainly fibrous tissue (about 90 percent) with only 10 percent smooth muscle, allowing dilation during labour.<br><br>Lined by stratified squamous (B) is only ectocervix, endocervix is columnar; lacks myometrium (C) is incorrect, less but not absent; has cilia (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The tunica vaginalis of the testis is derived from:',o:['Genital ridge','Mesonephric duct','Müllerian duct','Peritoneum'],a:3,
    e:`The tunica vaginalis of the testis is derived from the peritoneum, specifically the processus vaginalis (a peritoneal extension that follows the testis during its descent through the inguinal canal).<br><br>Normally, the processus vaginalis closes after testicular descent, leaving only the tunica vaginalis around the testis. Failure of closure causes patent processus vaginalis (predisposes to indirect inguinal hernia, hydrocele or communicating hydrocele in childhood). Hydrocele is fluid between the layers of tunica vaginalis.<br><br>Mesonephric duct (A) forms male tract; cremasteric fascia (B) is muscle layer; gubernaculum (C) guides testicular descent.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The epididymis functions mainly in:',o:['Hormone production','Sperm maturation and storage','Urine storage','Fertilization'],a:1,
    e:`The epididymis functions mainly in sperm maturation and storage. Sperm gain motility and fertilising capacity during transit through the epididymis.<br><br>Epididymal transit takes 1-3 weeks. Sperm acquire forward motility and the ability to undergo capacitation (final maturation in female tract). Stored sperm in the cauda epididymis can survive for several weeks. The wall contains smooth muscle that contracts during ejaculation, propelling sperm into the vas deferens.<br><br>Sperm production (A) is in seminiferous tubules; testosterone secretion (C) by Leydig cells; thermoregulation (D) by pampiniform plexus.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterine tube epithelium contains secretory cells that:',o:['Secrete urine','Produce testosterone','Produce progesterone','Provide nutrients for the ovum'],a:3,
    e:`The uterine tube epithelium contains secretory cells (peg cells) that produce nutrients for the ovum, supporting its survival and development during transit toward the uterus.<br><br>The tubal mucosa has two cell types: ciliated cells (most numerous, beat toward uterus for ovum transport) and non-ciliated secretory cells (peg cells, produce tubal fluid). The fluid contains nutrients, electrolytes and growth factors that support gametes and the early embryo before implantation.<br><br>Sperm capacitation (A) is in cervix/uterus mainly; cilia movement (B) is by ciliated cells; bacteriostatic action (C) is not the main function.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The muscular coat of the vas deferens consists of:',o:['Skeletal muscle','Two layers only','Three layers of smooth muscle','Cartilage rings'],a:2,
    e:`The muscular coat of the vas deferens consists of three layers of smooth muscle: inner longitudinal, middle circular and outer longitudinal.<br><br>This very thick muscular wall is responsible for powerful peristaltic contractions during ejaculation, propelling sperm from the epididymis to the ejaculatory duct. The thick muscular wall makes the vas palpable as a firm cord in the spermatic cord during physical examination of the scrotum.<br><br>Two layers (A) is incorrect; one layer (B) is incorrect; absence of muscle (D) is wrong.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The lumen of the seminal vesicle typically contains:',o:['Eosinophilic secretions','Blood cells','Urine','Cartilage fragments'],a:0,
    e:`The lumen of the seminal vesicle typically contains eosinophilic secretions (the alkaline fructose-rich fluid that contributes 60-70 percent of seminal volume).<br><br>The secretion contains fructose (energy for sperm), prostaglandins, semenogelin and other factors. Histologically, the eosinophilic material is visible in the lumens of the convoluted seminal vesicle. The mucosa is highly folded with primary, secondary and tertiary folds creating a labyrinthine pattern increasing surface area.<br><br>Mucinous secretion (B) is not characteristic; spermatozoa (C) are stored in epididymis, not seminal vesicle; cellular debris (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The penile erectile tissue spaces are lined by:',o:['Cuboidal epithelium','Endothelium','Stratified squamous epithelium','Transitional epithelium'],a:1,
    e:`The penile erectile tissue spaces (cavernous spaces) are lined by endothelium, allowing rapid filling with blood during erection.<br><br>The corpora cavernosa contain large endothelium-lined sinusoidal spaces (helicine arteries supply them). Parasympathetic stimulation from pelvic splanchnic nerves causes arterial vasodilation, filling these spaces with blood and compressing venous outflow against the tunica albuginea, producing rigidity. Sildenafil (Viagra) prolongs this by inhibiting phosphodiesterase 5.<br><br>Stratified squamous (A) is in skin/vagina; simple columnar (C) is in tube/uterus; transitional (D) is in urinary tract.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The bulbospongiosus muscle surrounds:',o:['Epididymis','Testis','Prostate','Bulb of penis and corpus spongiosum'],a:3,
    e:`The bulbospongiosus muscle surrounds the bulb of penis (and corpus spongiosum) in males, and the vestibular bulb and lower vagina in females.<br><br>Functions: in males, contraction during ejaculation expels semen from the urethra; in females, contributes to vaginal narrowing during arousal. The muscle is innervated by the perineal branch of the pudendal nerve. It attaches to the perineal body, contributing to perineal support and continence.<br><br>Glans penis only (A) is partial; corpora cavernosa (B) are surrounded by ischiocavernosus; root of penis only (C) is partial.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The fallopian tube mucosa facilitates ovum transport mainly through:',o:['Passive diffusion','Ciliary movement and muscular contractions','Blood flow','Cartilage movement'],a:1,
    e:`The fallopian tube mucosa facilitates ovum transport mainly through ciliary movement and muscular contractions, working together to propel the ovum from fimbriae toward the uterus.<br><br>Ciliated cells of the tubal epithelium beat toward the uterus; smooth muscle contractions create peristaltic waves. Estrogen increases both cilia activity and muscle contractions in mid-cycle, facilitating ovum transport. Tubal damage from PID, surgery or smoking can impair these mechanisms, causing infertility or ectopic pregnancy.<br><br>Cilia only (A) is partial; muscle only (C) is partial; gravity (D) is not the main mechanism.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During histological examination of the testis, a barrier is observed that separates the basal compartment containing spermatogonia from the adluminal compartment containing developing spermatocytes and spermatids. This barrier prevents autoimmune reactions against haploid germ cells and is formed by tight junctions between specialized supporting cells of the seminiferous tubules. Which cells are responsible for forming this barrier?',o:['Leydig cells','Peritubular myoid cells','Sertoli cells','Spermatogonia'],a:2,
    e:`During histological examination of the testis, a barrier is observed that separates germ cells from the systemic circulation - this is the blood-testis barrier formed by Sertoli cells.<br><br>Adjacent Sertoli cells form tight junctions creating the blood-testis barrier, dividing the seminiferous tubule into basal compartment (with spermatogonia, accessible to blood) and adluminal compartment (with later germ cells, immunologically isolated). This isolation is essential to prevent autoimmune destruction of haploid sperm.<br><br>Leydig cells (A) are interstitial; germ cells (B) form the cells but not the barrier; myoid cells (D) are peritubular.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'In histology of the ovary, the theca interna layer of a developing follicle contains steroid-producing cells rich in smooth endoplasmic reticulum and lipid droplets. These cells primarily synthesize androgens which are later converted into estrogen by granulosa cells. Which hormone precursor is mainly produced by the theca interna?',o:['Androstenedione','Progesterone','Prolactin','Oxytocin'],a:0,
    e:`In histology of the ovary, the theca interna layer of a developing follicle contains androstenedione (and testosterone) production, secreted under LH stimulation.<br><br>Theca interna cells lie outside the basement membrane of the follicle, producing androgens that diffuse to granulosa cells (which lack 17,20-lyase). Granulosa cells convert androgens to estrogens via aromatase under FSH stimulation. This is the two-cell, two-gonadotrophin theory of ovarian estrogen production.<br><br>Estrogen (B) is from granulosa; progesterone (C) is from corpus luteum; FSH (D) is from pituitary.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During the secretory phase of the menstrual cycle, the endometrial glands appear dilated and tortuous and contain glycogen-rich secretions. These secretions are released into the uterine cavity to provide nutritional support to a potential implanting blastocyst. Which histological feature is most characteristic of this phase?',o:['Straight tubular glands','Tortuous glands with luminal secretion','Keratinized epithelium','Absence of stromal cells'],a:1,
    e:`During the secretory phase of the menstrual cycle, the endometrial glands appear tortuous with luminal secretion, driven by progesterone from the corpus luteum.<br><br>Progesterone causes glands to become saw-toothed and dilated with luminal secretions of glycogen-rich material. Stromal cells decidualise. Spiral arteries become more coiled and prominent. The endometrium is prepared for blastocyst implantation in the mid-secretory phase (window of implantation, days 19-23 of typical cycle).<br><br>Straight tubular glands (A) are in proliferative phase; thinning mucosa (C) is in menstrual phase; squamous metaplasia (D) is unusual.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'In the epididymis, the pseudostratified columnar epithelium contains long non-motile projections known as stereocilia. These structures increase the absorptive surface area and help concentrate sperm by reabsorbing testicular fluid. What is the principal function of stereocilia in the epididymis?',o:['Secretion of testosterone','Formation of acrosomes','Mechanical propulsion of sperm','Absorption of luminal fluid'],a:3,
    e:`In the epididymis, the pseudostratified columnar epithelium contains long non-motile stereocilia involved in absorption of luminal fluid.<br><br>About 90 percent of testicular fluid is reabsorbed during epididymal transit, concentrating the sperm. The stereocilia are long microvilli (not true cilia despite the name) increasing surface area for absorption. The wall contains smooth muscle that contracts during ejaculation, propelling stored sperm into the vas deferens.<br><br>Movement of sperm (A) is by smooth muscle; secretion of fructose (B) is by seminal vesicle; protection (C) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The zona pellucida surrounding the oocyte is a glycoprotein-rich extracellular matrix that plays a crucial role during fertilization. It mediates sperm binding and prevents polyspermy once fertilization occurs. Which glycoprotein-mediated process is primarily associated with the zona pellucida during fertilization?',o:['Sperm binding and acrosomal reaction','Capacitation','Cortical reaction','Meiotic division'],a:0,
    e:`The zona pellucida surrounding the oocyte is a glycoprotein-rich extracellular matrix that functions in sperm binding and acrosomal reaction during fertilisation.<br><br>The zona pellucida is composed of glycoproteins (ZP1, ZP2, ZP3, ZP4). ZP3 binds the sperm and triggers the acrosomal reaction, releasing enzymes for zona penetration. After fertilisation, the cortical reaction modifies the zona to prevent polyspermy. The zona is shed at the blastocyst stage to allow implantation.<br><br>Energy production (B) is in mitochondria; tubal transport (C) is by cilia/muscle; cumulus oophorus (D) is the wider granulosa cell mass.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'In histological sections of the prostate gland in elderly men, laminated eosinophilic structures are frequently observed within glandular lumina. These bodies increase with age and are composed of condensed secretory material. What are these structures called?',o:['Hassall corpuscles','Pacinian corpuscles','Corpora amylacea','Meissner corpuscles'],a:2,
    e:`In histological sections of the prostate gland in elderly men, laminated eosinophilic concretions in glandular acini are corpora amylacea (prostatic concretions).<br><br>These lamellated calcified or partially calcified bodies increase in number with age and are typical findings in elderly prostates. They are not pathological per se but indicate prostatic gland activity. They form by precipitation of glycoproteins and calcium salts in the acinar lumens of the prostate.<br><br>Sertoli cells (A) are in testes; Leydig cells (B) are in interstitium of testes; Müllerian remnants (D) form prostatic utricle.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterine tube contains two types of epithelial cells: ciliated cells and secretory (peg) cells. The secretory cells produce nutrient-rich fluid that supports the ovum and early embryo before implantation. Which region of the fallopian tube shows the most elaborate mucosal folds and highest concentration of these cells?',o:['Ampulla','Isthmus','Intramural part','Uterine cornua'],a:0,
    e:`The uterine tube contains two types of epithelial cells: ciliated cells and secretory (peg) cells. The mucosal folds are most numerous and complex in the ampulla, the wide thin-walled middle segment.<br><br>Ciliated cells beat toward the uterus, propelling the ovum; non-ciliated peg cells produce tubal fluid for ovum nutrition. Estrogen increases ciliary activity in mid-cycle. The fimbriae of the infundibulum are the most extreme mucosal projections, capturing the ovum at ovulation.<br><br>Isthmus (B) has fewer folds; intramural part (C) has minimal folds; infundibulum (D) has fimbriae but ampullary folds are most complex.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'In the seminiferous tubules, developing germ cells progress from spermatogonia near the basement membrane toward the lumen as spermatogenesis proceeds. Which cell type is located closest to the basement membrane of seminiferous tubules?',o:['Spermatids','Spermatogonia','Primary spermatocytes','Spermatozoa'],a:1,
    e:`In the seminiferous tubules, developing germ cells progress from spermatogonia near the basal lamina, through primary spermatocytes, secondary spermatocytes, spermatids and finally spermatozoa near the lumen.<br><br>Spermatogonia (diploid) divide by mitosis; primary spermatocytes (diploid) undergo meiosis I to form secondary spermatocytes (haploid); secondary spermatocytes complete meiosis II to form spermatids (haploid); spermatids undergo spermiogenesis to become spermatozoa, released into the lumen at spermiation.<br><br>Sertoli cells (A) provide support; Leydig cells (C) are interstitial; myoid cells (D) are peritubular.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The vas deferens is characterized histologically by a thick muscular wall that facilitates rapid transport of sperm during ejaculation. How many smooth muscle layers are typically present in the muscular coat of the vas deferens?',o:['Two','One','Four','Three'],a:3,
    e:`The vas deferens is characterised histologically by a thick muscular wall that forms three layers of smooth muscle: inner longitudinal, middle circular and outer longitudinal.<br><br>This very thick muscular wall is responsible for powerful peristaltic contractions during ejaculation, propelling sperm from the epididymis to the ejaculatory duct. The thick muscular wall makes the vas palpable as a firm cord in the spermatic cord during physical examination of the scrotum.<br><br>One layer (A) is incorrect; two layers (B) is incorrect; four layers (C) is incorrect; vas has three muscular layers.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'In the ovary, after ovulation the follicular remnants undergo luteinization forming a temporary endocrine structure. The granulosa cells enlarge and accumulate lipid droplets, becoming granulosa lutein cells that secrete progesterone. What is the name of this temporary endocrine gland?',o:['Corpus albicans','Corpus hemorrhagicum','Corpus luteum','Theca folliculi'],a:2,
    e:`In the ovary, after ovulation the follicular remnants undergo luteinisation forming the corpus luteum, composed of granulosa lutein cells and theca lutein cells.<br><br>Granulosa lutein cells are the major source of progesterone; theca lutein cells produce androgens converted to estrogens. The corpus luteum has a yellow color (lutein meaning yellow) due to lipid content. It functions for about 14 days unless rescued by hCG of pregnancy, otherwise regressing to corpus albicans.<br><br>Primordial follicle (A) is dormant; Graafian follicle (B) is pre-ovulation; corpus albicans (D) is post-luteal scar.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During histological examination of the uterine cervix, the transformation zone is frequently sampled in cervical screening because it is the most common site for development of cervical intraepithelial neoplasia. Which two epithelial types meet at the transformation zone?',o:['Transitional and cuboidal epithelium','Transitional and squamous epithelium','Cuboidal and columnar epithelium','Stratified squamous and simple columnar epithelium'],a:3,
    e:`During histological examination of the uterine cervix, the transformation zone is the area where the stratified squamous epithelium of the ectocervix meets the simple columnar epithelium of the endocervix.<br><br>The T-zone is the site of squamous metaplasia (columnar replaced by squamous) and the most common location for cervical cancer development from HPV infection. Pap smear samples this zone for cervical cytology screening. Colposcopic biopsies are also targeted to abnormal areas in this zone.<br><br>Stratified squamous only (A) is ectocervix; simple columnar only (B) is endocervix; transitional epithelium (C) is in bladder.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The corpus spongiosum differs from the corpora cavernosa histologically because:',o:['It lacks vascular spaces','It contains cartilage','It contains fewer smooth muscle fibers and a thinner tunica albuginea','It lacks endothelium'],a:2,
    e:`The corpus spongiosum differs from the corpora cavernosa histologically because it contains fewer smooth muscle fibres and a thinner tunica albuginea, allowing the urethra to remain patent during erection.<br><br>The thinner tunica means corpus spongiosum does not become as rigid as the cavernosa during erection. This anatomical arrangement permits both micturition and ejaculation through the patent urethra at all times. The corpus spongiosum surrounds the urethra and expands distally to form the glans penis.<br><br>Larger size (A) is incorrect; located dorsally (B) is incorrect (it is ventral); contains seminiferous tubules (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterine endometrium shows cyclic changes during the menstrual cycle. Which phase is characterized by spiral arteries extending toward the superficial endometrium and stromal edema?',o:['Secretory phase','Proliferative phase','Menstrual phase','Ischemic phase'],a:0,
    e:`The uterine endometrium shows cyclic changes during the menstrual cycle. The secretory phase is characterised by tortuous glands with luminal secretion and decidualisation of stromal cells.<br><br>These changes are driven by progesterone from the corpus luteum after ovulation. The glands become saw-toothed and dilated with luminal secretions of glycogen-rich material. Spiral arteries become more coiled. The endometrium is prepared for blastocyst implantation in the mid-secretory phase.<br><br>Proliferative phase (B) has straight tubular glands; menstrual phase (C) has shedding; ischemic phase (D) precedes menstruation with vasoconstriction.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'In histology of the testis, Leydig cells are located:',o:['Within seminiferous tubules','In the interstitial spaces between seminiferous tubules','Inside rete testis','Within epididymal ducts'],a:1,
    e:`In histology of the testis, Leydig cells are located in the interstitial spaces between seminiferous tubules. They are large, polygonal cells with eosinophilic cytoplasm.<br><br>Leydig cells produce testosterone under LH stimulation. Their cytoplasm contains lipid droplets and characteristic Reinke crystals (rod-shaped eosinophilic inclusions). Leydig cell tumours can cause virilising or feminising syndromes due to abnormal hormone production. They are part of the interstitium with vessels.<br><br>Within seminiferous tubules (A) is where germ cells are; in tunica albuginea (C) is connective tissue; on rete testis (D) is conduction system.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The mucosa of the seminal vesicle forms numerous complex folds creating a honeycomb-like appearance in histological sections. This structural arrangement primarily increases:',o:['Muscular strength','Blood flow','Hormonal synthesis','Secretory surface area'],a:3,
    e:`The mucosa of the seminal vesicle forms numerous complex folds creating a honeycomb pattern. This increases the secretory surface area for production of the alkaline fructose-rich fluid.<br><br>The folded mucosa creates primary, secondary and tertiary folds visible on histology. The lining is pseudostratified columnar epithelium with apical secretory granules producing the alkaline fructose-rich fluid (60-70 percent of seminal volume). Smooth muscle in the wall contracts during ejaculation.<br><br>Mechanical strength (A) is by muscle; sperm storage (B) is in epididymis; thermoregulation (C) is by pampiniform plexus.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'During histological study of ovarian follicles, the cumulus oophorus refers to:',o:['A cluster of granulosa cells surrounding the oocyte','The fibrous capsule of ovary','Theca externa layer','Zona pellucida'],a:0,
    e:`During histological study of ovarian follicles, the cumulus oophorus refers to a cluster of granulosa cells surrounding the oocyte and projecting into the antrum of the Graafian follicle.<br><br>The oocyte sits on this mound of granulosa cells. The innermost layer immediately around the zona pellucida is the corona radiata. At ovulation, the secondary oocyte is released along with the corona radiata and zona pellucida into the peritoneal cavity, captured by tubal fimbriae.<br><br>Antrum (B) is the fluid-filled cavity; theca interna (C) is outside follicle; corpus luteum (D) is post-ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The trigone region of the urinary bladder differs histologically from the rest of the bladder because:',o:['It lacks transitional epithelium','It is firmly attached to underlying muscle and lacks mucosal folds','It contains stratified squamous epithelium','It contains cartilage'],a:1,
    e:`The trigone region of the urinary bladder differs histologically from the rest of the bladder because it is firmly attached to underlying muscle and lacks mucosal folds (rugae).<br><br>The trigone is smooth-surfaced (unlike the rugose rest of the bladder which has folds when empty). It is derived embryologically from mesoderm (mesonephric duct), unlike the rest of the bladder (endoderm of urogenital sinus). Trigonitis can cause urgency and frequency of micturition.<br><br>It has stratified squamous epithelium (A) is incorrect (transitional throughout bladder); contains glands (C) is incorrect; absent muscle (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'In histological sections of the uterine tube, which component is responsible for peristaltic movement aiding ovum transport toward the uterus?',o:['Lamina propria','Serosa','Smooth muscle layers of muscularis','Basement membrane'],a:2,
    e:`In histological sections of the uterine tube, the smooth muscle layers of muscularis (inner circular and outer longitudinal) are responsible for peristaltic contractions that propel the ovum.<br><br>Peristaltic contractions of the tubal smooth muscle work with ciliary movement of the epithelium to propel the ovum from fimbriae toward the uterus. Estrogen increases tubal motility in mid-cycle. Tubal damage from PID can impair this transport, causing infertility or ectopic pregnancy.<br><br>Cilia of epithelium (A) help but smooth muscle does the propulsion; mucosal folds (B) are passive; serosa (D) is the outer covering.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During spermatogenesis, primary spermatocytes undergo meiosis I to form:',o:['Secondary spermatocytes','Spermatogonia','Spermatids','Spermatozoa'],a:0,
    e:`During spermatogenesis, primary spermatocytes (diploid, 46 chromosomes) undergo meiosis I to form secondary spermatocytes (haploid, 23 chromosomes each, but with sister chromatids).<br><br>The cell sequence: spermatogonia (mitosis) → primary spermatocytes (meiosis I) → secondary spermatocytes (meiosis II) → spermatids (spermiogenesis) → spermatozoa. Meiosis I reduces chromosome number; meiosis II separates sister chromatids. The whole process takes about 74 days in humans.<br><br>Spermatogonia (B) are the starting cells; spermatids (C) are after meiosis II; spermatozoa (D) are mature gametes.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'During histological analysis of the ovary, a structure composed mainly of dense connective tissue replacing a degenerated corpus luteum is observed. This scar-like structure persists in the ovary after luteal regression. What is this structure called?',o:['Corpus luteum','Corpus albicans','Corpus hemorrhagicum','Graafian follicle'],a:1,
    e:`During histological analysis of the ovary, a structure composed mainly of dense fibrous connective tissue (white scar) is the corpus albicans, formed from the regressed corpus luteum.<br><br>The corpus luteum regresses if no pregnancy: progesterone production falls, granulosa lutein and theca lutein cells die, and connective tissue forms a scar (corpus albicans) that gradually shrinks. If pregnancy occurs, hCG from trophoblast maintains the corpus luteum until placental progesterone takes over.<br><br>Corpus luteum (A) is functional; primordial follicle (C) is dormant; Graafian follicle (D) is pre-ovulation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A congenital anomaly characterized by complete absence of uterus and upper two-thirds of the vagina in a phenotypically normal female with normal ovaries and secondary sexual characteristics is known as:',o:['Turner syndrome','Sheehan syndrome','Asherman syndrome','Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser syndrome'],a:3,
    e:`Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser (MRKH) syndrome is a congenital anomaly characterised by complete absence of uterus and upper two-thirds of vagina with normal ovaries and karyotype 46,XX.<br><br>It results from failure of Müllerian duct development. Ovaries function normally (genital ridge origin) producing normal hormones, so secondary sexual characteristics are normal. Patients present with primary amenorrhoea. Treatment includes vaginal dilatation or surgical creation of a neovagina for sexual function.<br><br>Turner syndrome (A) is 45,X with gonadal dysgenesis; AIS (B) is 46,XY with female phenotype; Kallmann (C) has anosmia.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A bicornuate uterus results from:',o:['Regression of Müllerian ducts','Failure of canalization of vagina','Failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts','Absence of genital ridge'],a:2,
    e:`A bicornuate uterus results from failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts (incomplete fusion). Two horns share one cervix but the upper portions remain separate.<br><br>Bicornuate uterus is a common Müllerian fusion anomaly. Pregnancy can occur but with increased risk of preterm labour, malpresentation and miscarriage. It is differentiated from didelphys (two cervices, complete failure of fusion) and septate uterus (normal external contour, failed septum resorption).<br><br>Failure of resorption (A) causes septate; failure of canalisation (B) causes vaginal anomalies; failure of one duct (D) causes unicornuate.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A septate uterus occurs due to:',o:['Failure of Müllerian duct fusion','Agenesis of genital ridge','Failure of urogenital sinus formation','Failure of resorption of Müllerian septum'],a:3,
    e:`A septate uterus occurs due to failure of resorption of Müllerian septum after the paramesonephric ducts have fused. The external uterine contour is normal, but a septum persists in the cavity.<br><br>A complete septum extends to the cervix; an incomplete (partial) septum extends part way down. Septate uterus is the most common Müllerian anomaly causing recurrent miscarriage; hysteroscopic septum resection improves pregnancy outcomes for most affected women significantly.<br><br>Failure of fusion (A) causes bicornuate or didelphys; failure of canalisation (B) causes vaginal anomalies; failure of descent (C) is for ovaries.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A uterus didelphys is characterized by:',o:['Two separate uteri and two cervices','Single uterus with septum','Absence of uterus','Enlarged uterus'],a:0,
    e:`A uterus didelphys is characterised by two separate uteri and two cervices (often with a longitudinal vaginal septum), resulting from complete failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts.<br><br>Each Müllerian duct develops independently into a uterine horn with its own cervix. Pregnancy can occur in either horn but with increased risk of preterm labour and malpresentation. Surgical correction is rarely indicated unless reproductive outcomes are significantly affected by the anatomical anomaly.<br><br>Single uterus with septum (B) is septate; bicornuate (C) has one cervix; arcuate (D) has minor indentation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Unicornuate uterus results from:',o:['Partial fusion of Müllerian ducts','Failure of septum resorption','Failure of development of one Müllerian duct','Failure of vaginal canalization'],a:2,
    e:`Unicornuate uterus results from failure of development of one Müllerian duct. Only one duct forms a uterine horn with one fallopian tube; the other side fails to develop.<br><br>Unicornuate uterus accounts for about 5 percent of Müllerian anomalies. It is associated with renal anomalies (ipsilateral renal agenesis in 40 percent) due to shared embryological origin from intermediate mesoderm. Pregnancy outcomes can be poorer with increased miscarriage and preterm birth risks.<br><br>Failure of fusion (A) causes didelphys/bicornuate; failure of resorption (B) causes septate; failure of canalisation (D) causes vaginal anomalies.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Imperforate hymen occurs due to:',o:['Failure of Müllerian fusion','Failure of perforation of hymenal membrane','Failure of germ cell migration','Failure of ovarian descent'],a:1,
    e:`Imperforate hymen occurs due to failure of perforation of hymenal membrane during development. The hymen normally develops a central perforation allowing menstrual flow.<br><br>Imperforate hymen presents at puberty with primary amenorrhoea, cyclical pelvic pain and haematocolpos (collection of menstrual blood). Examination shows a bulging bluish hymenal membrane. Treatment is hymenotomy with cruciate incision under anaesthesia for symptomatic relief and to allow normal menstruation.<br><br>Failure of Müllerian fusion (A) causes uterine anomalies; failure of canalisation (C) is broader; agenesis of vagina (D) is more extensive.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Transverse vaginal septum develops due to:',o:['Failure of ovarian descent','Failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts','Failure of genital ridge formation','Failure of fusion between Müllerian ducts and urogenital sinus'],a:3,
    e:`Transverse vaginal septum develops due to failure of fusion between Müllerian ducts and urogenital sinus, where the upper vagina (Müllerian) meets the lower vagina (urogenital sinus).<br><br>The septum can be at any level (low, mid or upper) but is most common in the middle vagina. It causes obstruction at puberty with primary amenorrhoea and haematocolpos. Treatment is surgical excision of the septum to restore vaginal continuity and allow normal menstrual flow.<br><br>Failure of Müllerian fusion (A) causes uterine anomalies; failure of one duct (B) is unicornuate; imperforate hymen (C) is at lower end.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Vaginal agenesis is commonly associated with:',o:['Turner syndrome','Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser syndrome','Down syndrome','Klinefelter syndrome'],a:1,
    e:`Vaginal agenesis is commonly associated with Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser (MRKH) syndrome, characterised by absence of uterus and upper vagina with normal ovaries.<br><br>MRKH affects about 1 in 4500 women. Karyotype is 46,XX; ovaries function normally producing normal hormones, so secondary sexual characteristics are normal. Patients present with primary amenorrhoea. Treatment includes vaginal dilatation or surgical creation of a neovagina for sexual function and cosmetic result.<br><br>Turner syndrome (A) is 45,X gonadal dysgenesis; AIS (C) is 46,XY female phenotype; Kallmann (D) is hypogonadotrophic with anosmia.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common congenital uterine anomaly is:',o:['Bicornuate uterus','Unicornuate uterus','Septate uterus','Uterus didelphys'],a:2,
    e:`The most common congenital uterine anomaly is septate uterus, accounting for about 35 percent of Müllerian anomalies overall.<br><br>Septate uterus has a normal external uterine contour but a midline septum dividing the cavity. It is the most common Müllerian anomaly causing recurrent miscarriage. Hysteroscopic septum resection improves pregnancy outcomes. Other anomalies (bicornuate, didelphys, unicornuate, arcuate) are less common.<br><br>Bicornuate (A) is second most common at about 25 percent; uterus didelphys (B) is rare; unicornuate (D) about 5 percent.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Gartner duct cyst arises from remnants of:',o:['Mesonephric duct','Müllerian duct','Urogenital sinus','Genital tubercle'],a:0,
    e:`Gartner duct cyst arises from remnants of the mesonephric (Wolffian) duct in the lateral wall of the vagina or paracervical region in females.<br><br>The mesonephric ducts largely regress in females (due to absence of testosterone), but small remnants may persist as Gartner ducts running along the lateral aspects of the female reproductive tract. They occasionally develop into cysts on imaging or vaginal examination, usually asymptomatic but may rarely require excision.<br><br>Müllerian duct (B) forms upper female tract; urogenital sinus (C) forms lower vagina; cloaca (D) is broader origin.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient presents with primary amenorrhea and cyclic pelvic pain. Examination shows a bulging bluish hymen. Which congenital anomaly is most likely responsible?',o:['Vaginal agenesis','Septate uterus','Imperforate hymen','Bicornuate uterus'],a:2,
    e:`A patient presents with primary amenorrhoea and cyclic pelvic pain. Examination shows a bulging bluish membrane at the introitus, indicating imperforate hymen.<br><br>Imperforate hymen results from failure of perforation of the hymenal membrane during development. Menstrual blood accumulates behind the obstruction (haematocolpos). Treatment is hymenotomy with cruciate incision under anaesthesia, releasing the accumulated blood and restoring normal menstrual flow.<br><br>Vaginal atresia (A) has no introitus opening; transverse septum (B) is higher in vagina; cervical stenosis (D) is at cervix.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with recurrent miscarriages is diagnosed with a septate uterus. The recurrent pregnancy loss occurs mainly because:',o:['Excess estrogen production','Poor vascular supply of septum','Cervical incompetence','Ovarian failure'],a:1,
    e:`A woman with recurrent miscarriages diagnosed with septate uterus has poor reproductive outcomes due to poor vascular supply of the septum, which provides inadequate support for implantation and placentation.<br><br>The septum is composed of fibrous tissue with little vascular supply. Embryos implanting on the septum often fail to develop adequately. Hysteroscopic septum resection (metroplasty) improves pregnancy outcomes significantly, with miscarriage rates reducing from over 80 percent to under 20 percent post-correction.<br><br>Hormonal imbalance (A) is not the mechanism; cervical incompetence (C) is separate condition; uterine size (D) is normal in septate.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Cervical agenesis is characterized by:',o:['Absence of cervix','Enlarged cervix','Double cervix','Short cervix'],a:0,
    e:`Cervical agenesis is characterised by absence of cervix, with the uterus present but disconnected from the vagina (or the vagina also absent in some cases).<br><br>Cervical agenesis results from failure of canalisation of the cervical part of the uterovaginal canal. Patients present with primary amenorrhoea, cyclical abdominal pain and haematometra (blood collection in uterus). Treatment is challenging; uterovaginal anastomosis or hysterectomy may be considered.<br><br>Absence of vagina alone (B) is vaginal atresia; absence of uterus (C) is uterine agenesis; absence of ovaries (D) is gonadal dysgenesis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A double vagina is usually associated with:',o:['Septate uterus','Hypoplastic uterus','Unicornuate uterus','Uterus didelphys'],a:3,
    e:`A double vagina is usually associated with uterus didelphys (two complete uteri with two cervices), reflecting complete failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts and the longitudinal vaginal septum.<br><br>The longitudinal vaginal septum results from failure of fusion of the lower part of the Müllerian ducts with the urogenital sinus. Each hemivagina drains its respective hemi-uterus. Pregnancy can occur in either side. Surgical excision of the septum may improve sexual function and delivery passage.<br><br>Bicornuate (A) has one cervix and vagina; septate uterus (B) has one cervix and vagina; unicornuate (C) has one horn.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Hematocolpos refers to:',o:['Blood accumulation in uterus','Blood in ovary','Blood accumulation in vagina','Blood in fallopian tube'],a:2,
    e:`Haematocolpos refers to blood accumulation in the vagina, typically due to obstruction of menstrual outflow at the lower vagina (imperforate hymen or transverse vaginal septum).<br><br>It presents at puberty with primary amenorrhoea, cyclical abdominal pain and a palpable lower abdominal mass. Examination shows a bulging bluish membrane (in imperforate hymen). Treatment is surgical relief of the obstruction. Untreated, blood may back up to cause haematometra and haematosalpinx.<br><br>Blood in uterus (A) is haematometra; blood in tube (B) is haematosalpinx; blood in peritoneum (D) is haemoperitoneum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Hematometra refers to:',o:['Blood in tube','Blood in ovary','Blood in vagina','Blood in uterus'],a:3,
    e:`Haematometra refers to blood accumulation in the uterus, typically due to obstruction of menstrual outflow at the cervix or below.<br><br>Causes include cervical stenosis (post-surgical or post-radiation), cervical agenesis, imperforate hymen with backup, or transverse vaginal septum with backup. It presents with cyclical abdominal pain and palpable uterine mass. Treatment is relief of obstruction and drainage of the accumulated menstrual blood.<br><br>Blood in vagina (A) is haematocolpos; blood in tube (B) is haematosalpinx; blood in peritoneum (C) is haemoperitoneum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Hematosalpinx refers to:',o:['Blood in uterus','Blood in fallopian tube','Blood in ovary','Blood in cervix'],a:1,
    e:`Haematosalpinx refers to blood accumulation in the fallopian tube. Causes include retrograde menstruation in obstructed outflow tract anomalies, ruptured ectopic pregnancy or salpingitis.<br><br>In congenital outflow obstruction (imperforate hymen, transverse septum), blood backs up from haematocolpos through haematometra into the tubes. In ectopic pregnancy, the tube fills with blood from trophoblastic invasion. Treatment depends on cause: relief of obstruction or salpingectomy for ectopic pregnancy.<br><br>Blood in vagina (A) is haematocolpos; blood in uterus (C) is haematometra; blood in peritoneum (D) is haemoperitoneum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A transverse vaginal septum usually occurs at:',o:['Junction of Müllerian ducts and urogenital sinus','Cervix','Ovarian ligament','Pelvic wall'],a:0,
    e:`A transverse vaginal septum usually occurs at the junction of Müllerian ducts and urogenital sinus, where the upper vagina (Müllerian) meets the lower vagina (urogenital sinus).<br><br>The septum can be at any level (low, mid or upper) but is most common in the middle vagina at the embryological junction. It causes obstruction at puberty with primary amenorrhoea and haematocolpos. Treatment is surgical excision of the septum to restore vaginal continuity and menstrual flow.<br><br>Junction of Müllerian ducts only (B) is for uterine anomalies; cervix (C) is for cervical anomalies; introitus (D) is for hymenal anomalies.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Vaginal duplication usually results from:',o:['Failure of genital ridge formation','Failure of vaginal canalization','Failure of Müllerian duct fusion','Failure of ovarian descent'],a:2,
    e:`Vaginal duplication usually results from failure of Müllerian duct fusion with persistence of a longitudinal septum dividing the vagina into two channels.<br><br>Most commonly associated with uterus didelphys (two uteri, two cervices, two vaginas). Each hemivagina drains its respective hemi-uterus. Pregnancy can occur in either side. Surgical excision of the septum may improve sexual function and provide a single delivery passage in subsequent pregnancies.<br><br>Failure of canalisation (A) causes vaginal atresia; failure of perforation (B) causes imperforate hymen; failure of resorption (D) causes septate uterus.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Congenital absence of uterus with normal ovaries is most commonly due to:',o:['Turner syndrome','MRKH syndrome','Sheehan syndrome','Asherman syndrome'],a:1,
    e:`Congenital absence of uterus with normal ovaries is most commonly due to MRKH (Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser) syndrome, with karyotype 46,XX.<br><br>MRKH results from failure of Müllerian duct development. Ovaries function normally (genital ridge origin) producing normal hormones, so secondary sexual characteristics are normal. Patients present with primary amenorrhoea. Treatment includes vaginal dilatation or surgical creation of a neovagina for sexual function.<br><br>Turner syndrome (A) has gonadal dysgenesis; AIS (C) has 46,XY karyotype; Kallmann (D) has anosmia and hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During embryological development of the female genital tract, failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts results in duplication anomalies of the uterus. A patient with two separate uterine cavities and two cervices but a single vagina is most likely suffering from which anomaly?',o:['Septate uterus','Unicornuate uterus','Bicornuate uterus','Uterus didelphys'],a:3,
    e:`During embryological development of the female genital tract, complete failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts results in uterus didelphys, with two complete uteri and two cervices.<br><br>The two Müllerian ducts develop independently into separate uteri, each with its own cervix and often with a longitudinal vaginal septum. Pregnancy can occur in either uterus. Surgical correction is rarely indicated unless reproductive outcomes are significantly affected by the anatomical anomaly.<br><br>Bicornuate (A) is partial fusion failure with one cervix; septate (B) is failed septum resorption; unicornuate (C) is one duct failure.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A congenital anomaly in which the uterus has a single horn and a rudimentary second horn is termed:',o:['Unicornuate uterus','Septate uterus','Bicornuate uterus','Arcuate uterus'],a:0,
    e:`A congenital anomaly in which the uterus has a single horn and a rudimentary second horn is called unicornuate uterus with rudimentary horn.<br><br>The rudimentary horn may communicate with the main cavity (rare) or be non-communicating (more common). Non-communicating horns with functioning endometrium can cause cyclical pain and haematometra in the rudimentary horn. Pregnancy in the rudimentary horn carries a high risk of rupture.<br><br>Bicornuate (B) has two horns of similar size; septate (C) has fibrous division; uterus didelphys (D) has two complete uteri.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'An arcuate uterus results from:',o:['Complete absence of uterus','Failure of Müllerian fusion','Mild indentation of uterine fundus due to incomplete septal resorption','Vaginal agenesis'],a:2,
    e:`An arcuate uterus results from mild indentation of uterine fundus due to incomplete septal resorption. It is the mildest form of Müllerian anomaly and considered by some a normal variant.<br><br>Arcuate uterus has a heart-shaped fundal contour with normal cavity volume. It usually has good reproductive outcomes, often considered a normal variant rather than a true anomaly. Some classifications no longer include it as a Müllerian anomaly given excellent pregnancy outcomes in most cases.<br><br>Complete failure of fusion (A) is didelphys; complete septum (B) is septate; one Müllerian duct failure (D) is unicornuate.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Which congenital uterine anomaly is most strongly associated with recurrent pregnancy loss?',o:['Septate uterus','Bicornuate uterus','Unicornuate uterus','Arcuate uterus'],a:0,
    e:`Septate uterus is the congenital uterine anomaly most strongly associated with recurrent pregnancy loss, due to poor vascular supply of the fibrous septum where embryos implant.<br><br>The miscarriage rate in untreated septate uterus exceeds 80 percent in some series. Hysteroscopic septum resection (metroplasty) improves pregnancy outcomes significantly, with miscarriage rates reducing to under 20 percent post-correction. It is the most common Müllerian anomaly causing infertility/recurrent loss.<br><br>Bicornuate (B) has lower miscarriage risk; uterus didelphys (C) is rare; arcuate (D) has good outcomes.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Congenital cervical stenosis may lead to:',o:['Hematometra','All of the above','Hematocolpos','Hematosalpinx'],a:1,
    e:`Congenital cervical stenosis may lead to multiple complications: dysmenorrhoea, haematometra (blood accumulation in uterus), and infertility due to obstruction of menstrual flow and sperm transit.<br><br>Treatment may involve cervical dilatation, but recurrence is common. Surgical correction with uterovaginal anastomosis is challenging. Untreated cervical stenosis can also cause endometriosis through retrograde menstruation. Some women may require hysterectomy for severe symptomatic cases.<br><br>Dysmenorrhoea only (A) is partial; haematometra only (C) is partial; infertility only (D) is partial; all three can occur.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Vaginal atresia refers to:',o:['Complete absence of vagina','Narrow vaginal opening','Enlarged vagina','Partial or complete obstruction of vagina'],a:3,
    e:`Vaginal atresia refers to partial or complete obstruction of vagina, due to failure of canalisation of the vaginal plate or absence of the lower vagina.<br><br>Vaginal atresia presents at puberty with primary amenorrhoea, cyclical pain and haematocolpos (if upper vagina is present). Treatment depends on extent: dilatation for short atresia; surgical reconstruction with skin graft or bowel for long-segment atresia. MRKH syndrome involves combined uterine and vaginal absence.<br><br>Absence of uterus (A) is uterine agenesis; absence of cervix (B) is cervical agenesis; absence of ovaries (C) is gonadal dysgenesis.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Paraovarian cysts develop from remnants of:',o:['Urogenital sinus','Müllerian ducts','Mesonephric ducts','Genital ridge'],a:2,
    e:`Paraovarian cysts develop from remnants of the mesonephric (Wolffian) duct, specifically from the epoöphoron or paroöphoron in the broad ligament near the ovary.<br><br>These cysts lie within the mesosalpinx between the ovary and fallopian tube. Most are small and asymptomatic, found incidentally on imaging or laparoscopy. Larger paraovarian cysts can cause torsion or pelvic discomfort, and may be excised surgically when symptomatic or causing concern about malignancy.<br><br>Müllerian duct (A) forms tubes/uterus/upper vagina; urogenital sinus (B) forms lower vagina; gubernaculum (D) forms ligaments.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Congenital uterine anomalies are most often associated with abnormalities of which organ system?',o:['Nervous system','Respiratory system','Cardiovascular system','Renal system'],a:3,
    e:`Congenital uterine anomalies are most often associated with abnormalities of the renal system (urinary tract). Up to 40 percent of women with Müllerian anomalies have renal anomalies.<br><br>The association reflects shared embryological origin from intermediate mesoderm. Common renal anomalies include unilateral renal agenesis, ectopic kidney, horseshoe kidney and duplex collecting system. Imaging the urinary tract (renal ultrasound or IVU) is recommended in all women diagnosed with Müllerian anomalies.<br><br>Cardiovascular (A) is unrelated; gastrointestinal (B) is unrelated; respiratory (C) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common presenting symptom of Müllerian anomalies is:',o:['Infertility or recurrent miscarriage','Primary amenorrhea','Severe infection','Ovarian torsion'],a:0,
    e:`The most common presenting symptom of Müllerian anomalies is infertility or recurrent miscarriage, particularly with septate uterus where embryos implant on the poorly vascularised septum.<br><br>Other presentations include primary amenorrhoea (in obstructive anomalies like imperforate hymen, transverse vaginal septum, MRKH), cyclical pain (in obstructive anomalies with functioning endometrium), and dysmenorrhoea. Many anomalies are asymptomatic and detected incidentally on imaging or surgery.<br><br>Pelvic infections (B) are not typical; menorrhagia (C) is not characteristic; ovarian masses (D) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A longitudinal vaginal septum results from:',o:['Failure of septal resorption','Incomplete fusion of Müllerian ducts','Failure of vaginal canalization','Failure of ovarian descent'],a:1,
    e:`A longitudinal vaginal septum results from incomplete fusion of Müllerian ducts in their caudal portions, leaving a midline septum dividing the vagina.<br><br>Most commonly associated with uterus didelphys. Each hemivagina drains its respective hemi-uterus. Pregnancy can occur in either side. Surgical excision of the septum may improve sexual function and provide a single delivery passage in subsequent pregnancies. May also occur with bicornuate uterus.<br><br>Failure of canalisation (A) causes vaginal atresia; failure of perforation (C) causes imperforate hymen; failure of resorption (D) causes septate uterus.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'In MRKH syndrome, which structure is usually normal?',o:['Ovaries','Cervix','Uterus','Upper vagina'],a:0,
    e:`In MRKH syndrome, the ovaries are usually normal in structure and function, since they develop from the genital ridge (intermediate mesoderm) independently of the Müllerian ducts.<br><br>Ovaries produce normal hormones, so secondary sexual characteristics develop normally. The Müllerian-derived structures (fallopian tubes, uterus, upper vagina) are absent or hypoplastic. Karyotype is 46,XX. Patients present with primary amenorrhoea but have normal breasts and pubic hair development.<br><br>Uterus (B) is absent in MRKH; vagina (C) upper part is absent; cervix (D) is absent.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Congenital absence of cervix with normal uterus is termed:',o:['Cervical duplication','Cervical stenosis','Cervical agenesis','Cervical hypertrophy'],a:2,
    e:`Congenital absence of cervix with normal uterus is termed cervical agenesis. The uterus is present but disconnected from the vagina due to failure of cervical canalisation.<br><br>Patients present with primary amenorrhoea, cyclical abdominal pain and haematometra (blood collection in uterus). Treatment is challenging; uterovaginal anastomosis or hysterectomy may be considered. Cervical agenesis is often associated with other Müllerian anomalies and may have poor reproductive outcomes.<br><br>Vaginal atresia (A) is absent vagina; uterine agenesis (B) is absent uterus; uterus didelphys (D) is two uteri.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Which uterine anomaly often presents with premature labor due to reduced uterine volume?',o:['Normal uterus','Septate uterus','Arcuate uterus','Unicornuate uterus'],a:3,
    e:`Unicornuate uterus often presents with premature labour due to reduced uterine cavity size. The single horn cannot expand adequately to accommodate the growing fetus.<br><br>Pregnancy outcomes in unicornuate uterus are poorer with increased rates of miscarriage, preterm labour, malpresentation and IUGR (intrauterine growth restriction). Caesarean section may be needed due to abnormal lie. Renal anomalies (especially ipsilateral renal agenesis) coexist in about 40 percent of cases.<br><br>Uterus didelphys (A) has two uteri but each can accommodate; bicornuate (B) has two horns; septate (C) has normal external contour.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A rudimentary uterine horn may lead to:',o:['Ectopic pregnancy','All of the above','Pelvic pain','Hematometra'],a:1,
    e:`A rudimentary uterine horn (in unicornuate uterus) may lead to multiple complications: cyclical pain, haematometra in the rudimentary horn, and rupture if pregnancy occurs in it.<br><br>Non-communicating horns with functioning endometrium are most problematic. Sperm can enter the rudimentary horn through the peritoneum, causing potential implantation in the horn. Rupture risk is high (about 50 percent if pregnancy occurs there). Prophylactic resection is often recommended for rudimentary horns with endometrium.<br><br>Cyclical pain only (A) is partial; haematometra only (C) is partial; rupture only (D) is partial; all three can occur.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Obstructed hemivagina with ipsilateral renal anomaly is characteristic of:',o:['Herlyn-Werner-Wunderlich syndrome','Turner syndrome','Asherman syndrome','Sheehan syndrome'],a:0,
    e:`Obstructed hemivagina with ipsilateral renal anomaly is characteristic of Herlyn-Werner-Wunderlich (HWW) syndrome, also called OHVIRA syndrome.<br><br>HWW syndrome is a rare Müllerian anomaly: uterus didelphys plus longitudinal vaginal septum with one hemivagina obstructed plus ipsilateral renal agenesis. Patients present at puberty with cyclical pain on the obstructed side. Treatment is excision of the vaginal septum to relieve obstruction, with good prognosis.<br><br>MRKH (B) has uterine and vaginal absence; Mayer-Rokitansky (C) is same as MRKH; Robinow syndrome (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Congenital uterine anomalies are best diagnosed using:',o:['MRI','Ultrasound','All of the above','Hysterosalpingography'],a:2,
    e:`Congenital uterine anomalies are best diagnosed using a combination of imaging modalities: 3D ultrasound, MRI and hysterosalpingography (HSG), each providing complementary information.<br><br>MRI is the gold standard for distinguishing septate from bicornuate uterus, providing excellent visualisation of both internal cavity and external uterine contour. 3D ultrasound is non-invasive and reliable. HSG demonstrates cavity shape but not external contour. Hysteroscopy and laparoscopy provide direct visualisation.<br><br>Ultrasound only (A) is partial; MRI only (B) is excellent but not always sufficient alone; HSG only (D) is partial; combined modalities are best.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The presence of a uterine septum dividing the uterine cavity into two compartments occurs because:',o:['Failure of Müllerian duct fusion','Failure of septal resorption','Failure of ovarian descent','Failure of germ cell migration'],a:1,
    e:`The presence of a uterine septum dividing the uterine cavity into two compartments results from failure of septal resorption after Müllerian duct fusion.<br><br>The two Müllerian ducts fuse normally creating one external uterine outline, but the midline septum between them fails to resorb (which normally occurs by week 20). This produces a septate uterus with normal external contour but divided cavity. Hysteroscopic septum resection improves reproductive outcomes significantly.<br><br>Failure of fusion (A) causes bicornuate or didelphys; failure of canalisation (C) causes vaginal anomalies; failure of one duct (D) is unicornuate.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A bicornuate uterus typically shows:',o:['Single uterine cavity','Single uterine horn only','Complete absence of uterus','Two uterine horns with partial separation'],a:3,
    e:`A bicornuate uterus typically shows two uterine horns with partial separation, sharing one cervix. The external contour shows a fundal cleft (heart-shape).<br><br>It results from incomplete fusion of Müllerian ducts. Pregnancy can occur but with increased risk of preterm labour, malpresentation and miscarriage. It is differentiated from didelphys (two cervices, complete failure of fusion) and septate uterus (normal external contour, failed septum resorption).<br><br>Two complete uteri (A) is didelphys; one fibrous septum (B) is septate; one horn only (C) is unicornuate.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Which Müllerian anomaly has the best reproductive outcome?',o:['Septate uterus','Arcuate uterus','Unicornuate uterus','Uterus didelphys'],a:1,
    e:`Arcuate uterus has the best reproductive outcome among Müllerian anomalies. It has a mild fundal indentation due to incomplete septal resorption but with normal cavity volume.<br><br>Pregnancy outcomes in arcuate uterus are similar to normal uterus, with low miscarriage and preterm labour rates. Some classifications no longer include it as a true Müllerian anomaly given excellent outcomes. Other anomalies (septate, bicornuate, didelphys, unicornuate) have variable but poorer outcomes.<br><br>Septate (A) has high miscarriage rates; bicornuate (C) has increased preterm; unicornuate (D) has poorest outcomes.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During embryologic development of the female genital tract, abnormalities in Müllerian duct formation, fusion, or septal resorption can produce a wide spectrum of congenital uterine malformations. These defects often present clinically with infertility, recurrent miscarriage, or menstrual obstruction depending on the specific anomaly. Which developmental mechanism most commonly leads to a bicornuate uterus?',o:['Failure of Müllerian duct fusion','Failure of septal resorption','Failure of urogenital sinus development','Failure of ovarian descent'],a:0,
    e:`During embryologic development of the female genital tract, abnormalities in Müllerian duct development cause uterine and vaginal anomalies. Failure of Müllerian duct fusion is the underlying defect in didelphys and bicornuate uterus.<br><br>Other defects include failure of resorption of the median septum (septate uterus), failure of one duct development (unicornuate uterus), and failure of canalisation of the vaginal plate (vaginal atresia or transverse septum). All Müllerian anomalies should prompt assessment of the renal tract.<br><br>Failure of fertilisation (B) is unrelated; failure of implantation (C) is later; failure of meiosis (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'A congenital anomaly in which there is a complete absence of the vagina while the uterus may be present is termed:',o:['Vaginal prolapse','Vaginal duplication','Vaginal stenosis','Vaginal atresia'],a:3,
    e:`A congenital anomaly in which there is a complete absence of the vagina while the uterus is present is termed vaginal atresia.<br><br>Vaginal atresia results from failure of development of the urogenital sinus contribution to the lower vagina, while the upper vagina (Müllerian) may be present. Patients present at puberty with primary amenorrhoea, cyclical pain and haematometra. Treatment involves surgical creation of a neovagina with skin graft or bowel.<br><br>Cervical agenesis (A) is absent cervix; Müllerian agenesis (B) is absent uterus; uterine didelphys (C) is two uteri.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with a septate uterus is at increased risk of which obstetric complication?',o:['Postpartum hemorrhage','Placenta previa','Recurrent miscarriage','Polyhydramnios'],a:2,
    e:`A patient with septate uterus is at increased risk of recurrent miscarriage. The miscarriage rate in untreated septate uterus exceeds 80 percent in some series.<br><br>The fibrous septum has poor vascular supply, leading to inadequate placentation when embryos implant on it. Hysteroscopic septum resection (metroplasty) improves pregnancy outcomes significantly, with miscarriage rates reducing to under 20 percent post-correction. It is the most common Müllerian anomaly causing recurrent loss.<br><br>Cervical incompetence (A) is separate; preterm labour (B) is increased but not as much as miscarriage; placenta praevia (D) is not specifically associated.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'In uterus didelphys, which of the following anatomical findings is most typical?',o:['Two separate uterine cavities and two cervices','Single uterine cavity with septum','Absence of uterus','Single uterine horn'],a:0,
    e:`In uterus didelphys, the most typical anatomical findings are two separate uterine cavities and two cervices, often with a longitudinal vaginal septum.<br><br>Each Müllerian duct develops independently into a uterine horn with its own cervix. Pregnancy can occur in either horn but with increased risk of preterm labour and malpresentation. Surgical correction is rarely indicated unless reproductive outcomes are significantly affected by the anatomical anomaly.<br><br>Single uterus with septum (B) is septate; two horns with one cervix (C) is bicornuate; one horn (D) is unicornuate.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Failure of canalization of the vaginal plate results in:',o:['Vaginal agenesis','Cervical stenosis','Uterine septum','Imperforate hymen'],a:3,
    e:`Failure of canalisation of the vaginal plate results in imperforate hymen (or higher levels: transverse vaginal septum or vaginal atresia depending on level of failure).<br><br>The vaginal plate is a solid epithelial structure formed by the sinovaginal bulbs (urogenital sinus origin). Canalisation begins centrally and proceeds craniocaudally. Failure of complete canalisation produces obstructive lesions presenting at puberty with primary amenorrhoea and haematocolpos. Treatment is surgical relief of obstruction.<br><br>Bicornuate uterus (A) is from fusion failure; uterus didelphys (B) is from fusion failure; septate uterus (C) is from septum resorption failure.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common congenital anomaly of the vagina is:',o:['Transverse vaginal septum','Longitudinal vaginal septum','Vaginal agenesis','Vaginal cyst'],a:1,
    e:`The most common congenital anomaly of the vagina is longitudinal vaginal septum, often associated with uterus didelphys.<br><br>It results from incomplete fusion of Müllerian ducts in their caudal portions. Each hemivagina drains its respective hemi-uterus. Pregnancy can occur in either side. Surgical excision of the septum may improve sexual function and provide a single delivery passage in subsequent pregnancies, though many cases are asymptomatic.<br><br>Vaginal atresia (A) is rarer; transverse septum (C) is less common; vaginal duplication (D) is associated finding, not common anomaly.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Cervical stenosis may result in accumulation of menstrual blood within the uterus producing:',o:['Hematocolpos','Hematosalpinx','Hematometra','Pyometra'],a:2,
    e:`Cervical stenosis may result in accumulation of menstrual blood within the uterus (haematometra), due to obstruction of menstrual outflow at the cervix.<br><br>Causes of cervical stenosis include congenital cervical agenesis, post-surgical (cone biopsy, LEEP), post-radiation, post-menopausal atrophy, or cervical cancer. Patients present with cyclical abdominal pain and a palpable uterine mass. Treatment is cervical dilatation; recurrence is common requiring repeated procedures.<br><br>Haematocolpos (A) is in vagina; haematosalpinx (B) is in tube; haemoperitoneum (D) is in peritoneal cavity.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with bicornuate uterus usually has:',o:['Two uterine horns','Single uterine cavity','Absence of cervix','Complete vaginal agenesis'],a:0,
    e:`A woman with bicornuate uterus usually has two uterine horns sharing one cervix. The external contour shows a fundal cleft, distinguishing it from septate uterus (normal external contour).<br><br>It results from incomplete fusion of Müllerian ducts. Pregnancy can occur but with increased risk of preterm labour, malpresentation and miscarriage. Imaging (3D ultrasound or MRI) is essential to differentiate bicornuate from septate uterus, as treatment differs (surgical metroplasty vs hysteroscopic resection).<br><br>Two complete uteri (B) is didelphys; one fibrous septum (C) is septate; one horn only (D) is unicornuate.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Which congenital uterine anomaly results from partial resorption of the Müllerian septum?',o:['Bicornuate uterus','Unicornuate uterus','Arcuate uterus','Didelphys uterus'],a:2,
    e:`Arcuate uterus results from partial resorption of the Müllerian septum, leaving a mild fundal indentation. The cavity volume and external contour are otherwise normal.<br><br>Arcuate uterus is the mildest form of Müllerian anomaly and considered by some a normal variant. Pregnancy outcomes are similar to normal uterus, with low miscarriage and preterm labour rates. Some classifications no longer include it as a true Müllerian anomaly given excellent reproductive outcomes.<br><br>Septate (A) has full septum; bicornuate (B) is fusion failure; uterus didelphys (D) is complete fusion failure.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The condition characterized by obstruction of vaginal outflow leading to accumulation of menstrual blood in vagina is:',o:['Hematometra','Hematosalpinx','Hydrosalpinx','Hematocolpos'],a:3,
    e:`The condition characterised by obstruction of vaginal outflow leading to accumulation of menstrual blood in the vagina is haematocolpos.<br><br>Causes include imperforate hymen, transverse vaginal septum or vaginal atresia. It presents at puberty with primary amenorrhoea, cyclical abdominal pain and a palpable lower abdominal mass. Examination shows a bulging bluish membrane (in imperforate hymen). Treatment is surgical relief of obstruction.<br><br>Haematometra (A) is in uterus; haematosalpinx (B) is in tube; haemoperitoneum (C) is in peritoneal cavity.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Congenital absence of uterus and cervix with normal ovaries most commonly indicates:',o:['Turner syndrome','MRKH syndrome','Klinefelter syndrome','Asherman syndrome'],a:1,
    e:`Congenital absence of uterus and cervix with normal ovaries most commonly indicates MRKH (Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser) syndrome, with karyotype 46,XX.<br><br>MRKH results from failure of Müllerian duct development. Ovaries function normally (genital ridge origin) producing normal hormones, so secondary sexual characteristics are normal. Patients present with primary amenorrhoea. Treatment includes vaginal dilatation or surgical creation of a neovagina for sexual function.<br><br>Turner syndrome (A) has 45,X karyotype with gonadal dysgenesis; AIS (C) is 46,XY female phenotype; Kallmann (D) has anosmia.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A rudimentary uterine horn in a unicornuate uterus may contain functioning endometrium and can present clinically with:',o:['Hyperprolactinemia','Amenorrhea only','Cyclic pelvic pain','Menopause'],a:2,
    e:`A rudimentary uterine horn in a unicornuate uterus may contain functioning endometrium, presenting with cyclic pelvic pain due to obstructed menstrual flow if non-communicating.<br><br>Non-communicating horns with functioning endometrium are most problematic, causing cyclical pain and haematometra in the rudimentary horn. Sperm can enter the rudimentary horn through the peritoneum, causing potential implantation. Pregnancy in the rudimentary horn carries high rupture risk, often requiring prophylactic resection.<br><br>Recurrent infection (A) is not characteristic; menorrhagia (B) is unrelated; infertility alone (D) is partial.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Which congenital uterine anomaly involves two uterine cavities separated by a fibrous or muscular septum but with a normal external uterine contour?',o:['Bicornuate uterus','Septate uterus','Unicornuate uterus','Arcuate uterus'],a:1,
    e:`Septate uterus involves two uterine cavities separated by a fibrous septum but with a normal external uterine contour.<br><br>It results from failure of resorption of Müllerian septum after fusion. The septum is composed of fibrous tissue with poor vascular supply. It is the most common Müllerian anomaly causing recurrent miscarriage. Hysteroscopic septum resection (metroplasty) improves pregnancy outcomes significantly.<br><br>Bicornuate (A) has fundal cleft externally; uterus didelphys (C) has two cervices; unicornuate (D) has one horn only.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A transverse vaginal septum most commonly occurs in which part of the vagina?',o:['Upper vagina','Vaginal introitus','Lower vagina','Middle vagina'],a:3,
    e:`A transverse vaginal septum most commonly occurs in the middle vagina, at the embryological junction between Müllerian-derived upper vagina and urogenital sinus-derived lower vagina.<br><br>The septum can be at any level (low, mid or upper) but is most common in the middle vagina at this junction. It causes obstruction at puberty with primary amenorrhoea and haematocolpos. Treatment is surgical excision of the septum to restore vaginal continuity and allow normal menstrual flow.<br><br>Upper vagina (A) is less common; lower vagina (B) is less common; introitus (C) is hymenal level.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Obstruction of menstrual flow due to congenital vaginal anomalies may lead to retrograde menstruation and subsequent development of:',o:['Endometriosis','Fibroids','Adenomyosis','Pelvic inflammatory disease'],a:0,
    e:`Obstruction of menstrual flow due to congenital vaginal anomalies may lead to retrograde menstruation, causing endometriosis. Blood backs up through tubes into the peritoneal cavity, depositing endometrial cells.<br><br>This is one of Sampson\'s theories of endometriosis. Surgical relief of obstruction may halt progression. Endometriosis from this cause is often more severe and earlier-onset than usual cases. Imperforate hymen, transverse vaginal septum and vaginal atresia all predispose to endometriosis if not corrected promptly.<br><br>PID (B) is from infection; uterine cancer (C) is unrelated; ovarian torsion (D) is from cysts/masses.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Which congenital uterine anomaly is most frequently associated with renal agenesis on the same side?',o:['Septate uterus','Unicornuate uterus','Arcuate uterus','Normal uterus'],a:1,
    e:`Unicornuate uterus is most frequently associated with renal agenesis (especially ipsilateral renal agenesis in about 40 percent of cases).<br><br>The association reflects shared embryological origin from intermediate mesoderm. Imaging the urinary tract (renal ultrasound or IVU) is recommended in all women diagnosed with Müllerian anomalies. Other Müllerian anomalies (didelphys, bicornuate, septate) also have higher rates of renal anomalies but unicornuate has the highest correlation.<br><br>Septate uterus (A) has lower association; uterus didelphys (C) has association but less; arcuate (D) is mild and rarely associated.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Vaginal duplication is most commonly associated with:',o:['Septate uterus','Bicornuate uterus','Uterus didelphys','Arcuate uterus'],a:2,
    e:`Vaginal duplication is most commonly associated with uterus didelphys (two complete uteri with two cervices), reflecting complete failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts.<br><br>The longitudinal vaginal septum results from failure of fusion of the lower part of the Müllerian ducts with the urogenital sinus. Each hemivagina drains its respective hemi-uterus. Pregnancy can occur in either side. Surgical excision of the septum may improve sexual function and provide a single delivery passage.<br><br>Bicornuate (A) has one cervix and vagina; septate (B) has one cervix and vagina; unicornuate (D) has one horn only.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient presents with primary amenorrhea and cyclical abdominal pain. Imaging shows accumulation of blood in uterus and vagina due to obstruction. This condition is termed:',o:['Ovarian cyst','Hydrosalpinx','Pyosalpinx','Hematometrocolpos'],a:3,
    e:`A patient presents with primary amenorrhoea and cyclical abdominal pain. Imaging shows haematometrocolpos (blood in both uterus and vagina), due to obstruction of menstrual outflow at the lower vagina.<br><br>Causes include imperforate hymen, transverse vaginal septum or vaginal atresia. Treatment is surgical relief of obstruction. Untreated, blood may back up further to cause haematosalpinx and predispose to endometriosis through retrograde menstruation. Examination identifies the level of obstruction.<br><br>Haematocolpos (A) is vagina only; haematometra (B) is uterus only; haemoperitoneum (C) is peritoneal cavity.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Congenital cervical atresia most commonly results in:',o:['Obstructed menstrual flow','Hypermenorrhea','Early menopause','Ovarian failure'],a:0,
    e:`Congenital cervical atresia most commonly results in obstructed menstrual flow, causing cyclical pelvic pain and haematometra (blood collection in the uterus).<br><br>Cervical atresia results from failure of canalisation of the cervical part of the uterovaginal canal. Patients present at puberty with primary amenorrhoea and cyclical abdominal pain. Treatment is challenging; uterovaginal anastomosis or hysterectomy may be considered. Endometriosis from retrograde menstruation is common.<br><br>Hypermenorrhoea (B) is unrelated; ovarian torsion (C) is from cysts/masses; ectopic pregnancy (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The presence of a fibrous band dividing the vaginal cavity into two parts is termed:',o:['Vaginal agenesis','Vaginal septum','Vaginal atresia','Vaginal stenosis'],a:1,
    e:`The presence of a fibrous band dividing the vaginal cavity into two parts is termed a vaginal septum (longitudinal or transverse depending on orientation).<br><br>Longitudinal vaginal septum results from failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts in their caudal portions. Transverse vaginal septum results from failure of fusion between Müllerian ducts and urogenital sinus. Both can be treated by surgical excision; longitudinal septum may be asymptomatic, transverse causes obstruction.<br><br>Vaginal atresia (A) is absent vagina; vaginal stenosis (C) is narrowing without septum; vaginal cyst (D) is a cyst, not a band.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During embryological development, structural defects of pelvic organs may arise from abnormalities in formation, fusion, or canalization of Müllerian ducts. These congenital malformations frequently present clinically with infertility, recurrent pregnancy loss, dysmenorrhea, or obstructed menstrual flow depending on the severity and location of the anomaly. Which developmental defect most commonly results in a septate uterus?',o:['Complete failure of Müllerian duct fusion','Failure of development of one Müllerian duct','Failure of septal resorption after Müllerian duct fusion','Failure of urogenital sinus formation'],a:2,
    e:`During embryological development, structural defects of pelvic organs may arise from various causes; septate uterus specifically arises from failure of septal resorption after Müllerian duct fusion.<br><br>The two Müllerian ducts fuse normally creating one external uterine outline, but the midline septum between them fails to resorb (which normally occurs by week 20). This produces a septate uterus with normal external contour but divided cavity. Hysteroscopic septum resection improves reproductive outcomes significantly.<br><br>Failure of fusion (A) causes bicornuate or didelphys; failure of canalisation (B) causes vaginal anomalies; failure of one duct (D) is unicornuate.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The breast is a modified form of which type of gland?',o:['Apocrine sweat gland','Eccrine sweat gland','Sebaceous gland','Endocrine gland'],a:0,
    e:`The breast is a modified form of apocrine sweat gland. Both share embryological origin from epidermal downgrowths and similar histological structure with secretory units and ducts.<br><br>The breast develops from the mammary ridge (milk line) along the ventral surface of the embryo. Apocrine glands secrete by pinching off apical cytoplasm with their secretion. Other apocrine glands include those of the axilla, perineum and external auditory canal (ceruminous glands).<br><br>Sebaceous gland (B) secretes sebum into hair follicles; eccrine sweat gland (C) is in skin for cooling; mucous gland (D) secretes mucus.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The functional units of the breast responsible for milk secretion are called:',o:['Lobules','Ducts','Acini','Alveoli'],a:3,
    e:`The functional units of the breast responsible for milk secretion are alveoli, sac-like glandular structures lined by secretory cuboidal or columnar cells.<br><br>Alveoli are grouped into lobules; lobules grouped into lobes (15-20 per breast). Each lobe drains via a lactiferous duct opening at the nipple. Alveolar cells produce milk under prolactin stimulation. Myoepithelial cells around alveoli contract under oxytocin to eject milk during breastfeeding.<br><br>Lobules (A) are groups of alveoli; lactiferous ducts (B) are conducting; lobes (C) are larger units of lobules.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The breast typically contains how many lobes?',o:['5-10','15-20','25-30','35-40'],a:1,
    e:`The breast typically contains 15-20 lobes, arranged radially around the nipple. Each lobe is drained by its own lactiferous duct opening on the nipple surface.<br><br>Each lobe consists of multiple lobules, which contain the milk-secreting alveoli. Lobes are separated by fibrous septa (Cooper\'s ligaments) that suspend the breast from the pectoral fascia. Mastectomy procedures must address all lobes for complete removal of breast tissue.<br><br>5-10 (A) is too few; 25-30 (C) is too many; 40-50 (D) is too many.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Each lobe of the breast drains into:',o:['One lactiferous duct','A lymphatic vessel','Two ducts','Multiple ducts'],a:0,
    e:`Each lobe of the breast drains into one lactiferous duct, which opens on the nipple surface. There are therefore 15-20 lactiferous duct openings on the nipple.<br><br>Each lactiferous duct dilates beneath the nipple as the lactiferous sinus (a temporary milk reservoir during lactation), then narrows again as it opens at the nipple surface. The ducts are lined by simple cuboidal/columnar epithelium proximally, changing to stratified squamous near the nipple opening.<br><br>Multiple ducts (B) is incorrect; common terminal duct (C) is incorrect; single areolar duct (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The lactiferous ducts open onto which structure?',o:['Areola','Axilla','Nipple','Montgomery glands'],a:2,
    e:`The lactiferous ducts open onto the nipple, with 15-20 separate openings on the surface, one for each lobe of the breast.<br><br>The nipple is a conical or cylindrical projection in the centre of the breast, surrounded by the pigmented areola. The nipple contains smooth muscle fibres responsible for erection of the nipple in response to stimulation, cold or breastfeeding. The nipple is innervated by the 4th intercostal nerve.<br><br>Areola (A) is around nipple but not duct opening; lobule (B) is internal; alveolus (D) is internal.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The dilated portion of a lactiferous duct beneath the nipple is known as:',o:['Mammary sinus','Glandular sinus','Ductal ampulla','Lactiferous sinus'],a:3,
    e:`The dilated portion of a lactiferous duct beneath the nipple is known as the lactiferous sinus, a temporary milk reservoir during lactation.<br><br>The lactiferous sinuses store milk during the periods between feeds. They are emptied during breastfeeding by myoepithelial cell contraction (under oxytocin from the let-down reflex). The ducts narrow again as they open at the nipple surface, with 15-20 separate openings.<br><br>Alveolus (A) is the secretory unit; ampulla (B) is in fallopian tube; lobule (C) is a group of alveoli.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The breast lies on which muscle primarily?',o:['Serratus anterior','Pectoralis minor','Pectoralis major','Rectus abdominis'],a:2,
    e:`The breast lies primarily on the pectoralis major muscle, with the lower lateral part extending over the serratus anterior. The retromammary space lies between the breast and pectoral fascia.<br><br>The breast extends from the 2nd to 6th ribs vertically and from the sternum to the mid-axillary line horizontally. The axillary tail of Spence extends into the axilla. The retromammary space allows the breast to move on the pectoral fascia, lost when carcinoma fixes the breast (peau d\'orange).<br><br>Pectoralis minor (A) is deeper; serratus anterior (B) is partial; latissimus dorsi (D) is lateral.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The axillary tail of Spence extends into:',o:['Abdomen','Axilla','Arm','Neck'],a:1,
    e:`The axillary tail of Spence extends into the axilla, the upper outer quadrant projection of breast tissue.<br><br>The axillary tail is clinically important because breast cancer can arise here and present as an axillary mass, sometimes mistaken for axillary lymphadenopathy. It is also a site of accessory breast tissue (axillary polymastia). Examination of the breast must include the axillary tail to detect masses there.<br><br>Pectoral region (A) is the body of breast; supraclavicular (C) is too high; abdominal wall (D) is too low.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The main arterial supply of the breast is from:',o:['All of the above','Axillary artery branches','Internal thoracic artery','Intercostal arteries'],a:0,
    e:`The main arterial supply of the breast is from multiple sources: internal thoracic (mammary) artery (medial), lateral thoracic artery (from axillary, lateral), and posterior intercostal arteries (perforating branches).<br><br>Internal thoracic artery branches (perforating branches of intercostal spaces 2-4) supply the medial breast. Lateral thoracic artery supplies the lateral breast. Posterior intercostal arteries supply via perforating branches. This rich vascular supply is important in plastic and reconstructive breast surgery planning.<br><br>Internal thoracic only (B) is partial; lateral thoracic only (C) is partial; posterior intercostals only (D) is partial.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The majority of lymphatic drainage of the breast goes to:',o:['Internal mammary nodes','Cervical nodes','Supraclavicular nodes','Axillary lymph nodes'],a:3,
    e:`The majority of lymphatic drainage of the breast (about 75 percent) goes to the axillary lymph nodes, particularly the pectoral (anterior) group of axillary nodes initially.<br><br>The remaining 25 percent drains to internal mammary (parasternal) nodes (mainly from medial quadrants). Some drainage also goes to supraclavicular nodes (especially with advanced disease) and rarely to opposite breast or abdomen. Sentinel lymph node biopsy in breast cancer most often samples the axillary nodes initially.<br><br>Internal mammary (A) drain medial quadrants; supraclavicular (B) is small drainage; pectoral (C) is part of axillary group.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The nipple is surrounded by pigmented skin called:',o:['Areola','Papilla','Mammary disc','Lobule'],a:0,
    e:`The nipple is surrounded by pigmented skin called the areola. The areola contains modified sebaceous glands (Montgomery glands or tubercles) that lubricate the nipple during breastfeeding.<br><br>Areolar pigmentation increases during pregnancy due to estrogen and progesterone, becoming permanently darker. The areola contains smooth muscle fibres similar to those of the nipple, contributing to nipple erection. Montgomery tubercles enlarge during pregnancy, becoming visible as small bumps on the areola.<br><br>Lobe (B) is internal structure; lactiferous duct (C) is internal; lactiferous sinus (D) is internal.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Montgomery glands are modified:',o:['Sweat glands','Sebaceous glands','Endocrine glands','Lymph glands'],a:1,
    e:`Montgomery glands are modified sebaceous glands of the areola, opening into small projections (Montgomery tubercles) visible on the areolar surface.<br><br>They lubricate the nipple during breastfeeding and have a role in mother-infant bonding through scent. The tubercles enlarge during pregnancy under hormonal influence and become more visible. Inflammation or infection of these glands can cause areolar discomfort or small abscesses requiring treatment.<br><br>Sweat glands (A) are eccrine in skin; mucous glands (C) secrete mucus; mammary alveoli (D) produce milk.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The mammary ridge (milk line) extends embryologically from:',o:['Shoulder to abdomen','Neck to chest','Axilla to groin','Thorax to pelvis'],a:2,
    e:`The mammary ridge (milk line) extends embryologically from axilla to groin (along the ventrolateral surface of the embryo on each side).<br><br>The breast normally develops only at the pectoral region; the rest of the milk line regresses. Failure of regression leads to supernumerary nipples (polythelia) or accessory breast tissue (polymastia) anywhere along the milk line, most commonly in the axilla or on the upper abdomen below the breast.<br><br>Neck to umbilicus (A) is partial; chest to perineum (B) is partial; thorax to pubis (D) is partial.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Supernumerary nipples occurring along the milk line are termed:',o:['Gynecomastia','Polymastia','Mastitis','Polythelia'],a:3,
    e:`Supernumerary nipples occurring along the milk line are termed polythelia. They are extra nipples without underlying breast tissue.<br><br>Polythelia results from failure of regression of part of the mammary ridge. Most common site is below the normal breast on the upper abdomen. Polythelia is usually asymptomatic and cosmetic. It may rarely be associated with renal anomalies (since the milk line shares embryological development period with the kidney).<br><br>Polymastia (A) is extra breast tissue; gynecomastia (B) is male breast development; mastitis (C) is breast inflammation.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Presence of extra breast tissue is called:',o:['Polymastia','Polythelia','Macromastia','Gynecomastia'],a:0,
    e:`Presence of extra breast tissue is called polymastia, including both supernumerary breast tissue and supernumerary nipples in some cases.<br><br>Polymastia results from failure of regression of part of the mammary ridge. Most common site is the axilla (axillary polymastia). The accessory tissue can undergo cyclical changes with the menstrual cycle and may enlarge during pregnancy or develop the same diseases as normal breast tissue including cancer.<br><br>Polythelia (B) is just extra nipples; gynecomastia (C) is male breast development; mastitis (D) is inflammation.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Development of breast tissue in males is known as:',o:['Polymastia','Mastalgia','Polythelia','Gynecomastia'],a:3,
    e:`Development of breast tissue in males is known as gynecomastia, due to imbalance of estrogen-to-testosterone ratio favouring estrogen.<br><br>Causes include physiological (newborn, puberty, ageing), pathological (testicular tumours, liver disease, hyperthyroidism, hypogonadism) or drugs (spironolactone, ketoconazole, anabolic steroids, marijuana). Treatment depends on cause; persistent cases may need surgical correction. It must be distinguished from male breast cancer.<br><br>Polythelia (A) is extra nipples; polymastia (B) is extra breast tissue (in females or males); galactorrhoea (C) is milk discharge.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The breast develops embryologically from:',o:['Neural crest','Surface ectoderm','Mesoderm','Endoderm'],a:1,
    e:`The breast develops embryologically from surface ectoderm, specifically from epidermal downgrowths along the mammary ridge (milk line).<br><br>The mammary buds appear during the 6th week of development as solid epidermal projections into the underlying mesenchyme. They form 15-20 secondary buds (future lobes) by week 12. Lactiferous ducts canalise late in gestation. Underlying mesoderm forms the connective tissue and fat of the breast.<br><br>Mesoderm (A) forms connective tissue and fat; endoderm (C) forms gut; neural crest (D) forms nerves and skin pigment.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The mammary buds appear during which week of development?',o:['4th week','12th week','6th week','8th week'],a:2,
    e:`The mammary buds appear during the 6th week of embryonic development, as solid epidermal projections into the underlying mesenchyme along the mammary ridge.<br><br>By week 12, secondary buds (15-20) form, becoming the future lobes of the breast. Lactiferous ducts canalise late in gestation under maternal hormonal influence. The underlying mesoderm forms the connective tissue and fat. Newborn breast may show a small amount of milky discharge (\'witch\'s milk\') due to maternal hormones.<br><br>4th week (A) is too early; 8th week (B) is buds already formed; 12th week (D) is when secondary buds develop.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The connective tissue supporting the breast is known as:',o:['Suspensory ligaments of uterus','Inguinal ligaments','Round ligaments','Cooper\'s ligaments'],a:3,
    e:`The connective tissue supporting the breast is known as Cooper\'s ligaments (suspensory ligaments of Cooper). They are fibrous bands extending from the pectoral fascia through the breast tissue to the dermis of the skin.<br><br>Cooper\'s ligaments suspend the breast from the pectoral fascia and support its shape. With age and breast enlargement, they stretch causing breast ptosis. Involvement by carcinoma (tethering) causes characteristic skin dimpling, an important clinical sign of breast cancer detected on physical examination.<br><br>Pectoralis major (A) is the underlying muscle; broad ligament (B) is in pelvis; round ligament (C) is in pelvis.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Retraction of the skin overlying a breast tumor occurs due to involvement of:',o:['Mammary ducts','Cooper\'s ligaments','Lactiferous sinuses','Areolar glands'],a:1,
    e:`Retraction of the skin overlying a breast tumour occurs due to involvement of Cooper\'s ligaments by the tumour.<br><br>When carcinoma invades and shortens Cooper\'s ligaments, it pulls the skin inward, producing characteristic skin dimpling. This is an important clinical sign of breast cancer detected on physical examination, especially when the breast is elevated to put tension on the ligaments. Nipple retraction can occur similarly with central tumours.<br><br>Pectoralis major (A) is muscle; broad ligament (C) is in pelvis; round ligament (D) is in pelvis.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The epithelium lining lactiferous ducts near the nipple becomes:',o:['Stratified squamous epithelium','Simple cuboidal epithelium','Transitional epithelium','Columnar epithelium'],a:0,
    e:`The epithelium lining lactiferous ducts near the nipple becomes stratified squamous epithelium, providing protection against mechanical and chemical insults at the duct opening.<br><br>The lactiferous ducts are lined by simple cuboidal/columnar epithelium proximally (in the breast tissue), changing to stratified squamous near the nipple opening. The transition zone is similar to other ducts opening to skin or mucous membranes (where stratified squamous provides surface protection).<br><br>Simple columnar (B) is in proximal ducts; pseudostratified columnar (C) is in respiratory tract; transitional (D) is in urinary tract.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The alveoli of the lactating breast are lined by:',o:['Transitional cells','Stratified squamous cells','Secretory cuboidal or columnar cells','Endothelial cells'],a:2,
    e:`The alveoli of the lactating breast are lined by secretory cuboidal or columnar cells, surrounded by a basket of myoepithelial cells.<br><br>The secretory cells produce milk components (lactose, lipids, proteins like casein and whey). Myoepithelial cells are contractile, expelling milk into the ducts during the let-down reflex (oxytocin-stimulated). In non-lactating breast, the alveoli are smaller and inactive, with simpler epithelium.<br><br>Stratified squamous (A) is in skin/vagina; transitional (B) is in urinary tract; pseudostratified columnar (D) is in respiratory tract.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Milk ejection from the breast is mainly stimulated by:',o:['Prolactin','Oxytocin','Estrogen','Progesterone'],a:1,
    e:`Milk ejection from the breast is mainly stimulated by oxytocin, which causes contraction of myoepithelial cells around the alveoli, expelling milk into the ducts (the \'let-down reflex\').<br><br>Oxytocin is released from the posterior pituitary in response to nipple stimulation by suckling, or by emotional/sensory cues (baby crying, sight of baby). Oxytocin also stimulates uterine contractions, helping postpartum uterine involution. Stress and anxiety can inhibit oxytocin release, impairing milk ejection.<br><br>Prolactin (A) stimulates milk production not ejection; estrogen (C) stimulates ductal growth; progesterone (D) stimulates alveolar development.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Milk production in the breast is stimulated primarily by:',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Prolactin','Oxytocin'],a:2,
    e:`Milk production in the breast is stimulated primarily by prolactin from the anterior pituitary. Prolactin acts on alveolar secretory cells to produce milk components.<br><br>Prolactin secretion is normally inhibited by dopamine from the hypothalamus. During lactation, suckling stimulates prolactin release through neuroendocrine reflex. Prolactin levels also suppress GnRH release, causing lactational amenorrhoea (a natural contraceptive effect, though not reliable for individual contraception).<br><br>Oxytocin (A) causes ejection not production; estrogen (B) stimulates ductal growth; progesterone (D) stimulates alveolar development.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'During pregnancy, enlargement of the breast occurs mainly due to:',o:['Increased adipose tissue','Muscle hypertrophy','Increased connective tissue','Proliferation of glandular tissue'],a:3,
    e:`During pregnancy, enlargement of the breast occurs mainly due to proliferation of glandular tissue (alveolar and ductal proliferation) under hormonal influence.<br><br>Estrogen stimulates ductal growth; progesterone stimulates alveolar development. Human placental lactogen (hPL), prolactin and other hormones contribute. Alveoli become functional in the second half of pregnancy, producing colostrum. After delivery, prolactin activates milk synthesis with the loss of placental progesterone.<br><br>Adipose tissue (A) is the major non-pregnant component; muscular hypertrophy (B) is incorrect; venous engorgement (C) is partial.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'In the non-lactating breast, the majority of the breast tissue consists of:',o:['Adipose tissue','Glandular tissue','Lymphoid tissue','Smooth muscle'],a:0,
    e:`In the non-lactating breast, the majority of the breast tissue consists of adipose tissue (with small amounts of glandular tissue and connective tissue/Cooper\'s ligaments).<br><br>The amount of glandular tissue varies between women. Mammographic density is determined by the proportion of glandular versus fatty tissue: dense breasts (more glandular) are harder to image and have slightly higher cancer risk. Postmenopausal breasts have more adipose, easier mammographic interpretation.<br><br>Glandular tissue (B) is small in non-lactating; fibrous tissue (C) is moderate; muscular tissue (D) is absent within breast.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The lymph from medial quadrants of breast primarily drains to:',o:['Cervical nodes','Internal mammary nodes','Axillary nodes','Inguinal nodes'],a:1,
    e:`The lymph from medial quadrants of breast primarily drains to the internal mammary (parasternal) nodes, located along the internal thoracic artery on the deep aspect of the chest wall.<br><br>The internal mammary nodes drain about 25 percent of breast lymphatic drainage (mainly the medial quadrants). The remaining 75 percent (lateral quadrants) drains to axillary nodes. Internal mammary node involvement in breast cancer indicates locally advanced disease and influences staging and treatment.<br><br>Axillary nodes (A) drain lateral quadrants; supraclavicular (C) is small drainage; cervical (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which lymph nodes receive drainage from the upper outer quadrant of breast?',o:['Internal mammary nodes','Cervical nodes','Supraclavicular nodes','Axillary lymph nodes'],a:3,
    e:`The axillary lymph nodes receive drainage from the upper outer quadrant of breast (the most common site of breast cancer). About 75 percent of breast lymphatic drainage goes to axillary nodes.<br><br>The axillary nodes are arranged in groups: anterior (pectoral), posterior (subscapular), lateral, central and apical. Axillary lymphadenectomy (Level I, II, III) is part of breast cancer staging and treatment. Sentinel lymph node biopsy may avoid extensive lymphadenectomy in early breast cancer.<br><br>Internal mammary nodes (A) drain medial quadrants; supraclavicular (B) is small drainage; mediastinal nodes (C) is rare for breast.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The nipple contains which type of muscle fibers responsible for erection of the nipple?',o:['Cardiac muscle fibers','Skeletal muscle fibers','Smooth muscle fibers','Elastic cartilage'],a:2,
    e:`The nipple contains smooth muscle fibres responsible for erection of the nipple in response to stimulation, cold or breastfeeding.<br><br>These smooth muscle fibres are arranged longitudinally and circularly under the skin of the nipple and areola. Their contraction makes the nipple firm and protruding, facilitating breastfeeding. The nipple is innervated by the 4th intercostal nerve, which carries sympathetic fibres to these smooth muscles.<br><br>Skeletal muscle (A) is voluntary; cardiac muscle (B) is in heart; absence of muscle (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'A congenital condition where the nipple fails to protrude is called:',o:['Inverted nipple','Gynecomastia','Polythelia','Polymastia'],a:0,
    e:`A congenital condition where the nipple fails to protrude is called inverted nipple. The nipple is retracted into the breast tissue rather than projecting outward.<br><br>Congenital inverted nipple is bilateral and longstanding. Acquired nipple inversion is unilateral and recent, suspicious for breast cancer (especially when associated with bloody nipple discharge). Inverted nipples can cause difficulties with breastfeeding; nipple eversion devices may help in some cases.<br><br>Polythelia (B) is extra nipples; gynecomastia (C) is male breast development; Paget disease (D) is nipple cancer.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'During embryological development of the mammary gland, epithelial buds from the mammary ridge penetrate the underlying mesenchyme and branch to form lactiferous ducts. What is the embryological structure responsible for formation of the mammary gland?',o:['Genital ridge','Mammary ridge','Neural crest','Urogenital sinus'],a:1,
    e:`During embryological development of the mammary gland, epithelial buds from the surface ectoderm form the mammary ridge (milk line) along the ventrolateral surface of the embryo.<br><br>The mammary ridge extends from axilla to groin. The breast normally develops only at the pectoral region; the rest of the milk line regresses. Failure of regression leads to supernumerary nipples (polythelia) or accessory breast tissue (polymastia) anywhere along the milk line.<br><br>Genital ridge (A) is for gonads; pronephros (C) is vestigial; metanephros (D) is for kidneys.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The suspensory ligaments of the breast attach the breast tissue to:',o:['Dermis of the skin','Rib periosteum','Pectoralis major muscle','Axillary fascia'],a:0,
    e:`The suspensory ligaments of the breast (Cooper\'s ligaments) attach the breast tissue to the dermis of the skin and to the pectoral fascia, suspending the breast.<br><br>These fibrous bands extend through the breast tissue, supporting its shape against gravity. With age and breast enlargement, they stretch causing breast ptosis. Involvement by carcinoma (tethering) causes characteristic skin dimpling, an important clinical sign detected on physical examination of the breast.<br><br>Pectoralis major fascia (B) only is partial - they connect both; muscle directly (C) is incorrect; vertebrae (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The retromammary space lies between:',o:['Skin and breast tissue','Breast and ribs','Breast and pectoral fascia','Breast and axilla'],a:2,
    e:`The retromammary space lies between the breast and pectoral fascia. It is a loose areolar layer allowing the breast to move freely on the underlying chest wall.<br><br>This space is important for breast mobility on the chest wall. Loss of mobility (fixation to chest wall) suggests advanced breast cancer with deep invasion. The retromammary space is also important in plastic surgery (placement of breast implants is typically in this space, called subglandular placement).<br><br>Skin and breast (A) is superficial; ribs and pleura (B) is deeper; pectoralis major and minor (D) is between muscles.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Fixation of breast to the pectoral fascia occurs due to:',o:['Axillary tail','Areola','Retromammary space','Cooper\'s ligaments'],a:3,
    e:`Fixation of breast to the pectoral fascia occurs due to invasion of Cooper\'s ligaments by tumour, extending into the retromammary space.<br><br>Cooper\'s ligaments extend from the dermis through the breast tissue to the pectoral fascia, suspending the breast. Tumour invasion shortens these ligaments and obliterates the retromammary space, fixing the breast to the chest wall. This indicates advanced disease (T4 in TNM staging) and influences treatment decisions.<br><br>Pectoralis major fascia (A) directly is later involvement; skin (B) is more superficial; bone (C) is even later metastatic invasion.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Paget disease of the breast primarily affects:',o:['Mammary ducts only','Axilla','Nipple and areola','Lobules'],a:2,
    e:`Paget disease of the breast primarily affects the nipple and areola, presenting with eczematous changes (itching, scaling, redness) of the nipple-areolar complex.<br><br>It is associated with underlying breast cancer (intraductal or invasive) in over 95 percent of cases. The skin changes result from migration of malignant cells from the underlying duct cancer to the nipple epidermis. Diagnosis is by skin biopsy showing Paget cells; treatment includes mastectomy or wide excision plus axillary assessment.<br><br>Whole breast (A) is not specific; axillary tail (B) is unrelated; lower outer quadrant (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone causes proliferation of breast ducts during puberty?',o:['Estrogen','Oxytocin','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:0,
    e:`Estrogen causes proliferation of breast ducts during puberty. Estrogen levels rise at puberty under HPG axis activation, driving ductal growth as the first stage of breast development (thelarche).<br><br>After ductal development, progesterone (from luteal phase cycles) stimulates alveolar development. Adult breast is a balance of estrogen and progesterone effects. Pregnancy further enhances breast development with hPL, prolactin and high estrogen and progesterone, preparing the breast for lactation.<br><br>Progesterone (B) stimulates alveolar development; prolactin (C) stimulates milk production; oxytocin (D) causes milk ejection.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Progesterone primarily stimulates which component of breast development?',o:['Connective tissue growth','Alveolar development','Ductal growth','Adipose deposition'],a:1,
    e:`Progesterone primarily stimulates alveolar development of the breast. After estrogen-driven ductal proliferation, progesterone causes the formation of alveolar buds at the ends of the ducts.<br><br>Progesterone effects are evident during luteal phase of menstrual cycle (some breast tenderness/swelling premenstrually) and become marked during pregnancy. The combination of estrogen and progesterone with placental hormones in pregnancy completes alveolar development for lactation. Prolactin then activates milk production.<br><br>Ductal proliferation (A) is by estrogen; nipple erection (C) is smooth muscle; milk production (D) is by prolactin.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'During lactation, myoepithelial cells surrounding alveoli help in:',o:['Lymph drainage','Hormone synthesis','Blood supply regulation','Milk ejection'],a:3,
    e:`During lactation, myoepithelial cells surrounding alveoli help in milk ejection. Their contraction (under oxytocin) expels milk from alveoli into the ducts and out through the nipple.<br><br>Myoepithelial cells are basket-shaped contractile cells of ectodermal origin (despite being smooth muscle-like). They surround both alveoli and ducts. Oxytocin from the posterior pituitary triggers contraction in response to suckling stimulation - the let-down reflex. Stress can inhibit oxytocin and impair milk ejection.<br><br>Milk synthesis (A) is by alveolar secretory cells; structural support (B) is partial; immune defence (C) is by other cells.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which histological feature distinguishes lactating breast from non-lactating breast?',o:['Keratinized ducts','Increased adipose tissue','Enlarged alveoli filled with milk','Absence of lobules'],a:2,
    e:`The histological feature distinguishing lactating breast from non-lactating breast is enlarged alveoli filled with milk, with active secretory cuboidal/columnar cells lining them.<br><br>In lactating breast, alveoli are dilated with milk in their lumens (visible eosinophilic material). Secretory cells show evidence of active synthesis (lipid droplets, vesicles). In non-lactating breast, alveoli are small or collapsed with simpler epithelium. Myoepithelial cells are present in both states surrounding alveoli.<br><br>Increased fat tissue (A) is non-specific; thicker septa (B) is incorrect; absence of ducts (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Breast carcinoma most commonly arises from:',o:['Lobular epithelium','Adipose tissue','Connective tissue','Ductal epithelium'],a:3,
    e:`Breast carcinoma most commonly arises from ductal epithelium. Invasive ductal carcinoma is the most common type, accounting for about 75 percent of breast cancers.<br><br>Lobular carcinoma (from terminal duct lobular unit) is the second most common at about 10-15 percent. Other types include medullary, mucinous, tubular and inflammatory. Most ductal cancers begin as ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) before becoming invasive. Mammographic screening detects many cancers at the DCIS stage.<br><br>Adipose tissue (A) gives liposarcoma (rare); muscle (B) is rare; lymphatic vessels (C) gives angiosarcoma (rare).<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common type of breast cancer is:',o:['Lobular carcinoma','Invasive ductal carcinoma','Medullary carcinoma','Mucinous carcinoma'],a:1,
    e:`The most common type of breast cancer is invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC), accounting for about 75 percent of breast cancers.<br><br>IDC arises from ductal epithelium and invades the surrounding stroma. It typically presents as a hard, irregular mass on examination. On mammography, it appears as a stellate or spiculated lesion. Diagnosis is by core biopsy; treatment includes surgery (lumpectomy or mastectomy), axillary assessment, plus chemotherapy, radiotherapy and hormonal therapy as indicated.<br><br>Lobular carcinoma (A) is second most common; medullary (C) is uncommon; inflammatory (D) is rare and aggressive.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Orange peel appearance of breast skin in carcinoma is called:',o:['Peau d\'orange','Mastitis','Dermatitis','Cellulitis'],a:0,
    e:`Orange peel appearance of breast skin in carcinoma is called peau d\'orange, due to dermal lymphatic obstruction by tumour causing skin oedema with retention of hair follicle pits.<br><br>Peau d\'orange is a sign of locally advanced breast cancer (T4 in TNM staging) or inflammatory breast cancer. The skin is thick, oedematous, with prominent hair follicle dimples giving the orange peel appearance. Inflammatory breast cancer presents with rapid progression, redness, warmth and peau d\'orange but no discrete mass.<br><br>Inverted nipple (B) is from duct involvement; skin dimpling (C) is from Cooper\'s ligament; nipple discharge (D) is from duct involvement.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which structure is responsible for dimpling of breast skin in carcinoma?',o:['Mammary ducts','Lactiferous sinus','Areola','Cooper\'s ligaments'],a:3,
    e:`Cooper\'s ligaments are responsible for dimpling of breast skin in carcinoma. When the tumour invades and shortens these fibrous bands, it pulls the skin inward, producing characteristic skin dimpling.<br><br>Skin dimpling is an important clinical sign of breast cancer detected on physical examination, especially when the breast is elevated or the arms raised to put tension on Cooper\'s ligaments. Nipple retraction can occur similarly with central tumours involving the lactiferous ducts and surrounding tissues.<br><br>Pectoralis major (A) involvement causes fixation; lactiferous ducts (B) cause nipple inversion; lymphatics (C) cause peau d\'orange.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Enlargement of breast tissue in adolescent males during puberty is usually:',o:['Breast carcinoma','Physiological gynecomastia','Mastitis','Polymastia'],a:1,
    e:`Enlargement of breast tissue in adolescent males during puberty is usually physiological gynecomastia, due to transient imbalance of estrogen-to-testosterone ratio.<br><br>Pubertal gynecomastia affects up to 70 percent of adolescent boys and usually resolves spontaneously within 1-2 years as testosterone levels rise. It can be unilateral or bilateral and may be tender. Persistent or progressive cases beyond 2 years should be investigated for pathological causes (testicular tumours, drugs, endocrine disorders).<br><br>Pathological gynecomastia (A) has organic cause; lipomastia (C) is fat-related; gynecological cancer (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Accessory breast tissue located in the axilla is known as:',o:['Mastitis','Polythelia','Axillary polymastia','Gynecomastia'],a:2,
    e:`Accessory breast tissue located in the axilla is known as axillary polymastia. It results from failure of regression of the upper end of the mammary ridge (milk line).<br><br>Axillary polymastia is the most common site of accessory breast tissue. It can undergo cyclical changes with the menstrual cycle and may enlarge during pregnancy or develop the same diseases as normal breast tissue including cancer. Surgical excision may be considered for cosmetic or symptomatic reasons.<br><br>Polythelia (A) is extra nipples; gynecomastia (B) is in males; mastitis (D) is inflammation.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The nipple receives sensory innervation mainly from:',o:['4th intercostal nerve','2nd intercostal nerve','6th intercostal nerve','Phrenic nerve'],a:0,
    e:`The nipple receives sensory innervation mainly from the 4th intercostal nerve, specifically its anterior cutaneous branch (lateral branch in some texts).<br><br>This dermatomal innervation is important to preserve during reduction mammoplasty or other breast surgeries to maintain nipple sensation. Sensation is essential for breastfeeding (suckling triggers oxytocin release for the let-down reflex). Damage to this nerve causes nipple anaesthesia, which can occur after breast surgery.<br><br>T2 nerve (B) is too high; T6 nerve (C) is too low; thoracodorsal nerve (D) supplies latissimus dorsi.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The lymphatics of the breast may communicate with the opposite breast mainly through:',o:['Cooper ligaments','Retromammary space','Subareolar plexus','Axillary tail'],a:2,
    e:`The lymphatics of the breast may communicate with the opposite breast mainly through the subareolar plexus (Sappey\'s plexus), via lymphatic channels crossing the midline.<br><br>This communication is clinically important: breast cancer can occasionally metastasise to the contralateral breast or contralateral axillary nodes through this route, although it is uncommon. Subareolar plexus is also important in lymphoscintigraphy for sentinel lymph node biopsy in breast cancer assessment.<br><br>Internal mammary chain (A) is mostly ipsilateral; deep cervical (B) is unrelated; axillary directly (D) is ipsilateral.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The subareolar lymphatic plexus is also called:',o:['Sappey\'s plexus','Auerbach plexus','Meissner plexus','Luschka plexus'],a:0,
    e:`The subareolar lymphatic plexus is also called Sappey\'s plexus, located beneath the areola where lymphatic vessels from the breast converge before draining to axillary or internal mammary nodes.<br><br>Sappey\'s plexus is a key landmark in lymphoscintigraphy for sentinel lymph node biopsy in breast cancer. Radioactive tracer or blue dye injected here drains via the same lymphatics as cancer cells would, identifying the sentinel node. Communication with contralateral breast can occur through this plexus rarely.<br><br>Cooper\'s plexus (B) is not a lymphatic plexus; pectoral plexus (C) is in axilla; mammary plexus (D) is non-specific.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Inflammatory carcinoma of the breast produces skin edema mainly due to obstruction of:',o:['Arteries','Veins','Nerves','Lymphatic vessels'],a:3,
    e:`Inflammatory carcinoma of the breast produces skin oedema mainly due to obstruction of lymphatic vessels by tumour cells in the dermal lymphatics.<br><br>The blockage prevents lymphatic drainage of interstitial fluid from the skin, causing oedema. The thick oedematous skin with retained hair follicle pits gives peau d\'orange appearance. Inflammatory breast cancer presents with rapid progression, redness, warmth and peau d\'orange but no discrete mass; it has poor prognosis.<br><br>Bacterial infection (A) is mastitis; venous obstruction (B) is rare; muscular invasion (C) causes fixation.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'During histological examination of the mammary gland, clusters of secretory alveoli surrounded by myoepithelial cells and draining into small ducts are identified. These clusters together form the basic structural and functional unit of the breast responsible for milk production. What is this unit called?',o:['Sinus','Lobule','Duct','Areola'],a:1,
    e:`During histological examination of the mammary gland, clusters of secretory alveoli grouped together form a lobule. Multiple lobules form a lobe.<br><br>The breast has 15-20 lobes, each with multiple lobules. Each lobule contains the milk-secreting alveoli grouped around small ductules. Lobules drain via intralobular ducts into the lactiferous duct of each lobe. The terminal duct lobular unit (TDLU) is the basic functional unit and the most common site of breast cancer origin.<br><br>Lobe (A) is composed of multiple lobules; alveolus (C) is single secretory unit; lactiferous duct (D) is conducting duct.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The placenta is formed from which two components?',o:['Amnion and chorion','Chorion laeve and decidua capsularis','Chorion frondosum and decidua basalis','Decidua parietalis and amnion'],a:2,
    e:`The placenta is formed from the chorion frondosum (fetal part) and the decidua basalis (maternal part), which interface to allow exchange between maternal and fetal circulations.<br><br>The chorion frondosum forms the bushy part of the chorion overlying the embryonic pole, with branching villi that contact maternal blood. The decidua basalis is the modified endometrium beneath the implantation site. Together they form the discoid placenta with about 15-20 cotyledons by the second trimester.<br><br>Chorion laeve and decidua capsularis (A) regress; amnion and chorion (B) are membranes only; yolk sac and allantois (D) are vestigial.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The fetal part of the placenta is derived from:',o:['Decidua basalis','Chorion frondosum','Amnion','Decidua capsularis'],a:1,
    e:`The fetal part of the placenta is derived from the chorion frondosum, the bushy part of the chorion overlying the embryonic pole, with branching villi that contact maternal blood.<br><br>The chorion frondosum villi develop into the structural and functional units of the fetal placenta (cotyledons). Each cotyledon contains a stem villus with branches into the intervillous space, allowing exchange with maternal blood. The chorion laeve (smooth chorion) regresses to form the chorion membrane.<br><br>Decidua basalis (A) is maternal part; chorion laeve (C) regresses; yolk sac (D) is vestigial.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The maternal part of the placenta develops from:',o:['Chorion laeve','Decidua capsularis','Decidua parietalis','Decidua basalis'],a:3,
    e:`The maternal part of the placenta develops from the decidua basalis, the modified endometrium directly beneath the implantation site.<br><br>The decidua basalis contributes the basal plate of the placenta and the maternal blood supply via spiral arteries. The decidua capsularis (covering the conceptus on the cavity side) and decidua parietalis (rest of endometrium) regress as the fetus grows. Trophoblastic invasion of spiral arteries is essential for normal placental function.<br><br>Chorion frondosum (A) is fetal part; chorion laeve (B) regresses; amnion (C) covers fetal surface.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The basic structural and functional unit of the placenta is:',o:['Cotyledon','Placental lobule','Chorionic plate','Decidual septum'],a:0,
    e:`The basic structural and functional unit of the placenta is the cotyledon, formed by a major stem villus and its branches in the intervillous space.<br><br>There are about 15-20 cotyledons in the term placenta, separated by placental septa from the maternal side. Each cotyledon has its own stem villus with branches functioning as the unit of maternofetal exchange. Cotyledons are visible as lobes on the maternal surface of the delivered placenta during inspection.<br><br>Trophoblast (B) is the cell layer; villus (C) is the basic projection; intervillous space (D) is the maternal blood pool.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The placenta is usually discoid in shape and weighs approximately:',o:['200 g','500 g','350 g','800 g'],a:1,
    e:`The placenta is usually discoid in shape and weighs approximately 500 g (about one-sixth of fetal weight) at term.<br><br>Normal placenta is 15-20 cm in diameter, 2-3 cm thick at the centre, and weighs 400-600 g at term. Abnormalities of placental size or shape (e.g. small placenta in IUGR, large placenta in diabetes, succenturiate or bilobed placenta) may be associated with pregnancy complications. Placental weight is documented at delivery.<br><br>200 g (A) is too small; 1 kg (C) is too large; 2 kg (D) is much too large.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The average diameter of the placenta at term is:',o:['15-20 cm','10-15 cm','5-10 cm','25-30 cm'],a:0,
    e:`The average diameter of the placenta at term is 15-20 cm. Other dimensions: thickness 2-3 cm at centre and weight 400-600 g (typically 500 g).<br><br>Abnormalities of placental shape include succenturiate placenta (accessory lobe), bilobed placenta, circumvallate placenta and battledore placenta (eccentric cord insertion). Placenta praevia is when the placenta covers or partially covers the internal cervical os, requiring careful management to avoid antepartum haemorrhage.<br><br>5-10 cm (B) is too small; 25-30 cm (C) is too large; 30-40 cm (D) is much too large.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The umbilical cord normally contains how many vessels?',o:['One artery and one vein','One artery and two veins','Two arteries and two veins','Two arteries and one vein'],a:3,
    e:`The umbilical cord normally contains three vessels: two umbilical arteries (carrying deoxygenated blood from fetus to placenta) and one umbilical vein (carrying oxygenated blood from placenta to fetus).<br><br>These vessels are embedded in Wharton\'s jelly, a gelatinous connective tissue providing protection and preventing kinking. Single umbilical artery (SUA) occurs in about 1 percent of pregnancies and may be associated with congenital anomalies (especially renal). Cord vessels are routinely examined after delivery.<br><br>One artery one vein (A) is single artery; two veins one artery (B) is reversed; two arteries two veins (C) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The main function of the placenta is:',o:['Gas exchange','Nutrient transfer','All of the above','Hormone production'],a:2,
    e:`The main function of the placenta includes gas exchange (oxygen and CO2), transport of nutrients and waste, hormone production (hCG, hPL, estrogen, progesterone) and immune protection of the fetus.<br><br>These functions make the placenta a multi-functional organ replacing fetal lungs, kidneys, GI tract, liver and endocrine glands during fetal life. Placental insufficiency (poor placental function) leads to IUGR (intrauterine growth restriction), pre-eclampsia and other pregnancy complications requiring careful monitoring.<br><br>Gas exchange only (A) is partial; nutrient transport only (B) is partial; hormone production only (C) is partial; all three are major functions.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone is produced by the placenta during pregnancy?',o:['Human chorionic gonadotropin','All of the above','Human placental lactogen','Progesterone'],a:1,
    e:`The placenta produces multiple hormones during pregnancy: human chorionic gonadotrophin (hCG), human placental lactogen (hPL), estrogen and progesterone.<br><br>hCG is produced by syncytiotrophoblast from very early pregnancy, rescuing the corpus luteum and forming the basis of pregnancy tests. Progesterone is produced by placenta from week 7-10 onwards (taking over from corpus luteum). Estrogen requires fetal adrenal precursors. hPL increases maternal insulin resistance and lipid metabolism.<br><br>hCG only (A) is partial; progesterone only (C) is partial; estrogen only (D) is partial; all four are produced.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The placental barrier primarily separates:',o:['Umbilical vessels','Two fetal circulations','Maternal arteries and veins','Maternal and fetal blood circulation'],a:3,
    e:`The placental barrier primarily separates maternal and fetal blood circulation. The two circulations come close at the chorionic villi but do not normally mix.<br><br>The placental barrier consists of: syncytiotrophoblast, cytotrophoblast (in early pregnancy), basement membranes and fetal capillary endothelium. As pregnancy progresses, the barrier becomes thinner (cytotrophoblast disappears in third trimester), facilitating exchange. Some substances (e.g. anti-Rh antibodies) can cross via active transport.<br><br>Maternal and amniotic fluid (A) is by amnion; fetal and amniotic fluid (B) is by amnion; uterus and chorion (C) is decidual interface.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The earliest hormone detected in pregnancy produced by trophoblast cells is:',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','hCG','hPL'],a:2,
    e:`The earliest hormone detected in pregnancy produced by trophoblast cells is human chorionic gonadotrophin (hCG). It is produced by syncytiotrophoblast from about day 7-10 post-fertilisation.<br><br>hCG is the basis of pregnancy tests (urine and serum). Levels rise rapidly in early pregnancy, doubling every 48-72 hours, peaking at 8-10 weeks. hCG rescues the corpus luteum, maintaining progesterone production until placental progesterone takes over by week 7-10. High hCG suggests molar pregnancy or multiple gestation.<br><br>hPL (A) is later; progesterone (B) takes over from corpus luteum; estrogen (D) requires fetal adrenal precursors.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The trophoblast differentiates into which two layers?',o:['Cytotrophoblast and syncytiotrophoblast','Endoderm and mesoderm','Chorion and amnion','Decidua and chorion'],a:0,
    e:`The trophoblast differentiates into two layers: cytotrophoblast (inner, mononuclear cells) and syncytiotrophoblast (outer, multinucleated mass without cell boundaries).<br><br>Cytotrophoblast acts as a stem cell layer, producing new syncytiotrophoblast by fusion. Syncytiotrophoblast is the functional layer that invades the endometrium during implantation, contacts maternal blood in the intervillous space, and produces hCG and other placental hormones. The cytotrophoblast layer disappears in third trimester.<br><br>Inner and outer cell mass (B) is embryonic; ectoderm and endoderm (C) is later development; epiblast and hypoblast (D) is earlier embryonic disc.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The syncytiotrophoblast is responsible for:',o:['Hormone secretion','Nutrient transport','Implantation','All of the above'],a:3,
    e:`The syncytiotrophoblast is responsible for invasion of endometrium during implantation, hormone production (hCG, hPL, estrogen, progesterone) and exchange between maternal and fetal blood.<br><br>It is the multinucleated outer layer of the trophoblast, formed by fusion of cytotrophoblast cells. It directly contacts maternal blood in the intervillous space (no cell boundaries between syncytiotrophoblast cells, ensuring no maternal blood leakage between cells). Functions throughout pregnancy.<br><br>Implantation only (A) is partial; hormone secretion only (B) is partial; nutrient exchange only (C) is partial; all are functions.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Chorionic villi first appear during which week of development?',o:['2nd week','1st week','3rd week','5th week'],a:0,
    e:`Chorionic villi first appear during the 2nd week of development as primary chorionic villi (cytotrophoblast covered by syncytiotrophoblast).<br><br>The villi develop progressively: primary villi (week 2, cytotrophoblast core covered by syncytiotrophoblast); secondary villi (week 3, mesoderm core invading the cytotrophoblast); tertiary villi (week 4, fetal blood vessels in the mesoderm core, allowing maternofetal exchange to begin).<br><br>1st week (B) is too early; 3rd week (C) is when secondary villi form; 4th week (D) is when tertiary villi form.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Primary chorionic villi consist of:',o:['Cytotrophoblast only','Syncytiotrophoblast only','Cytotrophoblast covered by syncytiotrophoblast','Mesoderm core only'],a:2,
    e:`Primary chorionic villi consist of cytotrophoblast covered by syncytiotrophoblast. They are the earliest chorionic villi, appearing in the 2nd week of development.<br><br>Primary villi are simple cytotrophoblast projections covered externally by syncytiotrophoblast. They have no mesoderm core or vessels yet. By week 3, mesoderm invades the core (secondary villi); by week 4, blood vessels form in the mesoderm (tertiary villi), allowing maternofetal exchange to begin.<br><br>Mesoderm core (A) is in secondary villi; fetal vessels (B) is in tertiary villi; epithelium only (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Secondary chorionic villi contain:',o:['Blood vessels','Mesoderm core','Endoderm','Amniotic cells'],a:1,
    e:`Secondary chorionic villi contain a mesoderm core (in addition to the cytotrophoblast and syncytiotrophoblast layers). They appear in the 3rd week of development.<br><br>The mesoderm core invades the cytotrophoblast core of the primary villi, forming secondary villi. The mesoderm core is the precursor of the fetal vessels that will form in the tertiary villi. Secondary villi do not yet have functional vessels for blood circulation between fetus and placenta.<br><br>Cytotrophoblast only (A) is primary villi; fetal vessels (C) is in tertiary villi; epithelium only (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Tertiary chorionic villi contain:',o:['Mesoderm only','Amnion','Fetal blood vessels','Decidual tissue'],a:2,
    e:`Tertiary chorionic villi contain fetal blood vessels (in addition to mesoderm core, cytotrophoblast and syncytiotrophoblast). They appear in the 4th week of development.<br><br>Tertiary villi enable maternofetal exchange of gases, nutrients and waste through the placental barrier. The vessels in the villi connect to the umbilical arteries and veins, completing the fetoplacental circulation. Tertiary villi continue to branch and mature throughout pregnancy, increasing surface area.<br><br>Cytotrophoblast only (A) is primary; mesoderm only (B) is secondary; epithelium only (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The maternal blood enters the intervillous space from:',o:['Ovarian arteries','Umbilical arteries','Uterine veins','Spiral arteries'],a:3,
    e:`Maternal blood enters the intervillous space from the spiral arteries of the decidua basalis. Trophoblastic invasion of these arteries is essential for normal placental function.<br><br>The spiral arteries are remodelled by extravillous trophoblast invasion in the first half of pregnancy, becoming dilated low-resistance vessels that deliver blood to the intervillous space. Failure of this remodelling (shallow trophoblastic invasion) causes pre-eclampsia, IUGR and other pregnancy complications.<br><br>Uterine arteries (A) supply the uterus generally; ovarian arteries (B) supply ovaries; arcuate arteries (C) feed spiral arteries.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Maternal blood leaves the intervillous space through:',o:['Uterine veins','Umbilical veins','Spiral arteries','Fetal capillaries'],a:0,
    e:`Maternal blood leaves the intervillous space through the uterine veins of the decidua basalis. The drainage is open and continuous with the maternal venous system.<br><br>The intervillous space contains maternal blood pooling around the chorionic villi, allowing maternofetal exchange. The blood enters via spiral arteries and exits via decidual veins to the uterine veins. The placenta has no direct sinusoidal connection to the maternal arterial system; blood pools in an open lake (intervillous space).<br><br>Spiral arteries (B) are entry points; ovarian veins (C) drain ovaries; arcuate veins (D) feed uterine veins.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The fetal surface of the placenta is covered by:',o:['Chorion','Amnion','Decidua','Peritoneum'],a:1,
    e:`The fetal surface of the placenta is covered by amnion, the inner of the two membranes surrounding the fetus.<br><br>The amnion is a thin transparent membrane lining the amniotic cavity. It covers the chorionic plate (fetal surface of placenta) and the umbilical cord. The chorion is outside the amnion, with the chorion frondosum forming the placenta. After delivery, the membranes are inspected for completeness; retained membranes can cause postpartum complications.<br><br>Chorion (A) is outer; decidua (C) is maternal; trophoblast (D) is part of chorion early in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'During placental development, trophoblastic cells invade the maternal endometrium forming chorionic villi that project into maternal blood-filled spaces. These villi greatly increase the surface area available for exchange of gases, nutrients, and metabolic waste products between maternal and fetal circulation. What is the primary functional role of chorionic villi?',o:['Hormone storage','Fetal immune response','Exchange between maternal and fetal blood','Blood clot formation'],a:2,
    e:`During placental development, trophoblastic cells invade the maternal endometrium to facilitate implantation, anchorage and exchange between maternal and fetal blood.<br><br>Cytotrophoblastic stem cells differentiate into syncytiotrophoblast (the invading layer) and extravillous trophoblast (which invades spiral arteries to remodel them). This invasion is essential for normal placental function. Inadequate invasion causes pre-eclampsia, IUGR and other pregnancy complications.<br><br>Implantation only (A) is partial; hormone production (B) is by syncytiotrophoblast; protection (D) is partial.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The placenta acts as an endocrine organ producing hormones that maintain pregnancy. Which hormone maintains the corpus luteum during early pregnancy?',o:['hCG','Progesterone','hPL','Estrogen'],a:0,
    e:`The placenta acts as an endocrine organ producing hormones that maintain pregnancy. hCG (human chorionic gonadotrophin) is the earliest, produced by syncytiotrophoblast from very early pregnancy.<br><br>hCG rescues the corpus luteum, maintaining progesterone production until placental progesterone takes over by week 7-10. Other placental hormones include hPL, estrogen, progesterone, relaxin and CRH. The placenta is a complex multi-functional organ with extensive endocrine activity throughout pregnancy.<br><br>FSH (B) is from pituitary; LH (C) from pituitary; ACTH (D) from pituitary primarily.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Human placental lactogen primarily functions to:',o:['Stimulate uterine contractions','Increase maternal insulin resistance','Produce fetal hemoglobin','Maintain corpus luteum'],a:1,
    e:`Human placental lactogen (hPL) primarily functions to increase maternal insulin resistance, ensuring adequate glucose availability for the fetus by reducing maternal glucose utilisation.<br><br>hPL also stimulates maternal lipolysis (alternative energy source for mother) and breast development for lactation. The insulin resistance effect of hPL contributes to gestational diabetes mellitus in susceptible women. hPL levels rise progressively during pregnancy, peaking at term, falling rapidly after delivery.<br><br>Suppress lactation (A) is opposite; cause uterine contraction (C) is oxytocin/prostaglandins; cause labour (D) is multiple factors.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The placental membrane separating maternal and fetal blood consists of:',o:['Syncytiotrophoblast','Cytotrophoblast','Fetal capillary endothelium','All of the above'],a:3,
    e:`The placental membrane separating maternal and fetal blood consists of multiple layers: syncytiotrophoblast, cytotrophoblast (early pregnancy), basement membranes and fetal capillary endothelium.<br><br>As pregnancy progresses, the barrier becomes thinner (cytotrophoblast disappears in third trimester), facilitating exchange. The barrier prevents most maternal blood cells from reaching the fetus but allows passage of small molecules, gases, antibodies (IgG) and many drugs. Some drugs (heparin, insulin) do not cross.<br><br>Syncytiotrophoblast only (A) is partial; cytotrophoblast only (B) is partial; endothelium only (C) is partial; all layers form barrier.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Which structure anchors the placenta to the uterine wall?',o:['Chorionic plate','Floating villi','Anchoring villi','Umbilical cord'],a:2,
    e:`Anchoring villi anchor the placenta to the uterine wall. They extend from the chorionic plate to the basal plate (decidua basalis), providing structural attachment.<br><br>Anchoring villi are continuous with the trophoblastic shell at the maternal interface. Other villi are floating villi (free-floating in intervillous space, primary site of exchange). Both types contain stem villi with branching tertiary villi for maternofetal exchange. Adequate anchoring is essential for placental integrity.<br><br>Free villi (A) are floating; stem villi (B) are major branches; mesenchymal villi (D) are immature precursors.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The chorionic plate is located on which surface of the placenta?',o:['Fetal surface','Maternal surface','Decidual surface','Basal plate'],a:0,
    e:`The chorionic plate is located on the fetal surface of the placenta, the smooth shiny surface covered by the amnion through which the umbilical cord enters the placenta.<br><br>The chorionic plate gives off the stem villi that branch into the intervillous space. The fetal blood vessels (umbilical artery and vein branches) run on the chorionic plate before entering the villi. After delivery, the chorionic plate is examined for completeness and any vascular anomalies.<br><br>Maternal surface (B) is the basal plate; central portion (C) is the bulk; both surfaces (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The maternal surface of placenta is divided into lobes called:',o:['Lobules','Cotyledons','Villous units','Septa'],a:1,
    e:`The maternal surface of placenta is divided into lobes called cotyledons. There are about 15-20 cotyledons in the term placenta, separated by placental septa from the maternal side.<br><br>Each cotyledon contains a major stem villus and its branches in the intervillous space. The cotyledons are visible as bumpy, rough lobes on the maternal surface of the delivered placenta. After delivery, the placenta is inspected for completeness; missing cotyledons require uterine exploration.<br><br>Cotyledons are correctly named (B); chorionic plate (A) is fetal surface; intervillous space (C) is the maternal blood pool; villus (D) is microscopic.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The placental septa arise from:',o:['Umbilical cord','Chorionic plate','Amnion','Decidua basalis'],a:3,
    e:`The placental septa arise from the decidua basalis (maternal endometrium beneath the implantation site), projecting into the placenta and separating the cotyledons.<br><br>The septa do not extend completely to the chorionic plate; they incompletely separate the intervillous space, allowing maternal blood to flow throughout. The septa contain decidual cells and fibrous tissue, providing structural separation between cotyledons. They are visible on the maternal surface of the delivered placenta.<br><br>Chorion frondosum (A) gives villi; chorion laeve (B) is smooth chorion; amnion (C) covers fetal surface.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Placenta previa occurs when the placenta:',o:['Detaches prematurely','Covers the cervical os','Is abnormally small','Is abnormally thick'],a:1,
    e:`Placenta praevia occurs when the placenta covers the cervical os (internal os of the cervix), partially or completely. It is classified by degree: low-lying, marginal, partial or complete (total).<br><br>Placenta praevia presents with painless bright red vaginal bleeding in the second half of pregnancy. Diagnosis is by ultrasound. Caesarean section is required for delivery in major degrees. Risk factors include previous caesarean section, multiparity, advanced maternal age and prior placenta praevia.<br><br>Implants in tube (A) is ectopic; abrupts (C) is abruption; covers fundus (D) is normal location.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Placental abruption refers to:',o:['Retained placenta','Placenta covering cervix','Small placenta','Premature separation of placenta'],a:3,
    e:`Placental abruption refers to premature separation of placenta from the uterine wall before delivery, with bleeding behind the placenta (retroplacental haematoma).<br><br>It presents with painful vaginal bleeding (variable amount), uterine tenderness, hypertonic uterus and fetal distress. Risk factors include hypertension, pre-eclampsia, trauma, smoking, cocaine use and previous abruption. Maternal complications include DIC and shock; fetal complications include death and IUGR.<br><br>Placenta praevia (A) covers cervical os; placenta accreta (B) abnormally adherent; placenta retained (C) is post-delivery.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The umbilical vein carries:',o:['Oxygenated blood to fetus','Deoxygenated blood to placenta','Nutrient-poor blood','Waste products to fetus'],a:0,
    e:`The umbilical vein carries oxygenated blood from the placenta to the fetus. There is one umbilical vein in the umbilical cord (along with two umbilical arteries).<br><br>Oxygenated blood from the placenta returns to the fetus via the umbilical vein, which enters the fetal liver and joins the inferior vena cava via the ductus venosus (a fetal shunt). After birth, the umbilical vein closes to form the ligamentum teres (round ligament) of the liver running in the falciform ligament.<br><br>Deoxygenated blood from fetus (B) is in umbilical arteries; mixed blood (C) is incorrect; nutrients only (D) is partial.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The umbilical arteries carry:',o:['Nutrient-rich blood to fetus','Oxygenated blood to fetus','Deoxygenated blood from fetus to placenta','Hormones to fetus'],a:2,
    e:`The umbilical arteries carry deoxygenated blood from fetus to placenta. There are two umbilical arteries in the umbilical cord (along with one umbilical vein).<br><br>Umbilical arteries arise from the internal iliac arteries of the fetus. After birth, they obliterate to form the medial umbilical ligaments. The proximal patent portions become the superior vesical arteries supplying the bladder. Single umbilical artery (SUA) occurs in about 1 percent and may indicate fetal anomalies.<br><br>Oxygenated blood (A) is in umbilical vein; mixed blood (B) is incorrect; oxygenated to fetus (D) is umbilical vein.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The placenta acts as a barrier against:',o:['All of the above partially','Large proteins','Certain drugs','Some microorganisms'],a:0,
    e:`The placenta acts as a barrier (partial) against many but not all substances. Most maternal blood cells, large molecules and many bacteria are blocked, but viruses, drugs and small molecules can cross.<br><br>TORCH infections (Toxoplasmosis, Other - syphilis/varicella/parvovirus, Rubella, CMV, Herpes/HIV) cross to cause fetal infection. Many drugs cross (FDA pregnancy categories assess teratogenicity). The placenta is a selective barrier rather than a complete barrier, with active transport mechanisms for some substances.<br><br>Bacteria only (B) is partial; viruses only (C) is partial; drugs only (D) is partial; partial barrier against all.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Immunoglobulin transferred from mother to fetus through placenta is mainly:',o:['IgA','IgM','IgE','IgG'],a:3,
    e:`Immunoglobulin transferred from mother to fetus through placenta is mainly IgG, providing passive immunity to the newborn. IgG transfer occurs mostly in the third trimester.<br><br>Maternal IgG crosses the placenta via active transport (Fc receptors on syncytiotrophoblast). It provides passive immunity to the newborn against infections to which the mother has antibodies. Other immunoglobulins (IgA, IgM, IgD, IgE) do not cross significantly. Maternal IgG levels in the newborn decline over 6-12 months.<br><br>IgA (A) is in colostrum/breast milk; IgM (B) does not cross; IgE (C) does not cross significantly.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The placental circulation begins functioning effectively around:',o:['End of 2nd week','End of 3rd week','End of 5th week','End of 8th week'],a:1,
    e:`The placental circulation begins functioning effectively around the end of the 3rd week of development, when tertiary villi with fetal blood vessels form and connect to the embryonic circulation.<br><br>By the end of week 3, primitive heart begins beating and circulates blood through tertiary chorionic villi. Maternal-fetal exchange becomes increasingly efficient as villi proliferate and the placental membrane thins. By the second trimester, placental circulation is fully established and meets fetal metabolic needs.<br><br>End of 1st week (A) is implantation; end of 2nd week (C) is bilaminar disc; end of 4th week (D) is later.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The decidua during pregnancy refers to:',o:['Amniotic membrane','Chorionic villi','Modified endometrium','Placental septa'],a:2,
    e:`The decidua during pregnancy refers to the modified endometrium prepared for and supporting implantation. It develops in response to progesterone from the corpus luteum and later placenta.<br><br>The decidua has three regions: decidua basalis (beneath implantation site, becomes maternal placenta), decidua capsularis (covers implanting embryo from cavity side, regresses), and decidua parietalis (lines rest of uterine cavity). Decidual cells are large, glycogen-rich, supportive of pregnancy.<br><br>Trophoblast (A) is fetal; chorion (B) is fetal membrane; amnion (D) covers fetal surface.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Decidua capsularis covers:',o:['Umbilical cord','Placental base','Uterine wall opposite placenta','Implanting embryo'],a:3,
    e:`Decidua capsularis covers the implanting embryo from the uterine cavity side, separating it from the rest of the cavity. It regresses as the fetus grows.<br><br>As the conceptus expands into the uterine cavity, decidua capsularis stretches and thins. By the second trimester, it fuses with decidua parietalis on the opposite wall of the uterus, obliterating the uterine cavity. The chorion laeve underlies decidua capsularis. After fusion, the membranes appear as a single layer at delivery.<br><br>Maternal placenta site (A) is decidua basalis; rest of uterine cavity (B) is decidua parietalis; cervix (C) is mucosa.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Decidua parietalis lines:',o:['Remaining uterine cavity','Placental site','Chorionic plate','Amnion'],a:0,
    e:`Decidua parietalis lines the remaining uterine cavity (i.e., the parts away from the implantation site and the conceptus). It is the largest decidual area in early pregnancy.<br><br>As the fetus grows, decidua capsularis fuses with decidua parietalis on the opposite wall, obliterating the uterine cavity by the second trimester. After delivery, the decidua is shed with the placenta and membranes (\'lochia\' postpartum represents continued shedding of decidual remnants and blood).<br><br>Implantation site (B) is decidua basalis; embryo cover (C) is decidua capsularis; cervix (D) has its own mucosa.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which placental structure contains fetal blood vessels?',o:['Decidual septa','Chorionic villi','Amnion','Placental plate'],a:1,
    e:`The chorionic villi contain fetal blood vessels (in tertiary villi). The villi are the functional units of placental exchange between maternal and fetal blood.<br><br>Each villus has a core of mesoderm containing fetal capillaries (from umbilical artery branches), surrounded by cytotrophoblast (early pregnancy) and syncytiotrophoblast. The villi project into the intervillous space which is filled with maternal blood. Exchange occurs across the placental barrier between maternal and fetal blood.<br><br>Decidua basalis (A) is maternal; intervillous space (C) has maternal blood; chorion laeve (D) is smooth chorion.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'During placental development, progressive thinning of the placental membrane occurs to facilitate efficient exchange of oxygen and nutrients between maternal and fetal circulation. Which layer largely disappears from the placental barrier in late pregnancy?',o:['Fetal capillary endothelium','Syncytiotrophoblast','Cytotrophoblast layer','Basement membrane'],a:2,
    e:`During placental development, progressive thinning of the placental membrane occurs due to disappearance of the cytotrophoblast layer in the third trimester.<br><br>The placental barrier consists of: syncytiotrophoblast, cytotrophoblast (initially complete, becomes patchy, disappears in third trimester), basement membranes and fetal capillary endothelium. The thinner late-pregnancy barrier facilitates exchange. Some thickness reduction also occurs from villi branching and capillary apposition to syncytiotrophoblast.<br><br>Syncytiotrophoblast layer (A) persists; basement membrane (B) persists; endothelium (D) persists.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Placental weight normally corresponds to approximately what fraction of fetal weight at term?',o:['1/2','1/6','1/4','1/10'],a:1,
    e:`Placental weight normally corresponds to approximately 1/6 of fetal weight at term (about 500 g placenta for 3000 g fetus).<br><br>Abnormal placenta-to-fetus ratios may indicate pathology: small placenta (e.g., in IUGR) or large placenta (e.g., in maternal diabetes, hydrops fetalis, or syphilis). Placental examination after delivery includes weight measurement and inspection for abnormalities, which may reveal pathology not detected antenatally.<br><br>1/3 (A) is too large; 1/10 (C) is too small; 1/20 (D) is much too small.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The intervillous space of the placenta contains:',o:['Lymph','Fetal blood','Maternal blood','Amniotic fluid'],a:2,
    e:`The intervillous space of the placenta contains maternal blood, pooling around the chorionic villi. Maternal blood enters from spiral arteries and exits via decidual veins.<br><br>The intervillous space is the site of maternofetal exchange across the placental barrier. Maternal blood here is in direct contact with the syncytiotrophoblast covering the villi. There is no maternal-fetal blood mixing under normal conditions; mixing can occur with placental abruption, causing fetomaternal haemorrhage and Rh sensitisation.<br><br>Fetal blood (A) is in villi vessels; lymph (B) is incorrect; mixed blood (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The basal plate of placenta corresponds to:',o:['Maternal surface','Fetal surface','Amniotic surface','Umbilical surface'],a:0,
    e:`The basal plate of placenta corresponds to the maternal surface, formed by the decidua basalis and the trophoblastic shell from the fetal side.<br><br>The basal plate is rough and lobulated, divided into cotyledons by placental septa arising from it. After delivery, the basal plate is inspected for completeness; missing cotyledons require uterine exploration to remove retained tissue, which can cause postpartum haemorrhage and infection.<br><br>Fetal surface (B) is the chorionic plate; central portion (C) is bulk; both surfaces (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The fetal surface of the placenta appears:',o:['Spongy','Rough and lobulated','Irregular and nodular','Smooth and shiny'],a:3,
    e:`The fetal surface of the placenta appears smooth and shiny due to the amnion covering it. The chorionic plate underlies the amnion, with the umbilical cord entering at this surface.<br><br>The fetal blood vessels (umbilical artery and vein branches) are visible running on the chorionic plate before entering the villi. After delivery, the fetal surface is examined for vascular anomalies, accessory lobes (succenturiate placenta) and the cord insertion site (central, eccentric, marginal or velamentous).<br><br>Rough and lobulated (A) is maternal surface; covered by decidua (B) is maternal surface; vascular only (C) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The maternal surface of placenta appears:',o:['Thin and membranous','Smooth and transparent','Rough and lobulated','Shiny and bluish'],a:2,
    e:`The maternal surface of placenta appears rough and lobulated, with cotyledons (15-20 lobes) separated by placental septa visible on inspection.<br><br>After delivery, the maternal surface is examined for completeness; missing cotyledons indicate retained placental tissue requiring uterine exploration. Other findings on the maternal surface include calcifications (common at term, normal finding), infarcts (small areas usually insignificant) and retroplacental haematoma (suggests abruption requiring urgent assessment).<br><br>Smooth and shiny (A) is fetal surface; covered by amnion (B) is fetal surface; vascular only (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Placental hormones maintain pregnancy primarily by:',o:['Supporting uterine lining','Suppressing maternal immune response','Supporting fetal growth','All of the above'],a:3,
    e:`Placental hormones maintain pregnancy primarily by maintaining corpus luteum (hCG), supporting endometrium (progesterone), promoting fetal development (estrogen) and altering maternal metabolism (hPL).<br><br>hCG rescues the corpus luteum until placental progesterone takes over. Progesterone maintains the decidua and inhibits uterine contractions. Estrogen supports fetal development and preparing the breast. hPL increases maternal insulin resistance, ensuring adequate glucose for the fetus and stimulating maternal lipolysis for energy.<br><br>Maintaining corpus luteum only (A) is partial; suppressing menstruation only (B) is partial; supporting endometrium only (C) is partial; all functions are involved.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The umbilical cord is attached to the placenta at:',o:['Basal plate','Chorionic plate','Decidual septum','Cotyledon'],a:1,
    e:`The umbilical cord is attached to the placenta at the chorionic plate (fetal surface). The cord insertion can be central, eccentric, marginal (battledore) or velamentous.<br><br>Velamentous insertion (cord inserts into membranes, with vessels traversing the membranes before reaching the placenta) carries risk of vasa praevia (vessels crossing the cervical os) and vessel rupture during membrane rupture. Vasa praevia presents with vaginal bleeding and rapid fetal distress, requiring urgent caesarean section.<br><br>Maternal surface (A) is basal plate; cervical os (C) is incorrect; uterine fundus (D) is the implantation site externally.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'Wharton\'s jelly in the umbilical cord functions to:',o:['Protect umbilical vessels','Produce hormones','Store nutrients','Produce blood cells'],a:0,
    e:`Wharton\'s jelly in the umbilical cord functions to protect umbilical vessels from compression and kinking, ensuring continuous blood flow between fetus and placenta.<br><br>Wharton\'s jelly is a gelatinous mucopolysaccharide-rich connective tissue surrounding the three umbilical vessels (two arteries and one vein). It cushions and insulates the vessels. The cord can become twisted or knotted but Wharton\'s jelly usually prevents vessel occlusion. Cord prolapse is an obstetric emergency requiring urgent delivery.<br><br>Provide nutrients (B) is via cord vessels; conduct nerves (C) is unrelated; aid implantation (D) is incorrect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'The placenta allows passage of which substance from mother to fetus?',o:['Oxygen','All of the above','Amino acids','Glucose'],a:1,
    e:`The placenta allows passage of various substances from mother to fetus: oxygen and CO2 (gas exchange), nutrients (glucose, amino acids, lipids, vitamins), waste products and immunoglobulins (mainly IgG).<br><br>Different mechanisms transport different substances: simple diffusion (gases, water), facilitated diffusion (glucose), active transport (amino acids, ions), pinocytosis (large molecules including IgG via Fc receptors), and selective permeability (most maternal cells excluded). Some drugs and pathogens unfortunately also cross.<br><br>Oxygen only (A) is partial; nutrients only (C) is partial; antibodies only (D) is partial; all are transferred.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'During placental development, the chorion frondosum forms the fetal part of the placenta due to proliferation and branching of chorionic villi at the implantation site, while villi on the opposite side degenerate forming chorion laeve. Which structure therefore forms the fetal portion of the mature placenta?',o:['Decidua basalis','Decidua capsularis','Amnion','Chorion frondosum'],a:3,
    e:`During placental development, the chorion frondosum forms the fetal part of the placenta. It is the bushy part of the chorion overlying the embryonic pole, with branching villi.<br><br>The chorion frondosum villi develop into the structural and functional units of the fetal placenta (cotyledons). The chorion laeve (smooth chorion) is the rest of the chorion, which regresses to form the chorion membrane. Together with the amnion, the chorion laeve forms the fetal membranes.<br><br>Decidua basalis (A) is maternal part; chorion laeve (B) regresses to membrane; amnion (C) covers fetal surface.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'The main arterial supply of the uterus is from:',o:['Ovarian artery','Internal pudendal artery','Uterine artery','External iliac artery'],a:2,
    e:`The main arterial supply of the uterus is from the uterine artery, a major branch of the anterior division of the internal iliac (hypogastric) artery.<br><br>The uterine artery passes medially in the broad ligament base toward the cervix, crossing above the ureter near the cervix (\'water under the bridge\'). It anastomoses with the ovarian artery near the cornu, providing collateral supply. Uterine artery embolisation is used for fibroid treatment, exploiting this dual supply.<br><br>Ovarian artery (A) supplies ovaries and contributes minor uterine flow; vaginal artery (B) supplies vagina; internal pudendal artery (D) supplies perineum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The uterine artery arises from the:',o:['Internal iliac artery','Abdominal aorta','External iliac artery','Femoral artery'],a:0,
    e:`The uterine artery arises from the internal iliac artery (anterior division), passing medially in the broad ligament base toward the cervix.<br><br>It crosses above the ureter near the cervix (\'water under the bridge\') and reaches the uterus, anastomosing with the ovarian artery near the cornu. This anastomosis provides collateral supply if one vessel is ligated. Uterine artery embolisation is used for fibroid treatment by interventional radiologists.<br><br>External iliac artery (B) supplies lower limb; abdominal aorta (C) gives off ovarian; femoral artery (D) supplies lower limb.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During hysterectomy, the ureter is most closely related to which artery?',o:['Ovarian artery','Inferior epigastric artery','Uterine artery','Internal pudendal artery'],a:2,
    e:`During hysterectomy, the ureter is most closely related to the uterine artery, the classic \'water under the bridge\' relationship.<br><br>The relationship occurs about 2 cm lateral to the cervix at the cervical isthmus level. The ureter is at risk of injury during clamping or ligation of the uterine artery. Identification of the ureter before uterine artery ligation is essential to avoid injury during pelvic surgery, particularly in radical hysterectomy.<br><br>Ovarian artery (A) lies near pelvic brim; vaginal artery (B) supplies vagina; internal pudendal artery (D) supplies perineum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The ureter passes:',o:['Above the uterine artery','Below the uterine artery','Lateral to uterine artery','Anterior to uterine artery'],a:1,
    e:`The ureter passes below the uterine artery near the cervix, the classic \'water (ureter) under the bridge (uterine artery)\' relationship occurring about 2 cm lateral to the cervix.<br><br>This relationship is critical during hysterectomy: the ureter is at risk of injury during clamping or ligation of the uterine artery. Identification of the ureter before uterine artery ligation is essential to avoid injury. The ureter is also at risk near the suspensory ligament of ovary at the pelvic brim.<br><br>Above the uterine artery (A) is reverse; medial to vagina (C) is incorrect; lateral to ovary (D) is wrong relationship.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The ligament that maintains the anteversion of the uterus is:',o:['Round ligament','Uterosacral ligament','Broad ligament','Cardinal ligament'],a:0,
    e:`The ligament that maintains the anteversion of the uterus is the round ligament. It pulls the fundus forward toward the anterior abdominal wall via its passage through the inguinal canal.<br><br>The round ligament is a remnant of the gubernaculum. It is not a major support against prolapse (which is provided by pelvic diaphragm and cardinal ligaments) but contributes to maintaining the normal anteverted uterine position. It is a small, narrow fibromuscular cord originating at the uterine cornu.<br><br>Cardinal ligament (B) supports cervix; broad ligament (C) is peritoneal fold; uterosacral ligament (D) connects cervix to sacrum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The strongest support of the uterus is provided by:',o:['Broad ligament','Round ligament','Uterosacral ligament','Cardinal ligament'],a:3,
    e:`The strongest support of the uterus is provided by the cardinal (Mackenrodt) ligament, extending from the cervix and upper vagina to the lateral pelvic wall.<br><br>The cardinal ligaments contain the uterine vessels and are the strongest mechanical support of the uterus, working with uterosacral and pubocervical ligaments. The pelvic diaphragm (levator ani) provides primary muscular support. Repair of prolapse often involves shortening or repositioning the cardinal ligaments.<br><br>Round ligament (A) maintains anteversion; broad ligament (B) is peritoneal; uterosacral ligament (C) is supporting but not strongest.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The pouch located between uterus and rectum is called:',o:['Vesicouterine pouch','Rectouterine pouch','Rectovesical pouch','Peritoneal recess'],a:1,
    e:`The pouch located between uterus and rectum is called the rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas), the deepest peritoneal recess in the female pelvis.<br><br>It is the most dependent peritoneal space, where free pelvic fluid, blood (haemoperitoneum) or pus tends to collect. Posterior colpotomy through the posterior fornix accesses this pouch for drainage. It is also the site of drop metastases from gastric cancer (Krukenberg tumour) or other intra-abdominal malignancies.<br><br>Vesicouterine pouch (A) is between bladder and uterus; rectovesical pouch (C) is in males; paravesical fossa (D) is lateral.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The deepest peritoneal pouch in females is:',o:['Vesicouterine pouch','Rectovesical pouch','Paravesical pouch','Rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas)'],a:3,
    e:`The deepest peritoneal pouch in females is the rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas), lying between the rectum posteriorly and the uterus anteriorly.<br><br>Free pelvic fluid, blood or pus tends to collect here due to gravity (most dependent space). Posterior colpotomy through the posterior fornix accesses this pouch for drainage of pelvic abscess or fluid collections. Endometriosis commonly involves this pouch, causing posterior cul-de-sac obliteration.<br><br>Vesicouterine pouch (A) is shallower; paravesical fossa (B) is lateral to bladder; pararectal fossa (C) is lateral to rectum.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The lymphatic drainage of the ovary primarily goes to:',o:['Internal iliac nodes','External iliac nodes','Para-aortic nodes','Inguinal nodes'],a:2,
    e:`The lymphatic drainage of the ovary primarily goes to the para-aortic (lumbar) lymph nodes, following the ovarian vessels along their embryological course.<br><br>The high-level drainage reflects the ovary\'s embryological origin in the upper abdomen. This is important in ovarian cancer staging: para-aortic lymphadenectomy is part of staging surgery, with right and left side dissection up to the renal vessels. Pelvic lymph nodes are involved later in the disease progression.<br><br>Internal iliac nodes (A) drain cervix and upper vagina; superficial inguinal nodes (B) drain vulva; obturator nodes (D) drain cervix mainly.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'Lymph from the cervix primarily drains to:',o:['Internal iliac nodes','Para-aortic nodes','Superficial inguinal nodes','Mesenteric nodes'],a:0,
    e:`Lymph from the cervix primarily drains to the internal iliac (hypogastric) nodes, with secondary drainage to obturator, external iliac and presacral nodes.<br><br>Pelvic lymphadenectomy in cervical cancer involves removal of these node groups. Para-aortic node involvement indicates more advanced disease (Stage IIIC2) and influences treatment with extended-field radiotherapy. Sentinel lymph node biopsy is being explored as an alternative to full pelvic lymphadenectomy in early-stage cervical cancer.<br><br>Para-aortic nodes (B) drain ovaries primarily; superficial inguinal nodes (C) drain vulva; deep cervical nodes (D) drain head and neck.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During a radical hysterectomy for cervical cancer, the surgeon ligates the uterine artery. Injury to which nearby structure is most likely if the anatomy is not carefully identified?',o:['Internal iliac vein','Ovarian ligament','Ureter','Obturator nerve'],a:2,
    e:`During radical hysterectomy for cervical cancer, the surgeon ligates the uterine artery and must carefully identify the ureter, which passes beneath the uterine artery near the cervix.<br><br>The ureter is at risk of injury during clamping or ligation of the uterine artery (\'water under the bridge\' relationship). Pre-operative imaging (CT or MR urogram) and intraoperative identification by direct visualisation reduce injury risk. Ureteric injury during pelvic surgery may require ureteric stenting or surgical repair.<br><br>Bladder (A) is identified but anterior; rectum (B) is posterior; common iliac vein (D) is during lymphadenectomy.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A 32-year-old woman presents with deep dyspareunia and pelvic pain. Laparoscopy shows endometriosis deposits in the deepest peritoneal recess of the pelvis. Which anatomical space is most likely involved?',o:['Rectouterine pouch','Paravesical space','Rectovaginal septum','Vesicouterine pouch'],a:0,
    e:`A 32-year-old woman presents with deep dyspareunia and pelvic pain. Laparoscopy showing endometriotic deposits in the rectouterine pouch (Pouch of Douglas) is consistent with endometriosis - the most dependent peritoneal recess.<br><br>The Pouch of Douglas is a common site of endometriotic deposits, causing posterior cul-de-sac obliteration in advanced disease. Deep dyspareunia, dyschezia and chronic pelvic pain are typical. Treatment includes hormonal suppression (combined oral contraceptives, GnRH analogues) or surgical excision of deposits in symptomatic cases.<br><br>Vesicouterine pouch (B) is anterior, less common; paravesical fossa (C) is lateral; pararectal fossa (D) is lateral.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During childbirth, excessive stretching damages the muscle group primarily responsible for pelvic floor support, leading to uterine prolapse. Which muscle is most commonly involved?',o:['Piriformis','Gluteus maximus','Obturator internus','Levator ani'],a:3,
    e:`During childbirth, excessive stretching damages the levator ani muscle group primarily responsible for pelvic floor support, causing pelvic organ prolapse and stress urinary incontinence.<br><br>The levator ani has three components: pubococcygeus (most medial, around urogenital and rectal openings), puborectalis (around rectum) and iliococcygeus (most lateral). Damage during prolonged or instrumental delivery contributes to pelvic floor dysfunction. Pelvic floor exercises (Kegel) help strengthen the muscles post-delivery.<br><br>Iliopsoas (A) is hip flexor; piriformis (B) is posterior pelvic wall; obturator internus (C) is lateral pelvic wall.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman undergoes pelvic examination and the obstetrician measures the diagonal conjugate. This measurement helps estimate which important pelvic diameter?',o:['True conjugate','Obstetric conjugate','Interspinous diameter','Bituberous diameter'],a:1,
    e:`A pregnant woman undergoes pelvic examination and the obstetrician measures the obstetric conjugate, the shortest anteroposterior diameter of the pelvic inlet (about 11 cm), critical for fetal head engagement.<br><br>The obstetric conjugate is from sacral promontory to the inner upper border of pubic symphysis. It cannot be measured directly clinically; estimated from diagonal conjugate (subtract 1.5-2 cm). If contracted (less than 10 cm), the fetal head cannot engage, leading to cephalopelvic disproportion requiring caesarean.<br><br>Diagonal conjugate (A) is clinical measurement; transverse diameter (C) is wider; oblique diameter (D) is not standard.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus in vertex presentation is entering the pelvic inlet. Which fetal skull diameter usually engages in a normal labor with complete flexion of the head?',o:['Occipitofrontal diameter','Biparietal diameter','Suboccipitobregmatic diameter','Submentobregmatic diameter'],a:2,
    e:`A fetus in vertex presentation is entering the pelvic inlet. The suboccipitobregmatic diameter (9.5 cm) is the presenting diameter in well-flexed vertex, the smallest AP diameter of the fetal skull.<br><br>Flexion (chin on chest) maintains this small diameter as the leading edge, facilitating efficient passage through the birth canal. Maintaining flexion is the key mechanism of normal labour; deflexion increases presenting diameter to occipitofrontal (11.5 cm) and prolongs labour, sometimes requiring rotation or delivery assistance.<br><br>Biparietal (A) is transverse; occipitofrontal (B) is in deflexed positions; mentovertical (D) is in brow presentation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with cervical carcinoma shows metastasis to pelvic lymph nodes first. Which lymph nodes are most commonly affected initially?',o:['Para-aortic nodes','Mesenteric nodes','Superficial inguinal nodes','Internal iliac nodes'],a:3,
    e:`A woman with cervical carcinoma shows metastasis to pelvic lymph nodes first - the internal iliac (hypogastric) nodes are the primary regional drainage from the cervix.<br><br>Pelvic lymphadenectomy in cervical cancer involves removal of internal iliac, external iliac, obturator and common iliac nodes. Para-aortic node involvement indicates more advanced disease (Stage IIIC2). Sentinel lymph node biopsy is being explored as an alternative to full pelvic lymphadenectomy in early-stage cervical cancer with reduced morbidity.<br><br>Para-aortic nodes (A) receive secondary drainage; superficial inguinal nodes (B) drain vulva; deep cervical nodes (C) drain head and neck.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A surgeon performing oophorectomy must ligate the suspensory ligament of ovary. Which structure runs within this ligament and must be carefully controlled?',o:['Ovarian vessels','Uterine artery','Round ligament','Inferior epigastric artery'],a:0,
    e:`A surgeon performing oophorectomy must ligate the suspensory ligament of ovary, which contains the ovarian vessels (artery, vein and lymphatics).<br><br>The suspensory ligament (infundibulopelvic ligament) connects the lateral pole of the ovary to the lateral pelvic wall above the pelvic brim. The ureter lies close to the suspensory ligament at the pelvic brim and is at risk during clamping. Identification of the ureter is essential before clamping the suspensory ligament.<br><br>Round ligament (B) connects uterus to labium majus; uterine vessels (C) are in cardinal ligament; nerves (D) are present but main concern is vessels.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman presents with infertility due to a congenital uterine anomaly caused by failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts. Which anomaly is most consistent with this mechanism?',o:['Septate uterus','Bicornuate uterus','Unicornuate uterus','Uterine agenesis'],a:1,
    e:`A woman presents with infertility due to a congenital uterine anomaly caused by failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts - bicornuate uterus has incomplete fusion with two horns sharing one cervix.<br><br>Bicornuate uterus is a common Müllerian fusion anomaly. Pregnancy can occur but with increased risk of preterm labour, malpresentation and miscarriage. It is differentiated from didelphys (two cervices, complete failure of fusion) and septate uterus (normal external contour, failed septum resorption) by imaging.<br><br>Septate uterus (A) is failed septum resorption; uterus didelphys (C) is complete fusion failure; arcuate uterus (D) is mild indentation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During cesarean section, the surgeon accidentally injures the perineal body. Damage to this structure may weaken which anatomical support?',o:['Ovarian blood supply','Cervical canal integrity','Pelvic diaphragm stability','Fallopian tube mobility'],a:2,
    e:`During caesarean section, the surgeon accidentally injures the perineal body. Damage affects the pelvic diaphragm stability and continence functions.<br><br>The perineal body is a fibromuscular pyramidal structure central to perineal support, providing attachment for bulbospongiosus, transverse perineal muscles, levator ani and external anal sphincter. Injury during caesarean section is unusual; perineal body damage typically occurs during vaginal delivery (third- or fourth-degree tears) and contributes to faecal incontinence.<br><br>Bladder support (A) is by pubocervical fascia; vaginal lubrication (B) is by glands; uterine support (D) is by cardinal/uterosacral ligaments.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus is diagnosed with hydrocephalus, causing enlargement of the head. Which fetal skull diameter is most affected and may obstruct vaginal delivery?',o:['Biparietal diameter','Mentovertical diameter','Occipitofrontal diameter','Bitemporal diameter'],a:1,
    e:`A fetus is diagnosed with hydrocephalus, causing enlargement of the head. The mentovertical diameter (largest fetal skull diameter, 13.5 cm in normal) increases significantly with hydrocephaly.<br><br>All fetal skull diameters increase with hydrocephalus, but the mentovertical (or biparietal in transverse) is most relevant to passage through the birth canal. Hydrocephalus typically prevents vaginal delivery requiring caesarean section. Antenatal diagnosis allows planning, including possible drainage procedures or termination consideration.<br><br>Suboccipitobregmatic (A) is in well-flexed; biparietal (C) is transverse; submentobregmatic (D) is in face presentation.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman develops severe pelvic infection spreading through lymphatics from the uterine fundus. Which lymph nodes are most likely involved?',o:['Internal iliac nodes','Superficial inguinal nodes','External iliac nodes','Para-aortic nodes'],a:3,
    e:`A woman develops severe pelvic infection spreading through lymphatics from the uterine fundus. The fundus drains primarily to para-aortic nodes (following ovarian lymphatics).<br><br>The uterine fundus has an additional lymphatic drainage pathway following the round ligament through the inguinal canal to superficial inguinal nodes (minor route). Most uterine drainage goes to para-aortic and internal iliac nodes. Severe infection from the fundus could spread along these lymphatic routes to involve abdominal nodes.<br><br>Internal iliac (A) drains cervix and lower body; superficial inguinal (B) drains vulva; obturator (C) drains cervix.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During a vaginal delivery, an episiotomy is performed. Which nerve supplies the region most at risk of injury during this procedure?',o:['Pudendal nerve','Femoral nerve','Obturator nerve','Sciatic nerve'],a:0,
    e:`During a vaginal delivery, an episiotomy is performed. The pudendal nerve supplies the perineal area where the episiotomy is made.<br><br>The pudendal nerve (S2-S4) provides sensory and motor supply to the perineum, lower vagina, vulva and external anal sphincter. Pudendal nerve block at the ischial spine provides analgesia for episiotomy repair, second-stage labour and outlet forceps delivery. Local infiltration of the perineum with lidocaine is also used.<br><br>Femoral nerve (B) supplies anterior thigh; obturator nerve (C) supplies medial thigh; sciatic nerve (D) supplies lower limb posterior.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A surgeon identifies the ampulla of the fallopian tube during laparoscopy. Which reproductive event most commonly occurs at this anatomical site?',o:['Ovulation','Menstruation','Implantation','Fertilization'],a:3,
    e:`A surgeon identifies the ampulla of the fallopian tube during laparoscopy. Fertilisation is the main physiological event occurring in the ampulla, the wide thin-walled longest segment of the tube.<br><br>The ampulla\'s wide lumen and ciliated epithelium facilitate ovum capture and sperm-ovum interaction. After fertilisation, the embryo develops in the tube for several days before reaching the uterus for implantation. Ectopic pregnancy is most common in the ampulla (~70 percent), with lower rupture risk than other tubal sites.<br><br>Sperm production (A) is in testes; menstruation (B) is in uterus; implantation (C) is in uterus normally.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman has placenta previa covering the internal os. During delivery, hemorrhage occurs due to separation of placenta from which uterine segment?',o:['Fundus','Lower uterine segment','Upper uterine segment','Cervical canal'],a:1,
    e:`A pregnant woman has placenta praevia covering the internal os. During delivery, the surgeon avoids the lower uterine segment due to the abnormal placental location.<br><br>Placenta praevia requires caesarean section for delivery in major degrees. The lower uterine segment incision should typically be avoided due to placenta location; some surgeons use a vertical (classical) uterine incision to avoid the placenta. Placenta accreta (abnormally adherent) is increasingly common with previous caesarean sections, complicating delivery further.<br><br>Cervix (A) is the lower part below uterus; fundus (C) is upper part of uterus; uterine cornu (D) is at tube entry.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'A gynecologist performing lymph node biopsy for vulvar carcinoma expects primary drainage to which lymph nodes?',o:['Superficial inguinal nodes','Internal iliac nodes','External iliac nodes','Para-aortic nodes'],a:0,
    e:`A gynaecologist performing lymph node biopsy for vulval carcinoma expects primary lymph drainage to the superficial inguinal nodes, similar to the rest of the vulva and lower vagina.<br><br>Vulval cancer staging includes inguinal lymph node assessment. Bilateral involvement is common with midline lesions or lesions crossing the midline. Sentinel lymph node biopsy is increasingly used in early vulval cancer to reduce morbidity from full inguinofemoral lymphadenectomy. Deep inguinal and external iliac nodes are involved later.<br><br>Internal iliac nodes (B) drain upper vagina/cervix; para-aortic nodes (C) drain ovaries; obturator nodes (D) drain cervix.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with uterine prolapse has weakening of the main fibrous support of the uterus. Which ligament provides this critical structural support?',o:['Round ligament','Broad ligament','Cardinal ligament','Ovarian ligament'],a:2,
    e:`A patient with uterine prolapse has weakening of the main fibrous support of the uterus - the cardinal (Mackenrodt) ligament, extending from cervix and upper vagina to the lateral pelvic wall.<br><br>The cardinal ligaments contain the uterine vessels and are the strongest mechanical support of the uterus. Damage from childbirth or chronic strain (combined with menopausal collagen weakening) leads to prolapse. Repair of prolapse often involves shortening or repositioning the cardinal ligaments along with pelvic floor reconstruction.<br><br>Round ligament (A) maintains anteversion; broad ligament (B) is peritoneal; uterosacral ligament (D) is supporting but cardinal is main fibrous.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus presents in face presentation during labor. Which fetal skull diameter must pass through the pelvic inlet in this presentation?',o:['Biparietal diameter','Occipitofrontal diameter','Suboccipitobregmatic diameter','Submentobregmatic diameter'],a:3,
    e:`A fetus presents in face presentation during labour. The submentobregmatic diameter (9.5 cm) measures the AP diameter from below the chin to the centre of the anterior fontanelle.<br><br>Face presentation occurs when the head is fully extended. Mentoanterior position can deliver vaginally as the chin engages and rotates anteriorly. Mentoposterior position cannot deliver vaginally (chin cannot tuck under symphysis) and requires caesarean section due to mechanical incompatibility with the pelvis.<br><br>Suboccipitobregmatic (A) is in well-flexed vertex; mentovertical (B) is in brow; occipitofrontal (C) is in deflexed vertex.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During breast surgery for carcinoma, the surgeon notes that most lymphatic drainage goes to which group of lymph nodes?',o:['Cervical nodes','Axillary lymph nodes','Inguinal nodes','Para-aortic nodes'],a:1,
    e:`During breast surgery for carcinoma, the surgeon notes that most lymphatic drainage (about 75 percent) goes to the axillary lymph nodes, particularly the pectoral group initially.<br><br>The axillary nodes are arranged in groups: anterior (pectoral), posterior (subscapular), lateral, central and apical. Axillary lymphadenectomy (Level I, II, III) is part of breast cancer staging and treatment. Sentinel lymph node biopsy may avoid extensive lymphadenectomy in early breast cancer with reduced morbidity.<br><br>Internal mammary nodes (A) drain medial quadrants; supraclavicular (C) is small drainage; paratracheal nodes (D) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with carcinoma of the uterine fundus shows metastasis to lymph nodes following the ovarian vessels. Which lymph nodes are involved?',o:['Para-aortic nodes','Internal iliac nodes','External iliac nodes','Inguinal nodes'],a:0,
    e:`A woman with carcinoma of the uterine fundus shows metastasis to lymph nodes following ovarian drainage - para-aortic nodes are the primary route from the fundus.<br><br>The uterine fundus drains via lymphatics following the ovarian vessels to para-aortic nodes (similar to ovarian drainage). The body and cervix drain primarily to internal iliac nodes. The fundus also has a minor pathway via round ligament to superficial inguinal nodes. Endometrial cancer staging includes pelvic and para-aortic lymphadenectomy.<br><br>Internal iliac nodes (B) drain cervix; superficial inguinal nodes (C) drain vulva; obturator nodes (D) drain cervix.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During placental examination after delivery, the obstetrician notes that the placenta developed from both fetal and maternal tissues. Which two structures contribute to its formation?',o:['Amnion and decidua parietalis','Chorion laeve and decidua capsularis','Chorion frondosum and decidua basalis','Yolk sac and chorion'],a:2,
    e:`During placental examination after delivery, the obstetrician notes that the placenta consists of two main components: chorion frondosum (fetal part) and decidua basalis (maternal part).<br><br>The chorion frondosum forms the bushy part of the chorion overlying the embryonic pole, with branching villi that contact maternal blood. The decidua basalis is the modified endometrium beneath the implantation site. Together they form the discoid placenta with about 15-20 cotyledons by the second trimester.<br><br>Chorion laeve and decidua capsularis (A) regress; amnion and chorion (B) are membranes only; yolk sac and allantois (D) are vestigial.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'During early embryogenesis, the uterus, fallopian tubes, and upper vagina develop from which embryological structure?',o:['Müllerian (paramesonephric) ducts','Urogenital sinus','Mesonephric (Wolffian) ducts','Cloaca'],a:0,
    e:`During early embryogenesis, the uterus, fallopian tubes, and upper vagina develop from the Müllerian (paramesonephric) ducts. The Müllerian ducts develop in females in the absence of anti-Müllerian hormone.<br><br>The cranial parts of Müllerian ducts remain unfused (forming fallopian tubes); the caudal parts fuse to form the uterus and upper two-thirds of vagina. The midline septum normally resorbs by week 20 to create a single uterine cavity. Anomalies of fusion or resorption produce uterine malformations.<br><br>Mesonephric (Wolffian) ducts (B) form male tract; cloaca (C) is broader; urogenital sinus (D) forms lower vagina and bladder.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Failure of resorption of the midline septum after fusion of Müllerian ducts results in which congenital uterine anomaly?',o:['Bicornuate uterus','Unicornuate uterus','Uterus didelphys','Septate uterus'],a:3,
    e:`Failure of resorption of the midline septum after fusion of Müllerian ducts results in septate uterus. The external uterine contour is normal, but a fibrous septum persists in the cavity.<br><br>A complete septum extends to the cervix; an incomplete (partial) septum extends part way down. Septate uterus is the most common Müllerian anomaly causing recurrent miscarriage; hysteroscopic septum resection improves pregnancy outcomes for most affected women significantly. Imaging differentiates from bicornuate.<br><br>Bicornuate (A) is fusion failure; uterus didelphys (B) is complete fusion failure; arcuate (C) is mild indentation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'The lower one-third of the vagina develops embryologically from the:',o:['Müllerian ducts','Urogenital sinus','Mesonephric ducts','Genital tubercle'],a:1,
    e:`The lower one-third of the vagina develops embryologically from the urogenital sinus, specifically from the sinovaginal bulbs that proliferate from the posterior wall of the urogenital sinus.<br><br>The upper two-thirds of the vagina develops from the fused Müllerian ducts. The two parts canalise during fetal development; the hymen marks the junction between Müllerian and urogenital sinus origin. Vaginal atresia or transverse septa can occur if these processes fail to complete properly.<br><br>Müllerian ducts (A) form upper vagina; mesonephric ducts (C) form male tract; cloaca (D) is broader.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'During embryological development, the ovaries initially develop in which region before descending into the pelvis?',o:['Pelvic cavity','Labia majora','Posterior abdominal wall near the kidneys','Inguinal canal'],a:2,
    e:`During embryological development, the ovaries initially develop in the posterior abdominal wall near the kidneys (lumbar region), at the genital ridge of intermediate mesoderm.<br><br>Primordial germ cells migrate from the yolk sac to the genital ridge by week 5. Without SRY gene, the gonad develops as ovary by week 8-10. The ovary then descends along the gubernaculum to its final pelvic position by birth, retaining its blood supply from upper abdomen (ovarian artery from aorta).<br><br>Pelvic cavity directly (A) is final position; thoracic region (B) is too high; sacral region (D) is too low.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'A newborn female presents with primary amenorrhea and absence of uterus but normal ovaries and secondary sexual characteristics. Which syndrome is most likely responsible?',o:['Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser syndrome','Androgen insensitivity syndrome','Klinefelter syndrome','Turner syndrome'],a:0,
    e:`A newborn female presents with primary amenorrhoea and absence of uterus but normal ovaries - this is consistent with Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser (MRKH) syndrome.<br><br>MRKH results from failure of Müllerian duct development. Karyotype is 46,XX; ovaries function normally producing normal hormones. Patients present with primary amenorrhoea but have normal secondary sexual characteristics. Treatment includes vaginal dilatation or surgical creation of a neovagina for sexual function.<br><br>Turner syndrome (B) is 45,X with gonadal dysgenesis; AIS (C) is 46,XY female phenotype; Kallmann (D) has anosmia.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During embryonic development, the genital tubercle gives rise to which structure in females?',o:['Labia majora','Clitoris','Hymen','Vestibule'],a:1,
    e:`During embryonic development, the genital tubercle gives rise to the clitoris in females (or penis in males with androgen exposure). It is the midline anterior swelling of external genitalia.<br><br>Without androgen exposure, the genital tubercle becomes the clitoris with glans, body and crura. With androgens (5-alpha-reductase converting testosterone to dihydrotestosterone), it elongates to form the penis. Disorders of sex development can cause clitoromegaly or ambiguous genitalia presentation.<br><br>Vagina (A) develops from Müllerian ducts/urogenital sinus; labia majora (C) from labioscrotal swellings; labia minora (D) from urogenital folds.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'In the developing female embryo, absence of anti-Müllerian hormone leads to:',o:['Regression of Müllerian ducts','Development of male internal genitalia','Formation of testes','Persistence and development of Müllerian structures'],a:3,
    e:`In the developing female embryo, absence of anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH) leads to persistence and development of Müllerian structures (fallopian tubes, uterus and upper vagina).<br><br>AMH is produced by Sertoli cells of the testes in male embryos, causing Müllerian duct regression. Without testes (and AMH), the Müllerian ducts persist in females and develop into the female reproductive tract. Mesonephric ducts regress in females due to lack of testosterone, leaving only minor remnants.<br><br>Persistence of mesonephric ducts (A) requires testosterone; failure of gonadal development (B) is gonadal dysgenesis; ovarian hyperplasia (C) is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'Which embryological remnant of the mesonephric duct may persist as Gartner\'s duct cyst in the vaginal wall?',o:['Müllerian duct remnant','Cloacal remnant','Wolffian duct remnant','Yolk sac remnant'],a:2,
    e:`Gartner duct cysts are remnants of the Wolffian (mesonephric) duct, occurring in the lateral wall of the vagina or paracervical region in females.<br><br>The mesonephric ducts largely regress in females (due to absence of testosterone), but small remnants may persist as Gartner ducts running along the lateral aspects of the female reproductive tract. They occasionally develop into cysts on imaging or vaginal examination, usually asymptomatic but may rarely require excision when symptomatic.<br><br>Müllerian duct remnant (A) is for paramesonephric remnants; ureteric bud (B) forms ureter; cloacal remnant (D) is broader origin.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'During development of the placenta, which trophoblastic layer invades the maternal endometrium to establish uteroplacental circulation?',o:['Syncytiotrophoblast','Cytotrophoblast','Chorionic plate','Decidua capsularis'],a:0,
    e:`During development of the placenta, the syncytiotrophoblast invades the maternal endometrium during implantation, anchoring the conceptus and establishing the maternofetal interface.<br><br>The syncytiotrophoblast is the multinucleated outer layer of the trophoblast, formed by fusion of cytotrophoblast cells. It directly contacts maternal blood in the intervillous space and produces hCG and other placental hormones. Inadequate invasion causes pre-eclampsia, IUGR and other pregnancy complications.<br><br>Cytotrophoblast (B) is stem cell layer; epiblast (C) is embryonic; hypoblast (D) is embryonic.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus diagnosed with congenital uterine anomaly has two completely separate uterine cavities and two cervices. Which anomaly best explains this condition?',o:['Septate uterus','Uterus didelphys','Bicornuate uterus','Unicornuate uterus'],a:1,
    e:`A fetus diagnosed with congenital uterine anomaly has two completely separate uteri and two cervices - this is uterus didelphys, resulting from complete failure of fusion of Müllerian ducts.<br><br>Each Müllerian duct develops independently into a uterine horn with its own cervix, often with a longitudinal vaginal septum. Pregnancy can occur in either horn but with increased risk of preterm labour and malpresentation. Surgical correction is rarely indicated unless reproductive outcomes are significantly affected.<br><br>Bicornuate (A) has one cervix; septate uterus (C) has fibrous division with one cervix; arcuate (D) has minor indentation.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'During embryonic development of the genital tract, failure of Müllerian duct formation on one side leads to which anomaly?',o:['Bicornuate uterus','Septate uterus','Uterus didelphys','Unicornuate uterus'],a:3,
    e:`During embryonic development of the genital tract, failure of Müllerian duct formation on one side causes unicornuate uterus. Only one duct forms a uterine horn with one fallopian tube; the other side fails to develop.<br><br>Unicornuate uterus accounts for about 5 percent of Müllerian anomalies. It is associated with renal anomalies (ipsilateral renal agenesis in 40 percent) due to shared embryological origin from intermediate mesoderm. Pregnancy outcomes can be poorer with increased miscarriage and preterm birth risks.<br><br>Septate uterus (A) is failed septum resorption; bicornuate (B) is fusion failure; uterus didelphys (C) is complete fusion failure.<br><br><em>(Gynaecology by Ten Teachers)</em>`},
    {q:'In embryology of the breast, mammary glands develop from which structure?',o:['Mesonephric ridge','Genital tubercle','Mammary ridge (milk line)','Cloacal membrane'],a:2,
    e:`In embryology of the breast, mammary glands develop from the mammary ridge (milk line), an ectodermal thickening along the ventrolateral surface of the embryo extending from axilla to groin.<br><br>The breast normally develops only at the pectoral region; the rest of the milk line regresses. Failure of regression leads to supernumerary nipples (polythelia) or accessory breast tissue (polymastia) anywhere along the milk line, most commonly in the axilla or on the upper abdomen below the breast.<br><br>Genital ridge (A) is for gonads; pronephros (B) is vestigial; mesonephric duct (D) forms male tract.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman develops accessory breast tissue in the axilla. This condition results from persistence of which embryological structure?',o:['Mammary ridge','Wolffian duct','Müllerian duct','Urogenital sinus'],a:0,
    e:`A woman develops accessory breast tissue in the axilla. This condition results from persistence of the mammary ridge (milk line) in the axillary region.<br><br>Axillary polymastia is the most common site of accessory breast tissue. It can undergo cyclical changes with the menstrual cycle and may enlarge during pregnancy or develop the same diseases as normal breast tissue including cancer. Surgical excision may be considered for cosmetic or symptomatic reasons in selected cases.<br><br>Inguinal canal (B) is unrelated; lateral umbilicus (C) is unrelated; back of neck (D) is outside milk line.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'During fetal development, which hormone is primarily responsible for differentiation of male genitalia and suppression of female structures?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Anti-Müllerian hormone','Human chorionic gonadotropin'],a:2,
    e:`During fetal development, anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH) is primarily responsible for differentiation of male reproductive structures by causing regression of Müllerian ducts.<br><br>AMH is produced by Sertoli cells of the testes in male embryos. It causes Müllerian duct regression, preventing female internal genitalia. Testosterone (from Leydig cells) maintains Wolffian ducts (forming epididymis, vas deferens, seminal vesicles, ejaculatory ducts). Both hormones are needed for full male differentiation.<br><br>Estrogen (A) maintains female features; progesterone (B) is for endometrium; testosterone (D) maintains Wolffian ducts but does not regress Müllerian.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'A newborn female presents with imperforate hymen leading to hematocolpos at puberty. The hymen is derived embryologically from:',o:['Müllerian ducts','Cloacal membrane','Mesonephric duct','Urogenital sinus'],a:3,
    e:`A newborn female presents with imperforate hymen leading to haematocolpos at puberty - the hymen develops from the urogenital sinus at the junction with the lower end of the developing vagina.<br><br>The hymen is a membrane that partially closes the vaginal opening. Imperforate hymen presents at puberty with primary amenorrhoea, cyclical pelvic pain and haematocolpos (collection of menstrual blood). Treatment is hymenotomy with cruciate incision under anaesthesia, releasing accumulated blood and restoring normal menstruation.<br><br>Müllerian ducts (A) form upper vagina; mesonephric ducts (B) form male tract; cloaca (C) is broader, divides into urogenital sinus and rectum.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'During early pregnancy, the placenta secretes a hormone that maintains the corpus luteum and progesterone production. Which hormone is this?',o:['Estrogen','Human chorionic gonadotropin','Human placental lactogen','Relaxin'],a:1,
    e:`During early pregnancy, the placenta secretes human chorionic gonadotrophin (hCG), which maintains the corpus luteum until placental progesterone takes over by week 7-10.<br><br>hCG is produced by syncytiotrophoblast from very early pregnancy. Levels rise rapidly, doubling every 48-72 hours, peaking at 8-10 weeks. hCG is the basis of pregnancy tests. Without hCG rescue of the corpus luteum, progesterone levels would fall, causing menstruation and loss of the early pregnancy.<br><br>Estrogen (A) is later; progesterone (C) takes over from corpus luteum; hPL (D) is later in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus with congenital absence of vagina but normal uterus likely has failure of which developmental process?',o:['Fusion of Müllerian ducts','Development of Wolffian duct','Formation of urogenital sinus','Canalization of vaginal plate'],a:3,
    e:`A fetus with congenital absence of vagina but normal uterus likely has failure of canalisation of vaginal plate, the embryological precursor of the lower vagina.<br><br>The vaginal plate is a solid epithelial structure formed by the sinovaginal bulbs (urogenital sinus origin). Canalisation begins centrally and proceeds craniocaudally. Failure of complete canalisation produces obstructive lesions presenting at puberty with primary amenorrhoea, cyclical pain and haematocolpos. Treatment is surgical creation of a neovagina.<br><br>Müllerian fusion failure (A) causes uterine anomalies; gubernaculum failure (B) affects ovarian descent; sinovaginal bulbs failure (C) is overlapping but specifically vaginal plate canalisation.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'During embryogenesis, the external genitalia of both sexes initially develop from the same indifferent structures. Which structure later forms the labia majora in females?',o:['Genital tubercle','Urogenital folds','Labioscrotal swellings','Cloacal folds'],a:2,
    e:`During embryogenesis, the external genitalia of both sexes initially develop from labioscrotal swellings (and other structures - genital tubercle, urogenital folds), in the indifferent stage of development.<br><br>Without androgen exposure (in females), the labioscrotal swellings remain unfused as the labia majora; the urogenital folds remain unfused as the labia minora; the genital tubercle becomes the clitoris. With androgens (in males), the labioscrotal swellings fuse to form the scrotum, urogenital folds fuse to form the urethra, and the genital tubercle elongates to form the penis.<br><br>Genital tubercle alone (A) forms only clitoris/penis; urogenital folds alone (B) form labia minora/penile urethra; cloacal membrane (D) is broader origin.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'A newborn female has congenital absence of uterus and upper vagina but normal ovaries and karyotype 46,XX. Which embryological structure failed to develop?',o:['Müllerian duct','Mesonephric duct','Urogenital sinus','Genital tubercle'],a:0,
    e:`A newborn female has congenital absence of uterus and upper vagina but normal ovaries - this results from failure of Müllerian duct development (MRKH syndrome).<br><br>MRKH syndrome involves failure of Müllerian duct development. Karyotype is 46,XX; ovaries function normally (genital ridge origin) producing normal hormones. Patients present at puberty with primary amenorrhoea but have normal secondary sexual characteristics. Treatment includes vaginal dilatation or surgical creation of a neovagina.<br><br>Mesonephric duct (B) forms male tract; gubernaculum (C) forms ligaments; cloaca (D) is broader origin.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus with abnormal placental implantation shows defective trophoblastic invasion of maternal spiral arteries, predisposing the mother to preeclampsia. Which placental structure normally performs this invasive function?',o:['Cytotrophoblast','Syncytiotrophoblast','Chorionic villi','Decidua basalis'],a:1,
    e:`A fetus with abnormal placental implantation shows defective trophoblastic invasion of spiral arteries. The syncytiotrophoblast is the invading layer in normal implantation.<br><br>Inadequate trophoblastic invasion of spiral arteries causes pre-eclampsia, IUGR and other pregnancy complications. Normal trophoblast remodels spiral arteries into dilated low-resistance vessels delivering blood to the intervillous space. Failed remodelling leads to placental ischaemia, oxidative stress and release of factors causing maternal endothelial dysfunction.<br><br>Cytotrophoblast (A) is the stem cell layer; epiblast (C) is embryonic; hypoblast (D) is embryonic.<br><br><em>(Langman\'s Medical Embryology)</em>`}
  ];
})();